{"title_page": "Sten Lex", "text_new": "{{Notability|date=December 2011}}\n\n'''Sten''' (born 1982, [[Rome]]) and '''Lex''' (born 1982, [[Taranto]]), known as '''Sten & Lex''', are two [[Italy|Italian]] street artists.\n\nSten & Lex have been doing stencils on the street since 2000/2001 and today their work is part of the urban landscape in [[London]], [[Paris]], [[Barcelona]], [[New York City]], and in their home town of [[Rome]]. During that early period in Rome, and Italy in general, there wasn't a strong stencil culture such as there was in France, and Sten & Lex are seen by many as the pioneers of \"[[Stencil]] [[Graffiti]]\" in Italy and were the first to be considered \"[[stencil]] artists\". All the work of Sten & Lex results from an individual path that developed far from art academies and design institutes and far from a classic [[writing]] and [[graffiti]] background. The duo are best known in the history of [[stencil]]-making for introducing the halftone stencil technique, in which the greater part of their stencil portraits is composed of thousands of lines. They usually produce portraits of anonymous people they have photographed themselves or found in family photos album.\n\nIn 2008, they took part in the [[Cans Festival]] : Banksy invited thirty-nine artists from around the world, including, [[Prism (street artist)|Prism]], [[Blek le Rat|Blek]], [[Faile (artist)|Faile]], [[Vhils (artists)|Vhils]], [[Vexta]], to exhibit their work in an abandoned tunnel near [[Leake Street]] in South East [[London]].[[File:Sten lex banksy, cans festival, londra 2008.jpg|thumb|Banksy, Sten, Lex, Cans Festival, London 2008]]\n\nIn 2009, they started producing what they call \"[[Stencil]] [[Poster]]\".The technique derives from the union of two of the main techniques of [[street art]]: [[Stencil]] and [[Poster]]. They glue a [[stencil]] cut from paper on the wall and paint over it. They then destroy the matrix and apply its scraps to the wall, thus allowing them to become part of the work itself. The bits of matrix applied to the wall wear out over time, producing work in a state of constant change. Unlike [[stencil]] work in general, the images thus created cannot be reproduced, rendering each piece original and unique. A book documenting this technique entitled \"Stencil Poster\" was published in 2009 by [[Drago (publisher)|Drago]].\n\nIn 2011, they entered the contemporary art world with large-scale pieces in museums, such as the [[Museum of Contemporary Art of Rome]] (MACRO) in Rome, Italy and the Carandente Museum in Spoleto, Italy. That same year, they participated in major international festivals, such as the \"Walk This Way\" Festival in Koge, Denmark and the \"Nuart\" Festival in Stavanger, Norway, contributing to the growth of their fame and popularity.\n\n2012 saw the production of monumental projects that led to Sten Lex being recognized as emerging artists increasingly in demand. They were invited to the \"Living Walls\" show in Atlanta, USA; the Centre de la Gravure et de l\u2019Image imprim\u00e9e in La Louvi\u00e8re, Belgium, as well as to the \"Outer Spaces\" outdoor show in Poznan, Poland and the \"Open Walls\" in Baltimore, USA.\n\nIn 2012, they also presented their work in a large solo show at the [[Magda Danysz Gallery]] in Paris. The Shanghai, China branch of the same gallery granted them another solo show in the Spring of 2013, referring to the duo as among \"the most innovative at the moment.\"http://www.magda-gallery.com/en/sten-lex-shanghai-solo-show<ref>{{cite web|title=Gallery Magda Danysz|url=http://www.magda-gallery.com/en/sten-lex-shanghai-solo-show|website=http://www.magda-gallery.com/en/sten-lex-shanghai-solo-show|access-date=3 February 2015|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://archive.is/20150203130655/http://www.magda-gallery.com/en/sten-lex-shanghai-solo-show|archive-date=3 February 2015|df=}}</ref>\n\nIn anticipation of their solo show at Rome's \"Wunderkammern\" gallery in January 2015, AGRPress referred to them as \"among the most internationally recognized Italian street artists.\" <ref>{{cite web|last1=Currado|first1=Giovanni|title=Matrici Distrutte, l'attesa mostra personale di Sten Lex a Roma|url=http://www.agrpress.it/arte/matrici-distrutte-l-attesa-mostra-personale-di-sten-lex-a-roma-3461|accessdate=3 February 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017 StenLex worked with [https://www.allcitycanvas.com/sten-lex-stencil-mas-grande-del-mundo-distrito-tec Distrito Tec ], M\u00e9xico to do what it is considered the world's largest stencil. Their work consists of four thousand square meters of surface. Specifically, 1,952 square meters of black and white paint, plus 1,600 square meters of paper strips. The curatorship of the six works that make up the project is in charge of the art and design agency [http://arto.mx/ ARTO] Studio.\n\n\n==Videography==\n* 2009 Painted Poster, Via delle Conce, Rome [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Me_mZeZsfjY PAINTED POSTER on Youtube]\n* 2011 Stencil Poster, Walk This Way, K\u00f8ge,2011 [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=rzhKQl4byRM STENCIL POSTER, K\u00d8GE, 2011 on Youtube]\n\n==Bibliography==\n* ''Stencil Poster,'' [[Drago (publisher)|Drago]], 2009\n* ''Sten & Lex'', [[Drago (publisher)|Drago]], 2010\n* Maximiliano Ruiz, ''Walls & Frames'', Berlin, Gestalten, 2011.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|http://stenlex.net}}\n* Gallery : Magda Danysz Gallery (Paris -Shanghai) http://www.magda-gallery.com\n* Gallery : Wunderkammern (Rome) https://web.archive.org/web/20150203140709/http://www.wunderkammern.net/stenlex/stenlex.htm\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Italian artists]]\n[[Category:1982 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Art duos]]\n", "text_old": "{{Notability|date=December 2011}}\n\n'''Sten''' (born 1982, [[Rome]]) and '''Lex''' (born 1982, [[Taranto]]), known as '''Sten & Lex''', are two [[Italy|Italian]] street artists.\n\nSten & Lex have been doing stencils on the street since 2000/2001 and today their work is part of the urban landscape in [[London]], [[Paris]], [[Barcelona]], [[New York City]], and in their home town of [[Rome]]. During that early period in Rome, and Italy in general, there wasn't a strong stencil culture such as there was in France, and Sten & Lex are seen by many as the pioneers of \"[[Stencil]] [[Graffiti]]\" in Italy and were the first to be considered \"[[stencil]] artists\". All the work of Sten & Lex results from an individual path that developed far from art academies and design institutes and far from a classic [[writing]] and [[graffiti]] background. The duo are best known in the history of [[stencil]]-making for introducing the halftone stencil technique, in which the greater part of their stencil portraits is composed of thousands of lines. They usually produce portraits of anonymous people they have photographed themselves or found in family photos album.\n\nIn 2008, they took part in the [[Cans Festival]] : Banksy invited thirty-nine artists from around the world, including, [[Prism (street artist)|Prism]], [[Blek le Rat|Blek]], [[Faile (artist)|Faile]], [[Vhils (artists)|Vhils]], [[Vexta]], to exhibit their work in an abandoned tunnel near [[Leake Street]] in South East [[London]].[[File:Sten lex banksy, cans festival, londra 2008.jpg|thumb|Banksy, Sten, Lex, Cans Festival, London 2008]]\n\nIn 2009, they started producing what they call \"[[Stencil]] [[Poster]]\".The technique derives from the union of two of the main techniques of [[street art]]: [[Stencil]] and [[Poster]]. They glue a [[stencil]] cut from paper on the wall and paint over it. They then destroy the matrix and apply its scraps to the wall, thus allowing them to become part of the work itself. The bits of matrix applied to the wall wear out over time, producing work in a state of constant change. Unlike [[stencil]] work in general, the images thus created cannot be reproduced, rendering each piece original and unique. A book documenting this technique entitled \"Stencil Poster\" was published in 2009 by [[Drago (publisher)|Drago]].\n\nIn 2011, they entered the contemporary art world with large-scale pieces in museums, such as the [[Museum of Contemporary Art of Rome]] (MACRO) in Rome, Italy and the Carandente Museum in Spoleto, Italy. That same year, they participated in major international festivals, such as the \"Walk This Way\" Festival in Koge, Denmark and the \"Nuart\" Festival in Stavanger, Norway, contributing to the growth of their fame and popularity.\n\n2012 saw the production of monumental projects that led to Sten Lex being recognized as emerging artists increasingly in demand. They were invited to the \"Living Walls\" show in Atlanta, USA; the Centre de la Gravure et de l\u2019Image imprim\u00e9e in La Louvi\u00e8re, Belgium, as well as to the \"Outer Spaces\" outdoor show in Poznan, Poland and the \"Open Walls\" in Baltimore, USA.\n\nIn 2012, they also presented their work in a large solo show at the [[Magda Danysz Gallery]] in Paris. The Shanghai, China branch of the same gallery granted them another solo show in the Spring of 2013, referring to the duo as among \"the most innovative at the moment.\"http://www.magda-gallery.com/en/sten-lex-shanghai-solo-show<ref>{{cite web|title=Gallery Magda Danysz|url=http://www.magda-gallery.com/en/sten-lex-shanghai-solo-show|website=http://www.magda-gallery.com/en/sten-lex-shanghai-solo-show|access-date=3 February 2015|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://archive.is/20150203130655/http://www.magda-gallery.com/en/sten-lex-shanghai-solo-show|archive-date=3 February 2015|df=}}</ref>\n\nIn anticipation of their solo show at Rome's \"Wunderkammern\" gallery in January 2015, AGRPress referred to them as \"among the most internationally recognized Italian street artists.\" <ref>{{cite web|last1=Currado|first1=Giovanni|title=Matrici Distrutte, l'attesa mostra personale di Sten Lex a Roma|url=http://www.agrpress.it/arte/matrici-distrutte-l-attesa-mostra-personale-di-sten-lex-a-roma-3461|accessdate=3 February 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Videography==\n* 2009 Painted Poster, Via delle Conce, Rome [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Me_mZeZsfjY PAINTED POSTER on Youtube]\n* 2011 Stencil Poster, Walk This Way, K\u00f8ge,2011 [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=rzhKQl4byRM STENCIL POSTER, K\u00d8GE, 2011 on Youtube]\n\n==Bibliography==\n* ''Stencil Poster,'' [[Drago (publisher)|Drago]], 2009\n* ''Sten & Lex'', [[Drago (publisher)|Drago]], 2010\n* Maximiliano Ruiz, ''Walls & Frames'', Berlin, Gestalten, 2011.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|http://stenlex.net}}\n* Gallery : Magda Danysz Gallery (Paris -Shanghai) http://www.magda-gallery.com\n* Gallery : Wunderkammern (Rome) https://web.archive.org/web/20150203140709/http://www.wunderkammern.net/stenlex/stenlex.htm\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Italian artists]]\n[[Category:1982 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Art duos]]\n", "name_user": "Anna Velasco", "label": "safe", "comment": "add info", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sten_Lex"}
{"title_page": "Google", "text_new": "{{About|the company|the search engine|Google Search|other uses}}\n{{Distinguish|Googol|Goggles}}\n{{pp-semi-indef}}\n{{pp-move-indef}}\n{{short description|American multinational Internet and technology corporation}}\n{{Use American English|date=July 2018}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2019}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name = Google LLC\n| logo = Google 2015 logo.svg\n| logo_size = 250px\n| logo_alt = Each letter of \"Google\" is colored (from left to right) in blue, red, yellow, blue, green, and red.\n| logo_caption = Google's logo {{as of|2015|lc=y|since=y}}\n| image = Googleplex HQ (cropped).jpg\n| image_size = 250px\n| image_caption = Google's headquarters, the [[Googleplex]]\n| former_name = Google Inc. (1998\u20132017)\n| type = [[Subsidiary]]\n| industry = {{Unbulleted list\n| [[Internet]]  \n| [[Cloud computing]]\n| [[Computer software]]\n| [[Computer hardware]]\n| [[Artificial intelligence]]\n| [[Advertising]]\n}}\n| founded = {{Start date and age|1998|09|04}}{{efn|Google was originally incorporated on September 4, 1998, however, since 2002, the company has celebrated its anniversaries on various days in September, most frequently on September 27.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://time.com/3250807/google-anniversary/ |title=Google Used to Be the Company That Did 'Nothing But Search' |first=Alex |last=Fitzpatrick |date=September 4, 2014 |website=[[Time (magazine)|Time]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/technology/2019/09/27/when-is-googles-21st-birthday-doodle/ |title=When is Google's birthday \u2013 and why are people confused? |author=Telegraph Reporters |date=September 27, 2019 |website=[[The Daily Telegraph|The Telegraph]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/life-style/gadgets-and-tech/google-birthday-surprise-spinner-date-problem-start-company-a7968951.html |title=Google birthday: The one big problem with the company's celebratory doodle |first=Andrew |last=Griffin |date=September 27, 2019 |website=[[The Independent]]}}</ref> The shift in dates reportedly happened to celebrate index-size milestones in tandem with the birthday.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/business/2008/sep/05/google.mediabusiness |title=Happy birthday Google |first=Richard |last=Wray |date=September 5, 2008 |website=[[The Guardian]]}}</ref>}} in [[Menlo Park, California|Menlo Park]], California, U.S.\n| founders = {{Unbulleted list\n| [[Larry Page]]\n| [[Sergey Brin]]\n}}\n| defunct = \n| hq_location = 1600 Amphitheatre Parkway\n| hq_location_city = [[Mountain View, California]]\n| hq_location_country = U.S.\n| area_served = Worldwide\n| key_people = {{Unbulleted list\n| [[Sundar Pichai]] ([[Chief executive officer|CEO]])\n| [[Ruth Porat]] ([[Chief financial officer|CFO]])\n}}\n| products = [[List of Google products]]\n| num_employees = 114,096\n| num_employees_year = {{As of|2019|9|30|alt=Q3 2019}}\n| parent = [[Alphabet Inc.]] (2015\u2013present)\n| subsid = [[List of mergers and acquisitions by Alphabet|List of subsidiaries]]\n| website = {{URL|https://www.google.com/|google.com}}\n| footnotes = <ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.google.com/intl/en/about/company/ |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150116073513/https://www.google.com/intl/en/about/company/ |url-status=dead |archive-date=January 16, 2015 |title=Company \u2013 Google |date=January 16, 2015 |access-date=September 13, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first=Thomas |last=Claburn |title=Google Founded By Sergey Brin, Larry Page... And Hubert Chang?!? |url=https://www.informationweek.com/applications/google-founded-by-sergey-brin-larry-page-and-hubert-chang!/d/d-id/1072309 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110628231125/http://www.informationweek.com/news/internet/google/210603678 |website=[[InformationWeek]] |publisher=[[UBM plc]] |date=September 24, 2008 |archivedate=June 28, 2011 |accessdate=January 22, 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.google.com/about/jobs/locations/ |title=Locations&nbsp;\u2014 Google Jobs |accessdate=September 27, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130930200600/http://www.google.com/about/jobs/locations/ |archive-date=September 30, 2013 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"EmployeesAsOf2018Q4\">{{cite press release |date=February 4, 2019 |title=Alphabet Announces Fourth Quarter 2018 Results |url=https://abc.xyz/investor/static/pdf/2018Q4_alphabet_earnings_release.pdf |url-status=live |type=Press release |location=Mountain View, California |publisher=[[Alphabet Inc.]] |page=1 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190204221316/https://abc.xyz/investor/static/pdf/2018Q4_alphabet_earnings_release.pdf |archive-date=February 4, 2019 |access-date=February 4, 2019 |quote=Alphabet Inc. (NASDAQ: GOOG, GOOGL) today announced financial results for the quarter and fiscal year ended December 31, 2018.&nbsp;[...] Q1 2018 financial highlights[:] The following summarizes our consolidated financial results for the quarters ended December 31, 2017 and 2018&nbsp;[...]:&nbsp;[...] Number of employees [as of] Three Months Ended December 31, 2018 [is] 98,771[.]}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''Google LLC''' is an American multinational technology company that specializes in Internet-related services and products, which include [[online advertising|online advertising technologies]], a [[search engine]], [[cloud computing]], software, and hardware. It is considered one of the [[Big Four tech companies|Big Four]] [[List of public corporations by market capitalization|technology companies]], alongside [[Amazon (company)|Amazon]], [[Apple Inc.|Apple]], and [[Microsoft]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.barrons.com/articles/ranking-the-big-four-internet-stocks-google-is-no-1-apple-comes-in-last-1503412102 |title=Ranking The Big Four Tech Stocks: Google Is No. 1, Apple Comes In Last |last=Rivas |first=Teresa |website=www.barrons.com |language=en-US |access-date=December 27, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181228082808/https://www.barrons.com/articles/ranking-the-big-four-internet-stocks-google-is-no-1-apple-comes-in-last-1503412102 |archive-date=December 28, 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/opinion/articles/2017-10-31/the-big-four-of-technology|title=The Big Four of Technology|last=Ritholtz|first=Barry|date=2017-10-31|website=Bloomberg|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190626024146/https://www.bloomberg.com/opinion/articles/2017-10-31/the-big-four-of-technology|archive-date=2019-06-26|access-date=2018-12-27}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web url=https://whatis.techtarget.com/definition/GAFA|title=What is GAFA (the big four)? -\nDefinition from WhatIs.com|website=WhatIs.com|language=en|access-date=2020-03-05}}</ref>\n\nGoogle was founded in September 1998 by [[Larry Page]] and [[Sergey Brin]] while they were Ph.D. students at [[Stanford University]] in [[California]]. Together they own about 14 percent of its shares and control 56 percent of the stockholder voting power through [[Preferred stock|supervoting]] stock. They incorporated Google as a California privately held company on September 4, 1998, in California. Google was then reincorporated in Delaware on October 22, 2002.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://businesssearch.sos.ca.gov/Document/RetrievePDF?Id=02474131-5043839|title=Business Entity Filing|last=|first=|date=October 7, 2002|website=Business Search|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190814022055/https://businesssearch.sos.ca.gov/Document/RetrievePDF?Id=02474131-5043839|archive-date=August 14, 2019|url-status=live|access-date=August 14, 2019}}</ref> An initial public offering (IPO) took place on August 19, 2004, and Google moved to its headquarters in Mountain View, California, nicknamed the  [[Googleplex]]. In August 2015, Google announced plans to reorganize its various interests as a conglomerate called [[Alphabet Inc.]] Google is Alphabet's leading subsidiary and will continue to be the umbrella company for Alphabet's Internet interests. [[Sundar Pichai]] was appointed CEO of Google, replacing Larry Page who became the CEO of Alphabet.\n\nThe company's rapid growth since incorporation has triggered a chain of products, acquisitions, and partnerships beyond Google's core search engine ([[Google Search]]). It offers services designed for work and productivity ([[Google Docs]], [[Google Sheets]], and [[Google Slides]]), email ([[Gmail]]), scheduling and time management ([[Google Calendar]]), cloud storage ([[Google Drive]]), instant messaging and video chat ([[Google Duo|Duo]], [[Hangouts]]), language translation ([[Google Translate]]), mapping and navigation ([[Google Maps]], [[Waze]], [[Google Earth]], [[Street View]]), video sharing ([[YouTube]]), note-taking ([[Google Keep]]), and photo organizing and editing ([[Google Photos]]). The company leads the development of the [[Android (operating system)|Android]] mobile operating system, the [[Google Chrome]] web browser, and [[Chrome OS]], a lightweight operating system based on the Chrome browser. Google has moved increasingly into hardware; from 2010 to 2015, it partnered with major electronics manufacturers in the production of its [[Google Nexus|Nexus]] devices, and it released multiple hardware products in October 2016, including the [[Pixel (smartphone)|Google Pixel]] smartphone, [[Google Home]] smart speaker, [[Google Wifi (router)|Google Wifi]] mesh wireless router, and [[Google Daydream]] virtual reality headset. Google has also experimented with becoming an Internet carrier ([[Google Fiber]], [[Google Fi]], and [[Google Station]]).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theverge.com/2016/9/27/13070922/google-station-public-wi-fi-india|title=Google Station is a new platform that aims to make public Wi-Fi better|last=Byford|first=Sam|date=2016-09-27|website=The Verge|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170903210758/https://www.theverge.com/2016/9/27/13070922/google-station-public-wi-fi-india|archive-date=2017-09-03|access-date=2018-05-22}}</ref>\n\nGoogle.com is the most visited website in the world.<ref name=\"Alexa\"/> Several other Google services also figure in the top 100 most visited websites, including [[YouTube]] and [[Blogger (service)|Blogger]]. Google was the most valuable brand in the world {{as of|2017|lc=y|post=,}}<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/business/news/worlds-most-valuable-brands-facebook-google-apple-amazon-a7556571.html |title=Google is now the world's most valuable brand |date=February 1, 2017 |work=The Independent |access-date=August 31, 2017 |language=en-GB |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170831172223/http://www.independent.co.uk/news/business/news/worlds-most-valuable-brands-facebook-google-apple-amazon-a7556571.html |archive-date=August 31, 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref> but has received significant [[Criticism of Google|criticism]] involving issues such as [[Privacy concerns regarding Google|privacy concerns]], tax avoidance, antitrust, [[Censorship by Google|censorship]], and search neutrality. Google's [[mission statement]] is \"to organize the world's information and make it universally accessible and useful\". The company's unofficial slogan \"[[Don't be evil]]\" was removed from the company's code of conduct around May 2018, but reinstated by July 31, 2018.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web |url=https://abc.xyz/investor/other/google-code-of-conduct.html |title=Google Code of Conduct |publisher=Alphabet |accessdate=August 31, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170211223917/https://abc.xyz/investor/other/google-code-of-conduct.html |archive-date=February 11, 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://gizmodo.com/google-removes-nearly-all-mentions-of-dont-be-evil-from-1826153393 |title=Google Removes 'Don't Be Evil' Clause From Its Code of Conduct |first=Kate |last=Conger |access-date=May 24, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180525002631/https://gizmodo.com/google-removes-nearly-all-mentions-of-dont-be-evil-from-1826153393 |archive-date=May 25, 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\n{{Main|History of Google|List of mergers and acquisitions by Alphabet}}\n{{See also|Alphabet Inc.}}\n\n=== Early years ===\n[[File:Google page brin.jpg|thumb|[[Larry Page]] and [[Sergey Brin]] in 2003|alt=|left]]\nGoogle began in January 1996 as a research project by [[Larry Page]] and [[Sergey Brin]] when they were both PhD students at [[Stanford University]] in [[Stanford, California]].<ref name=\"milestones\">{{cite web |title=Our history in depth |url=https://www.google.com/about/company/history/ |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120401005940/http://www.google.com/about/company/history/ |website=Google Company |archivedate=April 1, 2012 |accessdate=July 15, 2017 |url-status=dead}}</ref> The project initially involved an unofficial \"third founder\", Scott Hassan, the original lead programmer who wrote much of the code for the original [[Google Search]] engine, but he left before Google was officially founded as a company;<ref name=\"vanityfair\">{{cite web |last=Fisher |first=Adam |title=Brin, Page, and Mayer on the Accidental Birth of the Company that Changed Everything |url=https://www.vanityfair.com/news/2018/07/valley-of-genius-excerpt-google |website=[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]] |date=July 10, 2018 |accessdate=23 August 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190704184309/https://www.vanityfair.com/news/2018/07/valley-of-genius-excerpt-google |archive-date=July 4, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=McHugh |first=Josh |title=Google vs. Evil |url=https://www.wired.com/2003/01/google-10/ |accessdate=24 August 2019 |work=[[Wired (magazine)|Wired]] |date=1 January 2003 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190602064540/https://www.wired.com/2003/01/google-10/ |archive-date=June 2, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> Hassan went on to pursue a career in [[robotics]] and founded the company [[Willow Garage]] in 2006.<ref>{{cite news |title=Willow Garage Founder Scott Hassan Aims To Build A Startup Village |url=https://spectrum.ieee.org/view-from-the-valley/at-work/start-ups/willow-garage-founder-scott-hassan-aims-to-build-a-startup-village |accessdate=1 September 2019 |work=[[IEEE Spectrum]] |date=5 September 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190824075356/https://spectrum.ieee.org/view-from-the-valley/at-work/start-ups/willow-garage-founder-scott-hassan-aims-to-build-a-startup-village |archive-date=August 24, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=D'Onfro |first=Jillian |title=How a billionaire who wrote Google's original code created a robot revolution |url=https://www.businessinsider.com/a-look-back-at-willow-garage-2016-2 |work=[[Business Insider]] |date=February 13, 2016 |access-date=August 24, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190824075346/https://www.businessinsider.com/a-look-back-at-willow-garage-2016-2 |archive-date=August 24, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nWhile conventional search engines ranked results by counting how many times the search terms appeared on the page, they theorized about a better system that analyzed the relationships among websites.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ilpubs.stanford.edu:8090/422/|title=The PageRank Citation Ranking: Bringing Order to the Web|last=Page|first=Lawrence|authorlink=Larry Page|last2=Brin|first2=Sergey|authorlink2=Sergey Brin|date=November 11, 1999|website=Stanford University|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091118014915/http://ilpubs.stanford.edu:8090/422/|archive-date=November 18, 2009|access-date=February 15, 2010|last3=Motwani|first3=Rajeev|last4=Winograd|first4=Terry}}</ref> They called this algorithm [[PageRank]]; it determined a website's [[Relevance (information retrieval)|relevance]] by the number of pages, and the importance of those pages that linked back to the original site.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.google.com/corporate/tech.html |title=Technology Overview |website=Google, Inc. |accessdate=February 15, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100210175913/http://www.google.com/corporate/tech.html |archive-date=February 10, 2010 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www-diglib.stanford.edu/cgi-bin/WP/get/SIDL-WP-1997-0072?1|title=PageRank: Bringing Order to the Web|last=Page|first=Larry|authorlink=Larry Page|date=August 18, 1997|website=Stanford Digital Library Project|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20020506051802/http://www-diglib.stanford.edu/cgi-bin/WP/get/SIDL-WP-1997-0072?1|archive-date=May 6, 2002|accessdate=November 27, 2010}}</ref> Page told his ideas to Hassan, who began writing the code to implement Page's ideas.<ref name=\"vanityfair\"/>\n\nPage and Brin originally nicknamed the new search engine \"BackRub\", because the system checked backlinks to estimate the importance of a site.<ref>{{Cite news |title=The Birth of Google |first=John |last=Battelle |newspaper=Wired |date=August 2005 |url=https://www.wired.com/wired/archive/13.08/battelle.html?tw=wn_tophead_4 |accessdate=October 12, 2010 |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6BYbTgdmC?url=http://www.wired.com/wired/archive/13.08/battelle.html?tw=wn_tophead_4 |archive-date=October 20, 2012 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Trex |first=Ethan |title=9 People, Places & Things That Changed Their Names |url=http://mentalfloss.com/article/20890/9-people-places-things-changed-their-names |website=Mental Floss |accessdate=August 4, 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140810100639/http://mentalfloss.com/article/20890/9-people-places-things-changed-their-names |archive-date=August 10, 2014 |url-status=live|date=February 17, 2009 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://huron.stanford.edu |title=Backrub search engine at Stanford University |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/19961224105215/http://huron.stanford.edu/ |archivedate=December 24, 1996 |accessdate=March 12, 2011}}</ref> Hassan as well as Alan Steremberg were cited by Page and Brin as being critical to the development of Google. [[Rajeev Motwani]] and [[Terry Winograd]] later co-authored with Page and Brin the first paper about the project, describing PageRank and the initial prototype of the Google search engine, published in 1998. [[H\u00e9ctor Garc\u00eda-Molina]] and [[Jeff Ullman]] were also cited as contributors to the project.<ref name=\"originalpaper\"/> PageRank was influenced by a similar page-ranking and site-scoring algorithm earlier used for [[RankDex]], developed by [[Robin Li]] in 1996, with Larry Page's PageRank patent including a citation to Li's earlier RankDex patent; Li later went on to create the Chinese search engine [[Baidu]].<ref>[http://www.rankdex.com/about.html \"About: RankDex\"] {{webarchive|url= https://www.webcitation.org/659XSbLCF?url=http://www.rankdex.com/about.html |date= 2012-02-02 }}, ''[[RankDex]]''</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Altucher |first=James |title=10 Unusual Things About Google |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/jamesaltucher/2011/03/18/10-unusual-things-about-google-also-the-worst-vc-decision-i-ever-made/ |date=March 18, 2011 |website=[[Forbes]] |accessdate=16 June 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190616133656/https://www.forbes.com/sites/jamesaltucher/2011/03/18/10-unusual-things-about-google-also-the-worst-vc-decision-i-ever-made/ |archive-date=June 16, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title = Method for node ranking in a linked database |url = https://www.google.com/patents/US6285999 |publisher = Google Patents |accessdate = 19 October 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20151015185034/http://www.google.com/patents/US6285999 |archivedate = 15 October 2015 |df = }}</ref>\n\nEventually, they changed the name to Google; the name of the search engine originated from a misspelling of the word \"[[googol]]\",<ref>{{cite web |url=http://graphics.stanford.edu/~dk/google_name_origin.html |title=Origin of the name \"Google\" |last=Koller |first=David |date=January 2004 |website=Stanford University |accessdate=July 4, 2012 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/68ubHzYs7?url=http://graphics.stanford.edu/~dk/google_name_origin.html |archivedate=July 4, 2012 |url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.stanforddaily.com/2003/02/12/from-googol-to-google |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100327141327/http://www.stanforddaily.com/2003/02/12/from-googol-to-google |archivedate=March 27, 2010 |title=From Googol to Google |last=Hanley |first=Rachael |date=February 12, 2003 |newspaper=The Stanford Daily |publisher=Stanford University |accessdate=February 15, 2010}}</ref> the number 1 followed by 100 zeros, which was picked to signify that the search engine was intended to provide large quantities of information.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.google.com/company.html |title=Google! Beta website |website=Google, Inc. |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/19990221202430/https://www.google.com/company.html |archivedate=February 21, 1999 |accessdate=October 12, 2010 |url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Google1998.png|thumb|upright=1.15|Google's original homepage had a simple design because the company founders had little experience in [[HTML]], the [[markup language]] used for designing web pages.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://alan.blog-city.com/an_evening_with_googles_marissa_mayer.htm |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/61rJXKAeq?url=http://alan.blog-city.com/an_evening_with_googles_marissa_mayer.htm |archivedate=September 21, 2011 |title=An evening with Google's Marissa Mayer |last=Williamson |first=Alan |website=Alan Williamson |date=January 12, 2005 |accessdate=July 5, 2010 |url-status=dead}}</ref>|alt=Google's homepage in 1998]]\n\nThe domain name for Google was registered on September 15, 1997,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://whois.domaintools.com/google.com |title=Google.com WHOIS, DNS, & Domain Info - DomainTools |website=[[WHOIS]] |date= |accessdate=July 11, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160314084453/http://whois.domaintools.com/google.com |archive-date=March 14, 2016 |url-status=live}}</ref> and the company was incorporated on September 4, 1998. It was based in the garage of a friend ([[Susan Wojcicki]]<ref name=\"milestones\" />) in [[Menlo Park, California]]. [[Craig Silverstein]], a fellow PhD student at Stanford, was hired as the first employee.<ref name=\"milestones\" /><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www-cs-students.stanford.edu/~csilvers/ |title=Craig Silverstein's website |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/19991002122809/http://www-cs-students.stanford.edu/~csilvers/ |archivedate=October 2, 1999 |website=Stanford University |accessdate=October 12, 2010 |url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last=Kopytoff |first=Verne |url=http://articles.sfgate.com/2008-09-07/news/17161124_1_larry-page-google-search-engine |title=Craig Silverstein grew a decade with Google |newspaper=San Francisco Chronicle |publisher=Hearst Communications, Inc. |date=September 7, 2008 |accessdate=October 12, 2010 |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6BYbUJWuY?url=http://www.sfgate.com/news/article/Craig-Silverstein-grew-a-decade-with-Google-3270079.php |archive-date=October 20, 2012 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nGoogle was initially funded by an August 1998 contribution of $100,000 from [[Andy Bechtolsheim]], co-founder of [[Sun Microsystems]]; the money was given before Google was incorporated.<ref name=\"Bechtolsheim\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi?file=/chronicle/archive/2004/04/29/MNGLD6CFND34.DTL |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090919030812/http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi?file=%2Fchronicle%2Farchive%2F2004%2F04%2F29%2FMNGLD6CFND34.DTL |archivedate=September 19, 2009 |title=For early Googlers, key word is $ |last=Kopytoff |first=Verne |date=April 29, 2004 |newspaper=San Francisco Chronicle |publisher=Hearst Communications |accessdate=February 19, 2010 |location=San Francisco |url-status=dead}}</ref> Google received money from three other [[angel investor]]s in 1998: [[Amazon.com]] founder [[Jeff Bezos]], Stanford University computer science professor [[David Cheriton]], and entrepreneur [[Ram Shriram]].<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite book|title=Googled: The End of the World as We Know it|last=Auletta|first=Ken|publisher=Penguin Books|year=2010|isbn=9780143118046|edition=Reprint|location=New York, N.Y.|oclc=515456623|quote=On September 7, 1998, the day Google officially incorporated, he [Shriram] wrote out a check for just over $250,000, one of four of this size the founders received.|author-link=Ken Auletta}}</ref> Between these initial investors, friends, and family Google raised around 1 million dollars, which is what allowed them to open up their original shop in [[Menlo Park, California]]. <ref>{{cite web |last=Hosch |first=William L. |last2=Hall |first2=Mark |title=Google Inc. |url=https://www.britannica.com/topic/Google-Inc |website=Britannica |publisher=Britannica |accessdate=March 17, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190220013941/https://www.britannica.com/topic/Google-Inc |archive-date=February 20, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nAfter some additional, small investments through the end of 1998 to early 1999,<ref name=\":3\" /> a new $25 million round of funding was announced on June 7, 1999,<ref>{{Cite press release |url=https://www.google.com/pressrel/pressrelease1.html |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20010212052759/http://www.google.com/pressrel/pressrelease1.html |archivedate=February 12, 2001 |title=Google Receives $25&nbsp;Million in Equity Funding |date=June 7, 1999 |location=Palo Alto, Calif. |accessdate=February 16, 2009 |url-status=live}}</ref> with major investors including the [[venture capital]] firms [[Kleiner Perkins]] and [[Sequoia Capital]].<ref name=\"Bechtolsheim\" />\n\n=== Growth ===\nIn March 1999, the company moved its offices to [[Palo Alto, California]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.businessinsider.com/google-history-in-photos-2015-10 |title=38 photos of Google's rise from a Stanford dorm room to world domination |last=Weinberger |first=Matt |date=October 12, 2015 |website=[[Business Insider]] |publisher=[[Axel Springer SE]] |accessdate=July 15, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170819101107/http://www.businessinsider.com/google-history-in-photos-2015-10 |archive-date=August 19, 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref> which is home to several prominent [[Silicon Valley]] technology start-ups.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.cnet.com/news/a-building-blessed-with-tech-success/ |title=A building blessed with tech success |website=[[CNET]] |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] |accessdate=July 15, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170523115134/https://www.cnet.com/news/a-building-blessed-with-tech-success/ |archive-date=May 23, 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref> The next year, Google began selling advertisements associated with search keywords against Page and Brin's initial opposition toward an advertising-funded search engine.<ref>{{Cite book |url=https://books.google.com/?id=xOk3EIUW9VgC&printsec=frontcover |title=Planet Google: One Company's Audacious Plan to Organize Everything We Know |last=Stross |first=Randall |date=September 2008 |publisher=Free Press |isbn=978-1-4165-4691-7 |location=New York |pages=3\u20134 |chapter=Introduction |accessdate=February 14, 2010 |chapterurl=https://books.google.com/?id=xOk3EIUW9VgC&printsec=frontcover}}</ref><ref name=\"milestones\" /> To maintain an uncluttered page design, advertisements were solely text-based.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.google.com/press/pressrel/pressrelease39.html |title=Google Launches Self-Service Advertising Program |date=October 23, 2000 |website=News from Google |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120401005413/http://www.google.com/press/pressrel/pressrelease39.html |archivedate=April 1, 2012 |accessdate=July 15, 2017}}</ref> In June 2000, it was announced that Google would become the default search engine provider for [[Yahoo!]], one of the most popular websites at the time, replacing [[Inktomi]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2000/jul/02/searchengines.columnists |title=Why's Yahoo gone to Google? Search me |last=Naughton |first=John |date=July 2, 2000 |via=www.theguardian.com |access-date=January 30, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190131040317/https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2000/jul/02/searchengines.columnists |archive-date=January 31, 2019 |url-status=live|newspaper=The Guardian }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://googlepress.blogspot.com/2000/06/yahoo-selects-google-as-its-default.html |title=Yahoo! Selects Google as its Default Search Engine Provider \u2013 News announcements \u2013 News from Google \u2013 Google |website=googlepress.blogspot.com |access-date=January 30, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190131041155/https://googlepress.blogspot.com/2000/06/yahoo-selects-google-as-its-default.html |archive-date=January 31, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Google\u2019s First Production Server.jpg|upright|thumb|Google's first production server.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.computerhistory.org/collections/accession/102662167 |title=Google Server Assembly |website=Computer History Museum |accessdate=July 4, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100722083804/http://www.computerhistory.org/collections/accession/102662167 |archive-date=July 22, 2010 |url-status=live}}</ref>|alt=Google's first servers, showing lots of exposed wiring and circuit boards]]\nIn 2003, after outgrowing two other locations, the company leased an office complex from [[Silicon Graphics]], at 1600 Amphitheatre Parkway in [[Mountain View, California]].<ref name=\"sgibldg\">{{Cite news |url=http://news.cnet.com/Googles-movin-on-up/2110-1032_3-1025111.html |title=Google's movin' on up |last=Olsen |first=Stephanie |date=July 11, 2003 |work=[[CNET]] |accessdate=February 15, 2010 |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6BYbYuLmq?url=http://news.cnet.com/Googles-movin-on-up/2110-1032_3-1025111.html |archive-date=October 20, 2012 |url-status=live}}</ref> The complex became known as the [[Googleplex]], a play on the word [[googolplex]], the number one followed by a googol zeroes. Three years later, Google bought the property from SGI for $319&nbsp;million.<ref name=\"googleplexpurchase\">{{Cite news |url=http://sanjose.bizjournals.com/sanjose/stories/2006/06/19/newscolumn3.html |title=Google to buy headquarters building from Silicon Graphics |date=June 16, 2006 |newspaper=Silicon Valley / San Jose Business Journal |accessdate=February 15, 2010 |publisher=American City Business Journals |location=San Jose |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100418071152/http://sanjose.bizjournals.com/sanjose/stories/2006/06/19/newscolumn3.html |archive-date=April 18, 2010 |url-status=live}}</ref> By that time, the name \"Google\" had found its way into everyday language, causing the verb \"[[google (verb)|google]]\" to be added to the ''[[Merriam-Webster Collegiate Dictionary]]'' and the ''[[Oxford English Dictionary]]'', denoted as: \"to use the Google search engine to obtain information on the Internet\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://googleblog.blogspot.com/2006/10/do-you-google.html |title=Do You \"Google\"? |last=Krantz |first=Michael |date=October 25, 2006 |website=Google, Inc. |accessdate=February 17, 2010 |archive-url=https://archive.today/20120530/http://googleblog.blogspot.com/2006/10/do-you-google.html |archive-date=May 30, 2012 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://msnbc.msn.com/id/13720643/ |title=To Google or Not to Google |last=Bylund |first=Anders |date=July 5, 2006 |website=msnbc.com |archiveurl=https://archive.today/20060707062623/http://msnbc.msn.com/id/13720643/ |archivedate=July 7, 2006 |url-status=dead |accessdate=February 17, 2010}}</ref> Additionally, in 2001 Google's Investors felt the need to have a strong internal management, and they agreed to hire [[Eric Schmidt]] as the Chairman and CEO of Google <ref name=\"Google Inc\">{{cite web |url=https://www.britannica.com/topic/Google-Inc |title=Google Inc. |last=Hosch |first=William L. |last2=Hall |first2=Mark |website=Britannica |publisher=Britannica |accessdate=March 17, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190220013941/https://www.britannica.com/topic/Google-Inc |archive-date=February 20, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== Initial public offering ===\nGoogle's [[initial public offering]] (IPO) took place five years later, on August 19, 2004. At that time Larry Page, Sergey Brin, and Eric Schmidt agreed to work together at Google for 20 years, until the year 2024.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://money.cnn.com/2008/01/18/news/companies/google.fortune/index.htm |title=Google wins again |date=January 29, 2008 |newspaper=Fortune |publisher=Time Warner |accessdate=January 22, 2011 |first=Adam |last=Lashinsky |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6BYbNOfxM?url=http://money.cnn.com/2008/01/18/news/companies/google.fortune/index.htm |archive-date=October 20, 2012 |url-status=live}}</ref> At IPO, the company offered 19,605,052 shares at a price of $85 per share.<ref name=\"IPO\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.businessweek.com/technology/content/aug2004/tc20040819_6843_tc120.htm |title=Google: Whiz Kids or Naughty Boys? |last=Elgin |first=Ben |date=August 19, 2004 |newspaper=BusinessWeek |publisher=[[Bloomberg L.P.]] |accessdate=February 19, 2010 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5hT7Hw63l?url=http://www.businessweek.com/technology/content/aug2004/tc20040819_6843_tc120.htm |archivedate=June 12, 2009 |url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{cite web |url=http://investor.google.com/pdf/2004_AnnualReport.pdf |title=2004 Annual Report |year=2004 |website=Google, Inc. |page=29 |accessdate=February 19, 2010 |location=Mountain View, California |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/659XUbJTj?url=http://investor.google.com/pdf/2004_AnnualReport.pdf |archive-date=February 2, 2012 |url-status=live}}</ref> Shares were sold in an online auction format using a system built by [[Morgan Stanley]] and [[Credit Suisse]], underwriters for the deal.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://money.cnn.com/2004/04/29/technology/google/ |title=Google sets $2.7&nbsp;billion IPO |last=La Monica |first=Paul R. |date=April 30, 2004 |work=CNN Money |accessdate=February 19, 2010 |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6BYbWCwIQ?url=http://money.cnn.com/2004/04/29/technology/google/ |archive-date=October 20, 2012 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.zdnet.com/news/want-in-on-googles-ipo/135799 |title=Want In on Google's IPO? |last=Kawamoto |first=Dawn |date=April 29, 2004 |website=ZDNet |accessdate=February 19, 2010 |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/659XV2yME?url=http://www.zdnet.com/news/want-in-on-googles-ipo/135799 |archive-date=February 2, 2012 |url-status=live}}</ref> The sale of $1.67 billion gave Google a [[market capitalization]] of more than $23 billion.<ref name=\"washpost\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/articles/A14939-2004Aug19.html |title=Google's IPO: Grate Expectations |last=Webb |first=Cynthia L. |newspaper=The Washington Post |accessdate=February 19, 2010 |location=Washington, D.C. |date=August 19, 2004 |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6BYbWsL9b?url=http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/articles/A14939-2004Aug19.html |archive-date=October 20, 2012 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Eric Schmidt at the 37th G8 Summit in Deauville 037.jpg|thumb|upright|left|[[Eric Schmidt]]]]\nIn October 2006, Google announced that it had acquired the video-sharing site YouTube for $1.65&nbsp;billion in Google stock,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://techcrunch.com/2006/10/09/google-has-acquired-youtube/ |title=Google Has Acquired YouTube |last=Arrington |first=Michael |date=October 9, 2006 |website=[[TechCrunch]] |publisher=[[AOL]] |accessdate=March 15, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170316024815/https://techcrunch.com/2006/10/09/google-has-acquired-youtube/ |archive-date=March 16, 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/10/09/business/09cnd-deal.html |title=Google to Acquire YouTube for $1.65 Billion |last=Sorkin |first=Andrew Ross |last2=Peters |first2=Jeremy W. |date=October 9, 2006 |website=[[The New York Times]] |accessdate=March 15, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170609080519/http://www.nytimes.com/2006/10/09/business/09cnd-deal.html |archive-date=June 9, 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref> and the deal was finalized on November 13, 2006.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://techcrunch.com/2006/11/13/google-closes-youtube-acquisition/ |title=Google Closes YouTube Acquisition |last=Arrington |first=Michael |date=November 13, 2006 |website=[[TechCrunch]] |publisher=[[AOL]] |accessdate=March 15, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170316024500/https://techcrunch.com/2006/11/13/google-closes-youtube-acquisition/ |archive-date=March 16, 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-google-idUSWEN973120061114 |title=Google closes YouTube deal |last=Auchard |first=Eric |date=November 14, 2006 |website=[[Reuters]] |publisher=[[Thomson Reuters]] |accessdate=March 15, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170316113147/http://www.reuters.com/article/us-google-idUSWEN973120061114 |archive-date=March 16, 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref> On April 13, 2007, Google reached an agreement to acquire [[DoubleClick]] for $3.1&nbsp;billion, transferring to Google valuable relationships that DoubleClick had with Web publishers and advertising agencies.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2007/04/14/technology/14DoubleClick.html |title=Google Buys DoubleClick for $3.1 Billion |last=Story |first=Louise |last2=Helft |first2=Miguel |date=April 14, 2007 |website=[[The New York Times]] |accessdate=March 9, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170404014741/http://www.nytimes.com/2007/04/14/technology/14DoubleClick.html |archive-date=April 4, 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn 2005, ''[[The Washington Post]]'' reported on a 700 percent increase in third-quarter profit for Google, largely thanks to large companies shifting their advertising strategies from newspapers, magazines, and television to the Internet.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2005/10/20/AR2005102002058.html |title=Online Ads Give Google Huge Gain in Profit |last=Vise |first=David |date=October 21, 2005 |work=[[The Washington Post]] |accessdate=November 27, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161020134416/http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2005/10/20/AR2005102002058.html |archive-date=October 20, 2016 |url-status=live}}</ref> In May 2011, the number of monthly unique visitors to Google surpassed one billion for the first time.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://itsalltech.com/2011/06/22/googles-new-record-1-billion-visitors-in-may/ |title=Google's new record, 1 billion visitors in May |author=Ben |date=June 2, 2011 |website=It's All Tech |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130116035631/http://itsalltech.com/2011/06/22/googles-new-record-1-billion-visitors-in-may/ |archivedate=January 16, 2013 |accessdate=November 30, 2016}}</ref> By 2011, Google was handling approximately 3 billion searches per day. To handle this workload, Google built 11 [[data centers]] around the world with some several thousand servers in each. These data centers allowed Google to handle the ever changing workload more efficiently.<ref name=\"Google Inc\"/>\n\nOn August 15, 2011, Google made its largest-ever acquisition to date when it announced that it would acquire [[Motorola Mobility]] for $12.5&nbsp;billion<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/faster-forward/post/google-agrees-to-acquire-motorola-mobility/2011/08/15/gIQABmTkGJ_blog.html |title=Google agrees to acquire Motorola Mobility |author=Tsukayama, Hayley |date=August 15, 2011 |work=The Washington Post |accessdate=August 17, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121113035358/http://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/faster-forward/post/google-agrees-to-acquire-motorola-mobility/2011/08/15/gIQABmTkGJ_blog.html |archive-date=November 13, 2012 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://investor.google.com/releases/2011/0815.html |title=Google to Acquire Motorola Mobility&nbsp;\u2014 Google Investor Relations |website=Google |accessdate=August 17, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110817101741/http://investor.google.com/releases/2011/0815.html |archive-date=August 17, 2011 |url-status=live}}</ref> This purchase was made in part to help Google gain Motorola's considerable patent portfolio on mobile phones and wireless technologies, to help protect Google in its ongoing patent disputes with other companies,<ref name=\"supercharging android\">{{cite web|url=http://googleblog.blogspot.com/2011/08/supercharging-android-google-to-acquire.html|title=Official Google Blog: Supercharging Android: Google to Acquire Motorola Mobility|last=Page|first=Larry|authorlink=Larry Page|date=2011-08-15|website=Official Google Blog|url-status=live|archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/69UHjJzgs?url=http://googleblog.blogspot.com/2011/08/supercharging-android-google-to-acquire.html|archive-date=2012-07-28|accessdate=2011-08-17}}</ref> mainly [[Apple Inc.|Apple]] and [[Microsoft]],<ref name=\"appleinsider1\">{{cite web |url=http://www.appleinsider.com/articles/11/08/15/google_ceo_anticompetitive_apple_microsoft_forced_motorola_deal.html |title=Google CEO: 'Anticompetitive' Apple, Microsoft forced Motorola deal |last=Hughes |first=Neil |website=AppleInsider |accessdate=August 17, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111210181127/http://www.appleinsider.com/articles/11/08/15/google_ceo_anticompetitive_apple_microsoft_forced_motorola_deal.html |archive-date=December 10, 2011 |url-status=live}}</ref> and to allow it to continue to freely offer [[Android (operating system)|Android]].<ref name=\"cnet\">{{cite web |url=http://news.cnet.com/8301-1035_3-20092362-94/google-to-buy-motorola-mobility-for-$12.5b/ |title=Google to buy Motorola Mobility for $12.5B |last=Cheng |first=Roger |date=August 15, 2011 |website=CNet News |access-date=August 15, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111006062539/http://news.cnet.com/8301-1035_3-20092362-94/google-to-buy-motorola-mobility-for-$12.5b/ |archive-date=October 6, 2011 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== 2012 onward ===\nThe year 2012 was the first time that Google generated $50 billion in annual revenue, generating $38 billion the previous year. In January 2013, then-CEO Larry Page commented, \"We ended 2012 with a strong quarter ... Revenues were up 36% year-on-year, and 8% quarter-on-quarter. And we hit $50 billion in revenues for the first time last year \u2013 not a bad achievement in just a decade and a half.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://mashable.com/2013/01/22/google-q4-earnings/#42cbeRCbSkqH |title=Google Has Its First $50 Billion Year |last=Fiegerman |first=Seth |date=January 22, 2013 |website=[[Mashable]] |accessdate=November 30, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161201014741/http://mashable.com/2013/01/22/google-q4-earnings/#42cbeRCbSkqH |archive-date=December 1, 2016 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2013, Google acquired [[Waze]], a $966 million deal.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.cnet.com/news/google-reveals-it-spent-966-million-in-waze-acquisition/ |title=Google reveals it spent $966 million in Waze acquisition |last=Kerr |first=Dara |date=July 25, 2013 |website=[[CNET]] |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] |accessdate=June 12, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170216011658/https://www.cnet.com/news/google-reveals-it-spent-966-million-in-waze-acquisition/ |archive-date=February 16, 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref> While Waze would remain an independent entity, its social features, such as its crowdsourced location platform, were reportedly valuable integrations between Waze and [[Google Maps]], Google's own mapping service.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://techcrunch.com/2013/06/11/its-official-google-buys-waze-giving-a-social-data-boost-to-its-location-and-mapping-business/ |title=Google Bought Waze For $1.1B, Giving A Social Data Boost To Its Mapping Business |last=Lunden |first=Ingrid |date=June 11, 2013 |website=[[TechCrunch]] |publisher=[[AOL]] |accessdate=June 12, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170706051802/https://techcrunch.com/2013/06/11/its-official-google-buys-waze-giving-a-social-data-boost-to-its-location-and-mapping-business/ |archive-date=July 6, 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nGoogle announced the launch of a new company, called [[Calico (company)|Calico]], on September 19, 2013, to be led by [[Apple Inc.]] chairman [[Arthur D. Levinson|Arthur Levinson]]. In the official public statement, Page explained that the \"health and well-being\" company would focus on \"the challenge of ageing and associated diseases\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/technology-24158924|title=Google spin-off Calico to search for answers to ageing|last=Wakefield|first=Jane|date=September 19, 2013|work=BBC News|accessdate=September 20, 2013|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130919201510/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/technology-24158924|archive-date=September 19, 2013}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Google-Deep Mind headquarters in London, 6 Pancras Square.jpg|thumb|upright|Entrance of building where Google and its subsidiary Deep Mind are located at 6 Pancras Square, London|alt=]]\nOn January 26, 2014, Google announced it had agreed to acquire [[DeepMind Technologies]], a privately held artificial intelligence company from [[London]].<ref name=\"Chowdhry-DeepMind\">{{cite news |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/amitchowdhry/2014/01/27/google-to-acquire-artificial-intelligence-company-deepmind/ |title=Google To Acquire Artificial Intelligence Company DeepMind |last=Chowdhry |first=Amit |date=January 27, 2014 |newspaper=Forbes |accessdate=January 27, 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140129142153/http://www.forbes.com/sites/amitchowdhry/2014/01/27/google-to-acquire-artificial-intelligence-company-deepmind/ |archive-date=January 29, 2014 |url-status=live}}</ref> Technology news website ''[[Recode]]'' reported that the company was purchased for $400 million though it was not disclosed where the information came from. A Google spokesman would not comment of the price.<ref name=\"Helgren- DeepMind\">{{cite news |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2014/01/27/us-google-deepmind-idUSBREA0Q03220140127 |title=Google to buy artificial intelligence company DeepMind |last=Helgren |first=Chris |date=January 27, 2014 |newspaper=Reuters |accessdate=January 27, 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140127042513/http://www.reuters.com/article/2014/01/27/us-google-deepmind-idUSBREA0Q03220140127 |archive-date=January 27, 2014 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"Ribeiro- DeepMind\">{{cite news |url=http://www.pcworld.com/article/2091500/google-acquires-artificial-intelligence-company-deepmind.html |title=Google buys artificial intelligence company DeepMind |last=Ribeiro |first=Jon |date=January 27, 2014 |newspaper=PC World |accessdate=January 27, 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140130042946/http://www.pcworld.com/article/2091500/google-acquires-artificial-intelligence-company-deepmind.html |archive-date=January 30, 2014 |url-status=live}}</ref> The purchase of DeepMind aids in Google's recent growth in the artificial intelligence and robotics community.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theverge.com/2014/1/26/5348640/google-deepmind-acquisition-robotics-ai |title=Google buying AI startup DeepMind for a reported $400 million |last=Opam |first=Kwame |date=January 26, 2014 |website=[[The Verge]] |publisher=[[Vox Media]] |accessdate=March 9, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170708161602/https://www.theverge.com/2014/1/26/5348640/google-deepmind-acquisition-robotics-ai |archive-date=July 8, 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nAccording to [[Interbrand]]'s annual Best Global Brands report, Google has been the second most valuable brand in the world (behind [[Apple Inc.]]) in 2013,<ref>{{cite web |title=Rankings - 2013 - Best Global Brands - Interbrand |url=http://interbrand.com/best-brands/best-global-brands/2013/ranking/#?listFormat=ls |website=Interbrand |accessdate=October 23, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161022013506/http://interbrand.com/best-brands/best-global-brands/2013/ranking/#?listFormat=ls |archive-date=October 22, 2016 |url-status=live}}</ref> 2014,<ref>{{cite web |title=Rankings - 2014 - Best Global Brands - Interbrand |url=http://interbrand.com/best-brands/best-global-brands/2014/ranking/#?listFormat=ls |website=Interbrand |accessdate=October 23, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161103140119/http://interbrand.com/best-brands/best-global-brands/2014/ranking/#?listFormat=ls |archive-date=November 3, 2016 |url-status=live}}</ref> 2015,<ref>{{cite web |title=Rankings - 2015 - Best Global Brands - Interbrand |url=http://interbrand.com/best-brands/best-global-brands/2015/ranking/#?listFormat=ls |website=Interbrand |accessdate=October 23, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161021100708/http://interbrand.com/best-brands/best-global-brands/2015/ranking/#?listFormat=ls |archive-date=October 21, 2016 |url-status=live}}</ref> and 2016, with a valuation of $133 billion.<ref>{{cite web |title=Rankings - 2016 - Best Global Brands |url=http://interbrand.com/best-brands/best-global-brands/2016/ranking/#?listFormat=ls |website=Interbrand |accessdate=October 23, 2016 |archive-url=https://archive.today/20161220191226/http://interbrand.com/best-brands/best-global-brands/2016/ranking/#?listFormat=ls |archive-date=December 20, 2016 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn August 10, 2015, Google announced plans to reorganize its various interests as a [[Conglomerate (company)|conglomerate]] called [[Alphabet Inc.|Alphabet]]. Google became Alphabet's leading subsidiary, and will continue to be the umbrella company for Alphabet's Internet interests. Upon completion of the restructure, [[Sundar Pichai]] became CEO of Google, replacing [[Larry Page]], who became CEO of Alphabet.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2015-08-10/google-to-adopt-new-holding-structure-under-name-alphabet- |title=Google Rises After Creating Holding Company Called Alphabet |last=Womack |first=Brian |date=August 10, 2015 |publisher=[[Bloomberg L.P.]] |accessdate=November 22, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161123054841/https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2015-08-10/google-to-adopt-new-holding-structure-under-name-alphabet- |archive-date=November 23, 2016 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/google-creates-new-company-alphabet-1439240645 |title=Google Creates Parent Company Called Alphabet in Restructuring |last=Barr |first=Alistair |last2=Winkler |first2=Rolf |date=August 10, 2015 |newspaper=[[The Wall Street Journal]] |accessdate=November 22, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161128112043/http://www.wsj.com/articles/google-creates-new-company-alphabet-1439240645 |archive-date=November 28, 2016 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/08/11/technology/google-alphabet-restructuring.html |title=Google to Reorganize as Alphabet to Keep Its Lead as an Innovator |last=Dougherty |first=Conor |date=August 10, 2015 |website=[[The New York Times]] |accessdate=November 22, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161019164806/http://www.nytimes.com/2015/08/11/technology/google-alphabet-restructuring.html |archive-date=October 19, 2016 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n{{As of|2016|10|post=,}} Google operates 70 offices in more than 40 countries.<ref>{{cite web |title=Google locations |url=https://www.google.com/about/company/facts/locations/ |website=Google, Inc. |accessdate=October 23, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130815024220/https://www.google.com/about/company/facts/locations/ |archive-date=August 15, 2013 |url-status=live}}</ref> [[Alexa Internet|Alexa]], a company that monitors commercial web traffic, lists Google.com as the most visited website in the world.<ref name=\"Alexa\">{{cite web |title=google.com Traffic Statistics |url=http://www.alexa.com/siteinfo/google.com |website=[[Alexa Internet]] |date=November 25, 2016 |accessdate=November 27, 2016 |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/659XN975m?url=http://www.alexa.com/siteinfo/google.com |archive-date=February 2, 2012 |url-status=live}}</ref> Several other Google services also figure in the top 100 most visited websites, including YouTube<ref>{{cite web |title=youtube.com Traffic Statistics |url=http://www.alexa.com/siteinfo/youtube.com |website=[[Alexa Internet]] |date=November 25, 2016 |accessdate=November 27, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161127004253/http://www.alexa.com/siteinfo/youtube.com |archive-date=November 27, 2016 |url-status=live}}</ref> and Blogger.<ref>{{cite web |title=blogger.com Traffic Statistics |url=http://www.alexa.com/siteinfo/blogger.com |website=[[Alexa Internet]] |date=November 25, 2016 |accessdate=November 27, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161112072306/http://www.alexa.com/siteinfo/blogger.com |archive-date=November 12, 2016 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn August 8, 2017, Google fired employee James Damore after he distributed a memo throughout the company which argued that bias and \"[[Google's Ideological Echo Chamber|Google's ideological echo chamber]]\" clouded their thinking about diversity and inclusion, and that it is also biological factors, not discrimination alone, that cause the average woman to be less interested than men in technical positions.<ref name=\"NYTFired\">[https://www.nytimes.com/2017/08/07/business/google-women-engineer-fired-memo.html \"Google Fires Engineer Who Wrote Memo Questioning Women in Tech\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170810185646/https://www.nytimes.com/2017/08/07/business/google-women-engineer-fired-memo.html |date=August 10, 2017 }}. ''[[The New York Times]]'', August 7, 2017</ref> Google CEO Sundar Pichai accused Damore in violating company policy by \"advancing harmful gender stereotypes in our workplace\", and he was fired on the same day.<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/2017/08/08/technology/google-engineer-fired-gender-memo.html Contentious Memo Strikes Nerve Inside Google and Out] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170809012140/https://www.nytimes.com/2017/08/08/technology/google-engineer-fired-gender-memo.html |date=August 9, 2017 }}. ''[[The New York Times]]'', August 8, 2017</ref><ref>diversitymemo.com</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theatlantic.com/politics/archive/2017/08/the-most-common-error-in-coverage-of-the-google-memo/536181/ |title=The Most Common Error in Media Coverage of the Google Memo |last=Friedersdorf |first=Conor |access-date=August 9, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170808230220/https://www.theatlantic.com/politics/archive/2017/08/the-most-common-error-in-coverage-of-the-google-memo/536181/ |archive-date=August 8, 2017 |url-status=live|date=August 8, 2017 }}</ref> ''New York Times'' columnist [[David Brooks (political commentator)|David Brooks]] argued Pichai had mishandled the case, and called for his resignation.<ref name=\"BrooksNYT\">{{cite web |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/08/11/opinion/sundar-pichai-google-memo-diversity.html |title=Sundar Pichai Should Resign as Google's C.E.O |last=Brooks |first=David |date=August 11, 2017 |website=The New York Times |url-access=limited |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170811124216/https://www.nytimes.com/2017/08/11/opinion/sundar-pichai-google-memo-diversity.html |archivedate=August 11, 2017 |url-status=live |accessdate=August 11, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.businessinsider.com/david-brooks-sundar-pichai-resignation-james-damore-2017-8 |title=New York Times columnist David Brooks wants Google's CEO to resign |website=Business Insider |language=en |archiveurl=https://archive.today/20170812131604/http://www.businessinsider.com/david-brooks-sundar-pichai-resignation-james-damore-2017-8 |archivedate=August 12, 2017 |url-status=live |access-date=August 12, 2017|date=August 11, 2017 }}</ref>\n\nBetween 2018 and 2019, [[Google worker organization|tensions between the company's leadership and its workers escalated]] as staff protested company decisions on internal sexual harassment, [[Dragonfly (search engine)|a censored Chinese search engine]], and [[Project Maven|a military drone artificial intelligence]], which had been seen as areas of revenue growth for the company.<ref name=\"Bloomberg 2019-11-22\">{{Cite news |last1=Bergen |first1=Mark |title=Google Workers Protest Company's 'Brute Force Intimidation' |work=[[Bloomberg.com]] |date=2019-11-22 |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2019-11-22/google-workers-protest-company-s-brute-force-intimidation |language=en |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref name=\"Verge busting\">{{Cite web |last1=Hollister |first1=Sean |title=Google is accused of union busting after firing four employees |work=[[The Verge]] |date=2019-11-25 |url=https://www.theverge.com/2019/11/25/20983053/google-fires-four-employees-memo-rebecca-rivers-laurence-berland-union-busting-accusation-walkout |language=en |accessdate=2019-11-26 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> On October 25, 2018, ''[[The New York Times]]'' published the ''expos\u00e9'', \"How Google Protected [[Andy Rubin]], the \u2018Father of Android\u2019\". The company subsequently announced that \"48 employees have been fired over the last two years\" for sexual misconduct.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theverge.com/2018/10/25/18024486/google-sexual-harassment-people-fired-rubin-2-years-ceo |title=Google says 48 people have been fired for sexual harassment in the last two years |last=Welch |first=Chris |date=October 25, 2018 |accessdate=October 31, 2018 |website=The Verge |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181031133020/https://www.theverge.com/2018/10/25/18024486/google-sexual-harassment-people-fired-rubin-2-years-ceo |archive-date=October 31, 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref> On November 1, 2018, more than 20,000 Google employees and contractors staged a global walk-out to protest the company's handling of sexual harassment complaints.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.businessinsider.com/google-walkout-live-pictures-of-protesting-google-workers-2018-11 |title=PHOTOS: Google employees all over the world left their desk and walked out in protest over sexual misconduct |last=Hamilton |first=Isobel Asher |date=November 1, 2018 |accessdate=November 6, 2018 |website=Business Insider |display-authors=etal |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181102174328/https://www.businessinsider.com/google-walkout-live-pictures-of-protesting-google-workers-2018-11 |archive-date=November 2, 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://fortune.com/2018/11/03/google-employees-walkout-demands/ |title=More Than 20,000 Google Employees Participated in Walkout Over Sexual Harassment Policy |last=Segarra |first=Lisa Marie |date=November 3, 2018 |accessdate=November 6, 2018 |publisher=Fortune |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181107013331/http://fortune.com/2018/11/03/google-employees-walkout-demands/ |archive-date=November 7, 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref> Later in 2019, some workers accused the company of retaliating against internal activists.{{r|Verge busting}}\n\nOn March 19, 2019, Google announced that it would enter the video game market, launching a [[cloud gaming]] platform called [[Google Stadia|Stadia]].<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nOn June 3, 2019, the [[United States Department of Justice]] reported that it would investigate Google for [[antitrust]] violations.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theregister.co.uk/2019/06/03/google_shares_take_a_dive_on_doj_reports/|title=Google shares take a dive with reports of US DoJ 'competition' probe}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2019, it was reported that former [[PayPal]] [[Chief Operating Officer]] Bill Ready would become Google's new commerce chief. Ready's role won't be directly involved with [[Google Pay]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://social.techcrunch.com/2019/12/11/paypals-exiting-coo-bill-ready-to-join-google-as-its-new-president-of-commerce/|title=PayPal's exiting COO Bill Ready to join Google as its new president of Commerce|website=TechCrunch|language=en-US|access-date=2019-12-11}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2020, it was reported that Google announced several cost-cutting measures as a response to the economic impact of the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]]. Such measures included slowing down hiring for the remainder of 2020, except for of a small number of strategic areas, recalibrating the focus and pace of investments in areas like data centers and machines, and non-business essential marketing and travel. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/tosv2.html?vid=&uuid=1024b270-7fb5-11ea-a60a-233b89b5eced&url=L25ld3MvYXJ0aWNsZXMvMjAyMC0wNC0xNS9nb29nbGUtdG8tc2xvdy1oaXJpbmctZm9yLXJlc3Qtb2YtMjAyMC1jZW8tcGljaGFpLXRlbGxzLXN0YWZm|title=Bloomberg - Google to Slow Hiring for Rest of 2020, CEO Tells Staff|last=|first=|date=2020-04-15|website=www.bloomberg.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref>\n\n== Products and services ==\n{{Main|List of Google products}}\n\n=== Search engine ===\n{{Main|Google Search|Google Images}}\n[[File:Google Homepage.svg|alt=|left|thumb|Google Search homepage {{as of|2020|03|df=US|lc=y}}]]\nGoogle [[search engine indexing|indexes]] billions of web pages to allow users to search for the information they desire through the use of keywords and [[Operator (computer programming)|operators]].<ref>{{cite web |first=Michael |last=Arrington |title=Google's Misleading Blog Post: The Size Of The Web And The Size Of Their Index Are Very Different |url=https://techcrunch.com/2008/07/25/googles-misleading-blog-post-on-the-size-of-the-web/ |website=[[TechCrunch]] |publisher=[[AOL]] |date=July 25, 2008 |accessdate=March 9, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170312042335/https://techcrunch.com/2008/07/25/googles-misleading-blog-post-on-the-size-of-the-web/ |archive-date=March 12, 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref> According to [[comScore]] market research from November 2009, [[Google Search]] is the dominant search engine in the United States market, with a [[market share]] of 65.6%.<ref name=\"comscore\">{{Cite news |date=December 16, 2006 |title=comScore Releases November 2009 U.S. Search Engine Rankings |url=http://www.comscore.com/Press_Events/Press_Releases/2009/12/comScore_Releases_November_2009_U.S._Search_Engine_Rankings |accessdate=July 5, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100225142724/http://www.comscore.com/Press_Events/Press_Releases/2009/12/comScore_Releases_November_2009_U.S._Search_Engine_Rankings |archive-date=February 25, 2010 |url-status=live}}</ref> In May 2017, Google enabled a new \"Personal\" tab in Google Search, letting users search for content in their Google accounts' various services, including email messages from [[Gmail]] and photos from [[Google Photos]].<ref>{{cite web |first=Barry |last=Schwartz |title=Google Adds Personal Tab To Search Filters |url=https://www.seroundtable.com/google-personal-tab-search-23912.html |website=Search Engine Roundtable |publisher=RustyBrick |date=May 26, 2017 |accessdate=May 27, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170527140309/https://www.seroundtable.com/google-personal-tab-search-23912.html |archive-date=May 27, 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first=Chaim |last=Gartenberg |title=Google adds new Personal tab to search results to show Gmail and Photos content |url=https://www.theverge.com/2017/5/26/15701778/google-personal-tab-search-results-gmail-photos-images-maps-news-filter |website=[[The Verge]] |publisher=[[Vox Media]] |date=May 26, 2017 |accessdate=May 27, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170526215945/https://www.theverge.com/2017/5/26/15701778/google-personal-tab-search-results-gmail-photos-images-maps-news-filter |archive-date=May 26, 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nGoogle launched its [[Google News]] service in 2002, an automated service which summarizes news articles from various websites.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.time.com/time/business/article/0,8599,356152,00.html |title=Automatic for the People |last=Macht |first=Joshua |date=September 30, 2002 |work=Time |access-date=June 7, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101022094519/http://www.time.com/time/business/article/0,8599,356152,00.html |archive-date=October 22, 2010 |url-status=live}}</ref> Google also hosts [[Google Books]], a service which searches the text found in books in its database and shows limited previews or and the full book where allowed.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.infoworld.com/t/platforms/google-hit-second-lawsuit-over-library-project-722 |title=Google hit with second lawsuit over Library project |last=Martin |first=China |date=November 26, 2007 |publisher=[[InfoWorld]] |access-date=July 5, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110510022853/http://www.infoworld.com/t/platforms/google-hit-second-lawsuit-over-library-project-722 |archive-date=May 10, 2011 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== Advertising ===\n[[File:Ad-tech London 2010 (2).JPG|thumb|Google on ad-tech London, 2010]]\n\nAs per its 2017 Annual report, Google generates most of its revenues from advertising. This includes sales of apps, purchases made in-app, digital content products on google and YouTube, android and licensing and service fees, including fees received for Google Cloud offerings. 46% of this was from clicks (cost per clicks), amounting to US$109,652 million in 2017. This includes three principal methods, namely [[AdMob]], [[AdSense]] (such as AdSense for Content, [[AdSense]] for Search, etc.) and DoubleClick AdExchange.<ref name=\"agm2017\">{{cite book |title=Annualg report (Alphabet Inc.) - 2017 |date=March 1, 2018 |publisher=Alphabet Inc. Investor relations |url=https://abc.xyz/investor |accessdate=December 3, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160203091612/https://abc.xyz/investor/ |archive-date=February 3, 2016 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nFor the 2006 fiscal year, the company reported $10.492 billion in total advertising revenues and only $112 million in licensing and other revenues.<ref name=\"10-K\">{{cite web |url=https://www.sec.gov/Archives/edgar/data/1288776/000119312507044494/d10k.htm |title=Form 10-K{{nbsp}}\u2013 Annual Report |accessdate=July 5, 2010 |publisher=SEC |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101106152355/http://www.sec.gov/Archives/edgar/data/1288776/000119312507044494/d10k.htm |archive-date=November 6, 2010 |url-status=live}}</ref> In 2011, 96% of Google's revenue was derived from its advertising programs.<ref name=\"Google-Inc-Jan-2012-10-K\">{{cite web |url=http://pdf.secdatabase.com/44/0001193125-12-025336.pdf |title=Google Inc, Form 10-K, Annual Report, Filing Date January 26, 2012 |publisher=secdatabase.com |accessdate=March 8, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130502193637/http://pdf.secdatabase.com/44/0001193125-12-025336.pdf |archive-date=May 2, 2013 |url-status=live}}</ref> In addition to its own algorithms for understanding search requests, Google uses technology from the company [[DoubleClick]], to project user interest and target advertising to the search context and the user history.<ref>{{Cite news |author=Nakashima, Ellen |title=Some Web Firms Say They Track Behavior Without Explicit Consent |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2008/08/11/AR2008081102270_pf.html |date=August 12, 2008 |work=The Washington Post |accessdate=July 5, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121112172756/http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2008/08/11/AR2008081102270_pf.html |archive-date=November 12, 2012 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first=Miguel |last=Helft |title=Google to Offer Ads Based on Interests |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/03/11/technology/internet/11google.html |website=[[The New York Times]] |date=March 11, 2009 |accessdate=March 9, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170328214358/http://www.nytimes.com/2009/03/11/technology/internet/11google.html |archive-date=March 28, 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn 2007, Google launched \"[[AdSense for Mobile]]\", taking advantage of the emerging mobile advertising market.<ref name=\"adsense_mobile\">{{cite web |url=https://www.google.com/intl/en/press/annc/20070917_mobileads.html |title=Google AdSense for Mobile unlocks the potential of the mobile advertising market |date=September 17, 2007 |website=Google, Inc. |accessdate=February 26, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120620042233/https://www.google.com/intl/en/press/annc/20070917_mobileads.html |archive-date=June 20, 2012 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n[[Google Analytics]] allows website owners to track where and how people use their website, for example by examining click rates for all the links on a page.<ref>{{cite web |first=Peter |last=Bright |title=Surfing on the sly with IE8's new \"InPrivate\" Internet |url=https://arstechnica.com/information-technology/2008/08/surfing-on-the-sly-ie8s-inprivate-internet/ |website=[[Ars Technica]] |publisher=[[Cond\u00e9 Nast]] |date=August 27, 2008 |accessdate=March 9, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170312040931/https://arstechnica.com/information-technology/2008/08/surfing-on-the-sly-ie8s-inprivate-internet/ |archive-date=March 12, 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref> Google advertisements can be placed on third-party websites in a two-part program. [[Google Ads]] allows advertisers to display their advertisements in the Google content network, through a cost-per-click scheme.<ref>{{cite web |first=Vangie |last=Beal |title=AdWords - Google AdWords |url=http://www.webopedia.com/TERM/A/adwords.html |website=Webopedia |publisher=QuinStreet Inc. |accessdate=May 27, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170629163240/http://www.webopedia.com/TERM/A/adwords.html |archive-date=June 29, 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref> The sister service, Google [[AdSense]], allows website owners to display these advertisements on their website and earn money every time ads are clicked.<ref>{{cite web |first=Vangie |last=Beal |title=AdSense - Google AdSense |url=http://www.webopedia.com/TERM/A/adsense.html |website=Webopedia |publisher=QuinStreet Inc. |accessdate=May 27, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170502044751/http://www.webopedia.com/TERM/A/adsense.html |archive-date=May 2, 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref> One of the criticisms of this program is the possibility of [[click fraud]], which occurs when a person or automated script clicks on advertisements without being interested in the product, causing the advertiser to pay money to Google unduly. Industry reports in 2006 claimed that approximately 14 to 20&nbsp;percent of clicks were fraudulent or invalid.<ref>{{cite news |last=Mills |first=Elinor |url=http://news.cnet.com/Google-to-offer-advertisers-click-fraud-stats/2100-1024_3-6098469.html |title=Google to offer advertisers click fraud stats |work=news.cnet.com |publisher=[[CNET]] |date=July 25, 2006 |accessdate=July 29, 2006 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110510075216/http://news.cnet.com/Google-to-offer-advertisers-click-fraud-stats/2100-1024_3-6098469.html |archive-date=May 10, 2011 |url-status=live}}</ref> [[Google Search Console]] (rebranded from Google Webmaster Tools in May 2015) allows [[webmasters]] to check the sitemap, crawl rate, and for security issues of their websites, as well as optimize their website's visibility.\n\n=== Consumer services ===\n\n==== Web-based services ====\nGoogle offers [[Gmail]] for [[email]],<ref>{{cite web |first=Chris |last=Gayomali |title=When Gmail Launched On April 1, 2004, People Thought It Was A Joke |url=https://www.fastcompany.com/3028513/when-gmail-launched-on-april-1-2004-people-thought-it-was-a-joke |website=[[Fast Company (magazine)|Fast Company]] |publisher=Mansueto Ventures |date=April 1, 2014 |accessdate=June 12, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171018201644/https://www.fastcompany.com/3028513/when-gmail-launched-on-april-1-2004-people-thought-it-was-a-joke |archive-date=October 18, 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref> [[Google Calendar]] for time-management and scheduling,<ref>{{cite web |first=James |last=Vincent |title=Google Calendar update makes it easier to track your New Year's fitness goals |url=https://www.theverge.com/2017/1/5/14175830/google-calendar-track-fitness-goals-health-data |website=[[The Verge]] |publisher=[[Vox Media]] |date=January 5, 2017 |accessdate=June 12, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170113025213/http://www.theverge.com/2017/1/5/14175830/google-calendar-track-fitness-goals-health-data |archive-date=January 13, 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref> [[Google Maps]] for mapping, navigation and [[satellite imagery]],<ref>{{cite web |first=Mitchel |last=Broussard |title=Google Maps Introduces New Location Sharing Feature With Real-Time Friend Tracking |url=https://www.macrumors.com/2017/03/22/google-maps-location-sharing/ |website=[[MacRumors]] |date=March 22, 2017 |accessdate=June 12, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170327173708/https://www.macrumors.com/2017/03/22/google-maps-location-sharing/ |archive-date=March 27, 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref> [[Google Drive]] for [[File hosting service|cloud storage]] of files,<ref name=\"verge-drive-announced\">{{cite web |first=T.C. |last=Sottek |title=Google Drive officially launches with 5&nbsp;GB free storage, Google Docs integration |url=https://www.theverge.com/2012/4/24/2971025/google-drive-official-launch-features |website=[[The Verge]] |publisher=[[Vox Media]] |date=April 24, 2012 |accessdate=June 12, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161226161807/http://www.theverge.com/2012/4/24/2971025/google-drive-official-launch-features |archive-date=December 26, 2016 |url-status=live}}</ref> [[Google Docs]], [[Google Sheets|Sheets]] and [[Google Slides|Slides]] for productivity,<ref name=\"verge-drive-announced\" /> [[Google Photos]] for photo storage and sharing,<ref>{{cite web |first=Sarah |last=Perez |title=Google Photos Breaks Free Of Google+, Now Offers Free, Unlimited Storage |url=https://techcrunch.com/2015/05/28/google-photos-breaks-free-of-google-now-offers-free-unlimited-storage/ |website=[[TechCrunch]] |publisher=[[AOL]] |date=May 28, 2015 |accessdate=June 12, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170706135643/https://techcrunch.com/2015/05/28/google-photos-breaks-free-of-google-now-offers-free-unlimited-storage/ |archive-date=July 6, 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref> [[Google Keep]] for [[note-taking]],<ref>{{cite web |first=Dan |last=Graziano |title=Google launches Google Keep note-taking service [video] |url=http://bgr.com/2013/03/20/google-keep-annnounced-388095/ |website=[[Boy Genius Report|BGR]] |publisher=[[Penske Media Corporation]] |date=March 20, 2013 |accessdate=June 12, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161008154306/http://bgr.com/2013/03/20/google-keep-annnounced-388095/ |archive-date=October 8, 2016 |url-status=live}}</ref> [[Google Translate]] for language translation,<ref>{{cite web |first=Lisa |last=Eadicicco |title=Google's Translation App Is About To Get Much Better |url=http://time.com/4572942/google-translate-app-update-2016/ |website=[[Time (magazine)|Time]] |date=November 16, 2016 |accessdate=June 12, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170401152526/http://time.com/4572942/google-translate-app-update-2016/ |archive-date=April 1, 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref> [[YouTube]] for video viewing and sharing,<ref>{{cite web |first=Saba |last=Hamedy |title=People now spend 1 billion hours watching YouTube every day |url=http://mashable.com/2017/02/27/youtube-one-billion-hours-of-video-daily/ |website=[[Mashable]] |date=February 28, 2017 |accessdate=June 12, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170517233015/http://mashable.com/2017/02/27/youtube-one-billion-hours-of-video-daily/ |archive-date=May 17, 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref> [[Google My Business]] for managing public business information,<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.google.com/business/ |title=Google My Business \u2013 Stand Out on Google for Free |website=www.google.com |access-date=February 6, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190207151521/https://www.google.com/business/ |archive-date=February 7, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> and [[Google Duo|Duo]] for social interaction.<ref>{{cite magazine |first=Steven |last=Levy |title=Inside Google+ - How the search giant plans to go social |url=https://www.wired.com/2011/06/inside-google-plus-social/ |magazine=[[Wired (website)|Wired]] |publisher=[[Cond\u00e9 Nast]] |date=June 28, 2011 |accessdate=June 12, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170405130052/https://www.wired.com/2011/06/inside-google-plus-social/ |archive-date=April 5, 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref> In March 2019, Google unveiled a [[cloud gaming]] service named [[Google Stadia|Stadia]].<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.theverge.com/2019/3/19/18271702/google-stadia-cloud-gaming-service-announcement-gdc-2019 |title=Google unveils Stadia cloud gaming service, launches in 2019 |last=Warren |first=Tom |date=March 19, 2019 |website=The Verge |access-date=April 8, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190319173136/https://www.theverge.com/2019/3/19/18271702/google-stadia-cloud-gaming-service-announcement-gdc-2019 |archive-date=March 19, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==== Software ====\nGoogle develops the [[Android (operating system)|Android]] [[mobile operating system]],<ref>{{cite web |first=Erick |last=Schonfeld |title=Breaking: Google Announces Android and Open Handset Alliance |url=https://techcrunch.com/2007/11/05/breaking-google-announces-android-and-open-handset-alliance/ |website=[[TechCrunch]] |publisher=[[AOL]] |date=November 5, 2007 |accessdate=June 12, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170622140334/https://techcrunch.com/2007/11/05/breaking-google-announces-android-and-open-handset-alliance/ |archive-date=June 22, 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref> as well as its [[Android Wear|smartwatch]],<ref>{{cite web |first=Dante |last=D'Orazio |title=Google reveals Android Wear, an operating system for smartwatches |url=https://www.theverge.com/2014/3/18/5522226/google-reveals-android-wear-an-operating-system-designed-for |website=[[The Verge]] |publisher=[[Vox Media]] |date=March 18, 2014 |accessdate=April 4, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170210034323/http://www.theverge.com/2014/3/18/5522226/google-reveals-android-wear-an-operating-system-designed-for |archive-date=February 10, 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref> [[Android TV|television]],<ref>{{cite web |first=Josh |last=Ong |title=Google announces Android TV to bring 'voice input, user experience and content' to the living room |url=https://thenextweb.com/google/2014/06/25/android-tv-google-io-2014/ |website=The Next Web |date=June 25, 2014 |accessdate=April 4, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170313130445/https://thenextweb.com/google/2014/06/25/android-tv-google-io-2014/ |archive-date=March 13, 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref> [[Android Auto|car]],<ref>{{cite web |first=Alex |last=Wilhelm |title=Google Announces Android Auto, Promises Enabled Cars By The End Of 2014 |url=https://techcrunch.com/2014/06/25/google-announces-android-auto-promises-enabled-cars-by-end-of-2014/ |website=[[TechCrunch]] |publisher=[[AOL]] |date=June 25, 2014 |accessdate=April 4, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170622135917/https://techcrunch.com/2014/06/25/google-announces-android-auto-promises-enabled-cars-by-end-of-2014/ |archive-date=June 22, 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref> and [[Internet of things]]-enabled [[Android Things|smart devices]] variations.<ref>{{cite web |first=Jacob |last=Kastrenakes |title=Android Things is Google's new OS for smart devices |url=https://www.theverge.com/2016/12/13/13924996/android-things-announced-smart-home-iot-operating-system |website=[[The Verge]] |publisher=[[Vox Media]] |date=December 13, 2016 |accessdate=April 4, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170217131058/http://www.theverge.com/2016/12/13/13924996/android-things-announced-smart-home-iot-operating-system |archive-date=February 17, 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIt also develops the [[Google Chrome]] web browser,<ref>{{cite web |first=Sundar |last=Pichai |first2=Linus |last2=Upson |title=A fresh take on the browser |url=https://googleblog.blogspot.no/2008/09/fresh-take-on-browser.html |website=Official Google Blog |date=September 1, 2008 |accessdate=November 22, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160315022315/https://googleblog.blogspot.no/2008/09/fresh-take-on-browser.html |archive-date=March 15, 2016 |url-status=live}}</ref> and [[Chrome OS]], an operating system based on Chrome.<ref>{{cite web |first=Sundar |last=Pichai |first2=Linus |last2=Upson |title=Introducing the Google Chrome OS |url=https://googleblog.blogspot.no/2009/07/introducing-google-chrome-os.html |website=Official Google Blog |date=July 7, 2009 |accessdate=November 22, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161122222918/https://googleblog.blogspot.no/2009/07/introducing-google-chrome-os.html |archive-date=November 22, 2016 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==== Hardware ====\n[[File:Pixel 3 \u3068 Pixel 3 XL \u3092\u521d\u89e6\u3002\u672c\u4f53\u3092\u30ae\u30e5\u30c3\u3068\u63e1\u308b\u3068 Google Assistant \u304c\u7acb\u3061\u4e0a\u304c\u308b\u306e\u304c\u304a\u3082\u3057\u308d\u3044\u3002 \u30ef\u30b7\u30f3\u30c8\u30f3DC (44519013945).jpg|alt=|thumb|Google Pixel smartphones on display in a store]]\nIn January 2010, Google released [[Nexus One]], the first Android phone under its own brand, \"Nexus\".<ref>{{cite web |first=MG |last=Siegler |title=The Droid You're Looking For: Live From The Nexus One Event |url=https://techcrunch.com/2010/01/05/nexus-one-event/ |website=[[TechCrunch]] |publisher=[[AOL]] |date=January 5, 2010 |accessdate=November 22, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161123054909/https://techcrunch.com/2010/01/05/nexus-one-event/ |archive-date=November 23, 2016 |url-status=live}}</ref> It spawned a number of phones and tablets under the \"Nexus\" branding<ref>{{cite web |first=Florence |last=Ion |title=From Nexus One to Nexus 10: a brief history of Google's flagship devices |url=https://arstechnica.com/gadgets/2013/05/from-the-nexus-one-to-the-nexus-10-a-brief-history-of-nexus-devices/ |website=[[Ars Technica]] |publisher=[[Cond\u00e9 Nast]] |date=May 15, 2013 |accessdate=June 12, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170624004245/https://arstechnica.com/gadgets/2013/05/from-the-nexus-one-to-the-nexus-10-a-brief-history-of-nexus-devices/ |archive-date=June 24, 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref> until its eventual discontinuation in 2016, replaced by a new brand called [[Pixel (smartphone)|Pixel]].<ref name=\"Pixel inside story\">{{cite web |first=Dieter |last=Bohn |title=The Google Phone: The inside story of Google's bold bet on hardware |url=https://www.theverge.com/a/google-pixel-phone-new-hardware-interview-2016 |website=[[The Verge]] |publisher=[[Vox Media]] |accessdate=June 12, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170106213353/http://www.theverge.com/a/google-pixel-phone-new-hardware-interview-2016 |archive-date=January 6, 2017 |url-status=live|date=October 4, 2016 }}</ref>\n\nIn 2011, the [[Chromebook]] was introduced, described as a \"new kind of computer\" running [[Chrome OS]].<ref>{{cite web |first=Sundar |last=Pichai |first2=Linus |last2=Upson |title=A new kind of computer: Chromebook |url=https://googleblog.blogspot.no/2011/05/new-kind-of-computer-chromebook.html |website=Official Google Blog |date=May 11, 2011 |accessdate=November 22, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161122222651/https://googleblog.blogspot.no/2011/05/new-kind-of-computer-chromebook.html |archive-date=November 22, 2016 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2013, Google introduced the [[Chromecast]] dongle, that allows users to stream content from their smartphones to televisions.<ref>{{cite web |first=Adi |last=Robertson |title=Google reveals Chromecast: video streaming to your TV from any device for $35 |url=https://www.theverge.com/2013/7/24/4552204/google-reveals-chromecast-tv-streaming |website=[[The Verge]] |publisher=[[Vox Media]] |date=July 24, 2013 |accessdate=November 29, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161226065215/http://www.theverge.com/2013/7/24/4552204/google-reveals-chromecast-tv-streaming |archive-date=December 26, 2016 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Google Chromecast takes on streaming content to TV |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/technology-23514400 |website=[[BBC News]] |publisher=[[BBC]] |date=July 31, 2013 |accessdate=November 29, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161129205929/http://www.bbc.com/news/technology-23514400 |archive-date=November 29, 2016 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2014, Google announced [[Google Cardboard]], a simple cardboard viewer that lets user place their smartphone in a special front compartment to view [[virtual reality]] (VR) media.<ref>{{cite web |first=James |last=O'Toole |title=Google's cardboard virtual-reality goggles |url=http://money.cnn.com/2014/06/25/technology/innovation/google-cardboard/ |publisher=[[CNN]] |date=June 26, 2014 |accessdate=November 29, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161129145138/http://money.cnn.com/2014/06/25/technology/innovation/google-cardboard/ |archive-date=November 29, 2016 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first=Erik |last=Kain |title=Google Cardboard Is Google's Awesomely Weird Answer To Virtual Reality |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/erikkain/2014/06/26/google-cardboard-is-googles-awesomely-weird-answer-to-virtual-reality/ |website=[[Forbes]] |date=June 26, 2014 |accessdate=November 29, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161129151747/http://www.forbes.com/sites/erikkain/2014/06/26/google-cardboard-is-googles-awesomely-weird-answer-to-virtual-reality/ |archive-date=November 29, 2016 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n* The [[Pixel (smartphone)|Pixel and Pixel XL]] smartphones with the [[Google Assistant]], a next-generation contextual voice assistant, built-in.<ref>{{cite web |first=Vlad |last=Savov |title=Pixel 'phone by Google' announced |url=https://www.theverge.com/2016/10/4/13161028/google-phone-announced-pixel-xl-price-release-date-specs |website=[[The Verge]] |publisher=[[Vox Media]] |date=October 4, 2016 |accessdate=October 8, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170210094337/http://www.theverge.com/2016/10/4/13161028/google-phone-announced-pixel-xl-price-release-date-specs |archive-date=February 10, 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n* [[Google Home]], an [[Amazon Echo]]-like voice assistant placed in the house that can answer voice queries, play music, find information from apps (calendar, weather etc.), and control third-party smart home appliances (users can tell it to turn on the lights, for example). The Google Home line also includes variants such as the [[Google Home Hub]], [[Google Home Mini]], and [[Google Home Max]]<ref>{{cite web |first=Dieter |last=Bohn |title=Google Home is smart, loud, and kind of cute |url=https://www.theverge.com/2016/10/4/13156676/google-home-assistant-speaker-photos-video-device-hands-on |website=[[The Verge]] |publisher=[[Vox Media]] |date=October 4, 2016 |accessdate=October 8, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161007204916/http://www.theverge.com/2016/10/4/13156676/google-home-assistant-speaker-photos-video-device-hands-on |archive-date=October 7, 2016 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n* [[Google Daydream|Daydream View]] [[virtual reality]] headset that lets [[Android (operating system)|Android]] users with compatible Daydream-ready smartphones put their phones in the headset and enjoy VR content.<ref>{{cite web |first=Adi |last=Robertson |first2=Jacob |last2=Kastrenakes |title=Google's Daydream View VR headset goes on sale next month for $79 |url=https://www.theverge.com/2016/10/4/13161506/google-vr-headset-photos-daydream-view-virtual-reality |website=[[The Verge]] |publisher=[[Vox Media]] |date=October 4, 2016 |accessdate=October 8, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161007203651/http://www.theverge.com/2016/10/4/13161506/google-vr-headset-photos-daydream-view-virtual-reality |archive-date=October 7, 2016 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n* [[Google Wifi]], a connected set of [[Wi-Fi]] routers to simplify and extend coverage of home Wi-Fi.<ref>{{cite web |first=Dieter |last=Bohn |title=The Google Wifi routers are little white pucks you can scatter throughout your house |url=https://www.theverge.com/2016/10/4/13157680/google-wifi-router-photos-hands-on |website=[[The Verge]] |publisher=[[Vox Media]] |date=October 4, 2016 |accessdate=October 8, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161007180430/http://www.theverge.com/2016/10/4/13157680/google-wifi-router-photos-hands-on |archive-date=October 7, 2016 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Enterprise services{{anchor|Enterprise_products}}===\n{{Main|G Suite|Google Cloud Platform}}\n\n[[G Suite]] is a monthly subscription offering for organizations and businesses to get access to a collection of Google's services, including [[Gmail]], [[Google Drive]] and [[Google Docs]], [[Google Sheets]] and [[Google Slides]], with additional administrative tools, unique domain names, and 24/7 support.<ref>{{cite web |title=Choose a Plan |url=https://gsuite.google.com/intl/en_ie/pricing.html |website=G Suite by Google Cloud |accessdate=December 2, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161212231639/https://gsuite.google.com/intl/en_ie/pricing.html |archive-date=December 12, 2016 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn September 24, 2012,<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://googleblog.blogspot.com/2012/09/celebrating-spirit-of-entrepreneurship.html |title=Celebrating the spirit of entrepreneurship with the new Google for Entrepreneurs |website=Official Google Blog |language=en |access-date=March 20, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180320171207/https://googleblog.blogspot.com/2012/09/celebrating-spirit-of-entrepreneurship.html |archive-date=March 20, 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref> Google launched [[Google for Entrepreneurs]], a largely not-for-profit [[business incubator]] providing startups with [[Coworking|co-working spaces]] known as Campuses, with assistance to startup founders that may include workshops, conferences, and mentorships.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.entrepreneur.com/article/224522 |title=How Google Wants to Make Starting Up Easier for Entrepreneurs |last=Fell |first=Jason |date=September 27, 2012 |work=Entrepreneur |access-date=March 20, 2018 |language=en |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180320230407/https://www.entrepreneur.com/article/224522 |archive-date=March 20, 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref> Presently, there are 7 Campus locations in [[Berlin]], [[London]], [[Madrid]], [[Seoul]], [[S\u00e3o Paulo]], [[Tel Aviv]], and [[Warsaw]].\n\nOn March 15, 2016, Google announced the introduction of Google Analytics 360 Suite, \"a set of integrated data and marketing analytics products, designed specifically for the needs of enterprise-class marketers\" which can be integrated with [[BigQuery]] on the Google Cloud Platform. Among other things, the suite is designed to help \"enterprise class marketers\" \"see the complete customer journey\", generate \"useful insights\", and \"deliver engaging experiences to the right people\".<ref>{{cite web |first=Paul |last=Muret |title=Introducing the Google Analytics 360 Suite |url=https://analytics.googleblog.com/2016/03/introducing-google-analytics-360-suite.html |date=March 15, 2016 |accessdate=January 22, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170112142850/https://analytics.googleblog.com/2016/03/introducing-google-analytics-360-suite.html |archive-date=January 12, 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref> Jack Marshall of ''[[The Wall Street Journal]]'' wrote that the suite competes with existing marketing cloud offerings by companies including [[Adobe Systems|Adobe]], [[Oracle Corporation|Oracle]], [[Salesforce.com|Salesforce]], and [[IBM]].<ref>{{cite news |first=Jack |last=Marshall |title=Google Launches New Data Tools for Marketers |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/google-launches-new-data-tools-for-marketers-1458043217 |newspaper=[[The Wall Street Journal]] |date=March 15, 2016 |accessdate=January 22, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161113150024/http://www.wsj.com/articles/google-launches-new-data-tools-for-marketers-1458043217 |archive-date=November 13, 2016 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== Internet services ===\nIn February 2010, Google announced the [[Google Fiber]] project, with experimental plans to build an ultra-high-speed broadband network for 50,000 to 500,000 customers in one or more American cities.<ref>{{cite web |first=Minnie |last=Ingersoll |first2=James |last2=Kelly |title=Think big with a gig: Our experimental fiber network |url=https://googleblog.blogspot.no/2010/02/think-big-with-gig-our-experimental.html |website=Official Google Blog |date=February 10, 2010 |accessdate=November 29, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161129150926/https://googleblog.blogspot.no/2010/02/think-big-with-gig-our-experimental.html |archive-date=November 29, 2016 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first=Erick |last=Schonfeld |title=Google Plans To Deliver 1Gb/sec Fiber-Optic Broadband Network To More Than 50,000 Homes |url=https://techcrunch.com/2010/02/10/google-fiber-optic-network-home/ |website=[[TechCrunch]] |publisher=[[AOL]] |date=February 10, 2010 |accessdate=November 29, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161129145628/https://techcrunch.com/2010/02/10/google-fiber-optic-network-home/ |archive-date=November 29, 2016 |url-status=live}}</ref> Following Google's corporate restructure to make [[Alphabet Inc.]] its parent company, Google Fiber was moved to Alphabet's Access division.<ref>{{cite web |first=Kevin |last=McLaughlin |title=Inside the Battle Over Google Fiber |url=https://www.theinformation.com/articles/inside-the-battle-over-google-fiber |website=The Information |date=August 25, 2016 |accessdate=November 29, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161129144256/https://www.theinformation.com/articles/inside-the-battle-over-google-fiber |archive-date=November 29, 2016 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first=Nick |last=Statt |title=Alphabet is putting serious pressure on Google Fiber to cut costs |url=https://www.theverge.com/2016/8/25/12652734/google-fiber-access-alphabet-layoffs-wireless-internet |website=[[The Verge]] |publisher=[[Vox Media]] |date=August 25, 2016 |accessdate=November 29, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161129145849/http://www.theverge.com/2016/8/25/12652734/google-fiber-access-alphabet-layoffs-wireless-internet |archive-date=November 29, 2016 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2015, Google announced [[Project Fi]], a mobile virtual network operator, that combines Wi-Fi and cellular networks from different telecommunication providers in an effort to enable seamless connectivity and fast Internet signal.<ref>{{cite web |first=Nick |last=Fox |title=Say hi to Fi: A new way to say hello |url=https://googleblog.blogspot.no/2015/04/project-fi.html |website=Official Google Blog |date=April 22, 2015 |accessdate=November 29, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161129150714/https://googleblog.blogspot.no/2015/04/project-fi.html |archive-date=November 29, 2016 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first=David |last=Goldman |title=Google launches 'Project Fi' wireless service |url=http://money.cnn.com/2015/04/22/technology/google-project-fi-wireless-service/ |website=[[CNN]] |date=April 22, 2015 |accessdate=November 29, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161129150255/http://money.cnn.com/2015/04/22/technology/google-project-fi-wireless-service/ |archive-date=November 29, 2016 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first=Ellen |last=Huet |title=Google Unveils Its 'Project Fi' Wireless Service |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/ellenhuet/2015/04/22/google-unveils-wireless-service-project-fi/ |website=[[Forbes]] |date=April 22, 2015 |accessdate=November 29, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161129152041/http://www.forbes.com/sites/ellenhuet/2015/04/22/google-unveils-wireless-service-project-fi/ |archive-date=November 29, 2016 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2016, Google began its Google Station initiative, a project for public Wi-Fi at railway stations in India. Caesar Sengupta, VP for Google's next billion users, told ''[[The Verge]]'' that 15,000 people get online for the first time thanks to Google Station and that 3.5 million people use the service every month. The expansion meant that Google was looking for partners around the world to further develop the initiative, which promised \"high-quality, secure, easily accessible Wi-Fi\".<ref>{{cite web |first=Sam |last=Byford |title=Google Station is a new platform that aims to make public Wi-Fi better |url=https://www.theverge.com/2016/9/27/13070922/google-station-public-wi-fi-india |website=[[The Verge]] |publisher=[[Vox Media]] |date=September 27, 2016 |accessdate=October 23, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161023203300/http://www.theverge.com/2016/9/27/13070922/google-station-public-wi-fi-india |archive-date=October 23, 2016 |url-status=live}}</ref> By December, Google Station had been deployed at 100 railway stations,<ref>{{cite web |first=Brian |last=Heater |title=After arriving at 100th railway station in India, Google's WiFi is set to hit another 100 in 2017 |url=https://techcrunch.com/2016/12/29/google-india-wifi/ |website=[[TechCrunch]] |publisher=[[AOL]] |date=December 29, 2016 |accessdate=June 12, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170510091945/https://techcrunch.com/2016/12/29/google-india-wifi/ |archive-date=May 10, 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref> and in February, Google announced its intention to expand beyond railway stations, with a plan to bring citywide Wi-Fi to [[Pune]].<ref>{{cite web |first=Stephen |last=Hall |title=Google Station expands beyond rail stations to bring citywide WiFi to Pune, India |url=https://9to5google.com/2017/02/09/google-station-expands-beyond-rail-stations-to-bring-citywide-wifi-to-pune-india/ |website=9to5Google |date=February 9, 2017 |accessdate=June 12, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170210233838/https://9to5google.com/2017/02/09/google-station-expands-beyond-rail-stations-to-bring-citywide-wifi-to-pune-india/ |archive-date=February 10, 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first=Manish |last=Singh |title=Indian city to become the first in the world to get Google Station public Wi-Fi network |url=http://mashable.com/2017/02/09/google-station-pune-india/ |website=[[Mashable]] |date=February 9, 2017 |accessdate=June 12, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170223153245/http://mashable.com/2017/02/09/google-station-pune-india/ |archive-date=February 23, 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== Other products ===\nIn May 2011, Google announced [[Google Wallet]], a mobile application for wireless payments.<ref>{{cite news |first=Tara |last=Bernard |title=Google Unveils App for Paying With Phone |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/05/27/technology/27google.html |website=[[The New York Times]] |date=May 26, 2011 |accessdate=November 29, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161012171341/http://www.nytimes.com/2011/05/27/technology/27google.html |archive-date=October 12, 2016 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013, Google launched [[Google Shopping Express]], a delivery service initially available only in San Francisco and Silicon Valley.<ref>{{cite news |last=Somerville |first=Heather |url=http://www.mercurynews.com/business/ci_24171776/exclusive-google-same-day-delivery-makes-public-debut |title=Google same-day delivery makes public debut |newspaper=Mercury News |date=September 25, 2013 |access-date=October 6, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131001221830/http://www.mercurynews.com/business/ci_24171776/exclusive-google-same-day-delivery-makes-public-debut |archive-date=October 1, 2013 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n== Corporate affairs ==\n\n=== Finance ===\n{{Further|Corporation tax in the Republic of Ireland#Multinational tax schemes|Google tax}}\n\n[[File:Schmidt-Brin-Page-20080520.jpg|thumb|Then-CEO, now Chairman of Google [[Eric Schmidt]] with cofounders [[Sergey Brin]] and [[Larry Page]] (left to right) in 2008.|alt=Eric Schmidt, Sergey Brin, and Larry Page sitting together]]\nGoogle's [[initial public offering]] (IPO) took place on August 19, 2004. At IPO, the company offered 19,605,052 shares at a price of $85 per share.<ref name=\"IPO\" /><ref name=\":1\" /> The sale of $1.67 billion gave Google a [[market capitalization]] of more than $23 billion.<ref name=\"washpost\" /> The stock performed well after the IPO, with shares hitting $350 for the first time on October 31, 2007,<ref>{{cite news |url=http://weblogs.baltimoresun.com/business/hancock/blog/2007/10/google_shares_hit_700.html |title=Google shares hit $700 |last=Hancock |first=Jay |date=October 31, 2007 |work=The Baltimore Sun |accessdate=November 27, 2010 |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/659XVy0yM?url=http://weblogs.baltimoresun.com/business/hancock/blog/2007/10/google_shares_hit_700.html |archive-date=February 2, 2012 |url-status=live}}</ref> primarily because of strong sales and earnings in the [[online advertising]] market.<ref name=\"bowlingforgoogle\">{{Cite news |url=http://money.cnn.com/2005/05/25/technology/techinvestor/lamonica/index.htm |title=Bowling for Google |last=La Monica |first=Paul R. |date=May 25, 2005 |work=CNN |accessdate=February 28, 2007 |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/659XXqofq?url=http://money.cnn.com/2005/05/25/technology/techinvestor/lamonica/index.htm |archive-date=February 2, 2012 |url-status=live}}</ref> The surge in stock price was fueled mainly by individual investors, as opposed to large institutional investors and [[mutual fund]]s.<ref name=\"bowlingforgoogle\" /> GOOG shares split into GOOG [[class C share]]s and GOOGL [[class A share]]s.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2015/04/02/stock-split-could-cost-google-over-500-million.html |title=This could cost Google more than $500 million |website=CNBC |accessdate=December 30, 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151226080454/http://www.cnbc.com/2015/04/02/stock-split-could-cost-google-over-500-million.html |archive-date=December 26, 2015 |url-status=live|date=April 2, 2015 }}</ref> The company is listed on the [[NASDAQ]] stock exchange under the [[ticker symbol]]s GOOGL and GOOG, and on the [[Frankfurt Stock Exchange]] under the ticker symbol GGQ1. These ticker symbols now refer to Alphabet Inc., Google's holding company, {{as of|2015|8|10|alt=since the fourth quarter of 2015.}}<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2015/08/10/google-announces-plans-for-new-operating-structure.html |title=Google to become part of new company, Alphabet |last=Pramuk |first=Jacob |date=August 10, 2015 |newspaper=[[CNBC]] |accessdate=August 11, 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150811000128/http://www.cnbc.com/2015/08/10/google-announces-plans-for-new-operating-structure.html |archive-date=August 11, 2015 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe corporation's consolidated revenue for the third quarter of 2013 was reported in mid-October 2013 as $14.89 billion, a 12 percent increase compared to the previous quarter.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.androidpolice.com/2013/10/18/google-beats-analyst-estimates-for-third-quarter-results-stock-passes-1000-per-share/ |title=Google Beats Analyst Estimates For Third Quarter Results, Stock Passes $1000 Per Share |last=Whitwam |first=Ryan |date=October 18, 2013 |website=Android Police |accessdate=March 15, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170316025733/http://www.androidpolice.com/2013/10/18/google-beats-analyst-estimates-for-third-quarter-results-stock-passes-1000-per-share/ |archive-date=March 16, 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref> Google's Internet business was responsible for $10.8 billion of this total, with an increase in the number of users' clicks on advertisements.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2013/oct/17/google-q3-revenue-earnings-report |title=Google earnings up 12% in third quarter even as Motorola losses deepen |agency=Reuters |date=October 17, 2013 |newspaper=The Guardian |accessdate=October 18, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131017221536/http://www.theguardian.com/technology/2013/oct/17/google-q3-revenue-earnings-report |archive-date=October 17, 2013 |url-status=dead}}</ref> By January 2014, Google's market capitalization had grown to $397 billion.<ref name=\"Marketwatch\">{{cite web |url=http://www.marketwatch.com/investing/stock/goog |title=Google Overview |website=Marketwatch |accessdate=February 2, 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140202073406/http://www.marketwatch.com/investing/stock/GOOG |archive-date=February 2, 2014 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nGoogle uses various [[Tax avoidance|tax avoidance strategies]]. Out of the [[List of the largest information technology companies|five largest American technology companies]], it pays the lowest taxes to the countries of origin of its revenues. Google between 2007 and 2010 saved $3.1 billion in taxes by shuttling non-U.S. profits through [[Ireland]] and the [[Netherlands]] and then to [[Bermuda]]. Such techniques lower its non-U.S. tax rate to 2.3 per cent, while normally the corporate tax rate in for instance the UK is 28 per cent.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theregister.co.uk/2010/10/22/google_double_irish_tax_loophole/ |title=Google slips $3.1bn through 'Double Irish' tax loophole. |last=Metz |first=Cade |date=October 22, 2010 |website=The Register |access-date=August 10, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170706132414/https://www.theregister.co.uk/2010/10/22/google_double_irish_tax_loophole/ |archive-date=July 6, 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref> This has reportedly sparked a French investigation into Google's [[transfer pricing]] practices.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theregister.co.uk/2012/10/31/google_france_tax_office_billion_euros/ |title=French gov 'plans to hand Google \u20ac1bn tax bill'&nbsp;\u2013 report |last=Leach |first=Anna |date=October 31, 2012 |publisher=Theregister.co.uk |accessdate=January 2, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130104002014/http://www.theregister.co.uk/2012/10/31/google_france_tax_office_billion_euros/ |archive-date=January 4, 2013 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nGoogle said it overhauled its controversial global tax structure and consolidated all of its intellectual property holdings back to the US.<ref name=\"GoogleIPRichardWaters\">{{cite news|first=Richard|last=Waters|url=https://www.ft.com/content/991f11ae-2c51-11ea-bc77-65e4aa615551|title=Google to end use of 'double Irish' as tax loophole set to close|work=[[The Times]]|date=2 January 2020}}</ref>\n\nGoogle Vice-President [[Matt Brittin]] testified to the [[Public Accounts Committee (United Kingdom)|Public Accounts Committee]] of the UK House of Commons that his UK sales team made no sales and hence owed no sales taxes to the UK.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theregister.co.uk/2013/05/17/quotw_ending_may_17/ |title=I think you DO do evil, using smoke and mirrors to avoid tax |author=Brid-Aine Parnell |date=May 17, 2013 |publisher=Theregister.co.uk |accessdate=March 13, 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131226090028/http://www.theregister.co.uk/2013/05/17/quotw_ending_may_17/ |archive-date=December 26, 2013 |url-status=live}}</ref> In January 2016, Google reached a settlement with the UK to pay \u00a3130m in back taxes plus higher taxes in future.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ft.com/cms/s/0/d50ad5f4-c125-11e5-9fdb-87b8d15baec2.html |title=Google strikes \u00a3130m back tax deal |author=John Gapper|date=January 23, 2016 |publisher=FT.com |accessdate=January 24, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160124195612/http://www.ft.com/cms/s/0/d50ad5f4-c125-11e5-9fdb-87b8d15baec2.html |archive-date=January 24, 2016 |url-status=live}}</ref> In 2017, Google channeled $22.7 billion from the Netherlands to Bermuda to reduce its tax bill.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-google-taxes-netherlands/google-shifted-23-billion-to-tax-haven-bermuda-in-2017-filing-idUSKCN1OX1G9 |title=Google shifted $23 billion to tax haven Bermuda in 2017: filing |last=Bart Meijer |date=January 3, 2019 |work=Reuters |accessdate=January 3, 2019 |quote=Google moved 19.9 billion euros ($22.7 billion) through a Dutch shell company to Bermuda in 2017, as part of an arrangement that allows it to reduce its foreign tax bill |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190103215930/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-google-taxes-netherlands/google-shifted-23-billion-to-tax-haven-bermuda-in-2017-filing-idUSKCN1OX1G9 |archive-date=January 3, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013, Google ranked 5th in [[Lobbying in the United States|lobbying]] spending, up from 213th in 2003. In 2012, the company ranked 2nd in campaign donations of technology and Internet sections.<ref name=\"lobby1\">{{cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/how-google-is-transforming-power-and-politicsgoogle-once-disdainful-of-lobbying-now-a-master-of-washington-influence/2014/04/12/51648b92-b4d3-11e3-8cb6-284052554d74_story.html |title=Google, once disdainful of lobbying, now a master of Washington influence |last=Hamburger |first=Tom |date=April 13, 2014 |work=[[The Washington Post]] |last2=Gold |first2=Matea |access-date=August 22, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171027124925/https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/how-google-is-transforming-power-and-politicsgoogle-once-disdainful-of-lobbying-now-a-master-of-washington-influence/2014/04/12/51648b92-b4d3-11e3-8cb6-284052554d74_story.html |archive-date=October 27, 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== Corporate identity ===\n{{Main|History of Google#Name|Google (verb)|Google logo|Google Doodle|List of Google April Fools' Day jokes|List of Google Easter eggs}}\n[[File:Logo Google 2013 Official.svg|thumb|200px|Google's logo from 2013-2015]]\nThe name \"Google\" originated from a misspelling of \"[[googol]]\",<ref>Koller, David. \"[http://graphics.stanford.edu/~dk/google_name_origin.html Origin of the name, \"Google.\"] {{webarchive|url=https://www.webcitation.org/68ubHzYs7?url=http://graphics.stanford.edu/~dk/google_name_origin.html|date=2012-07-04}} ''[[Stanford University]].'' January, 2004.</ref><ref name=\"Hanley\">Hanley, Rachael. \"[http://www.stanforddaily.com/2003/02/12/from-googol-to-google/ From Googol to Google: Co-founder returns] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100330004631/http://www.stanforddaily.com/2003/02/12/from-googol-to-google/|date=March 30, 2010}}.\" ''[[The Stanford Daily]].'' February 12, 2003. Retrieved on August 26, 2010.</ref> which refers to the number represented by a 1 followed by one-hundred zeros. Page and Brin write in their original paper on [[PageRank]]:<ref name=\"originalpaper\">{{Cite journal|last=Brin|first=Sergey|author-link=Sergey Brin|last2=Page|first2=Lawrence|author-link2=Larry Page|year=1998|title=The anatomy of a large-scale hypertextual Web search engine|url=http://infolab.stanford.edu/pub/papers/google.pdf|url-status=live|journal=Computer Networks and ISDN Systems|volume=30|issue=1\u20137|pages=107\u2013117|citeseerx=10.1.1.115.5930|doi=10.1016/S0169-7552(98)00110-X|issn=0169-7552|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150927004511/http://infolab.stanford.edu/pub/papers/google.pdf|archive-date=September 27, 2015|access-date=April 7, 2019}}</ref> \"We chose our systems name, Google, because it is a common spelling of googol, or 10<sup>100</sup> and fits well with our goal of building very large-scale search engines.\" Having found its way increasingly into everyday language, the verb \"[[Google (verb)|google]]\" was added to the ''[[Merriam-Webster Collegiate Dictionary|Merriam Webster Collegiate Dictionary]]'' and the ''[[Oxford English Dictionary]]'' in 2006, meaning \"to use the Google search engine to obtain information on the Internet.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.mercurynews.com/mld/mercurynews/business/14985574.htm|title=Dictionary adds verb: to google|work=San Jose Mercury News|last=Harris|first=Scott D.|date=July 7, 2006|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070206065348/http://www.mercurynews.com/mld/mercurynews/business/14985574.htm|archive-date=February 6, 2007|url-status=dead|access-date=July 7, 2006}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Bylund|first=Anders|url=http://msnbc.msn.com/id/13720643/|title=To Google or Not to Google|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://archive.today/20060707062623/http://msnbc.msn.com/id/13720643/|archive-date=July 7, 2006|work=[[The Motley Fool]]|via=[[MSNBC]]|date=July 5, 2006|access-date=July 7, 2006}}</ref> Google's [[mission statement]], from the outset, was \"to organize the world's information and make it universally accessible and useful\",<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2014/nov/03/larry-page-google-dont-be-evil-sergey-brin |title=Google has 'outgrown' its 14-year old mission statement, says Larry Page |last=Gibbs |first=Samuel |date=November 3, 2014 |website=[[The Guardian]] |publisher=[[Guardian Media Group]] |accessdate=March 25, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170326053031/https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2014/nov/03/larry-page-google-dont-be-evil-sergey-brin |archive-date=March 26, 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref> and its unofficial slogan is \"[[Don't be evil]]\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://abc.xyz/investor/other/google-code-of-conduct.html |title=Google Code of Conduct |date=April 11, 2012 |website=Alphabet Investor Relations |publisher=[[Alphabet Inc.]] |accessdate=March 25, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170211223917/https://abc.xyz/investor/other/google-code-of-conduct.html |archive-date=February 11, 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref> In October 2015, a related motto was adopted in the Alphabet corporate code of conduct by the phrase: \"Do the right thing\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.engadget.com/2015/10/02/alphabet-do-the-right-thing/ |title=Alphabet replaces Google's 'Don't be evil' with 'Do the right thing' |last=Lawler |first=Richard |date=October 2, 2015 |website=[[Engadget]] |publisher=[[AOL]] |accessdate=March 25, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170701225925/https://www.engadget.com/2015/10/02/alphabet-do-the-right-thing/ |archive-date=July 1, 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref> The original motto was retained in the code of conduct of Google, now a subsidiary of Alphabet.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nThe original [[Google logo]] was designed by Sergey Brin.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.ndtv.com/photos/news/happy-birthday-google--8267#photo-99345 |title=Happy Birthday Google! |accessdate=April 28, 2016 |publisher=ndtv.com |agency=NDTV Convergence Limited |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190407042748/https://www.ndtv.com/photos/news/happy-birthday-google--8267#photo-99345 |archive-date=April 7, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> {{As of|1998|since=y|post=,}} Google has been designing special, temporary alternate logos to place on their homepage intended to celebrate holidays, events, achievements and people. The first [[Google Doodle]] was in honor of the [[Burning Man|Burning Man Festival]] of 1998.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.google.com/doodle4google/history.html |title=Doodle 4 Google |date= |accessdate=April 23, 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140427143948/http://www.google.com/doodle4google/history.html |archive-date=April 27, 2014 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.google.com/doodles/burning-man-festival |title=Burning Man Festival |date=August 30, 1998 |accessdate=April 23, 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140425051111/https://www.google.com/doodles/burning-man-festival |archive-date=April 25, 2014 |url-status=live}}</ref> The doodle was designed by [[Larry Page]] and [[Sergey Brin]] to notify users of their absence in case the servers crashed. Subsequent Google Doodles were designed by an outside contractor, until Larry and Sergey asked then-[[intern]] [[Dennis Hwang]] to design a logo for [[Bastille Day]] in 2000. From that point onward, Doodles have been organized and created by a team of employees termed \"Doodlers\".<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2014/apr/12/meet-people-behind-google-doodles-logo |title=Meet the people behind the Google Doodles |date=April 12, 2014 |newspaper=The Guardian |accessdate=September 27, 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141006222909/http://www.theguardian.com/technology/2014/apr/12/meet-people-behind-google-doodles-logo |archive-date=October 6, 2014 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nGoogle has a tradition of creating [[April Fools' Day]] jokes. Its first on April 1, 2000 was [[Google's hoaxes#2000|Google MentalPlex]] which allegedly featured the use of mental power to search the web.<ref name=\"mentalplex\">{{cite web |url=https://www.google.com/mentalplex/ |title=Google MentalPlex |date=April 1, 2000 |publisher=Google, Inc. |accessdate=July 5, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100921223048/http://www.google.com/mentalplex/ |archive-date=September 21, 2010 |url-status=live}}</ref> In 2007, Google announced a free Internet service called [[TiSP]], or Toilet Internet Service Provider, where one obtained a connection by flushing one end of a [[optical fiber|fiber-optic]] cable down their toilet.<ref name=\"TiSP\">{{cite web |url=https://www.google.com/tisp/ |title=Welcome to Google TiSP |date=April 1, 2007 |publisher=Google, Inc. |accessdate=July 5, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100709034300/http://www.google.com/tisp/ |archive-date=July 9, 2010 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nGoogle's services contain [[Easter egg (media)|easter eggs]], such as the [[Swedish Chef]]'s \"Bork bork bork,\" [[Pig Latin]], \"Hacker\" or [[leet]]speak, [[Elmer Fudd]], [[International Talk Like a Pirate Day|Pirate]], and [[Klingon language|Klingon]] as language selections for its search engine.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.google.com/language_tools |title=Language Tools |publisher=Google, Inc. |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5hT77QDRS?url=http://www.google.com/language_tools |archivedate=June 12, 2009 |url-status=dead |accessdate=July 4, 2010}}</ref> When searching for the word \"[[anagram]],\" meaning a rearrangement of letters from one word to form other valid words, Google's suggestion feature displays \"Did you mean: nag a ram?\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.google.com/search?q=anagram |title=anagram search |publisher=Google, Inc. |accessdate=September 22, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130624205429/http://www.google.com/search?q=anagram |archive-date=June 24, 2013 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Workplace culture{{Anchor|Innovation Time Off|Employees}}===\n[[File:Pride in London 2016 - Google participating in the parade.png|alt=|left|thumb|Google employees marching in the [[Pride in London]] parade in 2016]]\nOn ''[[Fortune (magazine)|Fortune]]'' magazine's list of the best companies to work for, Google ranked first in 2007, 2008 and 2012,<ref name=\"best_company\">{{Cite journal |last=Levering |first=Robert |last2=Moskowitz |first2=Milton |date=January 22, 2007 |editor1-last=Serwer |editor1-first=Andrew |title=In good company |url=http://money.cnn.com/magazines/fortune/fortune_archive/2007/01/22/8398125/index.htm |journal=Fortune Magazine |volume=155 |issue=1 |pages=94-6, 100, 102 passim |pmid=17256628 |accessdate=June 19, 2010 |editor1-link=Andrew Serwer |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100301175257/http://money.cnn.com/magazines/fortune/fortune_archive/2007/01/22/8398125/index.htm |archive-date=March 1, 2010 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal |last=Levering |first=Robert |last2=Moskowitz |first2=Milton |date=February 4, 2008 |editor1-last=Serwer |editor1-first=Andrew |title=The 2008 list |url=http://money.cnn.com/magazines/fortune/bestcompanies/2008/full_list/index.html |journal=Fortune Magazine |volume=157 |issue=2 |accessdate=June 19, 2010 |editor1-link=Andrew Serwer |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100723223729/http://money.cnn.com/magazines/fortune/bestcompanies/2008/full_list/index.html |archive-date=July 23, 2010 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal |title=The 2012 list |url=http://money.cnn.com/magazines/fortune/best-companies/2012/full_list/ |journal=Fortune Magazine |accessdate=February 26, 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121031135647/http://money.cnn.com/magazines/fortune/best-companies/2012/full_list/ |archive-date=October 31, 2012 |url-status=live}}</ref> and fourth in 2009 and 2010.<ref>{{Cite journal |last=Levering |first=Robert |last2=Moskowitz |first2=Milton |date=February 2, 2009 |editor1-last=Serwer |editor1-first=Andrew |title=The 2009 list |url=http://money.cnn.com/magazines/fortune/bestcompanies/2009/full_list/index.html |journal=Fortune Magazine |volume=159 |issue=2 |accessdate=June 19, 2010 |editor1-link=Andrew Serwer |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100726042849/http://money.cnn.com/magazines/fortune/bestcompanies/2009/full_list/index.html |archive-date=July 26, 2010 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal |last=Levering |first=Robert |last2=Moskowitz |first2=Milton |date=February 8, 2010 |editor1-last=Serwer |editor1-first=Andrew |title=The 2010 list |url=http://money.cnn.com/magazines/fortune/bestcompanies/2010/full_list/ |journal=Fortune Magazine |volume=161 |issue=2 |accessdate=June 19, 2010 |editor1-link=Andrew Serwer |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100618125312/http://money.cnn.com/magazines/fortune/bestcompanies/2010/full_list/ |archive-date=June 18, 2010 |url-status=live}}</ref> Google was also nominated in 2010 to be the world's most attractive employer to graduating students in the Universum Communications talent attraction index.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.universumglobal.com/IDEAL-Employer-Rankings/Global-Top-50 |title=The World's Most Attractive Employers 2010 |date=September 28, 2010 |publisher=Universum Global |accessdate=October 28, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101112131208/http://www.universumglobal.com/IDEAL-Employer-Rankings/Global-Top-50 |archive-date=November 12, 2010 |url-status=dead}}</ref> Google's corporate philosophy includes principles such as \"you can make money without doing evil,\" \"you can be serious without a suit,\" and \"work should be challenging and the challenge should be fun.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.google.com/corporate/tenthings.html |title=Our Philosophy |publisher=Google, Inc. |accessdate=June 20, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100709041157/http://www.google.com/corporate/tenthings.html |archive-date=July 9, 2010 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n{{As of|2018|12|31|alt=As of December 2018,}} Google has 98,771 employees.<ref name=\"EmployeesAsOf2018Q4\" /> Google's {{as of|2017|6|29|alt=2017}} diversity report states that 31 percent of its workforce are women and 69 percent are men, with the ethnicity of its workforce being predominantly white (56%) and Asian (35%).<ref name=\"2017DiversityReport\">{{cite blog |url=https://www.blog.google/topics/diversity/making-progress-diversity-and-inclusion/ |title=Making progress on diversity and inclusion |last=Naughton |first=Eileen |date=June 29, 2017 |department=Diversity |website=The Keyword |publisher=Google |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180517170958/https://www.blog.google/topics/diversity/making-progress-diversity-and-inclusion/ |archive-date=May 17, 2018 |url-status=live |access-date=May 17, 2018}}{{pb}}{{cite news |last=Yurieff |first=Kaya |date=June 29, 2017 |title=Google struggles to increase workforce diversity |url=https://money.cnn.com/2017/06/29/technology/google-diversity-report/index.html |url-status=live |department=CNNTech |work=[[CNNMoney]] |publisher=[[Time Warner]] |location=New York |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180517174524/https://money.cnn.com/2017/06/29/technology/google-diversity-report/index.html |archive-date=May 17, 2018 |access-date=May 17, 2018}}</ref> Within tech roles, however, 20 percent were women; and 25 percent of leadership roles were held by women.<ref name=\"2017DiversityReport\" />\n\nGoogle's employees are hired based on a hierarchical system. Employees are split into six hierarchies based on experience and can range \"from entry-level data center workers at level one to managers and experienced engineers at level six.\"<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2017/09/08/google-gender-pay-gap-spreadsheet-finds-men-paid-more-than-women.html |title=Google workers collected data showing their male colleagues make more than women |last=Wakabayashi |first=Daisuke |date=September 8, 2017 |work=CNBC |access-date=September 25, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170926095602/https://www.cnbc.com/2017/09/08/google-gender-pay-gap-spreadsheet-finds-men-paid-more-than-women.html |archive-date=September 26, 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref> As a motivation technique, Google uses a policy known as [[Innovation Time Off]], where Google engineers are encouraged to spend 20% of their work time on projects that interest them. Some of Google's services, such as [[Gmail]], [[Google News]], [[Orkut]], and [[AdSense]] originated from these independent endeavors.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2007/10/21/jobs/21pre.html |title=The Google Way: Give Engineers Room |last=Mediratta |first=Bharat |last2=Bick |first2=Julie |date=October 21, 2007 |website=[[The New York Times]] |accessdate=March 9, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170402201354/http://www.nytimes.com/2007/10/21/jobs/21pre.html |archive-date=April 2, 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref> In a talk at Stanford University, [[Marissa Mayer]], Google's Vice-President of Search Products and User Experience until July 2012, showed that half of all new product launches in the second half of 2005 had originated from the Innovation Time Off.<ref>{{Cite video |people=Mayer, Marissa (speaker) |date=June 30, 2006 |title=Marissa Mayer at Stanford University |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=soYKFWqVVzg |medium=Seminar |publisher=Martin Lafrance |accessdate=June 20, 2010 |time=11:33 |quote=Fifty percent of what Google launched in the second half of 2005 actually got built out of 20% time. |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100816150501/http://www.youtube.com//watch?v=soYKFWqVVzg |archive-date=August 16, 2010 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn 2005, articles in ''[[The New York Times]]''<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2005/08/24/technology/relax-bill-gates-its-googles-turn-as-the-villain.html |title=Relax, Bill Gates; It's Google's Turn as the Villain |last=Rivlin |first=Gary |date=August 24, 2005 |website=[[The New York Times]] |accessdate=March 9, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170403014314/http://www.nytimes.com/2005/08/24/technology/relax-bill-gates-its-googles-turn-as-the-villain.html |archive-date=April 3, 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref> and other sources began suggesting that Google had lost its anti-corporate, no evil philosophy.<ref>{{cite journal |author=Utz, Richard |date=2013 |title=The Good Corporation? Google's Medievalism and Why It Matters |journal=Studies in Medievalism |volume=23 |pages=21\u201328}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.smh.com.au/news/technology/search-giant-may-outgrow-its-fans/2005/08/25/1124562975596.html3001.asp |title=Search giant may outgrow its fans |last=Gibson |first=Owen |date=August 25, 2005 |newspaper=The Sydney Morning Herald |accessdate=November 27, 2010 |last2=Wray |first2=Richard |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100517075346/http://www.smh.com.au/news/technology/search-giant-may-outgrow-its-fans/2005/08/25/1124562975596.html3001.asp |archive-date=May 17, 2010 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.osnews.com/story/17928/Google--Dont-Be-Evil |title=Google&nbsp;\u2013 Don't Be Evil |last=Ranka |first=Mohit |date=May 17, 2007 |publisher=OSNews |accessdate=November 27, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100706224751/http://www.osnews.com/story/17928/Google--Dont-Be-Evil |archive-date=July 6, 2010 |url-status=live}}</ref> In an effort to maintain the company's unique culture, Google designated a Chief Culture Officer whose purpose was to develop and maintain the culture and work on ways to keep true to the core values that the company was founded on.<ref name=\"CCO\">{{cite web |url=http://www.zdnet.com.au/meet-google-s-culture-czar-339275147.htm |title=Google's culture czar |last=Mills |first=Elinor |date=April 30, 2007 |website=ZDNet |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101031155723/http://www.zdnet.com.au/meet-google-s-culture-czar-339275147.htm |archivedate=October 31, 2010 |url-status=dead |accessdate=November 27, 2010}}</ref> Google has also faced allegations of [[sexism]] and [[ageism]] from former employees.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.cnet.com/Google-hit-with-job-discrimination-lawsuit/2100-1030_3-5807158.html?tag=nl |title=Google hit with job discrimination lawsuit |last=Kawamoto |first=Dawn |date=July 27, 2005 |work=[[CNET]] |accessdate=November 27, 2010 |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ctv.ca/servlet/ArticleNews/story/CTVNews/20071006/google_old_071006/20071006 |title=Google accused of ageism in reinstated lawsuit |date=October 6, 2007 |website=ctv.ca |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071011205140/http://www.ctv.ca/servlet/ArticleNews/story/CTVNews/20071006/google_old_071006/20071006 |archivedate=October 11, 2007 |url-status=dead |accessdate=January 22, 2017}}</ref> In 2013, a [[High-Tech Employee Antitrust Litigation|class action against]] several [[Silicon Valley]] companies, including Google, was filed for alleged \"no cold call\" agreements which restrained the recruitment of high-tech employees.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.cnet.com/news/judge-approves-first-payout-in-antitrust-wage-fixing-lawsuit/ |title=Judge approves first payout in antitrust wage-fixing lawsuit |last=Rosenblatt |first=Seth |date=May 16, 2014 |website=[[CNET]] |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] |accessdate=January 22, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170202030937/https://www.cnet.com/news/judge-approves-first-payout-in-antitrust-wage-fixing-lawsuit/ |archive-date=February 2, 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Office locations{{Anchor|Office locations and headquarters}}===\n{{Further|Googleplex}}\n[[File:111 Eighth Avenue.jpg|alt=|thumb|Google's New York City office building houses its largest advertising sales team.]]\n[[File:Google at 111 Richmond Street West in Toronto (cropped).jpg|thumb|Google's [[Toronto]] office.]]\nGoogle's headquarters in [[Mountain View, California|Mountain View]], California is referred to as \"the [[Googleplex]]\", a play on words on the number [[googolplex]] and the headquarters itself being a ''complex'' of buildings. Internationally, Google has over 78 offices in more than 50 countries.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.google.com/intl/en/about/locations/?region=north-america |title=Google: Our Offices |last= |first= |date= |website= |access-date=April 19, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180726014216/https://www.google.com/intl/en/about/locations/?region=north-america |archive-date=July 26, 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn 2006, Google moved into about {{convert|300000|sqft|m2|-2}} of office space in New York City, at [[111 Eighth Avenue]] in Manhattan. The office was designed and built specially for Google, and houses its largest advertising sales team, which has been instrumental in securing large partnerships.<ref>{{cite web |first=Marguerite |last=Reardon |title=Google takes a bigger bite of Big Apple |url=https://www.cnet.com/news/google-takes-a-bigger-bite-of-big-apple/ |website=[[CNET]] |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] |date=October 11, 2006 |accessdate=June 13, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161012171317/https://www.cnet.com/news/google-takes-a-bigger-bite-of-big-apple/ |archive-date=October 12, 2016 |url-status=live}}</ref> In 2010, Google bought the building housing the headquarter, in a deal that valued the property at around $1.9 billion.<ref>{{cite web |first=Peter |last=Grant |title=Google to Buy New York Office Building |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424052748704377004575651380545769418 |website=[[The Wall Street Journal]] |publisher=[[Dow Jones & Company]] |date=December 3, 2010 |accessdate=June 13, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161010041640/http://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424052748704377004575651380545769418 |archive-date=October 10, 2016 |url-status=live}}{{subscription required}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |first=Sam |last=Gustin |title=Google buys giant New York building for $1.9 billion |url=https://www.wired.com/2010/12/google-nyc/ |journal=[[Wired (website)|Wired]] |publisher=[[Cond\u00e9 Nast]] |date=December 22, 2010 |accessdate=June 13, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170102101149/https://www.wired.com/2010/12/google-nyc/ |archive-date=January 2, 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref> In March 2018, Google's parent company Alphabet bought the nearby [[Chelsea Market]] building for $2.4 billion. The sale is touted as one of the most expensive real estate transactions for a single building in the history of New York.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://phys.org/news/2018-03-google-nyc-chelsea-bn.html |title=Google buys NYC's Chelsea Market building for $2.4 bn |access-date=June 1, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180613184159/https://phys.org/news/2018-03-google-nyc-chelsea-bn.html |archive-date=June 13, 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://techcrunch.com/2018/03/20/google-bought-manhattans-chelsea-market-building-for-2-4-billion/ |title=Google bought Manhattan's Chelsea Market building for $2.4 billion \u2013 TechCrunch |website=techcrunch.com |language=en-US |access-date=June 1, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180608214250/https://techcrunch.com/2018/03/20/google-bought-manhattans-chelsea-market-building-for-2-4-billion/ |archive-date=June 8, 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-new-york-property-google-chelseamarke/google-closes-2-4-billion-chelsea-market-deal-to-expand-new-york-campus-idUSKBN1GW35U |title=Google closes $2.4 billion Chelsea Market deal to expand New York... |last=Editorial |first=Reuters |work=U.S. |access-date=June 1, 2018 |language=en-US |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180527003159/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-new-york-property-google-chelseamarke/google-closes-2-4-billion-chelsea-market-deal-to-expand-new-york-campus-idUSKBN1GW35U |archive-date=May 27, 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=http://uk.pcmag.com/news/93278/report-alphabet-is-buying-chelsea-market-for-over-2b |title=Report: Alphabet Is Buying Chelsea Market for Over $2B |date=February 9, 2018 |work=PCMag UK |access-date=June 1, 2018 |language=en-GB |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180613210609/http://uk.pcmag.com/news/93278/report-alphabet-is-buying-chelsea-market-for-over-2b |archive-date=June 13, 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref> In November 2018, Google announced its plan to expand its New York City office to a capacity of 12,000 employees.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/google-plans-large-new-york-city-expansion-1541636579 |title=Google Plans Large New York City Expansion |last=Grant |first=Douglas MacMillan, Eliot Brown and Peter |work=WSJ |access-date=November 8, 2018 |language=en-US |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181108182715/https://www.wsj.com/articles/google-plans-large-new-york-city-expansion-1541636579 |archive-date=November 8, 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref> The same December, it was announced that a $1 billion, {{convert|1,700,000|ft2|m2|adj=on}} headquarters for Google would be built in Manhattan's [[Hudson Square]] neighborhood.<ref>{{cite web |title=Google To Build New $1 Billion Campus In NYC |website=CBS New York |date=December 17, 2018 |url=https://newyork.cbslocal.com/2018/12/17/google-to-build-new-1-billion-campus-in-nyc/ |access-date=December 17, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181217165433/https://newyork.cbslocal.com/2018/12/17/google-to-build-new-1-billion-campus-in-nyc/ |archive-date=December 17, 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Gartenberg |first=Chaim |title=Google announces a new $1 billion NYC campus in Hudson Square |website=The Verge |date=December 17, 2018 |url=https://www.theverge.com/2018/12/17/18144448/google-nyc-campus-hudson-square-location-cost-open-date |access-date=December 17, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181217203157/https://www.theverge.com/2018/12/17/18144448/google-nyc-campus-hudson-square-location-cost-open-date |archive-date=December 17, 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref> Called Google Hudson Square, the new campus is projected to more than double the number of Google employees working in New York City.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.npr.org/2018/12/17/677450467/google-will-spend-1-billion-for-new-york-city-campus-on-hudson-river |title=Google Will Spend $1 Billion For New York City Campus On Hudson River |website=NPR.org |language=en |access-date=December 17, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181217211911/https://www.npr.org/2018/12/17/677450467/google-will-spend-1-billion-for-new-york-city-campus-on-hudson-river |archive-date=December 17, 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nBy late 2006, Google established a new headquarters for its AdWords division in [[Ann Arbor, Michigan]].<ref>{{cite web |first=Mary Hayes |last=Weier |title=Inside Google's Michigan Office |url=http://www.informationweek.com/news/internet/webdev/showArticle.jhtml?articleID=202600809 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080503233009/http://www.informationweek.com/news/internet/webdev/showArticle.jhtml?articleID=202600809 |website=[[InformationWeek]] |publisher=[[UBM plc]] |date=October 24, 2007 |archivedate=May 3, 2008 |accessdate=January 22, 2017 |url-status=dead}}</ref> In November 2006, Google opened offices on [[Carnegie Mellon]]'s campus in [[Pittsburgh]], focusing on shopping-related advertisement coding and [[smartphone applications]] and programs.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.thepittsburghchannel.com/technology/10346550/detail.html |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5hGpTE0LB?url=http://www.thepittsburghchannel.com/technology/10346550/detail.html |archivedate=June 4, 2009 |title=Google Completes Pittsburgh Office, Holds Open House |date=November 17, 2006 |accessdate=January 13, 2008 |publisher=[[WTAE TV|WTAE]] |url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://triblive.com/x/pittsburghtrib/business/s_712700.html |title=Google search: Tech-minded workers |last=Olson |first=Thomas |date=December 8, 2010 |publisher=[[Trib Total Media]] |accessdate=December 8, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130603080308/http://triblive.com/x/pittsburghtrib/business/s_712700.html |archive-date=June 3, 2013 |url-status=live}}</ref> Other office locations in the U.S. include [[Atlanta, Georgia]]; [[Austin, Texas]]; [[Boulder, Colorado]]; [[Cambridge, Massachusetts]]; [[San Francisco]], [[California]]; [[Seattle, Washington]]; [[Kirkland, Washington]]; [[Birmingham, Michigan]]; [[Reston, Virginia]], and [[Washington, D.C.]]<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.google.com/about/company/facts/locations/ |title=Google locations |access-date=March 16, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130815024220/https://www.google.com/about/company/facts/locations/ |archive-date=August 15, 2013 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n[[File:Google Headquarters in Ireland Building Sign.jpg|thumb|Google's Dublin Ireland office, headquarters of Google Ads for Europe]]\nIt also has product research and development operations in cities around the world, namely [[Sydney]] (birthplace location of [[Google Maps]])<ref>{{cite web |title=Sydney |url=https://careers.google.com/locations/sydney/ |website=Google Careers |accessdate=June 4, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170505110757/https://careers.google.com/locations/sydney/ |archive-date=May 5, 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref> and [[London]] (part of [[Android (operating system)|Android]] development).<ref>{{cite web |title=London |url=https://careers.google.com/locations/london/ |website=Google Careers |accessdate=June 4, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170214074855/https://careers.google.com/locations/london/ |archive-date=February 14, 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref> In November 2013, Google announced plans for a new [[London]] headquarter, a 1 million square foot office able to accommodate 4,500 employees. Recognized as one of the biggest ever commercial property acquisitions at the time of the deal's announcement in January,<ref>{{cite web |first=Leo |last=Mirani |title=Inside Google's new 1-million-square-foot London office\u2014three years before it's ready |url=https://qz.com/139794/inside-googles-new-1-million-square-foot-london-office-three-years-before-its-ready/ |website=[[Quartz (publication)|Quartz]] |publisher=[[Atlantic Media]] |date=November 1, 2013 |accessdate=March 15, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170316025208/https://qz.com/139794/inside-googles-new-1-million-square-foot-london-office-three-years-before-its-ready/ |archive-date=March 16, 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref> Google submitted plans for the new headquarter to the [[Camden London Borough Council|Camden Council]] in June 2017.<ref>{{cite web |first=James |last=Vincent |title=Google's new London HQ is a 'landscraper' with a rooftop garden |url=https://www.theverge.com/2017/6/1/15723642/google-london-office-pictures-headquarters-kings-cross |website=[[The Verge]] |publisher=[[Vox Media]] |date=June 1, 2017 |accessdate=June 4, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170603164958/https://www.theverge.com/2017/6/1/15723642/google-london-office-pictures-headquarters-kings-cross |archive-date=June 3, 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first=Matt |last=Brian |title=Google's 'innovative' new London HQ features giant moving blinds |url=https://www.engadget.com/2017/06/01/google-london-kings-cross-hq-plans-photos/ |website=[[Engadget]] |publisher=[[AOL]] |date=June 1, 2017 |accessdate=June 4, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170604003356/https://www.engadget.com/2017/06/01/google-london-kings-cross-hq-plans-photos/ |archive-date=June 4, 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref> In May 2015, Google announced its intention to create its own campus in [[Hyderabad]], India. The new campus, reported to be the company's largest outside the United States, will accommodate 13,000 employees.<ref>{{cite web |title=Google to build biggest campus outside US in Hyderabad |url=http://indianexpress.com/article/india/google-to-build-biggest-campus-outside-us-in-hyderabad/ |website=[[The Indian Express]] |date=May 12, 2015 |accessdate=June 13, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151118040601/http://indianexpress.com/article/india/google-to-build-biggest-campus-outside-us-in-hyderabad/ |archive-date=November 18, 2015 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Google's upcoming campus in Hyderabad to be its biggest outside the US |url=http://tech.firstpost.com/news-analysis/googles-upcoming-campus-in-hyderabad-to-be-its-biggest-outside-the-us-267059.html |website=[[Firstpost]] |publisher=[[Network 18]] |date=May 13, 2015 |accessdate=June 13, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161118003932/http://tech.firstpost.com/news-analysis/googles-upcoming-campus-in-hyderabad-to-be-its-biggest-outside-the-us-267059.html |archive-date=November 18, 2016 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Infrastructure===\n{{Further|Google data centers}}\n\n[[Google data centers]] are located in North and South America, Asia, and Europe.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.google.com/about/datacenters/inside/locations/index.html |title=Data center locations |date= |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180517162154/https://www.google.com/about/datacenters/inside/locations/index.html |archive-date=May 17, 2018 |url-status=live |access-date=May 17, 2018}}</ref> There is no official data on the number of [[Server (computing)|servers]] in Google data centers; however, research and advisory firm [[Gartner]] estimated in a July 2016 report that Google at the time had 2.5 million servers.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.datacenterknowledge.com/archives/2017/03/16/google-data-center-faq |title=How Many Servers Does Google Have? |website=Data Center Knowledge |accessdate=September 20, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190217073018/https://www.datacenterknowledge.com/archives/2017/03/16/google-data-center-faq |archive-date=February 17, 2019 |url-status=live|date=March 16, 2017 }}</ref> Traditionally, Google relied on [[parallel computing]] on commodity hardware like mainstream x86 computers (similar to home PCs) to keep costs per query low.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://research.google.com/archive/googlecluster-ieee.pdf |title=Google's Secret: 'Cheap and Fast' Hardware |date=October 10, 2003 |website=PCWorld |accessdate=May 26, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091214182753/http://research.google.com/archive/googlecluster-ieee.pdf |archive-date=December 14, 2009 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last=Barroso |first=L.A. |last2=Dean |first2=J. |last3=Holzle |first3=U. |date=April 29, 2003 |title=Web search for a planet: the google cluster architecture |journal=IEEE Micro |volume=23 |issue=2 |pages=22\u201328 |doi=10.1109/mm.2003.1196112 |issn=0272-1732 |quote=We believe that the best price/performance tradeoff for our applications comes from fashioning a reliable computing infrastructure from clusters of unreliable commodity PCs.|url=https://semanticscholar.org/paper/8db8e53c92af2f97974707119525aa089f6ed53a }}</ref><ref name=\"CNET2009\">{{cite news |url=https://www.cnet.com/news/google-uncloaks-once-secret-server-10209580/ |title=Google uncloaks once-secret server |date=April 1, 2009 |newspaper=CNET |accessdate=May 26, 2018 |quote=Mainstream servers with x86 processors were the only option, he added. \"Ten years ago...it was clear the only way to make (search) work as free product was to run on relatively cheap hardware. You can't run it on a [[mainframe server|mainframe]]. The margins just don't work out,\" he said. |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180606105133/https://www.cnet.com/news/google-uncloaks-once-secret-server-10209580/ |archive-date=June 6, 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref> In 2005, it started developing its own designs, which were only revealed in 2009.<ref name=\"CNET2009\" />\n\nIn the late 2010s, Google began to build its own private [[submarine communications cable]]s. The first, named Curie, connects California with [[Chile]] and is to be completed in 2019.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://venturebeat.com/2019/04/06/google-and-other-tech-giants-are-quietly-buying-up-the-most-important-part-of-the-internet/ |title=Google and other tech giants are quietly buying up the most important part of the internet |date=April 6, 2019 |website=VentureBeat |language=en-US |access-date=April 25, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190425024849/https://venturebeat.com/2019/04/06/google-and-other-tech-giants-are-quietly-buying-up-the-most-important-part-of-the-internet/ |archive-date=April 25, 2019 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref> The second fully Google-owned undersea cable, named Dunant, connects the United States with France and is planned to begin operation in 2020.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://venturebeat.com/2019/04/24/how-google-is-building-its-huge-subsea-cable-infrastructure/ |title=How Google is building its huge subsea cable infrastructure |last=Sawers |first=Paul |date=April 24, 2019 |website=VentureBeat |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190425163121/https://venturebeat.com/2019/04/24/how-google-is-building-its-huge-subsea-cable-infrastructure/ |archive-date=April 25, 2019 |url-status=live |access-date=April 26, 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Environment ===\nIn October 2006, the company announced plans to install thousands of [[solar panel]]s to provide up to 1.6&nbsp;mega[[watt]]s of electricity, enough to satisfy approximately 30% of the campus' energy needs.<ref name=\"solar\">{{cite web |url=http://www.post1.net/lowem/entry/google_plans_to_build_huge |title=Google plans to build huge solar energy system for headquarters |last=Richmond |first=Riva |date=October 17, 2006 |website=post1.net |publisher=[[MarketWatch]] |archiveurl=http://arquivo.pt/wayback/20160519010259/http://www.post1.net/lowem/entry/google_plans_to_build_huge |archivedate=May 19, 2016 |url-status=dead |accessdate=October 17, 2006}}</ref> The system will be the largest [[Rooftop photovoltaic power station|solar power system]] constructed on a U.S. corporate campus and one of the largest on any corporate site in the world.<ref name=\"solar\" /> {{As of|2007|since=y|post=,}} Google has aimed for [[carbon neutrality]] in regard to its operations.<ref>{{cite web |first=Jack |last=McGrath |title=Google's Green Initiative: Environmentally Conscious Technology |url=http://www.technobuffalo.com/2011/05/18/googles-green-initiative-environmentally-conscious-technology/ |publisher=TechnoBuffalo |date=May 18, 2011 |accessdate=January 22, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161012172247/http://www.technobuffalo.com/2011/05/18/googles-green-initiative-environmentally-conscious-technology/ |archive-date=October 12, 2016 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nGoogle disclosed in September 2011 that it \"continuously uses enough electricity to power 200,000 homes\", almost 260 million watts or about a quarter of the output of a nuclear power plant. Total carbon emissions for 2010 were just under 1.5 million metric tons, mostly due to fossil fuels that provide electricity for the data centers. Google said that 25 percent of its energy was supplied by renewable fuels in 2010. An average search uses only 0.3 watt-hours of electricity, so all global searches are only 12.5 million watts or 5% of the total electricity consumption by Google.<ref>{{cite web |first=James |last=Glanz |title=Google Details, and Defends, Its Use of Electricity |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/09/09/technology/google-details-and-defends-its-use-of-electricity.html |website=[[The New York Times]] |date=September 8, 2011 |accessdate=March 9, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170312053616/http://www.nytimes.com/2011/09/09/technology/google-details-and-defends-its-use-of-electricity.html |archive-date=March 12, 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn 2010, [[Google Energy]] made its first investment in a [[renewable energy]] project, putting $38.8&nbsp;million into two [[wind farm]]s in [[North Dakota]]. The company announced the two locations will generate 169.5&nbsp;megawatts of power, enough to supply 55,000 homes.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424052748704342604575222420304732394 |title=Google Invests in Two Wind Farms |last=Morrison |first=Scott |date=May 4, 2010 |newspaper=[[The Wall Street Journal]] |accessdate=November 27, 2010 |last2=Sweet |first2=Cassandra |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150213232857/http://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424052748704342604575222420304732394 |archive-date=February 13, 2015 |url-status=live}}</ref> In February 2010, the [[Federal Energy Regulatory Commission]] FERC granted Google an authorization to buy and sell energy at market rates.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.cnet.com/8301-11128_3-10456435-54.html |title=Google Energy can now buy and sell energy |work=Cnet.com |access-date=September 23, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130919091407/http://news.cnet.com/8301-11128_3-10456435-54.html |archive-date=September 19, 2013 |url-status=live}}</ref> The corporation exercised this authorization in September 2013 when it announced it would purchase all the electricity produced by the not-yet-built 240-megawatt Happy Hereford wind farm.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://qz.com/125407/google-is-on-the-way-to-quietly-becoming-an-electric-utility/ |title=Google is on the way to quietly becoming an electric utility |author=Todd Woody |date=September 18, 2013 |newspaper=Quartz |accessdate=September 23, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130921050811/http://qz.com/125407/google-is-on-the-way-to-quietly-becoming-an-electric-utility/ |archive-date=September 21, 2013 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2010, Google signed an agreement with an Iowa wind farm to buy 114 megawatts of energy for 20 years.<ref name=\"wind energy\">{{cite web |url=http://news.techworld.com/green-it/3232690/google-buys-power-from-iowa-wind-farm/?olo=rss |title=Google buys power from Iowa wind farm |date=July 21, 2010 |website=News.techworld.com |accessdate=October 26, 2010 |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/659XgHPv9?url=http://news.techworld.com/green-it/3232690/google-buys-power-from-iowa-wind-farm/?olo=rss |archive-date=February 2, 2012 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2016, Google announced that\u2014starting in 2017\u2014it will power all of its data centers, as well as all of its offices, from 100% renewable energy. The commitment will make Google \"the world's largest corporate buyer of renewable power, with commitments reaching 2.6 gigawatts (2,600 megawatts) of wind and solar energy\". Google also stated that it does not count that as its final goal; it says that \"since the wind doesn't blow 24 hours a day, we'll also broaden our purchases to a variety of energy sources that can enable renewable power, every hour of every day\". Additionally, the project will \"help support communities\" around the world, as the purchase commitments will \"result in infrastructure investments of more than $3.5 billion globally\", and will \"generate tens of millions of dollars per year in revenue to local property owners, and tens of millions more to local and national governments in tax revenue\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://blog.google/topics/environment/100-percent-renewable-energy/ |title=We're set to reach 100% renewable energy \u2014 and it's just the beginning |last=H\u00f6lzle |first=Urs |date=December 6, 2016 |website=The Keyword Google Blog |accessdate=December 8, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161208102229/https://www.blog.google/topics/environment/100-percent-renewable-energy/ |archive-date=December 8, 2016 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theverge.com/2016/12/6/13852004/google-data-center-oklahoma-renewable-energy-climate-change |title=Google just notched a big victory in the fight against climate change |last=Statt |first=Nick |date=December 6, 2016 |website=[[The Verge]] |publisher=[[Vox Media]] |accessdate=December 8, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161208001307/http://www.theverge.com/2016/12/6/13852004/google-data-center-oklahoma-renewable-energy-climate-change |archive-date=December 8, 2016 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://techcrunch.com/2016/12/06/google-says-it-will-hit-100-renewable-energy-by-2017/ |title=Google says it will hit 100% renewable energy by 2017 |last=Etherington |first=Darrell |date=December 7, 2016 |website=[[TechCrunch]] |publisher=[[AOL]] |accessdate=December 8, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161207164915/https://techcrunch.com/2016/12/06/google-says-it-will-hit-100-renewable-energy-by-2017/ |archive-date=December 7, 2016 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2017, Google bought 536 megawatts of wind power. The purchase made the firm reach 100% renewable energy. The wind energy comes from two power plants in South Dakota, one in Iowa and one in Oklahoma.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://fortune.com/2017/12/01/google-clean-energy/ |title=Google Just Bought Enough Wind Power to Run 100% On Renewable Energy |date=November 30, 2017 |last=Donnelly |first=Grace |work=Fortune |access-date=December 1, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171201172833/http://fortune.com/2017/12/01/google-clean-energy/ |archive-date=December 1, 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2019, Google's chief executive announced plans for a $2 billion wind and solar investment, the biggest renewable energy deal in corporate history. This will grow their green energy profile by 40%, giving them an extra 1.6 gigawatt of clean energy, the company said.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2019/sep/20/google-says-its-energy-deals-will-lead-to-2bn-wind-and-solar-investment|title=Google signs up to $2bn wind and solar investment|last=correspondent|first=Jillian Ambrose Energy|date=2019-09-20|work=The Guardian|access-date=2019-09-25|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n\nGoogle donates to politicians who deny climate change including [[Jim Inhofe]] as well as sponsoring climate change denial political groups including the [[State Policy Network]] and the [[Competitive Enterprise Institute]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://popular.info/p/these-corporations-are-quietly-bankrolling|title=These corporations are quietly bankrolling Congress' top climate denier|last=Legum|first=Judd|website=popular.info|access-date=2020-02-07}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Kirchgaessner|first=Stephanie|url=https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2019/oct/11/google-contributions-climate-change-deniers|title=Revealed: Google made large contributions to climate change deniers|date=2019-10-11|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-02-07|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Kirchgaessner|first=Stephanie|url=https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2019/oct/11/obscure-law-google-climate-deniers-section-230|title=The obscure law that explains why Google backs climate deniers|date=2019-10-11|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-02-07|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n\n=== Philanthropy ===\n{{Main|Google.org}}\n\nIn 2004, Google formed the not-for-profit philanthropic [[Google.org]], with a start-up fund of $1&nbsp;billion.<ref name=\"philanthropy\">{{cite web |url=http://www.google.org/about.html |title=About the Foundation |publisher=Google, Inc. |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100714080922/http://www.google.org/about.html |archivedate=July 14, 2010 |url-status=dead |accessdate=July 16, 2010}}</ref> The mission of the organization is to create awareness about [[climate change]], global public health, and global poverty. One of its first projects was to develop a viable [[plug-in hybrid]] [[electric vehicle]] that can attain 100 miles per gallon. Google hired [[Larry Brilliant]] as the program's executive director in 2004<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/09/14/technology/14google.html |title=Philanthropy Google's Way: Not the Usual |last=Hafner |first=Katie |date=September 14, 2006 |website=[[The New York Times]] |accessdate=March 9, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160723065526/http://www.nytimes.com/2006/09/14/technology/14google.html |archive-date=July 23, 2016 |url-status=live}}</ref> and Megan Smith has {{as of|2009|2|23|alt=since}} replaced him as director.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/02/24/technology/companies/24google.html |title=Google Chief for Charity Steps Down on Revamp |last=Helft |first=Miguel |date=February 23, 2009 |website=[[The New York Times]] |accessdate=March 9, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170422112540/http://www.nytimes.com/2009/02/24/technology/companies/24google.html |archive-date=April 22, 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn 2008, Google announced its \"project 10<sup>100</sup>\" which accepted ideas for how to help the community and then allowed Google users to vote on their favorites.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.project10tothe100.com/ |title=Project 10 to the 100th |publisher=Google, Inc. |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5hT8OddCZ?url=http://www.project10tothe100.com/ |archivedate=June 12, 2009 |url-status=dead |accessdate=July 16, 2010}}</ref> After two years of silence, during which many wondered what had happened to the program,<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.wired.com/epicenter/2010/06/google-struggles-to-give-away-10-million/ |title=Google Struggles to Give Away $10&nbsp;million |last=Van Burskirk |first=Elliot |date=June 28, 2010 |work=[[Wired (website)|Wired]] |accessdate=September 26, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100831172215/http://www.wired.com/epicenter/2010/06/google-struggles-to-give-away-10-million/ |archive-date=August 31, 2010 |url-status=live}}</ref> Google revealed the winners of the project, giving a total of ten million dollars to various ideas ranging from non-profit organizations that promote education to a website that intends to make all legal documents public and online.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://googleblog.blogspot.com/2010/09/10-million-for-project-10100-winners.html |title=$10&nbsp;million for Project 10^100 winners |last=Twohill |first=Lorraine |date=September 24, 2010 |publisher=Google, Inc. |accessdate=September 26, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100926020623/http://googleblog.blogspot.com/2010/09/10-million-for-project-10100-winners.html |archive-date=September 26, 2010 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2007, in partnership with the [[Mathematical Sciences Research Institute]] (MSRI), Google hosted the first [[Julia Robinson Mathematics Festival]] at its headquarters in Mountain View.<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=qDL7yoz1TGQ The 2007] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181120090220/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=qDL7yoz1TGQ |date=November 20, 2018 }} [[Julia Robinson Mathematics Festival]]at Google was the founding of this event for middle school and high school students. video</ref> In 2011, Google donated 1&nbsp;million euros to [[International Mathematical Olympiad]] to support the next five annual International Mathematical Olympiads (2011\u20132015).<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.pcmag.com/article2/0,2817,2376099,00.asp |title=Mathletes Receive \u20ac1M Donation from Google |last=Duffy |first=Jill |date=January 21, 2011 |website=[[PC Magazine]] |publisher=[[Ziff Davis]] |accessdate=March 23, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170323234649/http://www.pcmag.com/article2/0,2817,2376099,00.asp |archive-date=March 23, 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.imo2011.nl/node/39 |title=Google donating 1&nbsp;million euros to IMO |date=January 20, 2011 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110724154518/https://www.imo2011.nl/node/39 |archivedate=July 24, 2011 |url-status=dead |accessdate=February 4, 2011}}</ref> In July 2012, Google launched a \"[[Legalize Love]]\" campaign in support of [[gay rights]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.pinknews.co.uk/2012/07/08/google-launches-legalise-love-gay-rights-campaign/ |title=Google launches 'Legalise Love' gay rights campaign |website=PinkNews.co.uk |accessdate=September 9, 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140819044558/http://www.pinknews.co.uk/2012/07/08/google-launches-legalise-love-gay-rights-campaign/ |archive-date=August 19, 2014 |url-status=live|date=July 8, 2012 }}</ref>\n\n== Criticism and controversy ==\n{{main|Criticism of Google|Censorship by Google|Privacy concerns regarding Google}}{{summarize|from|Criticism of Google|better=y|section=y|date=April 2019}}\n\n[[File:Google bus protest.jpg|thumb|San Francisco activists [[San Francisco tech bus protests|protest privately owned shuttle buses]] that transport workers for tech companies such as Google from their homes in San Francisco and Oakland to corporate campuses in Silicon Valley.]]\nGoogle's market dominance has led to prominent media coverage, including [[Criticism of Google|criticism of the company]] over issues such as [[Google tax avoidance|aggressive tax avoidance]],<ref>{{cite web |first=Jesse |last=Drucker |title=Google 2.4% Rate Shows How $60 Billion Is Lost to Tax Loopholes |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2010-10-21/google-2-4-rate-shows-how-60-billion-u-s-revenue-lost-to-tax-loopholes |website=[[Bloomberg Businessweek]] |publisher=[[Bloomberg L.P.]] |date=October 21, 2010 |accessdate=January 22, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160922035532/http://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2010-10-21/google-2-4-rate-shows-how-60-billion-u-s-revenue-lost-to-tax-loopholes |archive-date=September 22, 2016 |url-status=live}}{{subscription required}}</ref> [[Criticism of Google#Page rank|search neutrality]], [[Criticism of Google#Copyright issues|copyright]], [[censorship by Google|censorship]] of search results and content,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/02/20/magazine/the-case-against-google.html |title=The Case Against Google |website=nytimes.com |date=February 20, 2018 |accessdate=March 21, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180319192049/https://www.nytimes.com/2018/02/20/magazine/the-case-against-google.html |archive-date=March 19, 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref> and [[Google privacy|privacy]].<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/technology/6740075.stm |work=BBC News |title=Google ranked 'worst' on privacy |date=June 11, 2007 |accessdate=April 30, 2010 |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6BYbPRqrU?url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/technology/6740075.stm |archive-date=October 20, 2012 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first=Jeffrey |last=Rosen |title=Google's Gatekeepers |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/11/30/magazine/30google-t.html |website=[[The New York Times]] |date=November 28, 2008 |accessdate=March 9, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170228140546/http://www.nytimes.com/2008/11/30/magazine/30google-t.html |archive-date=February 28, 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref> Other criticisms include alleged misuse and manipulation of search results, its use of others' [[intellectual property]], concerns that its [[Data collection|compilation of data]] may violate people's [[Internet privacy|privacy]], and the [[energy consumption]] of its servers, as well as concerns over traditional business issues such as [[monopoly]], [[restraint of trade]], [[anti-competitive practices]], and [[patent infringement]].\n\nGoogle formerly adhered to the [[Internet censorship in the People's Republic of China|Internet censorship policies of China]],<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/technology/4645596.stm |title=Google censors itself for China |date=January 25, 2006 |work=BBC News |access-date=August 4, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181119073206/http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/technology/4645596.stm |archive-date=November 19, 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref> enforced by means of filters colloquially known as \"The [[Great Firewall of China]]\", but [[Censorship by Google#China|no longer does so]]. As a result, all Google services except for Chinese Google Maps are blocked from access within mainland China without the aid of VPNs, proxy servers, or other similar technologies. ''The Intercept'' reported in August 2018 that Google is developing for the People's Republic of China a censored version of its search engine (known as [[Dragonfly (search engine)|Dragonfly]]) \"that will blacklist websites and search terms about human rights, democracy, religion, and peaceful protest\".<ref>{{cite news |title=Google Plans to Launch Censored Search Engine in China, Leaked Documents Reveal \u00b7 Ryan Gallagher |url=https://theintercept.com/2018/08/01/google-china-search-engine-censorship/ |work=The Intercept |date=August 1, 2018 |access-date=August 4, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180801120009/https://theintercept.com/2018/08/01/google-china-search-engine-censorship/ |archive-date=August 1, 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last=Disis |first=Jill |title=Google grilled over 'Project Dragonfly' at Senate hearing on data privacy |date=September 26, 2018 |newspaper=CNN |url=https://money.cnn.com/2018/09/26/technology/google-dragonfly-senate-hearing/index.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180926222719/https://money.cnn.com/2018/09/26/technology/google-dragonfly-senate-hearing/index.html |archive-date=September 26, 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref> However, the project had been withheld due to privacy concerns.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://theintercept.com/2018/12/17/google-china-censored-search-engine-2/ |title=Google's Secret China Project \"Effectively Ended\" After Internal Confrontation |last=Gallagher |first=Ryan |date=December 17, 2018 |website=The Intercept |language=en-US |access-date=December 17, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190321020856/https://theintercept.com/2018/12/17/google-china-censored-search-engine-2/ |archive-date=March 21, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nFollowing media reports about [[PRISM (surveillance program)|PRISM]], NSA's massive electronic [[Mass surveillance|surveillance program]], in June 2013, several technology companies were identified as participants, including Google.<ref>{{cite web |title=Edward Snowden: Leaks that exposed US spy programme |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-23123964 |website=[[BBC News]] |date=January 17, 2014 |accessdate=March 25, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170320171345/http://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-23123964 |archive-date=March 20, 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref> According to leaks of said program, Google joined the PRISM program in 2009.<ref>{{cite web |first=Glenn |last=Greenwald |first2=Ewen |last2=MacAskill |title=NSA Prism program taps in to user data of Apple, Google and others |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2013/jun/06/us-tech-giants-nsa-data |website=[[The Guardian]] |publisher=[[Guardian Media Group]] |date=June 7, 2013 |accessdate=March 25, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060818114650/http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/2013/jun/06/us-tech-giants-nsa-data |archive-date=August 18, 2006 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nGoogle has worked with the [[United States Department of Defense]] on drone software through the 2017 \"Project Maven\" that could be used to improve the accuracy of [[drone strike]]s.<ref>\"[https://arstechnica.com/gadgets/2018/04/google-should-not-be-in-the-business-of-war-googlers-decry-pentagon-project/ Google employees revolt, say company should shut down military drone project] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180408141509/https://arstechnica.com/gadgets/2018/04/google-should-not-be-in-the-business-of-war-googlers-decry-pentagon-project/ |date=April 8, 2018 }}\". ''[[Ars Technica]]''. April 4, 2018.</ref> Thousands of Google employees, including senior engineers, have signed a letter urging Google CEO [[Sundar Pichai]] to end a controversial contract with the Pentagon.<ref>\"[https://www.independent.co.uk/news/business/news/google-protest-pentagon-drones-programme-company-sundar-pichai-department-of-defense-a8290111.html Google staff protest company's involvement with Pentagon drones programme] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180409174803/https://www.independent.co.uk/news/business/news/google-protest-pentagon-drones-programme-company-sundar-pichai-department-of-defense-a8290111.html |date=April 9, 2018 }}\". ''The Independent''. April 4, 2018.</ref> In response to the backlash, Google ultimately decided to not renew their DoD contract, set to expire in 2019.<ref>{{cite web |author1=Wakabayashi, Daisuke |author2=Shane, Scott |title=Google Will Not Renew Pentagon Contract That Upset Employees |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/06/01/technology/google-pentagon-project-maven.html |website=nytimes.com |publisher=The New York Times Company |accessdate=October 16, 2018 |date=June 1, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181016004020/https://www.nytimes.com/2018/06/01/technology/google-pentagon-project-maven.html |archive-date=October 16, 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nShona Ghosh, a journalist for [[Business Insider]], noted that an increasing digital [[resistance movement]] against Google has grown. A major hub for critics of Google in order to organize to abstain from using Google products is the [[Reddit]] page for the [[subreddit]] /r/degoogle.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.businessinsider.com/profile-reddit-de-google-community-2019-3 |title=Thousands of Reddit users are trying to delete Google from their lives, but they're finding it impossible because Google is everywhere |access-date=April 24, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190325123426/https://www.businessinsider.com/profile-reddit-de-google-community-2019-3/ |archive-date=March 25, 2019 |url-status=live|date=March 23, 2019 }}</ref>\n\nIn July 2018, Mozilla Program Manager Chris Peterson accused Google of intentionally slowing down YouTube performance on Firefox.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pcmag.com/news/362696/mozilla-developer-claims-google-is-slowing-youtube-on-firefo|title=Mozilla Developer Claims Google Is Slowing YouTube on Firefox|last=Kan|first=By Michael|last2=July 25|first2=2018 12:39PM EST|website=PCMAG|language=en|access-date=2019-08-13|last3=July 25|first3=2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190813134744/https://www.pcmag.com/news/362696/mozilla-developer-claims-google-is-slowing-youtube-on-firefo|archive-date=August 13, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2019 former [[Mozilla]] executive Jonathan Nightingale accused Google of intentionally and systematically sabotaging the [[Firefox]] browser over the past decade in order to boost [[Google Chrome|Chrome's]] adoption.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.zdnet.com/article/former-mozilla-exec-google-has-sabotaged-firefox-for-years/|title=Former Mozilla exec: Google has sabotaged Firefox for years|last=Cimpanu|first=Catalin|website=ZDNet|language=en|access-date=2019-08-13|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190819235446/https://www.zdnet.com/article/former-mozilla-exec-google-has-sabotaged-firefox-for-years/|archive-date=August 19, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2019, the Office for Civil Rights of the [[Department of Health and Human Services]] began investigation into [[Project Nightingale]], to assess whether the \"mass collection of individuals\u2019 medical records\" complied with [[Health Insurance Portability and Accountability Act|HIPAA]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/behind-googles-project-nightingale-a-health-data-gold-mine-of-50-million-patients-11573571867|title=Google's 'Project Nightingale' Triggers Federal Inquiry|last1=Copeland|first1=Rob|date=November 12, 2019|accessdate=November 18, 2019}}</ref> According to''The Wall Street Journal'', Google commenced the project in secret, in 2018, with [[St. Louis]]-based [[healthcare]] company [[Ascension (company)|Ascension]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/google-s-secret-project-nightingale-gathers-personal-health-data-on-millions-of-americans-11573496790|title=Google's 'Project Nightingale' Gathers Personal Health Data on Millions of Americans|last1=Copeland|first1=Rob|date=November 11, 2019|accessdate=November 17, 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Litigation ===\n{{main|Google litigation}}\n\nGoogle has been involved in a number of lawsuits including the [[High-Tech Employee Antitrust Litigation]] which resulted in Google being one of four companies to pay a $415 million settlement to employees.<ref>{{cite news |last=Rosenblatt |first=Joel |title=Apple-Google $415 Million No-Poaching Accord Wins Approval |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2015-03-02/tech-no-poaching-settlement-gets-judge-s-preliminary-approval |accessdate=January 24, 2016 |publisher=[[Bloomberg L.P.]] |date=March 2, 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160130214110/http://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2015-03-02/tech-no-poaching-settlement-gets-judge-s-preliminary-approval |archive-date=January 30, 2016 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn June 27, 2017, the company received a record fine of {{\u20ac|2.42 billion|link=yes}} from the [[European Union]] for \"promoting its own shopping comparison service at the top of search results.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/technology-40406542 |title=Google hit with record EU fine over Shopping service |first=Leo |last=Kelion |date=June 27, 2017 |publisher=bbc.co.uk |accessdate=June 29, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170627100311/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/technology-40406542 |archive-date=June 27, 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref> Commenting on the penalty, ''[[New Scientist]]'' magazine said: \"The hefty sum \u2013 the largest ever doled out by the EU's competition regulators \u2013 will sting in the short term, but Google can handle it. Alphabet, Google\u2019s parent company, made a profit of $2.5 billion (\u20ac2.2 billion) in the first six weeks of 2017 alone. The real impact of the ruling is that Google must stop using its dominance as a search engine to give itself the edge in another market: online price comparisons.\" The company disputed the ruling.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.newscientist.com/article/2139097-googles-e2-4bn-fine-is-small-change-the-eu-has-bigger-plans/ |title=Google's \u20ac2.4bn fine is small change \u2013 the EU has bigger plans |publisher=newscientist.com |accessdate=June 29, 2017 |archive-url=https://archive.today/20190124095546/https://www.newscientist.com/article/2139097-googles-e2-4bn-fine-is-small-change-the-eu-has-bigger-plans/ |archive-date=January 24, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> The hearing at the General Court of Luxembourg was scheduled for 2020. The court is going to deliver the ultimate judgment by the end of the year.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/technology-51462397?intlink_from_url=https://www.bbc.com/news/technology&link_location=live-reporting-story|title=Google starts appeal against \u00a32bn shopping fine|last=|first=|date=12 February 2020|website=BBC News|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nOn July 18, 2018,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://europa.eu/rapid/press-release_IP-17-685_hr.htm |title=Antitrust: Commission fines Google \u20ac4.34 billion for illegal practices regarding Android mobile devices to strengthen dominance of Google's search engine |location=Bruxelles |date=July 18, 2018 |website=European Commission |archive-url=https://archive.today/20180718112553/http://europa.eu/rapid/press-release_IP-18-4581_en.htm |archive-date=July 18, 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref> the [[European Commissioner for Competition|European Commission]] fined Google \u20ac4.34 billion for breaching EU antitrust rules. The abuse of dominant position has been referred to Google's constraint applied on Android device manufacturers and network operators to ensure that traffic on Android devices goes to the Google search engine. On October 9, 2018, Google confirmed<ref>{{cite web |url=https://apnews.com/f9797e4935c1464f8f6010793ded7c1d |title=Google appeals $5 billion EU fine in Android antitrust case |website=[[APNews.com]] |date=October 10, 2018 |language=en |location=Bruxelles |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181010101238/https://apnews.com/f9797e4935c1464f8f6010793ded7c1d |archive-date=October 10, 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref> that it had appealed the fine to the [[General Court (European Union)|General Court]] of the European Union.<ref>{{cite news |author=Foo Yun Chee |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-eu-alphabet-inc-antitrust/google-challenges-record-5-billion-eu-antitrust-fine-idUSKCN1MJ2CA |title=Google challenges record $5 billion EU antitrust fine |date=May 13, 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181222061539/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-eu-google-dataprotection/european-court-says-google-must-respect-right-to-be-forgotten-idUSBREA4C07120140513 |archive-date=December 22, 2018 |url-status=live|newspaper=Reuters }}</ref>\n\nOn January 21, 2019, French data regulator [[CNIL]] imposed a record \u20ac50 million fine on Google for breaching the European Union's [[General Data Protection Regulation]]. The judgment claimed Google had failed to sufficiently inform users of its methods for collecting data to personalize advertising. Google issued a statement saying it was \u201cdeeply committed\u201d to transparency and was \u201cstudying the decision\u201d before determining its response.<ref>{{cite web |last=Fox |first=Chris |title=Google hit with \u00a344m GDPR fine |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/technology-46944696 |website=BBC |accessdate=January 22, 2019 |date=January 21, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190121231240/https://www.bbc.com/news/technology-46944696 |archive-date=January 21, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn March 20, 2019, the European Commission imposed a \u20ac1.49 billion ($1.69 billion) fine on Google for preventing rivals from being able to \u201ccompete and innovate fairly\u201d in the online advertising market.<ref>{{cite web |title=Europe hits Google with a third, $1.7 billion antitrust fine |url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/03/20/tech/google-eu-antitrust/index.html |website=CNN |accessdate=March 21, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190320133734/https://www.cnn.com/2019/03/20/tech/google-eu-antitrust/index.html |archive-date=March 20, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> European Union competition commissioner Margrethe Vestager said Google had violated EU antitrust rules by \u201cimposing anti-competitive contractual restrictions on third-party websites\u201d that required them to exclude search results from Google's rivals. Kent Walker, Google's senior vice-president of global affairs, said the company had \u201calready made a wide range of changes to our products to address the Commission\u2019s concerns,\u201d and that \"we'll be making further updates to give more visibility to rivals in Europe.\"<ref>{{cite web |last=Reid |first=David |title=EU regulators hit Google with $1.7 billion fine for blocking ad rivals |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2019/03/20/eu-vestager-hits-google-with-fine-for.html |website=CNBC.com |accessdate=March 20, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190320155204/https://www.cnbc.com/2019/03/20/eu-vestager-hits-google-with-fine-for.html |archive-date=March 20, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn July 25, 2019, presidential hopeful [[Tulsi Gabbard]] sued Google for blocking her ads after the presidential debate when she became one of the most searched items on the search engine.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://thehill.com/policy/technology/454746-tulsi-gabbard-sues-google-over-censorship-claims | title=Tulsi Gabbard sues Google over censorship claims| date=2019-07-25}}</ref>\n\n===DeGoogle movement===\n{{main| DeGoogle}}\nThe term \"[[DeGoogle]]\" has grown in use as [[privacy]] activists urge users to stop using Google products entirely due to [[Privacy concerns regarding Google|growing privacy concerns]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.businessinsider.com/profile-reddit-de-google-community-2019-3|title=Thousands of Reddit users are trying to delete Google from their lives, but they're finding it impossible because Google is everywhere|date=2019-03-23}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://gizmodo.com/i-cut-google-out-of-my-life-it-screwed-up-everything-1830565500|title=I Cut Google Out Of My Life. It Screwed Up Everything}}</ref> The term refers to the act of removing Google from your life.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Outline of Google]]\n* [[History of Google]]\n* [[List of mergers and acquisitions by Alphabet]]\n* [[List of Google products]]\n* [[Google China]]\n* [[Google logo]]\n* [[Googlization]]\n* [[Google.org]]\n* [[Google ATAP]]\n{{Portal bar|Internet|Companies|San Francisco Bay Area|Technology|Computer programming}}\n\n== Notes ==\n{{Notelist}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n* {{cite book |title=The Mobile Wave: How Mobile Intelligence Will Change Everything |last=Saylor |first=Michael |authorlink=Michael J. Saylor |year=2012 |publisher=Perseus Books/Vanguard Press |isbn=978-1593157203 |ref=none}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{sisterlinks|n=Category:Google|s=no|b=Google Services And Products|voy=no|species=no|d=Q95|m=Google}}\n* {{Official website}}\n** [https://www.google.com/about/company/facts/management Corporate homepage]\n* {{Cite web |url=http://google.stanford.edu/ |title=Google website |access-date=September 28, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/19981111183552/http://google.stanford.edu/ |archive-date=November 11, 1998 |url-status=dead}}\n* {{cite journal |last=Carr |first=David F. |title=How Google Works |journal=Baseline Magazine |volume=6 |issue=6 |year=2006 |url=http://www.baselinemag.com/c/a/Infrastructure/How-Google-Works-1}}\n* {{Crunchbase|google|Google}}\n* {{OpenCorp|Google|Google}}\n{{Finance links\n|name = Google, Inc.\n|symbol = GOOG\n|bloomberg = GOOG:US\n|reuters = GOOG.OQ\n|sec_cik = 1288776\n|nasdaq = GOOG\n|hoovers = Google_Inc.fb3f79c4d1791506\n}}\n{{Google LLC|corporate=yes|products=yes}}\n{{Alphabet Inc.}}\n{{Navboxes|list1=\n{{Open Handset Alliance Members}}\n{{Google Lunar X Prize}}\n{{Major mobile device companies}}\n{{Major Internet companies}}\n{{Major software companies}}\n{{Prince of Asturias Award for Communication and Humanities}}\n}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Google]]\n[[Category:1998 establishments in California]]\n[[Category:2004 initial public offerings]]\n[[Category:Alphabet Inc.]]\n[[Category:Artificial intelligence]]\n[[Category:Cloud computing providers]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Mountain View, California]]\n[[Category:Companies in the PRISM network]]\n[[Category:Computer companies established in 1998]]\n[[Category:Computer-related introductions in 1998]]\n[[Category:Internet properties established in 1998]]\n[[Category:Mobile phone manufacturers]]\n[[Category:Multinational companies headquartered in the United States]]\n[[Category:Technology companies based in the San Francisco Bay Area]]\n[[Category:Technology companies established in 1998]]\n[[Category:University spin-offs]]\n[[Category:Virtual reality companies]]\n[[Category:Web portals]]\n[[Category:Web service providers]]\n[[Category:Webby Award winners]]\n[[Category:World Wide Web]]\n[[Category:Eyewear companies of the United States]]\n[[Category:American corporate subsidiaries]]\n", "text_old": "{{About|the company|the search engine|Google Search|other uses}}\n{{Distinguish|Googol|Goggles}}\n{{pp-semi-indef}}\n{{pp-move-indef}}\n{{short description|American multinational Internet and technology corporation}}\n{{Use American English|date=July 2018}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2019}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name = Google LLC\n| logo = Google 2015 logo.svg\n| logo_size = 250px\n| logo_alt = Each letter of \"Google\" is colored (from left to right) in blue, red, yellow, blue, green, and red.\n| logo_caption = Google's logo {{as of|2015|lc=y|since=y}}\n| image = Googleplex HQ (cropped).jpg\n| image_size = 250px\n| image_caption = Google's headquarters, the [[Googleplex]]\n| former_name = Google Inc. (1998\u20132017)\n| type = [[Subsidiary]]\n| industry = {{Unbulleted list\n| [[Internet]]  \n| [[Cloud computing]]\n| [[Computer software]]\n| [[Computer hardware]]\n| [[Artificial intelligence]]\n| [[Advertising]]\n}}\n| founded = {{Start date and age|1998|09|04}}{{efn|Google was originally incorporated on September 4, 1998, however, since 2002, the company has celebrated its anniversaries on various days in September, most frequently on September 27.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://time.com/3250807/google-anniversary/ |title=Google Used to Be the Company That Did 'Nothing But Search' |first=Alex |last=Fitzpatrick |date=September 4, 2014 |website=[[Time (magazine)|Time]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/technology/2019/09/27/when-is-googles-21st-birthday-doodle/ |title=When is Google's birthday \u2013 and why are people confused? |author=Telegraph Reporters |date=September 27, 2019 |website=[[The Daily Telegraph|The Telegraph]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/life-style/gadgets-and-tech/google-birthday-surprise-spinner-date-problem-start-company-a7968951.html |title=Google birthday: The one big problem with the company's celebratory doodle |first=Andrew |last=Griffin |date=September 27, 2019 |website=[[The Independent]]}}</ref> The shift in dates reportedly happened to celebrate index-size milestones in tandem with the birthday.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/business/2008/sep/05/google.mediabusiness |title=Happy birthday Google |first=Richard |last=Wray |date=September 5, 2008 |website=[[The Guardian]]}}</ref>}} in [[Menlo Park, California|Menlo Park]], California, U.S.\n| founders = {{Unbulleted list\n| [[Larry Page]]\n| [[Sergey Brin]]\n}}\n| defunct = \n| hq_location = 1600 Amphitheatre Parkway\n| hq_location_city = [[Mountain View, California]]\n| hq_location_country = U.S.\n| area_served = Worldwide\n| key_people = {{Unbulleted list\n| [[Sundar Pichai]] ([[Chief executive officer|CEO]])\n| [[Ruth Porat]] ([[Chief financial officer|CFO]])\n}}\n| products = [[List of Google products]]\n| num_employees = 114,096\n| num_employees_year = {{As of|2019|9|30|alt=Q3 2019}}\n| parent = [[Alphabet Inc.]] (2015\u2013present)\n| subsid = [[List of mergers and acquisitions by Alphabet|List of subsidiaries]]\n| website = {{URL|https://www.google.com/|google.com}}\n| footnotes = <ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.google.com/intl/en/about/company/ |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150116073513/https://www.google.com/intl/en/about/company/ |url-status=dead |archive-date=January 16, 2015 |title=Company \u2013 Google |date=January 16, 2015 |access-date=September 13, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first=Thomas |last=Claburn |title=Google Founded By Sergey Brin, Larry Page... And Hubert Chang?!? |url=https://www.informationweek.com/applications/google-founded-by-sergey-brin-larry-page-and-hubert-chang!/d/d-id/1072309 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110628231125/http://www.informationweek.com/news/internet/google/210603678 |website=[[InformationWeek]] |publisher=[[UBM plc]] |date=September 24, 2008 |archivedate=June 28, 2011 |accessdate=January 22, 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.google.com/about/jobs/locations/ |title=Locations&nbsp;\u2014 Google Jobs |accessdate=September 27, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130930200600/http://www.google.com/about/jobs/locations/ |archive-date=September 30, 2013 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"EmployeesAsOf2018Q4\">{{cite press release |date=February 4, 2019 |title=Alphabet Announces Fourth Quarter 2018 Results |url=https://abc.xyz/investor/static/pdf/2018Q4_alphabet_earnings_release.pdf |url-status=live |type=Press release |location=Mountain View, California |publisher=[[Alphabet Inc.]] |page=1 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190204221316/https://abc.xyz/investor/static/pdf/2018Q4_alphabet_earnings_release.pdf |archive-date=February 4, 2019 |access-date=February 4, 2019 |quote=Alphabet Inc. (NASDAQ: GOOG, GOOGL) today announced financial results for the quarter and fiscal year ended December 31, 2018.&nbsp;[...] Q1 2018 financial highlights[:] The following summarizes our consolidated financial results for the quarters ended December 31, 2017 and 2018&nbsp;[...]:&nbsp;[...] Number of employees [as of] Three Months Ended December 31, 2018 [is] 98,771[.]}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''Google LLC''' is an American multinational technology company that specializes in Internet-related services and products, which include [[online advertising|online advertising technologies]], a [[search engine]], [[cloud computing]], software, and hardware. It is considered one of the [[Big Four tech companies|Big Four]] [[List of public corporations by market capitalization|technology companies]], alongside [[Amazon (company)|Amazon]], [[Apple Inc.|Apple]], and [[Microsoft]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.barrons.com/articles/ranking-the-big-four-internet-stocks-google-is-no-1-apple-comes-in-last-1503412102 |title=Ranking The Big Four Tech Stocks: Google Is No. 1, Apple Comes In Last |last=Rivas |first=Teresa |website=www.barrons.com |language=en-US |access-date=December 27, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181228082808/https://www.barrons.com/articles/ranking-the-big-four-internet-stocks-google-is-no-1-apple-comes-in-last-1503412102 |archive-date=December 28, 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/opinion/articles/2017-10-31/the-big-four-of-technology|title=The Big Four of Technology|last=Ritholtz|first=Barry|date=2017-10-31|website=Bloomberg|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190626024146/https://www.bloomberg.com/opinion/articles/2017-10-31/the-big-four-of-technology|archive-date=2019-06-26|access-date=2018-12-27}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web url=https://whatis.techtarget.com/definition/GAFA|title=What is GAFA (the big four)? -\nDefinition from WhatIs.com|website=WhatIs.com|language=en|access-date=2020-03-05}}</ref>\n\nGoogle was founded in September 1998 by [[Larry Page]] and [[Sergey Brin]] while they were Ph.D. students at [[Stanford University]] in [[California]]. Together they own about 14 percent of its shares and control 56 percent of the stockholder voting power through [[Preferred stock|supervoting]] stock. They incorporated Google as a California privately held company on September 4, 1998, in California. Google was then reincorporated in Delaware on October 22, 2002.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://businesssearch.sos.ca.gov/Document/RetrievePDF?Id=02474131-5043839|title=Business Entity Filing|last=|first=|date=October 7, 2002|website=Business Search|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190814022055/https://businesssearch.sos.ca.gov/Document/RetrievePDF?Id=02474131-5043839|archive-date=August 14, 2019|url-status=live|access-date=August 14, 2019}}</ref> An initial public offering (IPO) took place on August 19, 2004, and Google moved to its headquarters in Mountain View, California, nicknamed the  [[Googleplex]]. In August 2015, Google announced plans to reorganize its various interests as a conglomerate called [[Alphabet Inc.]] Google is Alphabet's leading subsidiary and will continue to be the umbrella company for Alphabet's Internet interests. [[Sundar Pichai]] was appointed CEO of Google, replacing Larry Page who became the CEO of Alphabet.\n\nThe company's rapid growth since incorporation has triggered a chain of products, acquisitions, and partnerships beyond Google's core search engine ([[Google Search]]). It offers services designed for work and productivity ([[Google Docs]], [[Google Sheets]], and [[Google Slides]]), email ([[Gmail]]), scheduling and time management ([[Google Calendar]]), cloud storage ([[Google Drive]]), instant messaging and video chat ([[Google Duo|Duo]], [[Hangouts]]), language translation ([[Google Translate]]), mapping and navigation ([[Google Maps]], [[Waze]], [[Google Earth]], [[Street View]]), video sharing ([[YouTube]]), note-taking ([[Google Keep]]), and photo organizing and editing ([[Google Photos]]). The company leads the development of the [[Android (operating system)|Android]] mobile operating system, the [[Google Chrome]] web browser, and [[Chrome OS]], a lightweight operating system based on the Chrome browser. Google has moved increasingly into hardware; from 2010 to 2015, it partnered with major electronics manufacturers in the production of its [[Google Nexus|Nexus]] devices, and it released multiple hardware products in October 2016, including the [[Pixel (smartphone)|Google Pixel]] smartphone, [[Google Home]] smart speaker, [[Google Wifi (router)|Google Wifi]] mesh wireless router, and [[Google Daydream]] virtual reality headset. Google has also experimented with becoming an Internet carrier ([[Google Fiber]], [[Google Fi]], and [[Google Station]]).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theverge.com/2016/9/27/13070922/google-station-public-wi-fi-india|title=Google Station is a new platform that aims to make public Wi-Fi better|last=Byford|first=Sam|date=2016-09-27|website=The Verge|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170903210758/https://www.theverge.com/2016/9/27/13070922/google-station-public-wi-fi-india|archive-date=2017-09-03|access-date=2018-05-22}}</ref>\n\nGoogle.com is the most visited website in the world.<ref name=\"Alexa\"/> Several other Google services also figure in the top 100 most visited websites, including [[YouTube]] and [[Blogger (service)|Blogger]]. Google was the most valuable brand in the world {{as of|2017|lc=y|post=,}}<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/business/news/worlds-most-valuable-brands-facebook-google-apple-amazon-a7556571.html |title=Google is now the world's most valuable brand |date=February 1, 2017 |work=The Independent |access-date=August 31, 2017 |language=en-GB |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170831172223/http://www.independent.co.uk/news/business/news/worlds-most-valuable-brands-facebook-google-apple-amazon-a7556571.html |archive-date=August 31, 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref> but has received significant [[Criticism of Google|criticism]] involving issues such as [[Privacy concerns regarding Google|privacy concerns]], tax avoidance, antitrust, [[Censorship by Google|censorship]], and search neutrality. Google's [[mission statement]] is \"to organize the world's information and make it universally accessible and useful\". The company's unofficial slogan \"[[Don't be evil]]\" was removed from the company's code of conduct around May 2018, but reinstated by July 31, 2018.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web |url=https://abc.xyz/investor/other/google-code-of-conduct.html |title=Google Code of Conduct |publisher=Alphabet |accessdate=August 31, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170211223917/https://abc.xyz/investor/other/google-code-of-conduct.html |archive-date=February 11, 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://gizmodo.com/google-removes-nearly-all-mentions-of-dont-be-evil-from-1826153393 |title=Google Removes 'Don't Be Evil' Clause From Its Code of Conduct |first=Kate |last=Conger |access-date=May 24, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180525002631/https://gizmodo.com/google-removes-nearly-all-mentions-of-dont-be-evil-from-1826153393 |archive-date=May 25, 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\n{{Main|History of Google|List of mergers and acquisitions by Alphabet}}\n{{See also|Alphabet Inc.}}\n\n=== Early years ===\n[[File:Google page brin.jpg|thumb|[[Larry Page]] and [[Sergey Brin]] in 2003|alt=|left]]\nGoogle began in January 1996 as a research project by [[Larry Page]] and [[Sergey Brin]] when they were both PhD students at [[Stanford University]] in [[Stanford, California]].<ref name=\"milestones\">{{cite web |title=Our history in depth |url=https://www.google.com/about/company/history/ |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120401005940/http://www.google.com/about/company/history/ |website=Google Company |archivedate=April 1, 2012 |accessdate=July 15, 2017 |url-status=dead}}</ref> The project initially involved an unofficial \"third founder\", Scott Hassan, the original lead programmer who wrote much of the code for the original [[Google Search]] engine, but he left before Google was officially founded as a company;<ref name=\"vanityfair\">{{cite web |last=Fisher |first=Adam |title=Brin, Page, and Mayer on the Accidental Birth of the Company that Changed Everything |url=https://www.vanityfair.com/news/2018/07/valley-of-genius-excerpt-google |website=[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]] |date=July 10, 2018 |accessdate=23 August 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190704184309/https://www.vanityfair.com/news/2018/07/valley-of-genius-excerpt-google |archive-date=July 4, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=McHugh |first=Josh |title=Google vs. Evil |url=https://www.wired.com/2003/01/google-10/ |accessdate=24 August 2019 |work=[[Wired (magazine)|Wired]] |date=1 January 2003 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190602064540/https://www.wired.com/2003/01/google-10/ |archive-date=June 2, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> Hassan went on to pursue a career in [[robotics]] and founded the company [[Willow Garage]] in 2006.<ref>{{cite news |title=Willow Garage Founder Scott Hassan Aims To Build A Startup Village |url=https://spectrum.ieee.org/view-from-the-valley/at-work/start-ups/willow-garage-founder-scott-hassan-aims-to-build-a-startup-village |accessdate=1 September 2019 |work=[[IEEE Spectrum]] |date=5 September 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190824075356/https://spectrum.ieee.org/view-from-the-valley/at-work/start-ups/willow-garage-founder-scott-hassan-aims-to-build-a-startup-village |archive-date=August 24, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=D'Onfro |first=Jillian |title=How a billionaire who wrote Google's original code created a robot revolution |url=https://www.businessinsider.com/a-look-back-at-willow-garage-2016-2 |work=[[Business Insider]] |date=February 13, 2016 |access-date=August 24, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190824075346/https://www.businessinsider.com/a-look-back-at-willow-garage-2016-2 |archive-date=August 24, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nWhile conventional search engines ranked results by counting how many times the search terms appeared on the page, they theorized about a better system that analyzed the relationships among websites.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ilpubs.stanford.edu:8090/422/|title=The PageRank Citation Ranking: Bringing Order to the Web|last=Page|first=Lawrence|authorlink=Larry Page|last2=Brin|first2=Sergey|authorlink2=Sergey Brin|date=November 11, 1999|website=Stanford University|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091118014915/http://ilpubs.stanford.edu:8090/422/|archive-date=November 18, 2009|access-date=February 15, 2010|last3=Motwani|first3=Rajeev|last4=Winograd|first4=Terry}}</ref> They called this algorithm [[PageRank]]; it determined a website's [[Relevance (information retrieval)|relevance]] by the number of pages, and the importance of those pages that linked back to the original site.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.google.com/corporate/tech.html |title=Technology Overview |website=Google, Inc. |accessdate=February 15, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100210175913/http://www.google.com/corporate/tech.html |archive-date=February 10, 2010 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www-diglib.stanford.edu/cgi-bin/WP/get/SIDL-WP-1997-0072?1|title=PageRank: Bringing Order to the Web|last=Page|first=Larry|authorlink=Larry Page|date=August 18, 1997|website=Stanford Digital Library Project|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20020506051802/http://www-diglib.stanford.edu/cgi-bin/WP/get/SIDL-WP-1997-0072?1|archive-date=May 6, 2002|accessdate=November 27, 2010}}</ref> Page told his ideas to Hassan, who began writing the code to implement Page's ideas.<ref name=\"vanityfair\"/>\n\nPage and Brin originally nicknamed the new search engine \"BackRub\", because the system checked backlinks to estimate the importance of a site.<ref>{{Cite news |title=The Birth of Google |first=John |last=Battelle |newspaper=Wired |date=August 2005 |url=https://www.wired.com/wired/archive/13.08/battelle.html?tw=wn_tophead_4 |accessdate=October 12, 2010 |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6BYbTgdmC?url=http://www.wired.com/wired/archive/13.08/battelle.html?tw=wn_tophead_4 |archive-date=October 20, 2012 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Trex |first=Ethan |title=9 People, Places & Things That Changed Their Names |url=http://mentalfloss.com/article/20890/9-people-places-things-changed-their-names |website=Mental Floss |accessdate=August 4, 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140810100639/http://mentalfloss.com/article/20890/9-people-places-things-changed-their-names |archive-date=August 10, 2014 |url-status=live|date=February 17, 2009 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://huron.stanford.edu |title=Backrub search engine at Stanford University |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/19961224105215/http://huron.stanford.edu/ |archivedate=December 24, 1996 |accessdate=March 12, 2011}}</ref> Hassan as well as Alan Steremberg were cited by Page and Brin as being critical to the development of Google. [[Rajeev Motwani]] and [[Terry Winograd]] later co-authored with Page and Brin the first paper about the project, describing PageRank and the initial prototype of the Google search engine, published in 1998. [[H\u00e9ctor Garc\u00eda-Molina]] and [[Jeff Ullman]] were also cited as contributors to the project.<ref name=\"originalpaper\"/> PageRank was influenced by a similar page-ranking and site-scoring algorithm earlier used for [[RankDex]], developed by [[Robin Li]] in 1996, with Larry Page's PageRank patent including a citation to Li's earlier RankDex patent; Li later went on to create the Chinese search engine [[Baidu]].<ref>[http://www.rankdex.com/about.html \"About: RankDex\"] {{webarchive|url= https://www.webcitation.org/659XSbLCF?url=http://www.rankdex.com/about.html |date= 2012-02-02 }}, ''[[RankDex]]''</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Altucher |first=James |title=10 Unusual Things About Google |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/jamesaltucher/2011/03/18/10-unusual-things-about-google-also-the-worst-vc-decision-i-ever-made/ |date=March 18, 2011 |website=[[Forbes]] |accessdate=16 June 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190616133656/https://www.forbes.com/sites/jamesaltucher/2011/03/18/10-unusual-things-about-google-also-the-worst-vc-decision-i-ever-made/ |archive-date=June 16, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title = Method for node ranking in a linked database |url = https://www.google.com/patents/US6285999 |publisher = Google Patents |accessdate = 19 October 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20151015185034/http://www.google.com/patents/US6285999 |archivedate = 15 October 2015 |df = }}</ref>\n\nEventually, they changed the name to Google; the name of the search engine originated from a misspelling of the word \"[[googol]]\",<ref>{{cite web |url=http://graphics.stanford.edu/~dk/google_name_origin.html |title=Origin of the name \"Google\" |last=Koller |first=David |date=January 2004 |website=Stanford University |accessdate=July 4, 2012 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/68ubHzYs7?url=http://graphics.stanford.edu/~dk/google_name_origin.html |archivedate=July 4, 2012 |url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.stanforddaily.com/2003/02/12/from-googol-to-google |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100327141327/http://www.stanforddaily.com/2003/02/12/from-googol-to-google |archivedate=March 27, 2010 |title=From Googol to Google |last=Hanley |first=Rachael |date=February 12, 2003 |newspaper=The Stanford Daily |publisher=Stanford University |accessdate=February 15, 2010}}</ref> the number 1 followed by 100 zeros, which was picked to signify that the search engine was intended to provide large quantities of information.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.google.com/company.html |title=Google! Beta website |website=Google, Inc. |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/19990221202430/https://www.google.com/company.html |archivedate=February 21, 1999 |accessdate=October 12, 2010 |url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Google1998.png|thumb|upright=1.15|Google's original homepage had a simple design because the company founders had little experience in [[HTML]], the [[markup language]] used for designing web pages.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://alan.blog-city.com/an_evening_with_googles_marissa_mayer.htm |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/61rJXKAeq?url=http://alan.blog-city.com/an_evening_with_googles_marissa_mayer.htm |archivedate=September 21, 2011 |title=An evening with Google's Marissa Mayer |last=Williamson |first=Alan |website=Alan Williamson |date=January 12, 2005 |accessdate=July 5, 2010 |url-status=dead}}</ref>|alt=Google's homepage in 1998]]\n\nThe domain name for Google was registered on September 15, 1997,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://whois.domaintools.com/google.com |title=Google.com WHOIS, DNS, & Domain Info - DomainTools |website=[[WHOIS]] |date= |accessdate=July 11, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160314084453/http://whois.domaintools.com/google.com |archive-date=March 14, 2016 |url-status=live}}</ref> and the company was incorporated on September 4, 1998. It was based in the garage of a friend ([[Susan Wojcicki]]<ref name=\"milestones\" />) in [[Menlo Park, California]]. [[Craig Silverstein]], a fellow PhD student at Stanford, was hired as the first employee.<ref name=\"milestones\" /><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www-cs-students.stanford.edu/~csilvers/ |title=Craig Silverstein's website |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/19991002122809/http://www-cs-students.stanford.edu/~csilvers/ |archivedate=October 2, 1999 |website=Stanford University |accessdate=October 12, 2010 |url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last=Kopytoff |first=Verne |url=http://articles.sfgate.com/2008-09-07/news/17161124_1_larry-page-google-search-engine |title=Craig Silverstein grew a decade with Google |newspaper=San Francisco Chronicle |publisher=Hearst Communications, Inc. |date=September 7, 2008 |accessdate=October 12, 2010 |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6BYbUJWuY?url=http://www.sfgate.com/news/article/Craig-Silverstein-grew-a-decade-with-Google-3270079.php |archive-date=October 20, 2012 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nGoogle was initially funded by an August 1998 contribution of $100,000 from [[Andy Bechtolsheim]], co-founder of [[Sun Microsystems]]; the money was given before Google was incorporated.<ref name=\"Bechtolsheim\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi?file=/chronicle/archive/2004/04/29/MNGLD6CFND34.DTL |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090919030812/http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi?file=%2Fchronicle%2Farchive%2F2004%2F04%2F29%2FMNGLD6CFND34.DTL |archivedate=September 19, 2009 |title=For early Googlers, key word is $ |last=Kopytoff |first=Verne |date=April 29, 2004 |newspaper=San Francisco Chronicle |publisher=Hearst Communications |accessdate=February 19, 2010 |location=San Francisco |url-status=dead}}</ref> Google received money from three other [[angel investor]]s in 1998: [[Amazon.com]] founder [[Jeff Bezos]], Stanford University computer science professor [[David Cheriton]], and entrepreneur [[Ram Shriram]].<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite book|title=Googled: The End of the World as We Know it|last=Auletta|first=Ken|publisher=Penguin Books|year=2010|isbn=9780143118046|edition=Reprint|location=New York, N.Y.|oclc=515456623|quote=On September 7, 1998, the day Google officially incorporated, he [Shriram] wrote out a check for just over $250,000, one of four of this size the founders received.|author-link=Ken Auletta}}</ref> Between these initial investors, friends, and family Google raised around 1 million dollars, which is what allowed them to open up their original shop in [[Menlo Park, California]] <ref>{{cite web |last=Hosch |first=William L. |last2=Hall |first2=Mark |title=Google Inc. |url=https://www.britannica.com/topic/Google-Inc |website=Britannica |publisher=Britannica |accessdate=March 17, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190220013941/https://www.britannica.com/topic/Google-Inc |archive-date=February 20, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nAfter some additional, small investments through the end of 1998 to early 1999,<ref name=\":3\" /> a new $25 million round of funding was announced on June 7, 1999,<ref>{{Cite press release |url=https://www.google.com/pressrel/pressrelease1.html |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20010212052759/http://www.google.com/pressrel/pressrelease1.html |archivedate=February 12, 2001 |title=Google Receives $25&nbsp;Million in Equity Funding |date=June 7, 1999 |location=Palo Alto, Calif. |accessdate=February 16, 2009 |url-status=live}}</ref> with major investors including the [[venture capital]] firms [[Kleiner Perkins]] and [[Sequoia Capital]].<ref name=\"Bechtolsheim\" />\n\n=== Growth ===\nIn March 1999, the company moved its offices to [[Palo Alto, California]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.businessinsider.com/google-history-in-photos-2015-10 |title=38 photos of Google's rise from a Stanford dorm room to world domination |last=Weinberger |first=Matt |date=October 12, 2015 |website=[[Business Insider]] |publisher=[[Axel Springer SE]] |accessdate=July 15, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170819101107/http://www.businessinsider.com/google-history-in-photos-2015-10 |archive-date=August 19, 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref> which is home to several prominent [[Silicon Valley]] technology start-ups.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.cnet.com/news/a-building-blessed-with-tech-success/ |title=A building blessed with tech success |website=[[CNET]] |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] |accessdate=July 15, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170523115134/https://www.cnet.com/news/a-building-blessed-with-tech-success/ |archive-date=May 23, 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref> The next year, Google began selling advertisements associated with search keywords against Page and Brin's initial opposition toward an advertising-funded search engine.<ref>{{Cite book |url=https://books.google.com/?id=xOk3EIUW9VgC&printsec=frontcover |title=Planet Google: One Company's Audacious Plan to Organize Everything We Know |last=Stross |first=Randall |date=September 2008 |publisher=Free Press |isbn=978-1-4165-4691-7 |location=New York |pages=3\u20134 |chapter=Introduction |accessdate=February 14, 2010 |chapterurl=https://books.google.com/?id=xOk3EIUW9VgC&printsec=frontcover}}</ref><ref name=\"milestones\" /> To maintain an uncluttered page design, advertisements were solely text-based.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.google.com/press/pressrel/pressrelease39.html |title=Google Launches Self-Service Advertising Program |date=October 23, 2000 |website=News from Google |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120401005413/http://www.google.com/press/pressrel/pressrelease39.html |archivedate=April 1, 2012 |accessdate=July 15, 2017}}</ref> In June 2000, it was announced that Google would become the default search engine provider for [[Yahoo!]], one of the most popular websites at the time, replacing [[Inktomi]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2000/jul/02/searchengines.columnists |title=Why's Yahoo gone to Google? Search me |last=Naughton |first=John |date=July 2, 2000 |via=www.theguardian.com |access-date=January 30, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190131040317/https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2000/jul/02/searchengines.columnists |archive-date=January 31, 2019 |url-status=live|newspaper=The Guardian }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://googlepress.blogspot.com/2000/06/yahoo-selects-google-as-its-default.html |title=Yahoo! Selects Google as its Default Search Engine Provider \u2013 News announcements \u2013 News from Google \u2013 Google |website=googlepress.blogspot.com |access-date=January 30, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190131041155/https://googlepress.blogspot.com/2000/06/yahoo-selects-google-as-its-default.html |archive-date=January 31, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Google\u2019s First Production Server.jpg|upright|thumb|Google's first production server.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.computerhistory.org/collections/accession/102662167 |title=Google Server Assembly |website=Computer History Museum |accessdate=July 4, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100722083804/http://www.computerhistory.org/collections/accession/102662167 |archive-date=July 22, 2010 |url-status=live}}</ref>|alt=Google's first servers, showing lots of exposed wiring and circuit boards]]\nIn 2003, after outgrowing two other locations, the company leased an office complex from [[Silicon Graphics]], at 1600 Amphitheatre Parkway in [[Mountain View, California]].<ref name=\"sgibldg\">{{Cite news |url=http://news.cnet.com/Googles-movin-on-up/2110-1032_3-1025111.html |title=Google's movin' on up |last=Olsen |first=Stephanie |date=July 11, 2003 |work=[[CNET]] |accessdate=February 15, 2010 |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6BYbYuLmq?url=http://news.cnet.com/Googles-movin-on-up/2110-1032_3-1025111.html |archive-date=October 20, 2012 |url-status=live}}</ref> The complex became known as the [[Googleplex]], a play on the word [[googolplex]], the number one followed by a googol zeroes. Three years later, Google bought the property from SGI for $319&nbsp;million.<ref name=\"googleplexpurchase\">{{Cite news |url=http://sanjose.bizjournals.com/sanjose/stories/2006/06/19/newscolumn3.html |title=Google to buy headquarters building from Silicon Graphics |date=June 16, 2006 |newspaper=Silicon Valley / San Jose Business Journal |accessdate=February 15, 2010 |publisher=American City Business Journals |location=San Jose |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100418071152/http://sanjose.bizjournals.com/sanjose/stories/2006/06/19/newscolumn3.html |archive-date=April 18, 2010 |url-status=live}}</ref> By that time, the name \"Google\" had found its way into everyday language, causing the verb \"[[google (verb)|google]]\" to be added to the ''[[Merriam-Webster Collegiate Dictionary]]'' and the ''[[Oxford English Dictionary]]'', denoted as: \"to use the Google search engine to obtain information on the Internet\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://googleblog.blogspot.com/2006/10/do-you-google.html |title=Do You \"Google\"? |last=Krantz |first=Michael |date=October 25, 2006 |website=Google, Inc. |accessdate=February 17, 2010 |archive-url=https://archive.today/20120530/http://googleblog.blogspot.com/2006/10/do-you-google.html |archive-date=May 30, 2012 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://msnbc.msn.com/id/13720643/ |title=To Google or Not to Google |last=Bylund |first=Anders |date=July 5, 2006 |website=msnbc.com |archiveurl=https://archive.today/20060707062623/http://msnbc.msn.com/id/13720643/ |archivedate=July 7, 2006 |url-status=dead |accessdate=February 17, 2010}}</ref> Additionally, in 2001 Google's Investors felt the need to have a strong internal management, and they agreed to hire [[Eric Schmidt]] as the Chairman and CEO of Google <ref name=\"Google Inc\">{{cite web |url=https://www.britannica.com/topic/Google-Inc |title=Google Inc. |last=Hosch |first=William L. |last2=Hall |first2=Mark |website=Britannica |publisher=Britannica |accessdate=March 17, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190220013941/https://www.britannica.com/topic/Google-Inc |archive-date=February 20, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== Initial public offering ===\nGoogle's [[initial public offering]] (IPO) took place five years later, on August 19, 2004. At that time Larry Page, Sergey Brin, and Eric Schmidt agreed to work together at Google for 20 years, until the year 2024.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://money.cnn.com/2008/01/18/news/companies/google.fortune/index.htm |title=Google wins again |date=January 29, 2008 |newspaper=Fortune |publisher=Time Warner |accessdate=January 22, 2011 |first=Adam |last=Lashinsky |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6BYbNOfxM?url=http://money.cnn.com/2008/01/18/news/companies/google.fortune/index.htm |archive-date=October 20, 2012 |url-status=live}}</ref> At IPO, the company offered 19,605,052 shares at a price of $85 per share.<ref name=\"IPO\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.businessweek.com/technology/content/aug2004/tc20040819_6843_tc120.htm |title=Google: Whiz Kids or Naughty Boys? |last=Elgin |first=Ben |date=August 19, 2004 |newspaper=BusinessWeek |publisher=[[Bloomberg L.P.]] |accessdate=February 19, 2010 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5hT7Hw63l?url=http://www.businessweek.com/technology/content/aug2004/tc20040819_6843_tc120.htm |archivedate=June 12, 2009 |url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{cite web |url=http://investor.google.com/pdf/2004_AnnualReport.pdf |title=2004 Annual Report |year=2004 |website=Google, Inc. |page=29 |accessdate=February 19, 2010 |location=Mountain View, California |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/659XUbJTj?url=http://investor.google.com/pdf/2004_AnnualReport.pdf |archive-date=February 2, 2012 |url-status=live}}</ref> Shares were sold in an online auction format using a system built by [[Morgan Stanley]] and [[Credit Suisse]], underwriters for the deal.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://money.cnn.com/2004/04/29/technology/google/ |title=Google sets $2.7&nbsp;billion IPO |last=La Monica |first=Paul R. |date=April 30, 2004 |work=CNN Money |accessdate=February 19, 2010 |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6BYbWCwIQ?url=http://money.cnn.com/2004/04/29/technology/google/ |archive-date=October 20, 2012 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.zdnet.com/news/want-in-on-googles-ipo/135799 |title=Want In on Google's IPO? |last=Kawamoto |first=Dawn |date=April 29, 2004 |website=ZDNet |accessdate=February 19, 2010 |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/659XV2yME?url=http://www.zdnet.com/news/want-in-on-googles-ipo/135799 |archive-date=February 2, 2012 |url-status=live}}</ref> The sale of $1.67 billion gave Google a [[market capitalization]] of more than $23 billion.<ref name=\"washpost\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/articles/A14939-2004Aug19.html |title=Google's IPO: Grate Expectations |last=Webb |first=Cynthia L. |newspaper=The Washington Post |accessdate=February 19, 2010 |location=Washington, D.C. |date=August 19, 2004 |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6BYbWsL9b?url=http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/articles/A14939-2004Aug19.html |archive-date=October 20, 2012 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Eric Schmidt at the 37th G8 Summit in Deauville 037.jpg|thumb|upright|left|[[Eric Schmidt]]]]\nIn October 2006, Google announced that it had acquired the video-sharing site YouTube for $1.65&nbsp;billion in Google stock,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://techcrunch.com/2006/10/09/google-has-acquired-youtube/ |title=Google Has Acquired YouTube |last=Arrington |first=Michael |date=October 9, 2006 |website=[[TechCrunch]] |publisher=[[AOL]] |accessdate=March 15, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170316024815/https://techcrunch.com/2006/10/09/google-has-acquired-youtube/ |archive-date=March 16, 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/10/09/business/09cnd-deal.html |title=Google to Acquire YouTube for $1.65 Billion |last=Sorkin |first=Andrew Ross |last2=Peters |first2=Jeremy W. |date=October 9, 2006 |website=[[The New York Times]] |accessdate=March 15, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170609080519/http://www.nytimes.com/2006/10/09/business/09cnd-deal.html |archive-date=June 9, 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref> and the deal was finalized on November 13, 2006.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://techcrunch.com/2006/11/13/google-closes-youtube-acquisition/ |title=Google Closes YouTube Acquisition |last=Arrington |first=Michael |date=November 13, 2006 |website=[[TechCrunch]] |publisher=[[AOL]] |accessdate=March 15, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170316024500/https://techcrunch.com/2006/11/13/google-closes-youtube-acquisition/ |archive-date=March 16, 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-google-idUSWEN973120061114 |title=Google closes YouTube deal |last=Auchard |first=Eric |date=November 14, 2006 |website=[[Reuters]] |publisher=[[Thomson Reuters]] |accessdate=March 15, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170316113147/http://www.reuters.com/article/us-google-idUSWEN973120061114 |archive-date=March 16, 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref> On April 13, 2007, Google reached an agreement to acquire [[DoubleClick]] for $3.1&nbsp;billion, transferring to Google valuable relationships that DoubleClick had with Web publishers and advertising agencies.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2007/04/14/technology/14DoubleClick.html |title=Google Buys DoubleClick for $3.1 Billion |last=Story |first=Louise |last2=Helft |first2=Miguel |date=April 14, 2007 |website=[[The New York Times]] |accessdate=March 9, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170404014741/http://www.nytimes.com/2007/04/14/technology/14DoubleClick.html |archive-date=April 4, 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn 2005, ''[[The Washington Post]]'' reported on a 700 percent increase in third-quarter profit for Google, largely thanks to large companies shifting their advertising strategies from newspapers, magazines, and television to the Internet.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2005/10/20/AR2005102002058.html |title=Online Ads Give Google Huge Gain in Profit |last=Vise |first=David |date=October 21, 2005 |work=[[The Washington Post]] |accessdate=November 27, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161020134416/http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2005/10/20/AR2005102002058.html |archive-date=October 20, 2016 |url-status=live}}</ref> In May 2011, the number of monthly unique visitors to Google surpassed one billion for the first time.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://itsalltech.com/2011/06/22/googles-new-record-1-billion-visitors-in-may/ |title=Google's new record, 1 billion visitors in May |author=Ben |date=June 2, 2011 |website=It's All Tech |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130116035631/http://itsalltech.com/2011/06/22/googles-new-record-1-billion-visitors-in-may/ |archivedate=January 16, 2013 |accessdate=November 30, 2016}}</ref> By 2011, Google was handling approximately 3 billion searches per day. To handle this workload, Google built 11 [[data centers]] around the world with some several thousand servers in each. These data centers allowed Google to handle the ever changing workload more efficiently.<ref name=\"Google Inc\"/>\n\nOn August 15, 2011, Google made its largest-ever acquisition to date when it announced that it would acquire [[Motorola Mobility]] for $12.5&nbsp;billion<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/faster-forward/post/google-agrees-to-acquire-motorola-mobility/2011/08/15/gIQABmTkGJ_blog.html |title=Google agrees to acquire Motorola Mobility |author=Tsukayama, Hayley |date=August 15, 2011 |work=The Washington Post |accessdate=August 17, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121113035358/http://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/faster-forward/post/google-agrees-to-acquire-motorola-mobility/2011/08/15/gIQABmTkGJ_blog.html |archive-date=November 13, 2012 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://investor.google.com/releases/2011/0815.html |title=Google to Acquire Motorola Mobility&nbsp;\u2014 Google Investor Relations |website=Google |accessdate=August 17, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110817101741/http://investor.google.com/releases/2011/0815.html |archive-date=August 17, 2011 |url-status=live}}</ref> This purchase was made in part to help Google gain Motorola's considerable patent portfolio on mobile phones and wireless technologies, to help protect Google in its ongoing patent disputes with other companies,<ref name=\"supercharging android\">{{cite web|url=http://googleblog.blogspot.com/2011/08/supercharging-android-google-to-acquire.html|title=Official Google Blog: Supercharging Android: Google to Acquire Motorola Mobility|last=Page|first=Larry|authorlink=Larry Page|date=2011-08-15|website=Official Google Blog|url-status=live|archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/69UHjJzgs?url=http://googleblog.blogspot.com/2011/08/supercharging-android-google-to-acquire.html|archive-date=2012-07-28|accessdate=2011-08-17}}</ref> mainly [[Apple Inc.|Apple]] and [[Microsoft]],<ref name=\"appleinsider1\">{{cite web |url=http://www.appleinsider.com/articles/11/08/15/google_ceo_anticompetitive_apple_microsoft_forced_motorola_deal.html |title=Google CEO: 'Anticompetitive' Apple, Microsoft forced Motorola deal |last=Hughes |first=Neil |website=AppleInsider |accessdate=August 17, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111210181127/http://www.appleinsider.com/articles/11/08/15/google_ceo_anticompetitive_apple_microsoft_forced_motorola_deal.html |archive-date=December 10, 2011 |url-status=live}}</ref> and to allow it to continue to freely offer [[Android (operating system)|Android]].<ref name=\"cnet\">{{cite web |url=http://news.cnet.com/8301-1035_3-20092362-94/google-to-buy-motorola-mobility-for-$12.5b/ |title=Google to buy Motorola Mobility for $12.5B |last=Cheng |first=Roger |date=August 15, 2011 |website=CNet News |access-date=August 15, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111006062539/http://news.cnet.com/8301-1035_3-20092362-94/google-to-buy-motorola-mobility-for-$12.5b/ |archive-date=October 6, 2011 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== 2012 onward ===\nThe year 2012 was the first time that Google generated $50 billion in annual revenue, generating $38 billion the previous year. In January 2013, then-CEO Larry Page commented, \"We ended 2012 with a strong quarter ... Revenues were up 36% year-on-year, and 8% quarter-on-quarter. And we hit $50 billion in revenues for the first time last year \u2013 not a bad achievement in just a decade and a half.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://mashable.com/2013/01/22/google-q4-earnings/#42cbeRCbSkqH |title=Google Has Its First $50 Billion Year |last=Fiegerman |first=Seth |date=January 22, 2013 |website=[[Mashable]] |accessdate=November 30, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161201014741/http://mashable.com/2013/01/22/google-q4-earnings/#42cbeRCbSkqH |archive-date=December 1, 2016 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2013, Google acquired [[Waze]], a $966 million deal.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.cnet.com/news/google-reveals-it-spent-966-million-in-waze-acquisition/ |title=Google reveals it spent $966 million in Waze acquisition |last=Kerr |first=Dara |date=July 25, 2013 |website=[[CNET]] |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] |accessdate=June 12, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170216011658/https://www.cnet.com/news/google-reveals-it-spent-966-million-in-waze-acquisition/ |archive-date=February 16, 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref> While Waze would remain an independent entity, its social features, such as its crowdsourced location platform, were reportedly valuable integrations between Waze and [[Google Maps]], Google's own mapping service.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://techcrunch.com/2013/06/11/its-official-google-buys-waze-giving-a-social-data-boost-to-its-location-and-mapping-business/ |title=Google Bought Waze For $1.1B, Giving A Social Data Boost To Its Mapping Business |last=Lunden |first=Ingrid |date=June 11, 2013 |website=[[TechCrunch]] |publisher=[[AOL]] |accessdate=June 12, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170706051802/https://techcrunch.com/2013/06/11/its-official-google-buys-waze-giving-a-social-data-boost-to-its-location-and-mapping-business/ |archive-date=July 6, 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nGoogle announced the launch of a new company, called [[Calico (company)|Calico]], on September 19, 2013, to be led by [[Apple Inc.]] chairman [[Arthur D. Levinson|Arthur Levinson]]. In the official public statement, Page explained that the \"health and well-being\" company would focus on \"the challenge of ageing and associated diseases\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/technology-24158924|title=Google spin-off Calico to search for answers to ageing|last=Wakefield|first=Jane|date=September 19, 2013|work=BBC News|accessdate=September 20, 2013|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130919201510/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/technology-24158924|archive-date=September 19, 2013}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Google-Deep Mind headquarters in London, 6 Pancras Square.jpg|thumb|upright|Entrance of building where Google and its subsidiary Deep Mind are located at 6 Pancras Square, London|alt=]]\nOn January 26, 2014, Google announced it had agreed to acquire [[DeepMind Technologies]], a privately held artificial intelligence company from [[London]].<ref name=\"Chowdhry-DeepMind\">{{cite news |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/amitchowdhry/2014/01/27/google-to-acquire-artificial-intelligence-company-deepmind/ |title=Google To Acquire Artificial Intelligence Company DeepMind |last=Chowdhry |first=Amit |date=January 27, 2014 |newspaper=Forbes |accessdate=January 27, 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140129142153/http://www.forbes.com/sites/amitchowdhry/2014/01/27/google-to-acquire-artificial-intelligence-company-deepmind/ |archive-date=January 29, 2014 |url-status=live}}</ref> Technology news website ''[[Recode]]'' reported that the company was purchased for $400 million though it was not disclosed where the information came from. A Google spokesman would not comment of the price.<ref name=\"Helgren- DeepMind\">{{cite news |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2014/01/27/us-google-deepmind-idUSBREA0Q03220140127 |title=Google to buy artificial intelligence company DeepMind |last=Helgren |first=Chris |date=January 27, 2014 |newspaper=Reuters |accessdate=January 27, 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140127042513/http://www.reuters.com/article/2014/01/27/us-google-deepmind-idUSBREA0Q03220140127 |archive-date=January 27, 2014 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"Ribeiro- DeepMind\">{{cite news |url=http://www.pcworld.com/article/2091500/google-acquires-artificial-intelligence-company-deepmind.html |title=Google buys artificial intelligence company DeepMind |last=Ribeiro |first=Jon |date=January 27, 2014 |newspaper=PC World |accessdate=January 27, 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140130042946/http://www.pcworld.com/article/2091500/google-acquires-artificial-intelligence-company-deepmind.html |archive-date=January 30, 2014 |url-status=live}}</ref> The purchase of DeepMind aids in Google's recent growth in the artificial intelligence and robotics community.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theverge.com/2014/1/26/5348640/google-deepmind-acquisition-robotics-ai |title=Google buying AI startup DeepMind for a reported $400 million |last=Opam |first=Kwame |date=January 26, 2014 |website=[[The Verge]] |publisher=[[Vox Media]] |accessdate=March 9, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170708161602/https://www.theverge.com/2014/1/26/5348640/google-deepmind-acquisition-robotics-ai |archive-date=July 8, 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nAccording to [[Interbrand]]'s annual Best Global Brands report, Google has been the second most valuable brand in the world (behind [[Apple Inc.]]) in 2013,<ref>{{cite web |title=Rankings - 2013 - Best Global Brands - Interbrand |url=http://interbrand.com/best-brands/best-global-brands/2013/ranking/#?listFormat=ls |website=Interbrand |accessdate=October 23, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161022013506/http://interbrand.com/best-brands/best-global-brands/2013/ranking/#?listFormat=ls |archive-date=October 22, 2016 |url-status=live}}</ref> 2014,<ref>{{cite web |title=Rankings - 2014 - Best Global Brands - Interbrand |url=http://interbrand.com/best-brands/best-global-brands/2014/ranking/#?listFormat=ls |website=Interbrand |accessdate=October 23, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161103140119/http://interbrand.com/best-brands/best-global-brands/2014/ranking/#?listFormat=ls |archive-date=November 3, 2016 |url-status=live}}</ref> 2015,<ref>{{cite web |title=Rankings - 2015 - Best Global Brands - Interbrand |url=http://interbrand.com/best-brands/best-global-brands/2015/ranking/#?listFormat=ls |website=Interbrand |accessdate=October 23, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161021100708/http://interbrand.com/best-brands/best-global-brands/2015/ranking/#?listFormat=ls |archive-date=October 21, 2016 |url-status=live}}</ref> and 2016, with a valuation of $133 billion.<ref>{{cite web |title=Rankings - 2016 - Best Global Brands |url=http://interbrand.com/best-brands/best-global-brands/2016/ranking/#?listFormat=ls |website=Interbrand |accessdate=October 23, 2016 |archive-url=https://archive.today/20161220191226/http://interbrand.com/best-brands/best-global-brands/2016/ranking/#?listFormat=ls |archive-date=December 20, 2016 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn August 10, 2015, Google announced plans to reorganize its various interests as a [[Conglomerate (company)|conglomerate]] called [[Alphabet Inc.|Alphabet]]. Google became Alphabet's leading subsidiary, and will continue to be the umbrella company for Alphabet's Internet interests. Upon completion of the restructure, [[Sundar Pichai]] became CEO of Google, replacing [[Larry Page]], who became CEO of Alphabet.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2015-08-10/google-to-adopt-new-holding-structure-under-name-alphabet- |title=Google Rises After Creating Holding Company Called Alphabet |last=Womack |first=Brian |date=August 10, 2015 |publisher=[[Bloomberg L.P.]] |accessdate=November 22, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161123054841/https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2015-08-10/google-to-adopt-new-holding-structure-under-name-alphabet- |archive-date=November 23, 2016 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/google-creates-new-company-alphabet-1439240645 |title=Google Creates Parent Company Called Alphabet in Restructuring |last=Barr |first=Alistair |last2=Winkler |first2=Rolf |date=August 10, 2015 |newspaper=[[The Wall Street Journal]] |accessdate=November 22, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161128112043/http://www.wsj.com/articles/google-creates-new-company-alphabet-1439240645 |archive-date=November 28, 2016 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/08/11/technology/google-alphabet-restructuring.html |title=Google to Reorganize as Alphabet to Keep Its Lead as an Innovator |last=Dougherty |first=Conor |date=August 10, 2015 |website=[[The New York Times]] |accessdate=November 22, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161019164806/http://www.nytimes.com/2015/08/11/technology/google-alphabet-restructuring.html |archive-date=October 19, 2016 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n{{As of|2016|10|post=,}} Google operates 70 offices in more than 40 countries.<ref>{{cite web |title=Google locations |url=https://www.google.com/about/company/facts/locations/ |website=Google, Inc. |accessdate=October 23, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130815024220/https://www.google.com/about/company/facts/locations/ |archive-date=August 15, 2013 |url-status=live}}</ref> [[Alexa Internet|Alexa]], a company that monitors commercial web traffic, lists Google.com as the most visited website in the world.<ref name=\"Alexa\">{{cite web |title=google.com Traffic Statistics |url=http://www.alexa.com/siteinfo/google.com |website=[[Alexa Internet]] |date=November 25, 2016 |accessdate=November 27, 2016 |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/659XN975m?url=http://www.alexa.com/siteinfo/google.com |archive-date=February 2, 2012 |url-status=live}}</ref> Several other Google services also figure in the top 100 most visited websites, including YouTube<ref>{{cite web |title=youtube.com Traffic Statistics |url=http://www.alexa.com/siteinfo/youtube.com |website=[[Alexa Internet]] |date=November 25, 2016 |accessdate=November 27, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161127004253/http://www.alexa.com/siteinfo/youtube.com |archive-date=November 27, 2016 |url-status=live}}</ref> and Blogger.<ref>{{cite web |title=blogger.com Traffic Statistics |url=http://www.alexa.com/siteinfo/blogger.com |website=[[Alexa Internet]] |date=November 25, 2016 |accessdate=November 27, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161112072306/http://www.alexa.com/siteinfo/blogger.com |archive-date=November 12, 2016 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn August 8, 2017, Google fired employee James Damore after he distributed a memo throughout the company which argued that bias and \"[[Google's Ideological Echo Chamber|Google's ideological echo chamber]]\" clouded their thinking about diversity and inclusion, and that it is also biological factors, not discrimination alone, that cause the average woman to be less interested than men in technical positions.<ref name=\"NYTFired\">[https://www.nytimes.com/2017/08/07/business/google-women-engineer-fired-memo.html \"Google Fires Engineer Who Wrote Memo Questioning Women in Tech\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170810185646/https://www.nytimes.com/2017/08/07/business/google-women-engineer-fired-memo.html |date=August 10, 2017 }}. ''[[The New York Times]]'', August 7, 2017</ref> Google CEO Sundar Pichai accused Damore in violating company policy by \"advancing harmful gender stereotypes in our workplace\", and he was fired on the same day.<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/2017/08/08/technology/google-engineer-fired-gender-memo.html Contentious Memo Strikes Nerve Inside Google and Out] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170809012140/https://www.nytimes.com/2017/08/08/technology/google-engineer-fired-gender-memo.html |date=August 9, 2017 }}. ''[[The New York Times]]'', August 8, 2017</ref><ref>diversitymemo.com</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theatlantic.com/politics/archive/2017/08/the-most-common-error-in-coverage-of-the-google-memo/536181/ |title=The Most Common Error in Media Coverage of the Google Memo |last=Friedersdorf |first=Conor |access-date=August 9, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170808230220/https://www.theatlantic.com/politics/archive/2017/08/the-most-common-error-in-coverage-of-the-google-memo/536181/ |archive-date=August 8, 2017 |url-status=live|date=August 8, 2017 }}</ref> ''New York Times'' columnist [[David Brooks (political commentator)|David Brooks]] argued Pichai had mishandled the case, and called for his resignation.<ref name=\"BrooksNYT\">{{cite web |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/08/11/opinion/sundar-pichai-google-memo-diversity.html |title=Sundar Pichai Should Resign as Google's C.E.O |last=Brooks |first=David |date=August 11, 2017 |website=The New York Times |url-access=limited |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170811124216/https://www.nytimes.com/2017/08/11/opinion/sundar-pichai-google-memo-diversity.html |archivedate=August 11, 2017 |url-status=live |accessdate=August 11, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.businessinsider.com/david-brooks-sundar-pichai-resignation-james-damore-2017-8 |title=New York Times columnist David Brooks wants Google's CEO to resign |website=Business Insider |language=en |archiveurl=https://archive.today/20170812131604/http://www.businessinsider.com/david-brooks-sundar-pichai-resignation-james-damore-2017-8 |archivedate=August 12, 2017 |url-status=live |access-date=August 12, 2017|date=August 11, 2017 }}</ref>\n\nBetween 2018 and 2019, [[Google worker organization|tensions between the company's leadership and its workers escalated]] as staff protested company decisions on internal sexual harassment, [[Dragonfly (search engine)|a censored Chinese search engine]], and [[Project Maven|a military drone artificial intelligence]], which had been seen as areas of revenue growth for the company.<ref name=\"Bloomberg 2019-11-22\">{{Cite news |last1=Bergen |first1=Mark |title=Google Workers Protest Company's 'Brute Force Intimidation' |work=[[Bloomberg.com]] |date=2019-11-22 |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2019-11-22/google-workers-protest-company-s-brute-force-intimidation |language=en |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref name=\"Verge busting\">{{Cite web |last1=Hollister |first1=Sean |title=Google is accused of union busting after firing four employees |work=[[The Verge]] |date=2019-11-25 |url=https://www.theverge.com/2019/11/25/20983053/google-fires-four-employees-memo-rebecca-rivers-laurence-berland-union-busting-accusation-walkout |language=en |accessdate=2019-11-26 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> On October 25, 2018, ''[[The New York Times]]'' published the ''expos\u00e9'', \"How Google Protected [[Andy Rubin]], the \u2018Father of Android\u2019\". The company subsequently announced that \"48 employees have been fired over the last two years\" for sexual misconduct.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theverge.com/2018/10/25/18024486/google-sexual-harassment-people-fired-rubin-2-years-ceo |title=Google says 48 people have been fired for sexual harassment in the last two years |last=Welch |first=Chris |date=October 25, 2018 |accessdate=October 31, 2018 |website=The Verge |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181031133020/https://www.theverge.com/2018/10/25/18024486/google-sexual-harassment-people-fired-rubin-2-years-ceo |archive-date=October 31, 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref> On November 1, 2018, more than 20,000 Google employees and contractors staged a global walk-out to protest the company's handling of sexual harassment complaints.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.businessinsider.com/google-walkout-live-pictures-of-protesting-google-workers-2018-11 |title=PHOTOS: Google employees all over the world left their desk and walked out in protest over sexual misconduct |last=Hamilton |first=Isobel Asher |date=November 1, 2018 |accessdate=November 6, 2018 |website=Business Insider |display-authors=etal |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181102174328/https://www.businessinsider.com/google-walkout-live-pictures-of-protesting-google-workers-2018-11 |archive-date=November 2, 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://fortune.com/2018/11/03/google-employees-walkout-demands/ |title=More Than 20,000 Google Employees Participated in Walkout Over Sexual Harassment Policy |last=Segarra |first=Lisa Marie |date=November 3, 2018 |accessdate=November 6, 2018 |publisher=Fortune |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181107013331/http://fortune.com/2018/11/03/google-employees-walkout-demands/ |archive-date=November 7, 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref> Later in 2019, some workers accused the company of retaliating against internal activists.{{r|Verge busting}}\n\nOn March 19, 2019, Google announced that it would enter the video game market, launching a [[cloud gaming]] platform called [[Google Stadia|Stadia]].<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nOn June 3, 2019, the [[United States Department of Justice]] reported that it would investigate Google for [[antitrust]] violations.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theregister.co.uk/2019/06/03/google_shares_take_a_dive_on_doj_reports/|title=Google shares take a dive with reports of US DoJ 'competition' probe}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2019, it was reported that former [[PayPal]] [[Chief Operating Officer]] Bill Ready would become Google's new commerce chief. Ready's role won't be directly involved with [[Google Pay]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://social.techcrunch.com/2019/12/11/paypals-exiting-coo-bill-ready-to-join-google-as-its-new-president-of-commerce/|title=PayPal's exiting COO Bill Ready to join Google as its new president of Commerce|website=TechCrunch|language=en-US|access-date=2019-12-11}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2020, it was reported that Google announced several cost-cutting measures as a response to the economic impact of the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]]. Such measures included slowing down hiring for the remainder of 2020, except for of a small number of strategic areas, recalibrating the focus and pace of investments in areas like data centers and machines, and non-business essential marketing and travel. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/tosv2.html?vid=&uuid=1024b270-7fb5-11ea-a60a-233b89b5eced&url=L25ld3MvYXJ0aWNsZXMvMjAyMC0wNC0xNS9nb29nbGUtdG8tc2xvdy1oaXJpbmctZm9yLXJlc3Qtb2YtMjAyMC1jZW8tcGljaGFpLXRlbGxzLXN0YWZm|title=Bloomberg - Google to Slow Hiring for Rest of 2020, CEO Tells Staff|last=|first=|date=2020-04-15|website=www.bloomberg.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref>\n\n== Products and services ==\n{{Main|List of Google products}}\n\n=== Search engine ===\n{{Main|Google Search|Google Images}}\n[[File:Google Homepage.svg|alt=|left|thumb|Google Search homepage {{as of|2020|03|df=US|lc=y}}]]\nGoogle [[search engine indexing|indexes]] billions of web pages to allow users to search for the information they desire through the use of keywords and [[Operator (computer programming)|operators]].<ref>{{cite web |first=Michael |last=Arrington |title=Google's Misleading Blog Post: The Size Of The Web And The Size Of Their Index Are Very Different |url=https://techcrunch.com/2008/07/25/googles-misleading-blog-post-on-the-size-of-the-web/ |website=[[TechCrunch]] |publisher=[[AOL]] |date=July 25, 2008 |accessdate=March 9, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170312042335/https://techcrunch.com/2008/07/25/googles-misleading-blog-post-on-the-size-of-the-web/ |archive-date=March 12, 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref> According to [[comScore]] market research from November 2009, [[Google Search]] is the dominant search engine in the United States market, with a [[market share]] of 65.6%.<ref name=\"comscore\">{{Cite news |date=December 16, 2006 |title=comScore Releases November 2009 U.S. Search Engine Rankings |url=http://www.comscore.com/Press_Events/Press_Releases/2009/12/comScore_Releases_November_2009_U.S._Search_Engine_Rankings |accessdate=July 5, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100225142724/http://www.comscore.com/Press_Events/Press_Releases/2009/12/comScore_Releases_November_2009_U.S._Search_Engine_Rankings |archive-date=February 25, 2010 |url-status=live}}</ref> In May 2017, Google enabled a new \"Personal\" tab in Google Search, letting users search for content in their Google accounts' various services, including email messages from [[Gmail]] and photos from [[Google Photos]].<ref>{{cite web |first=Barry |last=Schwartz |title=Google Adds Personal Tab To Search Filters |url=https://www.seroundtable.com/google-personal-tab-search-23912.html |website=Search Engine Roundtable |publisher=RustyBrick |date=May 26, 2017 |accessdate=May 27, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170527140309/https://www.seroundtable.com/google-personal-tab-search-23912.html |archive-date=May 27, 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first=Chaim |last=Gartenberg |title=Google adds new Personal tab to search results to show Gmail and Photos content |url=https://www.theverge.com/2017/5/26/15701778/google-personal-tab-search-results-gmail-photos-images-maps-news-filter |website=[[The Verge]] |publisher=[[Vox Media]] |date=May 26, 2017 |accessdate=May 27, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170526215945/https://www.theverge.com/2017/5/26/15701778/google-personal-tab-search-results-gmail-photos-images-maps-news-filter |archive-date=May 26, 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nGoogle launched its [[Google News]] service in 2002, an automated service which summarizes news articles from various websites.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.time.com/time/business/article/0,8599,356152,00.html |title=Automatic for the People |last=Macht |first=Joshua |date=September 30, 2002 |work=Time |access-date=June 7, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101022094519/http://www.time.com/time/business/article/0,8599,356152,00.html |archive-date=October 22, 2010 |url-status=live}}</ref> Google also hosts [[Google Books]], a service which searches the text found in books in its database and shows limited previews or and the full book where allowed.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.infoworld.com/t/platforms/google-hit-second-lawsuit-over-library-project-722 |title=Google hit with second lawsuit over Library project |last=Martin |first=China |date=November 26, 2007 |publisher=[[InfoWorld]] |access-date=July 5, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110510022853/http://www.infoworld.com/t/platforms/google-hit-second-lawsuit-over-library-project-722 |archive-date=May 10, 2011 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== Advertising ===\n[[File:Ad-tech London 2010 (2).JPG|thumb|Google on ad-tech London, 2010]]\n\nAs per its 2017 Annual report, Google generates most of its revenues from advertising. This includes sales of apps, purchases made in-app, digital content products on google and YouTube, android and licensing and service fees, including fees received for Google Cloud offerings. 46% of this was from clicks (cost per clicks), amounting to US$109,652 million in 2017. This includes three principal methods, namely [[AdMob]], [[AdSense]] (such as AdSense for Content, [[AdSense]] for Search, etc.) and DoubleClick AdExchange.<ref name=\"agm2017\">{{cite book |title=Annualg report (Alphabet Inc.) - 2017 |date=March 1, 2018 |publisher=Alphabet Inc. Investor relations |url=https://abc.xyz/investor |accessdate=December 3, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160203091612/https://abc.xyz/investor/ |archive-date=February 3, 2016 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nFor the 2006 fiscal year, the company reported $10.492 billion in total advertising revenues and only $112 million in licensing and other revenues.<ref name=\"10-K\">{{cite web |url=https://www.sec.gov/Archives/edgar/data/1288776/000119312507044494/d10k.htm |title=Form 10-K{{nbsp}}\u2013 Annual Report |accessdate=July 5, 2010 |publisher=SEC |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101106152355/http://www.sec.gov/Archives/edgar/data/1288776/000119312507044494/d10k.htm |archive-date=November 6, 2010 |url-status=live}}</ref> In 2011, 96% of Google's revenue was derived from its advertising programs.<ref name=\"Google-Inc-Jan-2012-10-K\">{{cite web |url=http://pdf.secdatabase.com/44/0001193125-12-025336.pdf |title=Google Inc, Form 10-K, Annual Report, Filing Date January 26, 2012 |publisher=secdatabase.com |accessdate=March 8, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130502193637/http://pdf.secdatabase.com/44/0001193125-12-025336.pdf |archive-date=May 2, 2013 |url-status=live}}</ref> In addition to its own algorithms for understanding search requests, Google uses technology from the company [[DoubleClick]], to project user interest and target advertising to the search context and the user history.<ref>{{Cite news |author=Nakashima, Ellen |title=Some Web Firms Say They Track Behavior Without Explicit Consent |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2008/08/11/AR2008081102270_pf.html |date=August 12, 2008 |work=The Washington Post |accessdate=July 5, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121112172756/http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2008/08/11/AR2008081102270_pf.html |archive-date=November 12, 2012 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first=Miguel |last=Helft |title=Google to Offer Ads Based on Interests |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/03/11/technology/internet/11google.html |website=[[The New York Times]] |date=March 11, 2009 |accessdate=March 9, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170328214358/http://www.nytimes.com/2009/03/11/technology/internet/11google.html |archive-date=March 28, 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn 2007, Google launched \"[[AdSense for Mobile]]\", taking advantage of the emerging mobile advertising market.<ref name=\"adsense_mobile\">{{cite web |url=https://www.google.com/intl/en/press/annc/20070917_mobileads.html |title=Google AdSense for Mobile unlocks the potential of the mobile advertising market |date=September 17, 2007 |website=Google, Inc. |accessdate=February 26, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120620042233/https://www.google.com/intl/en/press/annc/20070917_mobileads.html |archive-date=June 20, 2012 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n[[Google Analytics]] allows website owners to track where and how people use their website, for example by examining click rates for all the links on a page.<ref>{{cite web |first=Peter |last=Bright |title=Surfing on the sly with IE8's new \"InPrivate\" Internet |url=https://arstechnica.com/information-technology/2008/08/surfing-on-the-sly-ie8s-inprivate-internet/ |website=[[Ars Technica]] |publisher=[[Cond\u00e9 Nast]] |date=August 27, 2008 |accessdate=March 9, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170312040931/https://arstechnica.com/information-technology/2008/08/surfing-on-the-sly-ie8s-inprivate-internet/ |archive-date=March 12, 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref> Google advertisements can be placed on third-party websites in a two-part program. [[Google Ads]] allows advertisers to display their advertisements in the Google content network, through a cost-per-click scheme.<ref>{{cite web |first=Vangie |last=Beal |title=AdWords - Google AdWords |url=http://www.webopedia.com/TERM/A/adwords.html |website=Webopedia |publisher=QuinStreet Inc. |accessdate=May 27, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170629163240/http://www.webopedia.com/TERM/A/adwords.html |archive-date=June 29, 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref> The sister service, Google [[AdSense]], allows website owners to display these advertisements on their website and earn money every time ads are clicked.<ref>{{cite web |first=Vangie |last=Beal |title=AdSense - Google AdSense |url=http://www.webopedia.com/TERM/A/adsense.html |website=Webopedia |publisher=QuinStreet Inc. |accessdate=May 27, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170502044751/http://www.webopedia.com/TERM/A/adsense.html |archive-date=May 2, 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref> One of the criticisms of this program is the possibility of [[click fraud]], which occurs when a person or automated script clicks on advertisements without being interested in the product, causing the advertiser to pay money to Google unduly. Industry reports in 2006 claimed that approximately 14 to 20&nbsp;percent of clicks were fraudulent or invalid.<ref>{{cite news |last=Mills |first=Elinor |url=http://news.cnet.com/Google-to-offer-advertisers-click-fraud-stats/2100-1024_3-6098469.html |title=Google to offer advertisers click fraud stats |work=news.cnet.com |publisher=[[CNET]] |date=July 25, 2006 |accessdate=July 29, 2006 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110510075216/http://news.cnet.com/Google-to-offer-advertisers-click-fraud-stats/2100-1024_3-6098469.html |archive-date=May 10, 2011 |url-status=live}}</ref> [[Google Search Console]] (rebranded from Google Webmaster Tools in May 2015) allows [[webmasters]] to check the sitemap, crawl rate, and for security issues of their websites, as well as optimize their website's visibility.\n\n=== Consumer services ===\n\n==== Web-based services ====\nGoogle offers [[Gmail]] for [[email]],<ref>{{cite web |first=Chris |last=Gayomali |title=When Gmail Launched On April 1, 2004, People Thought It Was A Joke |url=https://www.fastcompany.com/3028513/when-gmail-launched-on-april-1-2004-people-thought-it-was-a-joke |website=[[Fast Company (magazine)|Fast Company]] |publisher=Mansueto Ventures |date=April 1, 2014 |accessdate=June 12, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171018201644/https://www.fastcompany.com/3028513/when-gmail-launched-on-april-1-2004-people-thought-it-was-a-joke |archive-date=October 18, 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref> [[Google Calendar]] for time-management and scheduling,<ref>{{cite web |first=James |last=Vincent |title=Google Calendar update makes it easier to track your New Year's fitness goals |url=https://www.theverge.com/2017/1/5/14175830/google-calendar-track-fitness-goals-health-data |website=[[The Verge]] |publisher=[[Vox Media]] |date=January 5, 2017 |accessdate=June 12, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170113025213/http://www.theverge.com/2017/1/5/14175830/google-calendar-track-fitness-goals-health-data |archive-date=January 13, 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref> [[Google Maps]] for mapping, navigation and [[satellite imagery]],<ref>{{cite web |first=Mitchel |last=Broussard |title=Google Maps Introduces New Location Sharing Feature With Real-Time Friend Tracking |url=https://www.macrumors.com/2017/03/22/google-maps-location-sharing/ |website=[[MacRumors]] |date=March 22, 2017 |accessdate=June 12, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170327173708/https://www.macrumors.com/2017/03/22/google-maps-location-sharing/ |archive-date=March 27, 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref> [[Google Drive]] for [[File hosting service|cloud storage]] of files,<ref name=\"verge-drive-announced\">{{cite web |first=T.C. |last=Sottek |title=Google Drive officially launches with 5&nbsp;GB free storage, Google Docs integration |url=https://www.theverge.com/2012/4/24/2971025/google-drive-official-launch-features |website=[[The Verge]] |publisher=[[Vox Media]] |date=April 24, 2012 |accessdate=June 12, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161226161807/http://www.theverge.com/2012/4/24/2971025/google-drive-official-launch-features |archive-date=December 26, 2016 |url-status=live}}</ref> [[Google Docs]], [[Google Sheets|Sheets]] and [[Google Slides|Slides]] for productivity,<ref name=\"verge-drive-announced\" /> [[Google Photos]] for photo storage and sharing,<ref>{{cite web |first=Sarah |last=Perez |title=Google Photos Breaks Free Of Google+, Now Offers Free, Unlimited Storage |url=https://techcrunch.com/2015/05/28/google-photos-breaks-free-of-google-now-offers-free-unlimited-storage/ |website=[[TechCrunch]] |publisher=[[AOL]] |date=May 28, 2015 |accessdate=June 12, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170706135643/https://techcrunch.com/2015/05/28/google-photos-breaks-free-of-google-now-offers-free-unlimited-storage/ |archive-date=July 6, 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref> [[Google Keep]] for [[note-taking]],<ref>{{cite web |first=Dan |last=Graziano |title=Google launches Google Keep note-taking service [video] |url=http://bgr.com/2013/03/20/google-keep-annnounced-388095/ |website=[[Boy Genius Report|BGR]] |publisher=[[Penske Media Corporation]] |date=March 20, 2013 |accessdate=June 12, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161008154306/http://bgr.com/2013/03/20/google-keep-annnounced-388095/ |archive-date=October 8, 2016 |url-status=live}}</ref> [[Google Translate]] for language translation,<ref>{{cite web |first=Lisa |last=Eadicicco |title=Google's Translation App Is About To Get Much Better |url=http://time.com/4572942/google-translate-app-update-2016/ |website=[[Time (magazine)|Time]] |date=November 16, 2016 |accessdate=June 12, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170401152526/http://time.com/4572942/google-translate-app-update-2016/ |archive-date=April 1, 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref> [[YouTube]] for video viewing and sharing,<ref>{{cite web |first=Saba |last=Hamedy |title=People now spend 1 billion hours watching YouTube every day |url=http://mashable.com/2017/02/27/youtube-one-billion-hours-of-video-daily/ |website=[[Mashable]] |date=February 28, 2017 |accessdate=June 12, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170517233015/http://mashable.com/2017/02/27/youtube-one-billion-hours-of-video-daily/ |archive-date=May 17, 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref> [[Google My Business]] for managing public business information,<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.google.com/business/ |title=Google My Business \u2013 Stand Out on Google for Free |website=www.google.com |access-date=February 6, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190207151521/https://www.google.com/business/ |archive-date=February 7, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> and [[Google Duo|Duo]] for social interaction.<ref>{{cite magazine |first=Steven |last=Levy |title=Inside Google+ - How the search giant plans to go social |url=https://www.wired.com/2011/06/inside-google-plus-social/ |magazine=[[Wired (website)|Wired]] |publisher=[[Cond\u00e9 Nast]] |date=June 28, 2011 |accessdate=June 12, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170405130052/https://www.wired.com/2011/06/inside-google-plus-social/ |archive-date=April 5, 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref> In March 2019, Google unveiled a [[cloud gaming]] service named [[Google Stadia|Stadia]].<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.theverge.com/2019/3/19/18271702/google-stadia-cloud-gaming-service-announcement-gdc-2019 |title=Google unveils Stadia cloud gaming service, launches in 2019 |last=Warren |first=Tom |date=March 19, 2019 |website=The Verge |access-date=April 8, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190319173136/https://www.theverge.com/2019/3/19/18271702/google-stadia-cloud-gaming-service-announcement-gdc-2019 |archive-date=March 19, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==== Software ====\nGoogle develops the [[Android (operating system)|Android]] [[mobile operating system]],<ref>{{cite web |first=Erick |last=Schonfeld |title=Breaking: Google Announces Android and Open Handset Alliance |url=https://techcrunch.com/2007/11/05/breaking-google-announces-android-and-open-handset-alliance/ |website=[[TechCrunch]] |publisher=[[AOL]] |date=November 5, 2007 |accessdate=June 12, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170622140334/https://techcrunch.com/2007/11/05/breaking-google-announces-android-and-open-handset-alliance/ |archive-date=June 22, 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref> as well as its [[Android Wear|smartwatch]],<ref>{{cite web |first=Dante |last=D'Orazio |title=Google reveals Android Wear, an operating system for smartwatches |url=https://www.theverge.com/2014/3/18/5522226/google-reveals-android-wear-an-operating-system-designed-for |website=[[The Verge]] |publisher=[[Vox Media]] |date=March 18, 2014 |accessdate=April 4, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170210034323/http://www.theverge.com/2014/3/18/5522226/google-reveals-android-wear-an-operating-system-designed-for |archive-date=February 10, 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref> [[Android TV|television]],<ref>{{cite web |first=Josh |last=Ong |title=Google announces Android TV to bring 'voice input, user experience and content' to the living room |url=https://thenextweb.com/google/2014/06/25/android-tv-google-io-2014/ |website=The Next Web |date=June 25, 2014 |accessdate=April 4, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170313130445/https://thenextweb.com/google/2014/06/25/android-tv-google-io-2014/ |archive-date=March 13, 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref> [[Android Auto|car]],<ref>{{cite web |first=Alex |last=Wilhelm |title=Google Announces Android Auto, Promises Enabled Cars By The End Of 2014 |url=https://techcrunch.com/2014/06/25/google-announces-android-auto-promises-enabled-cars-by-end-of-2014/ |website=[[TechCrunch]] |publisher=[[AOL]] |date=June 25, 2014 |accessdate=April 4, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170622135917/https://techcrunch.com/2014/06/25/google-announces-android-auto-promises-enabled-cars-by-end-of-2014/ |archive-date=June 22, 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref> and [[Internet of things]]-enabled [[Android Things|smart devices]] variations.<ref>{{cite web |first=Jacob |last=Kastrenakes |title=Android Things is Google's new OS for smart devices |url=https://www.theverge.com/2016/12/13/13924996/android-things-announced-smart-home-iot-operating-system |website=[[The Verge]] |publisher=[[Vox Media]] |date=December 13, 2016 |accessdate=April 4, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170217131058/http://www.theverge.com/2016/12/13/13924996/android-things-announced-smart-home-iot-operating-system |archive-date=February 17, 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIt also develops the [[Google Chrome]] web browser,<ref>{{cite web |first=Sundar |last=Pichai |first2=Linus |last2=Upson |title=A fresh take on the browser |url=https://googleblog.blogspot.no/2008/09/fresh-take-on-browser.html |website=Official Google Blog |date=September 1, 2008 |accessdate=November 22, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160315022315/https://googleblog.blogspot.no/2008/09/fresh-take-on-browser.html |archive-date=March 15, 2016 |url-status=live}}</ref> and [[Chrome OS]], an operating system based on Chrome.<ref>{{cite web |first=Sundar |last=Pichai |first2=Linus |last2=Upson |title=Introducing the Google Chrome OS |url=https://googleblog.blogspot.no/2009/07/introducing-google-chrome-os.html |website=Official Google Blog |date=July 7, 2009 |accessdate=November 22, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161122222918/https://googleblog.blogspot.no/2009/07/introducing-google-chrome-os.html |archive-date=November 22, 2016 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==== Hardware ====\n[[File:Pixel 3 \u3068 Pixel 3 XL \u3092\u521d\u89e6\u3002\u672c\u4f53\u3092\u30ae\u30e5\u30c3\u3068\u63e1\u308b\u3068 Google Assistant \u304c\u7acb\u3061\u4e0a\u304c\u308b\u306e\u304c\u304a\u3082\u3057\u308d\u3044\u3002 \u30ef\u30b7\u30f3\u30c8\u30f3DC (44519013945).jpg|alt=|thumb|Google Pixel smartphones on display in a store]]\nIn January 2010, Google released [[Nexus One]], the first Android phone under its own brand, \"Nexus\".<ref>{{cite web |first=MG |last=Siegler |title=The Droid You're Looking For: Live From The Nexus One Event |url=https://techcrunch.com/2010/01/05/nexus-one-event/ |website=[[TechCrunch]] |publisher=[[AOL]] |date=January 5, 2010 |accessdate=November 22, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161123054909/https://techcrunch.com/2010/01/05/nexus-one-event/ |archive-date=November 23, 2016 |url-status=live}}</ref> It spawned a number of phones and tablets under the \"Nexus\" branding<ref>{{cite web |first=Florence |last=Ion |title=From Nexus One to Nexus 10: a brief history of Google's flagship devices |url=https://arstechnica.com/gadgets/2013/05/from-the-nexus-one-to-the-nexus-10-a-brief-history-of-nexus-devices/ |website=[[Ars Technica]] |publisher=[[Cond\u00e9 Nast]] |date=May 15, 2013 |accessdate=June 12, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170624004245/https://arstechnica.com/gadgets/2013/05/from-the-nexus-one-to-the-nexus-10-a-brief-history-of-nexus-devices/ |archive-date=June 24, 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref> until its eventual discontinuation in 2016, replaced by a new brand called [[Pixel (smartphone)|Pixel]].<ref name=\"Pixel inside story\">{{cite web |first=Dieter |last=Bohn |title=The Google Phone: The inside story of Google's bold bet on hardware |url=https://www.theverge.com/a/google-pixel-phone-new-hardware-interview-2016 |website=[[The Verge]] |publisher=[[Vox Media]] |accessdate=June 12, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170106213353/http://www.theverge.com/a/google-pixel-phone-new-hardware-interview-2016 |archive-date=January 6, 2017 |url-status=live|date=October 4, 2016 }}</ref>\n\nIn 2011, the [[Chromebook]] was introduced, described as a \"new kind of computer\" running [[Chrome OS]].<ref>{{cite web |first=Sundar |last=Pichai |first2=Linus |last2=Upson |title=A new kind of computer: Chromebook |url=https://googleblog.blogspot.no/2011/05/new-kind-of-computer-chromebook.html |website=Official Google Blog |date=May 11, 2011 |accessdate=November 22, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161122222651/https://googleblog.blogspot.no/2011/05/new-kind-of-computer-chromebook.html |archive-date=November 22, 2016 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2013, Google introduced the [[Chromecast]] dongle, that allows users to stream content from their smartphones to televisions.<ref>{{cite web |first=Adi |last=Robertson |title=Google reveals Chromecast: video streaming to your TV from any device for $35 |url=https://www.theverge.com/2013/7/24/4552204/google-reveals-chromecast-tv-streaming |website=[[The Verge]] |publisher=[[Vox Media]] |date=July 24, 2013 |accessdate=November 29, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161226065215/http://www.theverge.com/2013/7/24/4552204/google-reveals-chromecast-tv-streaming |archive-date=December 26, 2016 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Google Chromecast takes on streaming content to TV |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/technology-23514400 |website=[[BBC News]] |publisher=[[BBC]] |date=July 31, 2013 |accessdate=November 29, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161129205929/http://www.bbc.com/news/technology-23514400 |archive-date=November 29, 2016 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2014, Google announced [[Google Cardboard]], a simple cardboard viewer that lets user place their smartphone in a special front compartment to view [[virtual reality]] (VR) media.<ref>{{cite web |first=James |last=O'Toole |title=Google's cardboard virtual-reality goggles |url=http://money.cnn.com/2014/06/25/technology/innovation/google-cardboard/ |publisher=[[CNN]] |date=June 26, 2014 |accessdate=November 29, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161129145138/http://money.cnn.com/2014/06/25/technology/innovation/google-cardboard/ |archive-date=November 29, 2016 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first=Erik |last=Kain |title=Google Cardboard Is Google's Awesomely Weird Answer To Virtual Reality |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/erikkain/2014/06/26/google-cardboard-is-googles-awesomely-weird-answer-to-virtual-reality/ |website=[[Forbes]] |date=June 26, 2014 |accessdate=November 29, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161129151747/http://www.forbes.com/sites/erikkain/2014/06/26/google-cardboard-is-googles-awesomely-weird-answer-to-virtual-reality/ |archive-date=November 29, 2016 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n* The [[Pixel (smartphone)|Pixel and Pixel XL]] smartphones with the [[Google Assistant]], a next-generation contextual voice assistant, built-in.<ref>{{cite web |first=Vlad |last=Savov |title=Pixel 'phone by Google' announced |url=https://www.theverge.com/2016/10/4/13161028/google-phone-announced-pixel-xl-price-release-date-specs |website=[[The Verge]] |publisher=[[Vox Media]] |date=October 4, 2016 |accessdate=October 8, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170210094337/http://www.theverge.com/2016/10/4/13161028/google-phone-announced-pixel-xl-price-release-date-specs |archive-date=February 10, 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n* [[Google Home]], an [[Amazon Echo]]-like voice assistant placed in the house that can answer voice queries, play music, find information from apps (calendar, weather etc.), and control third-party smart home appliances (users can tell it to turn on the lights, for example). The Google Home line also includes variants such as the [[Google Home Hub]], [[Google Home Mini]], and [[Google Home Max]]<ref>{{cite web |first=Dieter |last=Bohn |title=Google Home is smart, loud, and kind of cute |url=https://www.theverge.com/2016/10/4/13156676/google-home-assistant-speaker-photos-video-device-hands-on |website=[[The Verge]] |publisher=[[Vox Media]] |date=October 4, 2016 |accessdate=October 8, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161007204916/http://www.theverge.com/2016/10/4/13156676/google-home-assistant-speaker-photos-video-device-hands-on |archive-date=October 7, 2016 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n* [[Google Daydream|Daydream View]] [[virtual reality]] headset that lets [[Android (operating system)|Android]] users with compatible Daydream-ready smartphones put their phones in the headset and enjoy VR content.<ref>{{cite web |first=Adi |last=Robertson |first2=Jacob |last2=Kastrenakes |title=Google's Daydream View VR headset goes on sale next month for $79 |url=https://www.theverge.com/2016/10/4/13161506/google-vr-headset-photos-daydream-view-virtual-reality |website=[[The Verge]] |publisher=[[Vox Media]] |date=October 4, 2016 |accessdate=October 8, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161007203651/http://www.theverge.com/2016/10/4/13161506/google-vr-headset-photos-daydream-view-virtual-reality |archive-date=October 7, 2016 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n* [[Google Wifi]], a connected set of [[Wi-Fi]] routers to simplify and extend coverage of home Wi-Fi.<ref>{{cite web |first=Dieter |last=Bohn |title=The Google Wifi routers are little white pucks you can scatter throughout your house |url=https://www.theverge.com/2016/10/4/13157680/google-wifi-router-photos-hands-on |website=[[The Verge]] |publisher=[[Vox Media]] |date=October 4, 2016 |accessdate=October 8, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161007180430/http://www.theverge.com/2016/10/4/13157680/google-wifi-router-photos-hands-on |archive-date=October 7, 2016 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Enterprise services{{anchor|Enterprise_products}}===\n{{Main|G Suite|Google Cloud Platform}}\n\n[[G Suite]] is a monthly subscription offering for organizations and businesses to get access to a collection of Google's services, including [[Gmail]], [[Google Drive]] and [[Google Docs]], [[Google Sheets]] and [[Google Slides]], with additional administrative tools, unique domain names, and 24/7 support.<ref>{{cite web |title=Choose a Plan |url=https://gsuite.google.com/intl/en_ie/pricing.html |website=G Suite by Google Cloud |accessdate=December 2, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161212231639/https://gsuite.google.com/intl/en_ie/pricing.html |archive-date=December 12, 2016 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn September 24, 2012,<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://googleblog.blogspot.com/2012/09/celebrating-spirit-of-entrepreneurship.html |title=Celebrating the spirit of entrepreneurship with the new Google for Entrepreneurs |website=Official Google Blog |language=en |access-date=March 20, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180320171207/https://googleblog.blogspot.com/2012/09/celebrating-spirit-of-entrepreneurship.html |archive-date=March 20, 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref> Google launched [[Google for Entrepreneurs]], a largely not-for-profit [[business incubator]] providing startups with [[Coworking|co-working spaces]] known as Campuses, with assistance to startup founders that may include workshops, conferences, and mentorships.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.entrepreneur.com/article/224522 |title=How Google Wants to Make Starting Up Easier for Entrepreneurs |last=Fell |first=Jason |date=September 27, 2012 |work=Entrepreneur |access-date=March 20, 2018 |language=en |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180320230407/https://www.entrepreneur.com/article/224522 |archive-date=March 20, 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref> Presently, there are 7 Campus locations in [[Berlin]], [[London]], [[Madrid]], [[Seoul]], [[S\u00e3o Paulo]], [[Tel Aviv]], and [[Warsaw]].\n\nOn March 15, 2016, Google announced the introduction of Google Analytics 360 Suite, \"a set of integrated data and marketing analytics products, designed specifically for the needs of enterprise-class marketers\" which can be integrated with [[BigQuery]] on the Google Cloud Platform. Among other things, the suite is designed to help \"enterprise class marketers\" \"see the complete customer journey\", generate \"useful insights\", and \"deliver engaging experiences to the right people\".<ref>{{cite web |first=Paul |last=Muret |title=Introducing the Google Analytics 360 Suite |url=https://analytics.googleblog.com/2016/03/introducing-google-analytics-360-suite.html |date=March 15, 2016 |accessdate=January 22, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170112142850/https://analytics.googleblog.com/2016/03/introducing-google-analytics-360-suite.html |archive-date=January 12, 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref> Jack Marshall of ''[[The Wall Street Journal]]'' wrote that the suite competes with existing marketing cloud offerings by companies including [[Adobe Systems|Adobe]], [[Oracle Corporation|Oracle]], [[Salesforce.com|Salesforce]], and [[IBM]].<ref>{{cite news |first=Jack |last=Marshall |title=Google Launches New Data Tools for Marketers |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/google-launches-new-data-tools-for-marketers-1458043217 |newspaper=[[The Wall Street Journal]] |date=March 15, 2016 |accessdate=January 22, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161113150024/http://www.wsj.com/articles/google-launches-new-data-tools-for-marketers-1458043217 |archive-date=November 13, 2016 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== Internet services ===\nIn February 2010, Google announced the [[Google Fiber]] project, with experimental plans to build an ultra-high-speed broadband network for 50,000 to 500,000 customers in one or more American cities.<ref>{{cite web |first=Minnie |last=Ingersoll |first2=James |last2=Kelly |title=Think big with a gig: Our experimental fiber network |url=https://googleblog.blogspot.no/2010/02/think-big-with-gig-our-experimental.html |website=Official Google Blog |date=February 10, 2010 |accessdate=November 29, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161129150926/https://googleblog.blogspot.no/2010/02/think-big-with-gig-our-experimental.html |archive-date=November 29, 2016 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first=Erick |last=Schonfeld |title=Google Plans To Deliver 1Gb/sec Fiber-Optic Broadband Network To More Than 50,000 Homes |url=https://techcrunch.com/2010/02/10/google-fiber-optic-network-home/ |website=[[TechCrunch]] |publisher=[[AOL]] |date=February 10, 2010 |accessdate=November 29, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161129145628/https://techcrunch.com/2010/02/10/google-fiber-optic-network-home/ |archive-date=November 29, 2016 |url-status=live}}</ref> Following Google's corporate restructure to make [[Alphabet Inc.]] its parent company, Google Fiber was moved to Alphabet's Access division.<ref>{{cite web |first=Kevin |last=McLaughlin |title=Inside the Battle Over Google Fiber |url=https://www.theinformation.com/articles/inside-the-battle-over-google-fiber |website=The Information |date=August 25, 2016 |accessdate=November 29, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161129144256/https://www.theinformation.com/articles/inside-the-battle-over-google-fiber |archive-date=November 29, 2016 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first=Nick |last=Statt |title=Alphabet is putting serious pressure on Google Fiber to cut costs |url=https://www.theverge.com/2016/8/25/12652734/google-fiber-access-alphabet-layoffs-wireless-internet |website=[[The Verge]] |publisher=[[Vox Media]] |date=August 25, 2016 |accessdate=November 29, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161129145849/http://www.theverge.com/2016/8/25/12652734/google-fiber-access-alphabet-layoffs-wireless-internet |archive-date=November 29, 2016 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2015, Google announced [[Project Fi]], a mobile virtual network operator, that combines Wi-Fi and cellular networks from different telecommunication providers in an effort to enable seamless connectivity and fast Internet signal.<ref>{{cite web |first=Nick |last=Fox |title=Say hi to Fi: A new way to say hello |url=https://googleblog.blogspot.no/2015/04/project-fi.html |website=Official Google Blog |date=April 22, 2015 |accessdate=November 29, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161129150714/https://googleblog.blogspot.no/2015/04/project-fi.html |archive-date=November 29, 2016 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first=David |last=Goldman |title=Google launches 'Project Fi' wireless service |url=http://money.cnn.com/2015/04/22/technology/google-project-fi-wireless-service/ |website=[[CNN]] |date=April 22, 2015 |accessdate=November 29, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161129150255/http://money.cnn.com/2015/04/22/technology/google-project-fi-wireless-service/ |archive-date=November 29, 2016 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first=Ellen |last=Huet |title=Google Unveils Its 'Project Fi' Wireless Service |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/ellenhuet/2015/04/22/google-unveils-wireless-service-project-fi/ |website=[[Forbes]] |date=April 22, 2015 |accessdate=November 29, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161129152041/http://www.forbes.com/sites/ellenhuet/2015/04/22/google-unveils-wireless-service-project-fi/ |archive-date=November 29, 2016 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2016, Google began its Google Station initiative, a project for public Wi-Fi at railway stations in India. Caesar Sengupta, VP for Google's next billion users, told ''[[The Verge]]'' that 15,000 people get online for the first time thanks to Google Station and that 3.5 million people use the service every month. The expansion meant that Google was looking for partners around the world to further develop the initiative, which promised \"high-quality, secure, easily accessible Wi-Fi\".<ref>{{cite web |first=Sam |last=Byford |title=Google Station is a new platform that aims to make public Wi-Fi better |url=https://www.theverge.com/2016/9/27/13070922/google-station-public-wi-fi-india |website=[[The Verge]] |publisher=[[Vox Media]] |date=September 27, 2016 |accessdate=October 23, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161023203300/http://www.theverge.com/2016/9/27/13070922/google-station-public-wi-fi-india |archive-date=October 23, 2016 |url-status=live}}</ref> By December, Google Station had been deployed at 100 railway stations,<ref>{{cite web |first=Brian |last=Heater |title=After arriving at 100th railway station in India, Google's WiFi is set to hit another 100 in 2017 |url=https://techcrunch.com/2016/12/29/google-india-wifi/ |website=[[TechCrunch]] |publisher=[[AOL]] |date=December 29, 2016 |accessdate=June 12, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170510091945/https://techcrunch.com/2016/12/29/google-india-wifi/ |archive-date=May 10, 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref> and in February, Google announced its intention to expand beyond railway stations, with a plan to bring citywide Wi-Fi to [[Pune]].<ref>{{cite web |first=Stephen |last=Hall |title=Google Station expands beyond rail stations to bring citywide WiFi to Pune, India |url=https://9to5google.com/2017/02/09/google-station-expands-beyond-rail-stations-to-bring-citywide-wifi-to-pune-india/ |website=9to5Google |date=February 9, 2017 |accessdate=June 12, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170210233838/https://9to5google.com/2017/02/09/google-station-expands-beyond-rail-stations-to-bring-citywide-wifi-to-pune-india/ |archive-date=February 10, 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first=Manish |last=Singh |title=Indian city to become the first in the world to get Google Station public Wi-Fi network |url=http://mashable.com/2017/02/09/google-station-pune-india/ |website=[[Mashable]] |date=February 9, 2017 |accessdate=June 12, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170223153245/http://mashable.com/2017/02/09/google-station-pune-india/ |archive-date=February 23, 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== Other products ===\nIn May 2011, Google announced [[Google Wallet]], a mobile application for wireless payments.<ref>{{cite news |first=Tara |last=Bernard |title=Google Unveils App for Paying With Phone |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/05/27/technology/27google.html |website=[[The New York Times]] |date=May 26, 2011 |accessdate=November 29, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161012171341/http://www.nytimes.com/2011/05/27/technology/27google.html |archive-date=October 12, 2016 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013, Google launched [[Google Shopping Express]], a delivery service initially available only in San Francisco and Silicon Valley.<ref>{{cite news |last=Somerville |first=Heather |url=http://www.mercurynews.com/business/ci_24171776/exclusive-google-same-day-delivery-makes-public-debut |title=Google same-day delivery makes public debut |newspaper=Mercury News |date=September 25, 2013 |access-date=October 6, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131001221830/http://www.mercurynews.com/business/ci_24171776/exclusive-google-same-day-delivery-makes-public-debut |archive-date=October 1, 2013 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n== Corporate affairs ==\n\n=== Finance ===\n{{Further|Corporation tax in the Republic of Ireland#Multinational tax schemes|Google tax}}\n\n[[File:Schmidt-Brin-Page-20080520.jpg|thumb|Then-CEO, now Chairman of Google [[Eric Schmidt]] with cofounders [[Sergey Brin]] and [[Larry Page]] (left to right) in 2008.|alt=Eric Schmidt, Sergey Brin, and Larry Page sitting together]]\nGoogle's [[initial public offering]] (IPO) took place on August 19, 2004. At IPO, the company offered 19,605,052 shares at a price of $85 per share.<ref name=\"IPO\" /><ref name=\":1\" /> The sale of $1.67 billion gave Google a [[market capitalization]] of more than $23 billion.<ref name=\"washpost\" /> The stock performed well after the IPO, with shares hitting $350 for the first time on October 31, 2007,<ref>{{cite news |url=http://weblogs.baltimoresun.com/business/hancock/blog/2007/10/google_shares_hit_700.html |title=Google shares hit $700 |last=Hancock |first=Jay |date=October 31, 2007 |work=The Baltimore Sun |accessdate=November 27, 2010 |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/659XVy0yM?url=http://weblogs.baltimoresun.com/business/hancock/blog/2007/10/google_shares_hit_700.html |archive-date=February 2, 2012 |url-status=live}}</ref> primarily because of strong sales and earnings in the [[online advertising]] market.<ref name=\"bowlingforgoogle\">{{Cite news |url=http://money.cnn.com/2005/05/25/technology/techinvestor/lamonica/index.htm |title=Bowling for Google |last=La Monica |first=Paul R. |date=May 25, 2005 |work=CNN |accessdate=February 28, 2007 |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/659XXqofq?url=http://money.cnn.com/2005/05/25/technology/techinvestor/lamonica/index.htm |archive-date=February 2, 2012 |url-status=live}}</ref> The surge in stock price was fueled mainly by individual investors, as opposed to large institutional investors and [[mutual fund]]s.<ref name=\"bowlingforgoogle\" /> GOOG shares split into GOOG [[class C share]]s and GOOGL [[class A share]]s.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2015/04/02/stock-split-could-cost-google-over-500-million.html |title=This could cost Google more than $500 million |website=CNBC |accessdate=December 30, 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151226080454/http://www.cnbc.com/2015/04/02/stock-split-could-cost-google-over-500-million.html |archive-date=December 26, 2015 |url-status=live|date=April 2, 2015 }}</ref> The company is listed on the [[NASDAQ]] stock exchange under the [[ticker symbol]]s GOOGL and GOOG, and on the [[Frankfurt Stock Exchange]] under the ticker symbol GGQ1. These ticker symbols now refer to Alphabet Inc., Google's holding company, {{as of|2015|8|10|alt=since the fourth quarter of 2015.}}<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2015/08/10/google-announces-plans-for-new-operating-structure.html |title=Google to become part of new company, Alphabet |last=Pramuk |first=Jacob |date=August 10, 2015 |newspaper=[[CNBC]] |accessdate=August 11, 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150811000128/http://www.cnbc.com/2015/08/10/google-announces-plans-for-new-operating-structure.html |archive-date=August 11, 2015 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe corporation's consolidated revenue for the third quarter of 2013 was reported in mid-October 2013 as $14.89 billion, a 12 percent increase compared to the previous quarter.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.androidpolice.com/2013/10/18/google-beats-analyst-estimates-for-third-quarter-results-stock-passes-1000-per-share/ |title=Google Beats Analyst Estimates For Third Quarter Results, Stock Passes $1000 Per Share |last=Whitwam |first=Ryan |date=October 18, 2013 |website=Android Police |accessdate=March 15, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170316025733/http://www.androidpolice.com/2013/10/18/google-beats-analyst-estimates-for-third-quarter-results-stock-passes-1000-per-share/ |archive-date=March 16, 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref> Google's Internet business was responsible for $10.8 billion of this total, with an increase in the number of users' clicks on advertisements.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2013/oct/17/google-q3-revenue-earnings-report |title=Google earnings up 12% in third quarter even as Motorola losses deepen |agency=Reuters |date=October 17, 2013 |newspaper=The Guardian |accessdate=October 18, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131017221536/http://www.theguardian.com/technology/2013/oct/17/google-q3-revenue-earnings-report |archive-date=October 17, 2013 |url-status=dead}}</ref> By January 2014, Google's market capitalization had grown to $397 billion.<ref name=\"Marketwatch\">{{cite web |url=http://www.marketwatch.com/investing/stock/goog |title=Google Overview |website=Marketwatch |accessdate=February 2, 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140202073406/http://www.marketwatch.com/investing/stock/GOOG |archive-date=February 2, 2014 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nGoogle uses various [[Tax avoidance|tax avoidance strategies]]. Out of the [[List of the largest information technology companies|five largest American technology companies]], it pays the lowest taxes to the countries of origin of its revenues. Google between 2007 and 2010 saved $3.1 billion in taxes by shuttling non-U.S. profits through [[Ireland]] and the [[Netherlands]] and then to [[Bermuda]]. Such techniques lower its non-U.S. tax rate to 2.3 per cent, while normally the corporate tax rate in for instance the UK is 28 per cent.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theregister.co.uk/2010/10/22/google_double_irish_tax_loophole/ |title=Google slips $3.1bn through 'Double Irish' tax loophole. |last=Metz |first=Cade |date=October 22, 2010 |website=The Register |access-date=August 10, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170706132414/https://www.theregister.co.uk/2010/10/22/google_double_irish_tax_loophole/ |archive-date=July 6, 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref> This has reportedly sparked a French investigation into Google's [[transfer pricing]] practices.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theregister.co.uk/2012/10/31/google_france_tax_office_billion_euros/ |title=French gov 'plans to hand Google \u20ac1bn tax bill'&nbsp;\u2013 report |last=Leach |first=Anna |date=October 31, 2012 |publisher=Theregister.co.uk |accessdate=January 2, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130104002014/http://www.theregister.co.uk/2012/10/31/google_france_tax_office_billion_euros/ |archive-date=January 4, 2013 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nGoogle said it overhauled its controversial global tax structure and consolidated all of its intellectual property holdings back to the US.<ref name=\"GoogleIPRichardWaters\">{{cite news|first=Richard|last=Waters|url=https://www.ft.com/content/991f11ae-2c51-11ea-bc77-65e4aa615551|title=Google to end use of 'double Irish' as tax loophole set to close|work=[[The Times]]|date=2 January 2020}}</ref>\n\nGoogle Vice-President [[Matt Brittin]] testified to the [[Public Accounts Committee (United Kingdom)|Public Accounts Committee]] of the UK House of Commons that his UK sales team made no sales and hence owed no sales taxes to the UK.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theregister.co.uk/2013/05/17/quotw_ending_may_17/ |title=I think you DO do evil, using smoke and mirrors to avoid tax |author=Brid-Aine Parnell |date=May 17, 2013 |publisher=Theregister.co.uk |accessdate=March 13, 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131226090028/http://www.theregister.co.uk/2013/05/17/quotw_ending_may_17/ |archive-date=December 26, 2013 |url-status=live}}</ref> In January 2016, Google reached a settlement with the UK to pay \u00a3130m in back taxes plus higher taxes in future.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ft.com/cms/s/0/d50ad5f4-c125-11e5-9fdb-87b8d15baec2.html |title=Google strikes \u00a3130m back tax deal |author=John Gapper|date=January 23, 2016 |publisher=FT.com |accessdate=January 24, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160124195612/http://www.ft.com/cms/s/0/d50ad5f4-c125-11e5-9fdb-87b8d15baec2.html |archive-date=January 24, 2016 |url-status=live}}</ref> In 2017, Google channeled $22.7 billion from the Netherlands to Bermuda to reduce its tax bill.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-google-taxes-netherlands/google-shifted-23-billion-to-tax-haven-bermuda-in-2017-filing-idUSKCN1OX1G9 |title=Google shifted $23 billion to tax haven Bermuda in 2017: filing |last=Bart Meijer |date=January 3, 2019 |work=Reuters |accessdate=January 3, 2019 |quote=Google moved 19.9 billion euros ($22.7 billion) through a Dutch shell company to Bermuda in 2017, as part of an arrangement that allows it to reduce its foreign tax bill |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190103215930/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-google-taxes-netherlands/google-shifted-23-billion-to-tax-haven-bermuda-in-2017-filing-idUSKCN1OX1G9 |archive-date=January 3, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013, Google ranked 5th in [[Lobbying in the United States|lobbying]] spending, up from 213th in 2003. In 2012, the company ranked 2nd in campaign donations of technology and Internet sections.<ref name=\"lobby1\">{{cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/how-google-is-transforming-power-and-politicsgoogle-once-disdainful-of-lobbying-now-a-master-of-washington-influence/2014/04/12/51648b92-b4d3-11e3-8cb6-284052554d74_story.html |title=Google, once disdainful of lobbying, now a master of Washington influence |last=Hamburger |first=Tom |date=April 13, 2014 |work=[[The Washington Post]] |last2=Gold |first2=Matea |access-date=August 22, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171027124925/https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/how-google-is-transforming-power-and-politicsgoogle-once-disdainful-of-lobbying-now-a-master-of-washington-influence/2014/04/12/51648b92-b4d3-11e3-8cb6-284052554d74_story.html |archive-date=October 27, 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== Corporate identity ===\n{{Main|History of Google#Name|Google (verb)|Google logo|Google Doodle|List of Google April Fools' Day jokes|List of Google Easter eggs}}\n[[File:Logo Google 2013 Official.svg|thumb|200px|Google's logo from 2013-2015]]\nThe name \"Google\" originated from a misspelling of \"[[googol]]\",<ref>Koller, David. \"[http://graphics.stanford.edu/~dk/google_name_origin.html Origin of the name, \"Google.\"] {{webarchive|url=https://www.webcitation.org/68ubHzYs7?url=http://graphics.stanford.edu/~dk/google_name_origin.html|date=2012-07-04}} ''[[Stanford University]].'' January, 2004.</ref><ref name=\"Hanley\">Hanley, Rachael. \"[http://www.stanforddaily.com/2003/02/12/from-googol-to-google/ From Googol to Google: Co-founder returns] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100330004631/http://www.stanforddaily.com/2003/02/12/from-googol-to-google/|date=March 30, 2010}}.\" ''[[The Stanford Daily]].'' February 12, 2003. Retrieved on August 26, 2010.</ref> which refers to the number represented by a 1 followed by one-hundred zeros. Page and Brin write in their original paper on [[PageRank]]:<ref name=\"originalpaper\">{{Cite journal|last=Brin|first=Sergey|author-link=Sergey Brin|last2=Page|first2=Lawrence|author-link2=Larry Page|year=1998|title=The anatomy of a large-scale hypertextual Web search engine|url=http://infolab.stanford.edu/pub/papers/google.pdf|url-status=live|journal=Computer Networks and ISDN Systems|volume=30|issue=1\u20137|pages=107\u2013117|citeseerx=10.1.1.115.5930|doi=10.1016/S0169-7552(98)00110-X|issn=0169-7552|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150927004511/http://infolab.stanford.edu/pub/papers/google.pdf|archive-date=September 27, 2015|access-date=April 7, 2019}}</ref> \"We chose our systems name, Google, because it is a common spelling of googol, or 10<sup>100</sup> and fits well with our goal of building very large-scale search engines.\" Having found its way increasingly into everyday language, the verb \"[[Google (verb)|google]]\" was added to the ''[[Merriam-Webster Collegiate Dictionary|Merriam Webster Collegiate Dictionary]]'' and the ''[[Oxford English Dictionary]]'' in 2006, meaning \"to use the Google search engine to obtain information on the Internet.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.mercurynews.com/mld/mercurynews/business/14985574.htm|title=Dictionary adds verb: to google|work=San Jose Mercury News|last=Harris|first=Scott D.|date=July 7, 2006|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070206065348/http://www.mercurynews.com/mld/mercurynews/business/14985574.htm|archive-date=February 6, 2007|url-status=dead|access-date=July 7, 2006}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Bylund|first=Anders|url=http://msnbc.msn.com/id/13720643/|title=To Google or Not to Google|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://archive.today/20060707062623/http://msnbc.msn.com/id/13720643/|archive-date=July 7, 2006|work=[[The Motley Fool]]|via=[[MSNBC]]|date=July 5, 2006|access-date=July 7, 2006}}</ref> Google's [[mission statement]], from the outset, was \"to organize the world's information and make it universally accessible and useful\",<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2014/nov/03/larry-page-google-dont-be-evil-sergey-brin |title=Google has 'outgrown' its 14-year old mission statement, says Larry Page |last=Gibbs |first=Samuel |date=November 3, 2014 |website=[[The Guardian]] |publisher=[[Guardian Media Group]] |accessdate=March 25, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170326053031/https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2014/nov/03/larry-page-google-dont-be-evil-sergey-brin |archive-date=March 26, 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref> and its unofficial slogan is \"[[Don't be evil]]\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://abc.xyz/investor/other/google-code-of-conduct.html |title=Google Code of Conduct |date=April 11, 2012 |website=Alphabet Investor Relations |publisher=[[Alphabet Inc.]] |accessdate=March 25, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170211223917/https://abc.xyz/investor/other/google-code-of-conduct.html |archive-date=February 11, 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref> In October 2015, a related motto was adopted in the Alphabet corporate code of conduct by the phrase: \"Do the right thing\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.engadget.com/2015/10/02/alphabet-do-the-right-thing/ |title=Alphabet replaces Google's 'Don't be evil' with 'Do the right thing' |last=Lawler |first=Richard |date=October 2, 2015 |website=[[Engadget]] |publisher=[[AOL]] |accessdate=March 25, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170701225925/https://www.engadget.com/2015/10/02/alphabet-do-the-right-thing/ |archive-date=July 1, 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref> The original motto was retained in the code of conduct of Google, now a subsidiary of Alphabet.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nThe original [[Google logo]] was designed by Sergey Brin.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.ndtv.com/photos/news/happy-birthday-google--8267#photo-99345 |title=Happy Birthday Google! |accessdate=April 28, 2016 |publisher=ndtv.com |agency=NDTV Convergence Limited |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190407042748/https://www.ndtv.com/photos/news/happy-birthday-google--8267#photo-99345 |archive-date=April 7, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> {{As of|1998|since=y|post=,}} Google has been designing special, temporary alternate logos to place on their homepage intended to celebrate holidays, events, achievements and people. The first [[Google Doodle]] was in honor of the [[Burning Man|Burning Man Festival]] of 1998.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.google.com/doodle4google/history.html |title=Doodle 4 Google |date= |accessdate=April 23, 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140427143948/http://www.google.com/doodle4google/history.html |archive-date=April 27, 2014 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.google.com/doodles/burning-man-festival |title=Burning Man Festival |date=August 30, 1998 |accessdate=April 23, 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140425051111/https://www.google.com/doodles/burning-man-festival |archive-date=April 25, 2014 |url-status=live}}</ref> The doodle was designed by [[Larry Page]] and [[Sergey Brin]] to notify users of their absence in case the servers crashed. Subsequent Google Doodles were designed by an outside contractor, until Larry and Sergey asked then-[[intern]] [[Dennis Hwang]] to design a logo for [[Bastille Day]] in 2000. From that point onward, Doodles have been organized and created by a team of employees termed \"Doodlers\".<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2014/apr/12/meet-people-behind-google-doodles-logo |title=Meet the people behind the Google Doodles |date=April 12, 2014 |newspaper=The Guardian |accessdate=September 27, 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141006222909/http://www.theguardian.com/technology/2014/apr/12/meet-people-behind-google-doodles-logo |archive-date=October 6, 2014 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nGoogle has a tradition of creating [[April Fools' Day]] jokes. Its first on April 1, 2000 was [[Google's hoaxes#2000|Google MentalPlex]] which allegedly featured the use of mental power to search the web.<ref name=\"mentalplex\">{{cite web |url=https://www.google.com/mentalplex/ |title=Google MentalPlex |date=April 1, 2000 |publisher=Google, Inc. |accessdate=July 5, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100921223048/http://www.google.com/mentalplex/ |archive-date=September 21, 2010 |url-status=live}}</ref> In 2007, Google announced a free Internet service called [[TiSP]], or Toilet Internet Service Provider, where one obtained a connection by flushing one end of a [[optical fiber|fiber-optic]] cable down their toilet.<ref name=\"TiSP\">{{cite web |url=https://www.google.com/tisp/ |title=Welcome to Google TiSP |date=April 1, 2007 |publisher=Google, Inc. |accessdate=July 5, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100709034300/http://www.google.com/tisp/ |archive-date=July 9, 2010 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nGoogle's services contain [[Easter egg (media)|easter eggs]], such as the [[Swedish Chef]]'s \"Bork bork bork,\" [[Pig Latin]], \"Hacker\" or [[leet]]speak, [[Elmer Fudd]], [[International Talk Like a Pirate Day|Pirate]], and [[Klingon language|Klingon]] as language selections for its search engine.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.google.com/language_tools |title=Language Tools |publisher=Google, Inc. |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5hT77QDRS?url=http://www.google.com/language_tools |archivedate=June 12, 2009 |url-status=dead |accessdate=July 4, 2010}}</ref> When searching for the word \"[[anagram]],\" meaning a rearrangement of letters from one word to form other valid words, Google's suggestion feature displays \"Did you mean: nag a ram?\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.google.com/search?q=anagram |title=anagram search |publisher=Google, Inc. |accessdate=September 22, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130624205429/http://www.google.com/search?q=anagram |archive-date=June 24, 2013 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Workplace culture{{Anchor|Innovation Time Off|Employees}}===\n[[File:Pride in London 2016 - Google participating in the parade.png|alt=|left|thumb|Google employees marching in the [[Pride in London]] parade in 2016]]\nOn ''[[Fortune (magazine)|Fortune]]'' magazine's list of the best companies to work for, Google ranked first in 2007, 2008 and 2012,<ref name=\"best_company\">{{Cite journal |last=Levering |first=Robert |last2=Moskowitz |first2=Milton |date=January 22, 2007 |editor1-last=Serwer |editor1-first=Andrew |title=In good company |url=http://money.cnn.com/magazines/fortune/fortune_archive/2007/01/22/8398125/index.htm |journal=Fortune Magazine |volume=155 |issue=1 |pages=94-6, 100, 102 passim |pmid=17256628 |accessdate=June 19, 2010 |editor1-link=Andrew Serwer |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100301175257/http://money.cnn.com/magazines/fortune/fortune_archive/2007/01/22/8398125/index.htm |archive-date=March 1, 2010 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal |last=Levering |first=Robert |last2=Moskowitz |first2=Milton |date=February 4, 2008 |editor1-last=Serwer |editor1-first=Andrew |title=The 2008 list |url=http://money.cnn.com/magazines/fortune/bestcompanies/2008/full_list/index.html |journal=Fortune Magazine |volume=157 |issue=2 |accessdate=June 19, 2010 |editor1-link=Andrew Serwer |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100723223729/http://money.cnn.com/magazines/fortune/bestcompanies/2008/full_list/index.html |archive-date=July 23, 2010 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal |title=The 2012 list |url=http://money.cnn.com/magazines/fortune/best-companies/2012/full_list/ |journal=Fortune Magazine |accessdate=February 26, 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121031135647/http://money.cnn.com/magazines/fortune/best-companies/2012/full_list/ |archive-date=October 31, 2012 |url-status=live}}</ref> and fourth in 2009 and 2010.<ref>{{Cite journal |last=Levering |first=Robert |last2=Moskowitz |first2=Milton |date=February 2, 2009 |editor1-last=Serwer |editor1-first=Andrew |title=The 2009 list |url=http://money.cnn.com/magazines/fortune/bestcompanies/2009/full_list/index.html |journal=Fortune Magazine |volume=159 |issue=2 |accessdate=June 19, 2010 |editor1-link=Andrew Serwer |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100726042849/http://money.cnn.com/magazines/fortune/bestcompanies/2009/full_list/index.html |archive-date=July 26, 2010 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal |last=Levering |first=Robert |last2=Moskowitz |first2=Milton |date=February 8, 2010 |editor1-last=Serwer |editor1-first=Andrew |title=The 2010 list |url=http://money.cnn.com/magazines/fortune/bestcompanies/2010/full_list/ |journal=Fortune Magazine |volume=161 |issue=2 |accessdate=June 19, 2010 |editor1-link=Andrew Serwer |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100618125312/http://money.cnn.com/magazines/fortune/bestcompanies/2010/full_list/ |archive-date=June 18, 2010 |url-status=live}}</ref> Google was also nominated in 2010 to be the world's most attractive employer to graduating students in the Universum Communications talent attraction index.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.universumglobal.com/IDEAL-Employer-Rankings/Global-Top-50 |title=The World's Most Attractive Employers 2010 |date=September 28, 2010 |publisher=Universum Global |accessdate=October 28, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101112131208/http://www.universumglobal.com/IDEAL-Employer-Rankings/Global-Top-50 |archive-date=November 12, 2010 |url-status=dead}}</ref> Google's corporate philosophy includes principles such as \"you can make money without doing evil,\" \"you can be serious without a suit,\" and \"work should be challenging and the challenge should be fun.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.google.com/corporate/tenthings.html |title=Our Philosophy |publisher=Google, Inc. |accessdate=June 20, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100709041157/http://www.google.com/corporate/tenthings.html |archive-date=July 9, 2010 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n{{As of|2018|12|31|alt=As of December 2018,}} Google has 98,771 employees.<ref name=\"EmployeesAsOf2018Q4\" /> Google's {{as of|2017|6|29|alt=2017}} diversity report states that 31 percent of its workforce are women and 69 percent are men, with the ethnicity of its workforce being predominantly white (56%) and Asian (35%).<ref name=\"2017DiversityReport\">{{cite blog |url=https://www.blog.google/topics/diversity/making-progress-diversity-and-inclusion/ |title=Making progress on diversity and inclusion |last=Naughton |first=Eileen |date=June 29, 2017 |department=Diversity |website=The Keyword |publisher=Google |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180517170958/https://www.blog.google/topics/diversity/making-progress-diversity-and-inclusion/ |archive-date=May 17, 2018 |url-status=live |access-date=May 17, 2018}}{{pb}}{{cite news |last=Yurieff |first=Kaya |date=June 29, 2017 |title=Google struggles to increase workforce diversity |url=https://money.cnn.com/2017/06/29/technology/google-diversity-report/index.html |url-status=live |department=CNNTech |work=[[CNNMoney]] |publisher=[[Time Warner]] |location=New York |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180517174524/https://money.cnn.com/2017/06/29/technology/google-diversity-report/index.html |archive-date=May 17, 2018 |access-date=May 17, 2018}}</ref> Within tech roles, however, 20 percent were women; and 25 percent of leadership roles were held by women.<ref name=\"2017DiversityReport\" />\n\nGoogle's employees are hired based on a hierarchical system. Employees are split into six hierarchies based on experience and can range \"from entry-level data center workers at level one to managers and experienced engineers at level six.\"<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2017/09/08/google-gender-pay-gap-spreadsheet-finds-men-paid-more-than-women.html |title=Google workers collected data showing their male colleagues make more than women |last=Wakabayashi |first=Daisuke |date=September 8, 2017 |work=CNBC |access-date=September 25, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170926095602/https://www.cnbc.com/2017/09/08/google-gender-pay-gap-spreadsheet-finds-men-paid-more-than-women.html |archive-date=September 26, 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref> As a motivation technique, Google uses a policy known as [[Innovation Time Off]], where Google engineers are encouraged to spend 20% of their work time on projects that interest them. Some of Google's services, such as [[Gmail]], [[Google News]], [[Orkut]], and [[AdSense]] originated from these independent endeavors.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2007/10/21/jobs/21pre.html |title=The Google Way: Give Engineers Room |last=Mediratta |first=Bharat |last2=Bick |first2=Julie |date=October 21, 2007 |website=[[The New York Times]] |accessdate=March 9, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170402201354/http://www.nytimes.com/2007/10/21/jobs/21pre.html |archive-date=April 2, 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref> In a talk at Stanford University, [[Marissa Mayer]], Google's Vice-President of Search Products and User Experience until July 2012, showed that half of all new product launches in the second half of 2005 had originated from the Innovation Time Off.<ref>{{Cite video |people=Mayer, Marissa (speaker) |date=June 30, 2006 |title=Marissa Mayer at Stanford University |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=soYKFWqVVzg |medium=Seminar |publisher=Martin Lafrance |accessdate=June 20, 2010 |time=11:33 |quote=Fifty percent of what Google launched in the second half of 2005 actually got built out of 20% time. |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100816150501/http://www.youtube.com//watch?v=soYKFWqVVzg |archive-date=August 16, 2010 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn 2005, articles in ''[[The New York Times]]''<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2005/08/24/technology/relax-bill-gates-its-googles-turn-as-the-villain.html |title=Relax, Bill Gates; It's Google's Turn as the Villain |last=Rivlin |first=Gary |date=August 24, 2005 |website=[[The New York Times]] |accessdate=March 9, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170403014314/http://www.nytimes.com/2005/08/24/technology/relax-bill-gates-its-googles-turn-as-the-villain.html |archive-date=April 3, 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref> and other sources began suggesting that Google had lost its anti-corporate, no evil philosophy.<ref>{{cite journal |author=Utz, Richard |date=2013 |title=The Good Corporation? Google's Medievalism and Why It Matters |journal=Studies in Medievalism |volume=23 |pages=21\u201328}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.smh.com.au/news/technology/search-giant-may-outgrow-its-fans/2005/08/25/1124562975596.html3001.asp |title=Search giant may outgrow its fans |last=Gibson |first=Owen |date=August 25, 2005 |newspaper=The Sydney Morning Herald |accessdate=November 27, 2010 |last2=Wray |first2=Richard |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100517075346/http://www.smh.com.au/news/technology/search-giant-may-outgrow-its-fans/2005/08/25/1124562975596.html3001.asp |archive-date=May 17, 2010 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.osnews.com/story/17928/Google--Dont-Be-Evil |title=Google&nbsp;\u2013 Don't Be Evil |last=Ranka |first=Mohit |date=May 17, 2007 |publisher=OSNews |accessdate=November 27, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100706224751/http://www.osnews.com/story/17928/Google--Dont-Be-Evil |archive-date=July 6, 2010 |url-status=live}}</ref> In an effort to maintain the company's unique culture, Google designated a Chief Culture Officer whose purpose was to develop and maintain the culture and work on ways to keep true to the core values that the company was founded on.<ref name=\"CCO\">{{cite web |url=http://www.zdnet.com.au/meet-google-s-culture-czar-339275147.htm |title=Google's culture czar |last=Mills |first=Elinor |date=April 30, 2007 |website=ZDNet |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101031155723/http://www.zdnet.com.au/meet-google-s-culture-czar-339275147.htm |archivedate=October 31, 2010 |url-status=dead |accessdate=November 27, 2010}}</ref> Google has also faced allegations of [[sexism]] and [[ageism]] from former employees.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.cnet.com/Google-hit-with-job-discrimination-lawsuit/2100-1030_3-5807158.html?tag=nl |title=Google hit with job discrimination lawsuit |last=Kawamoto |first=Dawn |date=July 27, 2005 |work=[[CNET]] |accessdate=November 27, 2010 |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ctv.ca/servlet/ArticleNews/story/CTVNews/20071006/google_old_071006/20071006 |title=Google accused of ageism in reinstated lawsuit |date=October 6, 2007 |website=ctv.ca |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071011205140/http://www.ctv.ca/servlet/ArticleNews/story/CTVNews/20071006/google_old_071006/20071006 |archivedate=October 11, 2007 |url-status=dead |accessdate=January 22, 2017}}</ref> In 2013, a [[High-Tech Employee Antitrust Litigation|class action against]] several [[Silicon Valley]] companies, including Google, was filed for alleged \"no cold call\" agreements which restrained the recruitment of high-tech employees.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.cnet.com/news/judge-approves-first-payout-in-antitrust-wage-fixing-lawsuit/ |title=Judge approves first payout in antitrust wage-fixing lawsuit |last=Rosenblatt |first=Seth |date=May 16, 2014 |website=[[CNET]] |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] |accessdate=January 22, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170202030937/https://www.cnet.com/news/judge-approves-first-payout-in-antitrust-wage-fixing-lawsuit/ |archive-date=February 2, 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Office locations{{Anchor|Office locations and headquarters}}===\n{{Further|Googleplex}}\n[[File:111 Eighth Avenue.jpg|alt=|thumb|Google's New York City office building houses its largest advertising sales team.]]\n[[File:Google at 111 Richmond Street West in Toronto (cropped).jpg|thumb|Google's [[Toronto]] office.]]\nGoogle's headquarters in [[Mountain View, California|Mountain View]], California is referred to as \"the [[Googleplex]]\", a play on words on the number [[googolplex]] and the headquarters itself being a ''complex'' of buildings. Internationally, Google has over 78 offices in more than 50 countries.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.google.com/intl/en/about/locations/?region=north-america |title=Google: Our Offices |last= |first= |date= |website= |access-date=April 19, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180726014216/https://www.google.com/intl/en/about/locations/?region=north-america |archive-date=July 26, 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn 2006, Google moved into about {{convert|300000|sqft|m2|-2}} of office space in New York City, at [[111 Eighth Avenue]] in Manhattan. The office was designed and built specially for Google, and houses its largest advertising sales team, which has been instrumental in securing large partnerships.<ref>{{cite web |first=Marguerite |last=Reardon |title=Google takes a bigger bite of Big Apple |url=https://www.cnet.com/news/google-takes-a-bigger-bite-of-big-apple/ |website=[[CNET]] |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] |date=October 11, 2006 |accessdate=June 13, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161012171317/https://www.cnet.com/news/google-takes-a-bigger-bite-of-big-apple/ |archive-date=October 12, 2016 |url-status=live}}</ref> In 2010, Google bought the building housing the headquarter, in a deal that valued the property at around $1.9 billion.<ref>{{cite web |first=Peter |last=Grant |title=Google to Buy New York Office Building |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424052748704377004575651380545769418 |website=[[The Wall Street Journal]] |publisher=[[Dow Jones & Company]] |date=December 3, 2010 |accessdate=June 13, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161010041640/http://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424052748704377004575651380545769418 |archive-date=October 10, 2016 |url-status=live}}{{subscription required}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |first=Sam |last=Gustin |title=Google buys giant New York building for $1.9 billion |url=https://www.wired.com/2010/12/google-nyc/ |journal=[[Wired (website)|Wired]] |publisher=[[Cond\u00e9 Nast]] |date=December 22, 2010 |accessdate=June 13, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170102101149/https://www.wired.com/2010/12/google-nyc/ |archive-date=January 2, 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref> In March 2018, Google's parent company Alphabet bought the nearby [[Chelsea Market]] building for $2.4 billion. The sale is touted as one of the most expensive real estate transactions for a single building in the history of New York.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://phys.org/news/2018-03-google-nyc-chelsea-bn.html |title=Google buys NYC's Chelsea Market building for $2.4 bn |access-date=June 1, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180613184159/https://phys.org/news/2018-03-google-nyc-chelsea-bn.html |archive-date=June 13, 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://techcrunch.com/2018/03/20/google-bought-manhattans-chelsea-market-building-for-2-4-billion/ |title=Google bought Manhattan's Chelsea Market building for $2.4 billion \u2013 TechCrunch |website=techcrunch.com |language=en-US |access-date=June 1, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180608214250/https://techcrunch.com/2018/03/20/google-bought-manhattans-chelsea-market-building-for-2-4-billion/ |archive-date=June 8, 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-new-york-property-google-chelseamarke/google-closes-2-4-billion-chelsea-market-deal-to-expand-new-york-campus-idUSKBN1GW35U |title=Google closes $2.4 billion Chelsea Market deal to expand New York... |last=Editorial |first=Reuters |work=U.S. |access-date=June 1, 2018 |language=en-US |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180527003159/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-new-york-property-google-chelseamarke/google-closes-2-4-billion-chelsea-market-deal-to-expand-new-york-campus-idUSKBN1GW35U |archive-date=May 27, 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=http://uk.pcmag.com/news/93278/report-alphabet-is-buying-chelsea-market-for-over-2b |title=Report: Alphabet Is Buying Chelsea Market for Over $2B |date=February 9, 2018 |work=PCMag UK |access-date=June 1, 2018 |language=en-GB |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180613210609/http://uk.pcmag.com/news/93278/report-alphabet-is-buying-chelsea-market-for-over-2b |archive-date=June 13, 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref> In November 2018, Google announced its plan to expand its New York City office to a capacity of 12,000 employees.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/google-plans-large-new-york-city-expansion-1541636579 |title=Google Plans Large New York City Expansion |last=Grant |first=Douglas MacMillan, Eliot Brown and Peter |work=WSJ |access-date=November 8, 2018 |language=en-US |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181108182715/https://www.wsj.com/articles/google-plans-large-new-york-city-expansion-1541636579 |archive-date=November 8, 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref> The same December, it was announced that a $1 billion, {{convert|1,700,000|ft2|m2|adj=on}} headquarters for Google would be built in Manhattan's [[Hudson Square]] neighborhood.<ref>{{cite web |title=Google To Build New $1 Billion Campus In NYC |website=CBS New York |date=December 17, 2018 |url=https://newyork.cbslocal.com/2018/12/17/google-to-build-new-1-billion-campus-in-nyc/ |access-date=December 17, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181217165433/https://newyork.cbslocal.com/2018/12/17/google-to-build-new-1-billion-campus-in-nyc/ |archive-date=December 17, 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Gartenberg |first=Chaim |title=Google announces a new $1 billion NYC campus in Hudson Square |website=The Verge |date=December 17, 2018 |url=https://www.theverge.com/2018/12/17/18144448/google-nyc-campus-hudson-square-location-cost-open-date |access-date=December 17, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181217203157/https://www.theverge.com/2018/12/17/18144448/google-nyc-campus-hudson-square-location-cost-open-date |archive-date=December 17, 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref> Called Google Hudson Square, the new campus is projected to more than double the number of Google employees working in New York City.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.npr.org/2018/12/17/677450467/google-will-spend-1-billion-for-new-york-city-campus-on-hudson-river |title=Google Will Spend $1 Billion For New York City Campus On Hudson River |website=NPR.org |language=en |access-date=December 17, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181217211911/https://www.npr.org/2018/12/17/677450467/google-will-spend-1-billion-for-new-york-city-campus-on-hudson-river |archive-date=December 17, 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nBy late 2006, Google established a new headquarters for its AdWords division in [[Ann Arbor, Michigan]].<ref>{{cite web |first=Mary Hayes |last=Weier |title=Inside Google's Michigan Office |url=http://www.informationweek.com/news/internet/webdev/showArticle.jhtml?articleID=202600809 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080503233009/http://www.informationweek.com/news/internet/webdev/showArticle.jhtml?articleID=202600809 |website=[[InformationWeek]] |publisher=[[UBM plc]] |date=October 24, 2007 |archivedate=May 3, 2008 |accessdate=January 22, 2017 |url-status=dead}}</ref> In November 2006, Google opened offices on [[Carnegie Mellon]]'s campus in [[Pittsburgh]], focusing on shopping-related advertisement coding and [[smartphone applications]] and programs.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.thepittsburghchannel.com/technology/10346550/detail.html |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5hGpTE0LB?url=http://www.thepittsburghchannel.com/technology/10346550/detail.html |archivedate=June 4, 2009 |title=Google Completes Pittsburgh Office, Holds Open House |date=November 17, 2006 |accessdate=January 13, 2008 |publisher=[[WTAE TV|WTAE]] |url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://triblive.com/x/pittsburghtrib/business/s_712700.html |title=Google search: Tech-minded workers |last=Olson |first=Thomas |date=December 8, 2010 |publisher=[[Trib Total Media]] |accessdate=December 8, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130603080308/http://triblive.com/x/pittsburghtrib/business/s_712700.html |archive-date=June 3, 2013 |url-status=live}}</ref> Other office locations in the U.S. include [[Atlanta, Georgia]]; [[Austin, Texas]]; [[Boulder, Colorado]]; [[Cambridge, Massachusetts]]; [[San Francisco]], [[California]]; [[Seattle, Washington]]; [[Kirkland, Washington]]; [[Birmingham, Michigan]]; [[Reston, Virginia]], and [[Washington, D.C.]]<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.google.com/about/company/facts/locations/ |title=Google locations |access-date=March 16, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130815024220/https://www.google.com/about/company/facts/locations/ |archive-date=August 15, 2013 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n[[File:Google Headquarters in Ireland Building Sign.jpg|thumb|Google's Dublin Ireland office, headquarters of Google Ads for Europe]]\nIt also has product research and development operations in cities around the world, namely [[Sydney]] (birthplace location of [[Google Maps]])<ref>{{cite web |title=Sydney |url=https://careers.google.com/locations/sydney/ |website=Google Careers |accessdate=June 4, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170505110757/https://careers.google.com/locations/sydney/ |archive-date=May 5, 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref> and [[London]] (part of [[Android (operating system)|Android]] development).<ref>{{cite web |title=London |url=https://careers.google.com/locations/london/ |website=Google Careers |accessdate=June 4, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170214074855/https://careers.google.com/locations/london/ |archive-date=February 14, 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref> In November 2013, Google announced plans for a new [[London]] headquarter, a 1 million square foot office able to accommodate 4,500 employees. Recognized as one of the biggest ever commercial property acquisitions at the time of the deal's announcement in January,<ref>{{cite web |first=Leo |last=Mirani |title=Inside Google's new 1-million-square-foot London office\u2014three years before it's ready |url=https://qz.com/139794/inside-googles-new-1-million-square-foot-london-office-three-years-before-its-ready/ |website=[[Quartz (publication)|Quartz]] |publisher=[[Atlantic Media]] |date=November 1, 2013 |accessdate=March 15, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170316025208/https://qz.com/139794/inside-googles-new-1-million-square-foot-london-office-three-years-before-its-ready/ |archive-date=March 16, 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref> Google submitted plans for the new headquarter to the [[Camden London Borough Council|Camden Council]] in June 2017.<ref>{{cite web |first=James |last=Vincent |title=Google's new London HQ is a 'landscraper' with a rooftop garden |url=https://www.theverge.com/2017/6/1/15723642/google-london-office-pictures-headquarters-kings-cross |website=[[The Verge]] |publisher=[[Vox Media]] |date=June 1, 2017 |accessdate=June 4, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170603164958/https://www.theverge.com/2017/6/1/15723642/google-london-office-pictures-headquarters-kings-cross |archive-date=June 3, 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first=Matt |last=Brian |title=Google's 'innovative' new London HQ features giant moving blinds |url=https://www.engadget.com/2017/06/01/google-london-kings-cross-hq-plans-photos/ |website=[[Engadget]] |publisher=[[AOL]] |date=June 1, 2017 |accessdate=June 4, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170604003356/https://www.engadget.com/2017/06/01/google-london-kings-cross-hq-plans-photos/ |archive-date=June 4, 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref> In May 2015, Google announced its intention to create its own campus in [[Hyderabad]], India. The new campus, reported to be the company's largest outside the United States, will accommodate 13,000 employees.<ref>{{cite web |title=Google to build biggest campus outside US in Hyderabad |url=http://indianexpress.com/article/india/google-to-build-biggest-campus-outside-us-in-hyderabad/ |website=[[The Indian Express]] |date=May 12, 2015 |accessdate=June 13, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151118040601/http://indianexpress.com/article/india/google-to-build-biggest-campus-outside-us-in-hyderabad/ |archive-date=November 18, 2015 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Google's upcoming campus in Hyderabad to be its biggest outside the US |url=http://tech.firstpost.com/news-analysis/googles-upcoming-campus-in-hyderabad-to-be-its-biggest-outside-the-us-267059.html |website=[[Firstpost]] |publisher=[[Network 18]] |date=May 13, 2015 |accessdate=June 13, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161118003932/http://tech.firstpost.com/news-analysis/googles-upcoming-campus-in-hyderabad-to-be-its-biggest-outside-the-us-267059.html |archive-date=November 18, 2016 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Infrastructure===\n{{Further|Google data centers}}\n\n[[Google data centers]] are located in North and South America, Asia, and Europe.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.google.com/about/datacenters/inside/locations/index.html |title=Data center locations |date= |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180517162154/https://www.google.com/about/datacenters/inside/locations/index.html |archive-date=May 17, 2018 |url-status=live |access-date=May 17, 2018}}</ref> There is no official data on the number of [[Server (computing)|servers]] in Google data centers; however, research and advisory firm [[Gartner]] estimated in a July 2016 report that Google at the time had 2.5 million servers.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.datacenterknowledge.com/archives/2017/03/16/google-data-center-faq |title=How Many Servers Does Google Have? |website=Data Center Knowledge |accessdate=September 20, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190217073018/https://www.datacenterknowledge.com/archives/2017/03/16/google-data-center-faq |archive-date=February 17, 2019 |url-status=live|date=March 16, 2017 }}</ref> Traditionally, Google relied on [[parallel computing]] on commodity hardware like mainstream x86 computers (similar to home PCs) to keep costs per query low.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://research.google.com/archive/googlecluster-ieee.pdf |title=Google's Secret: 'Cheap and Fast' Hardware |date=October 10, 2003 |website=PCWorld |accessdate=May 26, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091214182753/http://research.google.com/archive/googlecluster-ieee.pdf |archive-date=December 14, 2009 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last=Barroso |first=L.A. |last2=Dean |first2=J. |last3=Holzle |first3=U. |date=April 29, 2003 |title=Web search for a planet: the google cluster architecture |journal=IEEE Micro |volume=23 |issue=2 |pages=22\u201328 |doi=10.1109/mm.2003.1196112 |issn=0272-1732 |quote=We believe that the best price/performance tradeoff for our applications comes from fashioning a reliable computing infrastructure from clusters of unreliable commodity PCs.|url=https://semanticscholar.org/paper/8db8e53c92af2f97974707119525aa089f6ed53a }}</ref><ref name=\"CNET2009\">{{cite news |url=https://www.cnet.com/news/google-uncloaks-once-secret-server-10209580/ |title=Google uncloaks once-secret server |date=April 1, 2009 |newspaper=CNET |accessdate=May 26, 2018 |quote=Mainstream servers with x86 processors were the only option, he added. \"Ten years ago...it was clear the only way to make (search) work as free product was to run on relatively cheap hardware. You can't run it on a [[mainframe server|mainframe]]. The margins just don't work out,\" he said. |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180606105133/https://www.cnet.com/news/google-uncloaks-once-secret-server-10209580/ |archive-date=June 6, 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref> In 2005, it started developing its own designs, which were only revealed in 2009.<ref name=\"CNET2009\" />\n\nIn the late 2010s, Google began to build its own private [[submarine communications cable]]s. The first, named Curie, connects California with [[Chile]] and is to be completed in 2019.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://venturebeat.com/2019/04/06/google-and-other-tech-giants-are-quietly-buying-up-the-most-important-part-of-the-internet/ |title=Google and other tech giants are quietly buying up the most important part of the internet |date=April 6, 2019 |website=VentureBeat |language=en-US |access-date=April 25, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190425024849/https://venturebeat.com/2019/04/06/google-and-other-tech-giants-are-quietly-buying-up-the-most-important-part-of-the-internet/ |archive-date=April 25, 2019 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref> The second fully Google-owned undersea cable, named Dunant, connects the United States with France and is planned to begin operation in 2020.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://venturebeat.com/2019/04/24/how-google-is-building-its-huge-subsea-cable-infrastructure/ |title=How Google is building its huge subsea cable infrastructure |last=Sawers |first=Paul |date=April 24, 2019 |website=VentureBeat |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190425163121/https://venturebeat.com/2019/04/24/how-google-is-building-its-huge-subsea-cable-infrastructure/ |archive-date=April 25, 2019 |url-status=live |access-date=April 26, 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Environment ===\nIn October 2006, the company announced plans to install thousands of [[solar panel]]s to provide up to 1.6&nbsp;mega[[watt]]s of electricity, enough to satisfy approximately 30% of the campus' energy needs.<ref name=\"solar\">{{cite web |url=http://www.post1.net/lowem/entry/google_plans_to_build_huge |title=Google plans to build huge solar energy system for headquarters |last=Richmond |first=Riva |date=October 17, 2006 |website=post1.net |publisher=[[MarketWatch]] |archiveurl=http://arquivo.pt/wayback/20160519010259/http://www.post1.net/lowem/entry/google_plans_to_build_huge |archivedate=May 19, 2016 |url-status=dead |accessdate=October 17, 2006}}</ref> The system will be the largest [[Rooftop photovoltaic power station|solar power system]] constructed on a U.S. corporate campus and one of the largest on any corporate site in the world.<ref name=\"solar\" /> {{As of|2007|since=y|post=,}} Google has aimed for [[carbon neutrality]] in regard to its operations.<ref>{{cite web |first=Jack |last=McGrath |title=Google's Green Initiative: Environmentally Conscious Technology |url=http://www.technobuffalo.com/2011/05/18/googles-green-initiative-environmentally-conscious-technology/ |publisher=TechnoBuffalo |date=May 18, 2011 |accessdate=January 22, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161012172247/http://www.technobuffalo.com/2011/05/18/googles-green-initiative-environmentally-conscious-technology/ |archive-date=October 12, 2016 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nGoogle disclosed in September 2011 that it \"continuously uses enough electricity to power 200,000 homes\", almost 260 million watts or about a quarter of the output of a nuclear power plant. Total carbon emissions for 2010 were just under 1.5 million metric tons, mostly due to fossil fuels that provide electricity for the data centers. Google said that 25 percent of its energy was supplied by renewable fuels in 2010. An average search uses only 0.3 watt-hours of electricity, so all global searches are only 12.5 million watts or 5% of the total electricity consumption by Google.<ref>{{cite web |first=James |last=Glanz |title=Google Details, and Defends, Its Use of Electricity |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/09/09/technology/google-details-and-defends-its-use-of-electricity.html |website=[[The New York Times]] |date=September 8, 2011 |accessdate=March 9, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170312053616/http://www.nytimes.com/2011/09/09/technology/google-details-and-defends-its-use-of-electricity.html |archive-date=March 12, 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn 2010, [[Google Energy]] made its first investment in a [[renewable energy]] project, putting $38.8&nbsp;million into two [[wind farm]]s in [[North Dakota]]. The company announced the two locations will generate 169.5&nbsp;megawatts of power, enough to supply 55,000 homes.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424052748704342604575222420304732394 |title=Google Invests in Two Wind Farms |last=Morrison |first=Scott |date=May 4, 2010 |newspaper=[[The Wall Street Journal]] |accessdate=November 27, 2010 |last2=Sweet |first2=Cassandra |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150213232857/http://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424052748704342604575222420304732394 |archive-date=February 13, 2015 |url-status=live}}</ref> In February 2010, the [[Federal Energy Regulatory Commission]] FERC granted Google an authorization to buy and sell energy at market rates.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.cnet.com/8301-11128_3-10456435-54.html |title=Google Energy can now buy and sell energy |work=Cnet.com |access-date=September 23, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130919091407/http://news.cnet.com/8301-11128_3-10456435-54.html |archive-date=September 19, 2013 |url-status=live}}</ref> The corporation exercised this authorization in September 2013 when it announced it would purchase all the electricity produced by the not-yet-built 240-megawatt Happy Hereford wind farm.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://qz.com/125407/google-is-on-the-way-to-quietly-becoming-an-electric-utility/ |title=Google is on the way to quietly becoming an electric utility |author=Todd Woody |date=September 18, 2013 |newspaper=Quartz |accessdate=September 23, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130921050811/http://qz.com/125407/google-is-on-the-way-to-quietly-becoming-an-electric-utility/ |archive-date=September 21, 2013 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2010, Google signed an agreement with an Iowa wind farm to buy 114 megawatts of energy for 20 years.<ref name=\"wind energy\">{{cite web |url=http://news.techworld.com/green-it/3232690/google-buys-power-from-iowa-wind-farm/?olo=rss |title=Google buys power from Iowa wind farm |date=July 21, 2010 |website=News.techworld.com |accessdate=October 26, 2010 |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/659XgHPv9?url=http://news.techworld.com/green-it/3232690/google-buys-power-from-iowa-wind-farm/?olo=rss |archive-date=February 2, 2012 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2016, Google announced that\u2014starting in 2017\u2014it will power all of its data centers, as well as all of its offices, from 100% renewable energy. The commitment will make Google \"the world's largest corporate buyer of renewable power, with commitments reaching 2.6 gigawatts (2,600 megawatts) of wind and solar energy\". Google also stated that it does not count that as its final goal; it says that \"since the wind doesn't blow 24 hours a day, we'll also broaden our purchases to a variety of energy sources that can enable renewable power, every hour of every day\". Additionally, the project will \"help support communities\" around the world, as the purchase commitments will \"result in infrastructure investments of more than $3.5 billion globally\", and will \"generate tens of millions of dollars per year in revenue to local property owners, and tens of millions more to local and national governments in tax revenue\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://blog.google/topics/environment/100-percent-renewable-energy/ |title=We're set to reach 100% renewable energy \u2014 and it's just the beginning |last=H\u00f6lzle |first=Urs |date=December 6, 2016 |website=The Keyword Google Blog |accessdate=December 8, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161208102229/https://www.blog.google/topics/environment/100-percent-renewable-energy/ |archive-date=December 8, 2016 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theverge.com/2016/12/6/13852004/google-data-center-oklahoma-renewable-energy-climate-change |title=Google just notched a big victory in the fight against climate change |last=Statt |first=Nick |date=December 6, 2016 |website=[[The Verge]] |publisher=[[Vox Media]] |accessdate=December 8, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161208001307/http://www.theverge.com/2016/12/6/13852004/google-data-center-oklahoma-renewable-energy-climate-change |archive-date=December 8, 2016 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://techcrunch.com/2016/12/06/google-says-it-will-hit-100-renewable-energy-by-2017/ |title=Google says it will hit 100% renewable energy by 2017 |last=Etherington |first=Darrell |date=December 7, 2016 |website=[[TechCrunch]] |publisher=[[AOL]] |accessdate=December 8, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161207164915/https://techcrunch.com/2016/12/06/google-says-it-will-hit-100-renewable-energy-by-2017/ |archive-date=December 7, 2016 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2017, Google bought 536 megawatts of wind power. The purchase made the firm reach 100% renewable energy. The wind energy comes from two power plants in South Dakota, one in Iowa and one in Oklahoma.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://fortune.com/2017/12/01/google-clean-energy/ |title=Google Just Bought Enough Wind Power to Run 100% On Renewable Energy |date=November 30, 2017 |last=Donnelly |first=Grace |work=Fortune |access-date=December 1, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171201172833/http://fortune.com/2017/12/01/google-clean-energy/ |archive-date=December 1, 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2019, Google's chief executive announced plans for a $2 billion wind and solar investment, the biggest renewable energy deal in corporate history. This will grow their green energy profile by 40%, giving them an extra 1.6 gigawatt of clean energy, the company said.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2019/sep/20/google-says-its-energy-deals-will-lead-to-2bn-wind-and-solar-investment|title=Google signs up to $2bn wind and solar investment|last=correspondent|first=Jillian Ambrose Energy|date=2019-09-20|work=The Guardian|access-date=2019-09-25|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n\nGoogle donates to politicians who deny climate change including [[Jim Inhofe]] as well as sponsoring climate change denial political groups including the [[State Policy Network]] and the [[Competitive Enterprise Institute]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://popular.info/p/these-corporations-are-quietly-bankrolling|title=These corporations are quietly bankrolling Congress' top climate denier|last=Legum|first=Judd|website=popular.info|access-date=2020-02-07}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Kirchgaessner|first=Stephanie|url=https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2019/oct/11/google-contributions-climate-change-deniers|title=Revealed: Google made large contributions to climate change deniers|date=2019-10-11|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-02-07|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Kirchgaessner|first=Stephanie|url=https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2019/oct/11/obscure-law-google-climate-deniers-section-230|title=The obscure law that explains why Google backs climate deniers|date=2019-10-11|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-02-07|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n\n=== Philanthropy ===\n{{Main|Google.org}}\n\nIn 2004, Google formed the not-for-profit philanthropic [[Google.org]], with a start-up fund of $1&nbsp;billion.<ref name=\"philanthropy\">{{cite web |url=http://www.google.org/about.html |title=About the Foundation |publisher=Google, Inc. |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100714080922/http://www.google.org/about.html |archivedate=July 14, 2010 |url-status=dead |accessdate=July 16, 2010}}</ref> The mission of the organization is to create awareness about [[climate change]], global public health, and global poverty. One of its first projects was to develop a viable [[plug-in hybrid]] [[electric vehicle]] that can attain 100 miles per gallon. Google hired [[Larry Brilliant]] as the program's executive director in 2004<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/09/14/technology/14google.html |title=Philanthropy Google's Way: Not the Usual |last=Hafner |first=Katie |date=September 14, 2006 |website=[[The New York Times]] |accessdate=March 9, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160723065526/http://www.nytimes.com/2006/09/14/technology/14google.html |archive-date=July 23, 2016 |url-status=live}}</ref> and Megan Smith has {{as of|2009|2|23|alt=since}} replaced him as director.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/02/24/technology/companies/24google.html |title=Google Chief for Charity Steps Down on Revamp |last=Helft |first=Miguel |date=February 23, 2009 |website=[[The New York Times]] |accessdate=March 9, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170422112540/http://www.nytimes.com/2009/02/24/technology/companies/24google.html |archive-date=April 22, 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn 2008, Google announced its \"project 10<sup>100</sup>\" which accepted ideas for how to help the community and then allowed Google users to vote on their favorites.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.project10tothe100.com/ |title=Project 10 to the 100th |publisher=Google, Inc. |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5hT8OddCZ?url=http://www.project10tothe100.com/ |archivedate=June 12, 2009 |url-status=dead |accessdate=July 16, 2010}}</ref> After two years of silence, during which many wondered what had happened to the program,<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.wired.com/epicenter/2010/06/google-struggles-to-give-away-10-million/ |title=Google Struggles to Give Away $10&nbsp;million |last=Van Burskirk |first=Elliot |date=June 28, 2010 |work=[[Wired (website)|Wired]] |accessdate=September 26, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100831172215/http://www.wired.com/epicenter/2010/06/google-struggles-to-give-away-10-million/ |archive-date=August 31, 2010 |url-status=live}}</ref> Google revealed the winners of the project, giving a total of ten million dollars to various ideas ranging from non-profit organizations that promote education to a website that intends to make all legal documents public and online.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://googleblog.blogspot.com/2010/09/10-million-for-project-10100-winners.html |title=$10&nbsp;million for Project 10^100 winners |last=Twohill |first=Lorraine |date=September 24, 2010 |publisher=Google, Inc. |accessdate=September 26, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100926020623/http://googleblog.blogspot.com/2010/09/10-million-for-project-10100-winners.html |archive-date=September 26, 2010 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2007, in partnership with the [[Mathematical Sciences Research Institute]] (MSRI), Google hosted the first [[Julia Robinson Mathematics Festival]] at its headquarters in Mountain View.<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=qDL7yoz1TGQ The 2007] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181120090220/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=qDL7yoz1TGQ |date=November 20, 2018 }} [[Julia Robinson Mathematics Festival]]at Google was the founding of this event for middle school and high school students. video</ref> In 2011, Google donated 1&nbsp;million euros to [[International Mathematical Olympiad]] to support the next five annual International Mathematical Olympiads (2011\u20132015).<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.pcmag.com/article2/0,2817,2376099,00.asp |title=Mathletes Receive \u20ac1M Donation from Google |last=Duffy |first=Jill |date=January 21, 2011 |website=[[PC Magazine]] |publisher=[[Ziff Davis]] |accessdate=March 23, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170323234649/http://www.pcmag.com/article2/0,2817,2376099,00.asp |archive-date=March 23, 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.imo2011.nl/node/39 |title=Google donating 1&nbsp;million euros to IMO |date=January 20, 2011 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110724154518/https://www.imo2011.nl/node/39 |archivedate=July 24, 2011 |url-status=dead |accessdate=February 4, 2011}}</ref> In July 2012, Google launched a \"[[Legalize Love]]\" campaign in support of [[gay rights]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.pinknews.co.uk/2012/07/08/google-launches-legalise-love-gay-rights-campaign/ |title=Google launches 'Legalise Love' gay rights campaign |website=PinkNews.co.uk |accessdate=September 9, 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140819044558/http://www.pinknews.co.uk/2012/07/08/google-launches-legalise-love-gay-rights-campaign/ |archive-date=August 19, 2014 |url-status=live|date=July 8, 2012 }}</ref>\n\n== Criticism and controversy ==\n{{main|Criticism of Google|Censorship by Google|Privacy concerns regarding Google}}{{summarize|from|Criticism of Google|better=y|section=y|date=April 2019}}\n\n[[File:Google bus protest.jpg|thumb|San Francisco activists [[San Francisco tech bus protests|protest privately owned shuttle buses]] that transport workers for tech companies such as Google from their homes in San Francisco and Oakland to corporate campuses in Silicon Valley.]]\nGoogle's market dominance has led to prominent media coverage, including [[Criticism of Google|criticism of the company]] over issues such as [[Google tax avoidance|aggressive tax avoidance]],<ref>{{cite web |first=Jesse |last=Drucker |title=Google 2.4% Rate Shows How $60 Billion Is Lost to Tax Loopholes |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2010-10-21/google-2-4-rate-shows-how-60-billion-u-s-revenue-lost-to-tax-loopholes |website=[[Bloomberg Businessweek]] |publisher=[[Bloomberg L.P.]] |date=October 21, 2010 |accessdate=January 22, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160922035532/http://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2010-10-21/google-2-4-rate-shows-how-60-billion-u-s-revenue-lost-to-tax-loopholes |archive-date=September 22, 2016 |url-status=live}}{{subscription required}}</ref> [[Criticism of Google#Page rank|search neutrality]], [[Criticism of Google#Copyright issues|copyright]], [[censorship by Google|censorship]] of search results and content,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/02/20/magazine/the-case-against-google.html |title=The Case Against Google |website=nytimes.com |date=February 20, 2018 |accessdate=March 21, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180319192049/https://www.nytimes.com/2018/02/20/magazine/the-case-against-google.html |archive-date=March 19, 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref> and [[Google privacy|privacy]].<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/technology/6740075.stm |work=BBC News |title=Google ranked 'worst' on privacy |date=June 11, 2007 |accessdate=April 30, 2010 |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6BYbPRqrU?url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/technology/6740075.stm |archive-date=October 20, 2012 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first=Jeffrey |last=Rosen |title=Google's Gatekeepers |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/11/30/magazine/30google-t.html |website=[[The New York Times]] |date=November 28, 2008 |accessdate=March 9, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170228140546/http://www.nytimes.com/2008/11/30/magazine/30google-t.html |archive-date=February 28, 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref> Other criticisms include alleged misuse and manipulation of search results, its use of others' [[intellectual property]], concerns that its [[Data collection|compilation of data]] may violate people's [[Internet privacy|privacy]], and the [[energy consumption]] of its servers, as well as concerns over traditional business issues such as [[monopoly]], [[restraint of trade]], [[anti-competitive practices]], and [[patent infringement]].\n\nGoogle formerly adhered to the [[Internet censorship in the People's Republic of China|Internet censorship policies of China]],<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/technology/4645596.stm |title=Google censors itself for China |date=January 25, 2006 |work=BBC News |access-date=August 4, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181119073206/http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/technology/4645596.stm |archive-date=November 19, 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref> enforced by means of filters colloquially known as \"The [[Great Firewall of China]]\", but [[Censorship by Google#China|no longer does so]]. As a result, all Google services except for Chinese Google Maps are blocked from access within mainland China without the aid of VPNs, proxy servers, or other similar technologies. ''The Intercept'' reported in August 2018 that Google is developing for the People's Republic of China a censored version of its search engine (known as [[Dragonfly (search engine)|Dragonfly]]) \"that will blacklist websites and search terms about human rights, democracy, religion, and peaceful protest\".<ref>{{cite news |title=Google Plans to Launch Censored Search Engine in China, Leaked Documents Reveal \u00b7 Ryan Gallagher |url=https://theintercept.com/2018/08/01/google-china-search-engine-censorship/ |work=The Intercept |date=August 1, 2018 |access-date=August 4, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180801120009/https://theintercept.com/2018/08/01/google-china-search-engine-censorship/ |archive-date=August 1, 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last=Disis |first=Jill |title=Google grilled over 'Project Dragonfly' at Senate hearing on data privacy |date=September 26, 2018 |newspaper=CNN |url=https://money.cnn.com/2018/09/26/technology/google-dragonfly-senate-hearing/index.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180926222719/https://money.cnn.com/2018/09/26/technology/google-dragonfly-senate-hearing/index.html |archive-date=September 26, 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref> However, the project had been withheld due to privacy concerns.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://theintercept.com/2018/12/17/google-china-censored-search-engine-2/ |title=Google's Secret China Project \"Effectively Ended\" After Internal Confrontation |last=Gallagher |first=Ryan |date=December 17, 2018 |website=The Intercept |language=en-US |access-date=December 17, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190321020856/https://theintercept.com/2018/12/17/google-china-censored-search-engine-2/ |archive-date=March 21, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nFollowing media reports about [[PRISM (surveillance program)|PRISM]], NSA's massive electronic [[Mass surveillance|surveillance program]], in June 2013, several technology companies were identified as participants, including Google.<ref>{{cite web |title=Edward Snowden: Leaks that exposed US spy programme |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-23123964 |website=[[BBC News]] |date=January 17, 2014 |accessdate=March 25, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170320171345/http://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-23123964 |archive-date=March 20, 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref> According to leaks of said program, Google joined the PRISM program in 2009.<ref>{{cite web |first=Glenn |last=Greenwald |first2=Ewen |last2=MacAskill |title=NSA Prism program taps in to user data of Apple, Google and others |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2013/jun/06/us-tech-giants-nsa-data |website=[[The Guardian]] |publisher=[[Guardian Media Group]] |date=June 7, 2013 |accessdate=March 25, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060818114650/http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/2013/jun/06/us-tech-giants-nsa-data |archive-date=August 18, 2006 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nGoogle has worked with the [[United States Department of Defense]] on drone software through the 2017 \"Project Maven\" that could be used to improve the accuracy of [[drone strike]]s.<ref>\"[https://arstechnica.com/gadgets/2018/04/google-should-not-be-in-the-business-of-war-googlers-decry-pentagon-project/ Google employees revolt, say company should shut down military drone project] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180408141509/https://arstechnica.com/gadgets/2018/04/google-should-not-be-in-the-business-of-war-googlers-decry-pentagon-project/ |date=April 8, 2018 }}\". ''[[Ars Technica]]''. April 4, 2018.</ref> Thousands of Google employees, including senior engineers, have signed a letter urging Google CEO [[Sundar Pichai]] to end a controversial contract with the Pentagon.<ref>\"[https://www.independent.co.uk/news/business/news/google-protest-pentagon-drones-programme-company-sundar-pichai-department-of-defense-a8290111.html Google staff protest company's involvement with Pentagon drones programme] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180409174803/https://www.independent.co.uk/news/business/news/google-protest-pentagon-drones-programme-company-sundar-pichai-department-of-defense-a8290111.html |date=April 9, 2018 }}\". ''The Independent''. April 4, 2018.</ref> In response to the backlash, Google ultimately decided to not renew their DoD contract, set to expire in 2019.<ref>{{cite web |author1=Wakabayashi, Daisuke |author2=Shane, Scott |title=Google Will Not Renew Pentagon Contract That Upset Employees |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/06/01/technology/google-pentagon-project-maven.html |website=nytimes.com |publisher=The New York Times Company |accessdate=October 16, 2018 |date=June 1, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181016004020/https://www.nytimes.com/2018/06/01/technology/google-pentagon-project-maven.html |archive-date=October 16, 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nShona Ghosh, a journalist for [[Business Insider]], noted that an increasing digital [[resistance movement]] against Google has grown. A major hub for critics of Google in order to organize to abstain from using Google products is the [[Reddit]] page for the [[subreddit]] /r/degoogle.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.businessinsider.com/profile-reddit-de-google-community-2019-3 |title=Thousands of Reddit users are trying to delete Google from their lives, but they're finding it impossible because Google is everywhere |access-date=April 24, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190325123426/https://www.businessinsider.com/profile-reddit-de-google-community-2019-3/ |archive-date=March 25, 2019 |url-status=live|date=March 23, 2019 }}</ref>\n\nIn July 2018, Mozilla Program Manager Chris Peterson accused Google of intentionally slowing down YouTube performance on Firefox.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pcmag.com/news/362696/mozilla-developer-claims-google-is-slowing-youtube-on-firefo|title=Mozilla Developer Claims Google Is Slowing YouTube on Firefox|last=Kan|first=By Michael|last2=July 25|first2=2018 12:39PM EST|website=PCMAG|language=en|access-date=2019-08-13|last3=July 25|first3=2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190813134744/https://www.pcmag.com/news/362696/mozilla-developer-claims-google-is-slowing-youtube-on-firefo|archive-date=August 13, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2019 former [[Mozilla]] executive Jonathan Nightingale accused Google of intentionally and systematically sabotaging the [[Firefox]] browser over the past decade in order to boost [[Google Chrome|Chrome's]] adoption.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.zdnet.com/article/former-mozilla-exec-google-has-sabotaged-firefox-for-years/|title=Former Mozilla exec: Google has sabotaged Firefox for years|last=Cimpanu|first=Catalin|website=ZDNet|language=en|access-date=2019-08-13|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190819235446/https://www.zdnet.com/article/former-mozilla-exec-google-has-sabotaged-firefox-for-years/|archive-date=August 19, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2019, the Office for Civil Rights of the [[Department of Health and Human Services]] began investigation into [[Project Nightingale]], to assess whether the \"mass collection of individuals\u2019 medical records\" complied with [[Health Insurance Portability and Accountability Act|HIPAA]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/behind-googles-project-nightingale-a-health-data-gold-mine-of-50-million-patients-11573571867|title=Google's 'Project Nightingale' Triggers Federal Inquiry|last1=Copeland|first1=Rob|date=November 12, 2019|accessdate=November 18, 2019}}</ref> According to''The Wall Street Journal'', Google commenced the project in secret, in 2018, with [[St. Louis]]-based [[healthcare]] company [[Ascension (company)|Ascension]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/google-s-secret-project-nightingale-gathers-personal-health-data-on-millions-of-americans-11573496790|title=Google's 'Project Nightingale' Gathers Personal Health Data on Millions of Americans|last1=Copeland|first1=Rob|date=November 11, 2019|accessdate=November 17, 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Litigation ===\n{{main|Google litigation}}\n\nGoogle has been involved in a number of lawsuits including the [[High-Tech Employee Antitrust Litigation]] which resulted in Google being one of four companies to pay a $415 million settlement to employees.<ref>{{cite news |last=Rosenblatt |first=Joel |title=Apple-Google $415 Million No-Poaching Accord Wins Approval |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2015-03-02/tech-no-poaching-settlement-gets-judge-s-preliminary-approval |accessdate=January 24, 2016 |publisher=[[Bloomberg L.P.]] |date=March 2, 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160130214110/http://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2015-03-02/tech-no-poaching-settlement-gets-judge-s-preliminary-approval |archive-date=January 30, 2016 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn June 27, 2017, the company received a record fine of {{\u20ac|2.42 billion|link=yes}} from the [[European Union]] for \"promoting its own shopping comparison service at the top of search results.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/technology-40406542 |title=Google hit with record EU fine over Shopping service |first=Leo |last=Kelion |date=June 27, 2017 |publisher=bbc.co.uk |accessdate=June 29, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170627100311/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/technology-40406542 |archive-date=June 27, 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref> Commenting on the penalty, ''[[New Scientist]]'' magazine said: \"The hefty sum \u2013 the largest ever doled out by the EU's competition regulators \u2013 will sting in the short term, but Google can handle it. Alphabet, Google\u2019s parent company, made a profit of $2.5 billion (\u20ac2.2 billion) in the first six weeks of 2017 alone. The real impact of the ruling is that Google must stop using its dominance as a search engine to give itself the edge in another market: online price comparisons.\" The company disputed the ruling.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.newscientist.com/article/2139097-googles-e2-4bn-fine-is-small-change-the-eu-has-bigger-plans/ |title=Google's \u20ac2.4bn fine is small change \u2013 the EU has bigger plans |publisher=newscientist.com |accessdate=June 29, 2017 |archive-url=https://archive.today/20190124095546/https://www.newscientist.com/article/2139097-googles-e2-4bn-fine-is-small-change-the-eu-has-bigger-plans/ |archive-date=January 24, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> The hearing at the General Court of Luxembourg was scheduled for 2020. The court is going to deliver the ultimate judgment by the end of the year.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/technology-51462397?intlink_from_url=https://www.bbc.com/news/technology&link_location=live-reporting-story|title=Google starts appeal against \u00a32bn shopping fine|last=|first=|date=12 February 2020|website=BBC News|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nOn July 18, 2018,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://europa.eu/rapid/press-release_IP-17-685_hr.htm |title=Antitrust: Commission fines Google \u20ac4.34 billion for illegal practices regarding Android mobile devices to strengthen dominance of Google's search engine |location=Bruxelles |date=July 18, 2018 |website=European Commission |archive-url=https://archive.today/20180718112553/http://europa.eu/rapid/press-release_IP-18-4581_en.htm |archive-date=July 18, 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref> the [[European Commissioner for Competition|European Commission]] fined Google \u20ac4.34 billion for breaching EU antitrust rules. The abuse of dominant position has been referred to Google's constraint applied on Android device manufacturers and network operators to ensure that traffic on Android devices goes to the Google search engine. On October 9, 2018, Google confirmed<ref>{{cite web |url=https://apnews.com/f9797e4935c1464f8f6010793ded7c1d |title=Google appeals $5 billion EU fine in Android antitrust case |website=[[APNews.com]] |date=October 10, 2018 |language=en |location=Bruxelles |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181010101238/https://apnews.com/f9797e4935c1464f8f6010793ded7c1d |archive-date=October 10, 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref> that it had appealed the fine to the [[General Court (European Union)|General Court]] of the European Union.<ref>{{cite news |author=Foo Yun Chee |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-eu-alphabet-inc-antitrust/google-challenges-record-5-billion-eu-antitrust-fine-idUSKCN1MJ2CA |title=Google challenges record $5 billion EU antitrust fine |date=May 13, 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181222061539/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-eu-google-dataprotection/european-court-says-google-must-respect-right-to-be-forgotten-idUSBREA4C07120140513 |archive-date=December 22, 2018 |url-status=live|newspaper=Reuters }}</ref>\n\nOn January 21, 2019, French data regulator [[CNIL]] imposed a record \u20ac50 million fine on Google for breaching the European Union's [[General Data Protection Regulation]]. The judgment claimed Google had failed to sufficiently inform users of its methods for collecting data to personalize advertising. Google issued a statement saying it was \u201cdeeply committed\u201d to transparency and was \u201cstudying the decision\u201d before determining its response.<ref>{{cite web |last=Fox |first=Chris |title=Google hit with \u00a344m GDPR fine |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/technology-46944696 |website=BBC |accessdate=January 22, 2019 |date=January 21, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190121231240/https://www.bbc.com/news/technology-46944696 |archive-date=January 21, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn March 20, 2019, the European Commission imposed a \u20ac1.49 billion ($1.69 billion) fine on Google for preventing rivals from being able to \u201ccompete and innovate fairly\u201d in the online advertising market.<ref>{{cite web |title=Europe hits Google with a third, $1.7 billion antitrust fine |url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/03/20/tech/google-eu-antitrust/index.html |website=CNN |accessdate=March 21, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190320133734/https://www.cnn.com/2019/03/20/tech/google-eu-antitrust/index.html |archive-date=March 20, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> European Union competition commissioner Margrethe Vestager said Google had violated EU antitrust rules by \u201cimposing anti-competitive contractual restrictions on third-party websites\u201d that required them to exclude search results from Google's rivals. Kent Walker, Google's senior vice-president of global affairs, said the company had \u201calready made a wide range of changes to our products to address the Commission\u2019s concerns,\u201d and that \"we'll be making further updates to give more visibility to rivals in Europe.\"<ref>{{cite web |last=Reid |first=David |title=EU regulators hit Google with $1.7 billion fine for blocking ad rivals |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2019/03/20/eu-vestager-hits-google-with-fine-for.html |website=CNBC.com |accessdate=March 20, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190320155204/https://www.cnbc.com/2019/03/20/eu-vestager-hits-google-with-fine-for.html |archive-date=March 20, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn July 25, 2019, presidential hopeful [[Tulsi Gabbard]] sued Google for blocking her ads after the presidential debate when she became one of the most searched items on the search engine.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://thehill.com/policy/technology/454746-tulsi-gabbard-sues-google-over-censorship-claims | title=Tulsi Gabbard sues Google over censorship claims| date=2019-07-25}}</ref>\n\n===DeGoogle movement===\n{{main| DeGoogle}}\nThe term \"[[DeGoogle]]\" has grown in use as [[privacy]] activists urge users to stop using Google products entirely due to [[Privacy concerns regarding Google|growing privacy concerns]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.businessinsider.com/profile-reddit-de-google-community-2019-3|title=Thousands of Reddit users are trying to delete Google from their lives, but they're finding it impossible because Google is everywhere|date=2019-03-23}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://gizmodo.com/i-cut-google-out-of-my-life-it-screwed-up-everything-1830565500|title=I Cut Google Out Of My Life. It Screwed Up Everything}}</ref> The term refers to the act of removing Google from your life.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Outline of Google]]\n* [[History of Google]]\n* [[List of mergers and acquisitions by Alphabet]]\n* [[List of Google products]]\n* [[Google China]]\n* [[Google logo]]\n* [[Googlization]]\n* [[Google.org]]\n* [[Google ATAP]]\n{{Portal bar|Internet|Companies|San Francisco Bay Area|Technology|Computer programming}}\n\n== Notes ==\n{{Notelist}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n* {{cite book |title=The Mobile Wave: How Mobile Intelligence Will Change Everything |last=Saylor |first=Michael |authorlink=Michael J. Saylor |year=2012 |publisher=Perseus Books/Vanguard Press |isbn=978-1593157203 |ref=none}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{sisterlinks|n=Category:Google|s=no|b=Google Services And Products|voy=no|species=no|d=Q95|m=Google}}\n* {{Official website}}\n** [https://www.google.com/about/company/facts/management Corporate homepage]\n* {{Cite web |url=http://google.stanford.edu/ |title=Google website |access-date=September 28, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/19981111183552/http://google.stanford.edu/ |archive-date=November 11, 1998 |url-status=dead}}\n* {{cite journal |last=Carr |first=David F. |title=How Google Works |journal=Baseline Magazine |volume=6 |issue=6 |year=2006 |url=http://www.baselinemag.com/c/a/Infrastructure/How-Google-Works-1}}\n* {{Crunchbase|google|Google}}\n* {{OpenCorp|Google|Google}}\n{{Finance links\n|name = Google, Inc.\n|symbol = GOOG\n|bloomberg = GOOG:US\n|reuters = GOOG.OQ\n|sec_cik = 1288776\n|nasdaq = GOOG\n|hoovers = Google_Inc.fb3f79c4d1791506\n}}\n{{Google LLC|corporate=yes|products=yes}}\n{{Alphabet Inc.}}\n{{Navboxes|list1=\n{{Open Handset Alliance Members}}\n{{Google Lunar X Prize}}\n{{Major mobile device companies}}\n{{Major Internet companies}}\n{{Major software companies}}\n{{Prince of Asturias Award for Communication and Humanities}}\n}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Google]]\n[[Category:1998 establishments in California]]\n[[Category:2004 initial public offerings]]\n[[Category:Alphabet Inc.]]\n[[Category:Artificial intelligence]]\n[[Category:Cloud computing providers]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Mountain View, California]]\n[[Category:Companies in the PRISM network]]\n[[Category:Computer companies established in 1998]]\n[[Category:Computer-related introductions in 1998]]\n[[Category:Internet properties established in 1998]]\n[[Category:Mobile phone manufacturers]]\n[[Category:Multinational companies headquartered in the United States]]\n[[Category:Technology companies based in the San Francisco Bay Area]]\n[[Category:Technology companies established in 1998]]\n[[Category:University spin-offs]]\n[[Category:Virtual reality companies]]\n[[Category:Web portals]]\n[[Category:Web service providers]]\n[[Category:Webby Award winners]]\n[[Category:World Wide Web]]\n[[Category:Eyewear companies of the United States]]\n[[Category:American corporate subsidiaries]]\n", "name_user": "Objective3000", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eEarly years:add period", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Google"}
{"title_page": "New Ten Major Construction Projects", "text_new": "{{Multiple issues|\n{{Update|type=|date=January 2019|reason=}}\n{{Prose|date=July 2013}}\n}}\n{{Use American English|date = January 2019}}\n{{Short description|Infrastructure projects in Taiwan}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date = January 2019}}\n\nThe '''New Ten Major Construction Projects''' ({{zh|t=\u65b0\u5341\u5927\u5efa\u8a2d}}) refers to the construction plans in [[Taiwan]] introduced by then-premier [[Yu Shyi-kun]] in November 2003.\n\n== List of the projects ==\n\n* Top universities and research centers\n** Goal: to have at least 15 major [[graduate school]]s ranked number 1 in [[Asia]] in 5 years; to get at least one college ranked one of the top 100 colleges of the world in 10 years.\n* International arts and popular music centers\n** [[Northern Taiwan]]: Greater Taipei New Theater\n** [[Central Taiwan]]: Taichung Metropolitan Opera House\n** [[Southern Taiwan]]: [[Kaohsiung]] National Arts Cultural Center (to be called the Wei Wu Ying Cultural Center)\n* M-Taiwan plan\n** Goal: to build a world-class internet service environment, and become the third [[Orders of magnitude (numbers)#1012|trillion]]-dollar communication industrial development.\n* Taiwan exhibition\n** Goal: to exhibit Taiwan's creativity and vigor, and prompt the development of technology, tourism, and culture.\n* TRA MRTizion: Appealing for pass car of [[Taiwan High Speed Rail|THSR]], via additions of stations, train services, elevation, underground passages, make TRA transform to metro area and regional MRTs, let TRA transform and renewal,and lead to urban renewal along the line.\n* Freeway constructions\n** Goal: to develop tourist attraction areas such as [[Yilan County, Taiwan|Yilan]], [[Hualien County|Hualien]], [[Taitung County|Taitung]], and [[Nantou County|Nantou]]; to facilitate the everyday life circle; to expand the highway network.\n* [[Kaohsiung Harbor]] intercontinental container port center\n** Goal: to construct a new intercontinental container port for 15,000 [[Twenty-foot equivalent unit|TEU]] container ships; improve the transport ability of the Kaohsiung port.\n* Northern, central, and southern metro system\n** Goal: to plan and construct a total of 182&nbsp;km of metro routes; to improve the rapid transit systems in metropolitan areas of northern, central, and southern Taiwan.\n* Sewers\n** Goal: to improve the living environment; to purify the water; to regain beautiful rivers and ocean.\n* Turn seawater to drinking water; shut down other dams on the mountains. Solve the famine problems, make more tap water, create tourism and environmental friendly lakes.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Ten Major Construction Projects]]\n* [[History of Taiwan]]\n\n==References==\n\n* [[Republic of China|R.O.C]].'s Government Information Office: [http://www.gio.gov.tw/taiwan-website/5-gp/thenew/ ''The Ten New Major Construction Projects'']\n\n{{coord missing|Taiwan}}\n\n[[Category:Economy of Taiwan]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use American English|date = January 2019}}\n{{Short description|Infrastructure projects in Taiwan}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date = January 2019}}\n{{Update|type=|date=January 2019|reason=}}\n{{Prose|date=July 2013}}\nThe '''New Ten Major Construction Projects''' ({{zh|t=\u65b0\u5341\u5927\u5efa\u8a2d}}) refers to the construction plans in [[Taiwan]] introduced by then-premier [[Yu Shyi-kun]] in November 2003.\n\n== List of the projects ==\n\n* Top universities and research centers\n** Goal: to have at least 15 major [[graduate school]]s ranked number 1 in [[Asia]] in 5 years; to get at least one college ranked one of the top 100 colleges of the world in 10 years.\n* International arts and popular music centers\n** [[Northern Taiwan]]: Greater Taipei New Theater\n** [[Central Taiwan]]: Taichung Metropolitan Opera House\n** [[Southern Taiwan]]: [[Kaohsiung]] National Arts Cultural Center (to be called the Wei Wu Ying Cultural Center)\n* M-Taiwan plan\n** Goal: to build a world-class internet service environment, and become the third [[Orders of magnitude (numbers)#1012|trillion]]-dollar communication industrial development.\n* Taiwan exhibition\n** Goal: to exhibit Taiwan's creativity and vigor, and prompt the development of technology, tourism, and culture.\n* TRA MRTizion\uff1a Appealing for pass car of [[Taiwan High Speed Rail|THSR]]\uff0cvia additions of stations, train services\u3001elevation\u3001underground passages\uff0cmake TRA transform to metro area and regional MRTs\uff0clet TRA transform and renewal\uff0cand lead to urban renewal along the line.\n* Freeway constructions\n** Goal: to develop tourist attraction areas such as [[Yilan County, Taiwan|Yilan]], [[Hualien County|Hualien]], [[Taitung County|Taitung]], and [[Nantou County|Nantou]]; to facilitate the everyday life circle; to expand the highway network.\n* [[Kaohsiung Harbor]] intercontinental container port center\n** Goal: to construct a new intercontinental container port for 15,000 [[Twenty-foot equivalent unit|TEU]] container ships; improve the transport ability of the Kaohsiung port.\n* Northern, central, and southern metro system\n** Goal: to plan and construct a total of 182&nbsp;km of metro routes; to improve the rapid transit systems in metropolitan areas of northern, central, and southern Taiwan.\n* Sewers\n** Goal: to improve the living environment; to purify the water; to regain beautiful rivers and ocean.\n* Turn seawater to drinking water; shut down other dams on the mountains. Solve the famine problems, make more tap water, create tourism and environmental friendly lakes.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Ten Major Construction Projects]]\n* [[History of Taiwan]]\n\n==References==\n\n* [[Republic of China|R.O.C]].'s Government Information Office: [http://www.gio.gov.tw/taiwan-website/5-gp/thenew/ ''The Ten New Major Construction Projects'']\n\n{{coord missing|Taiwan}}\n\n[[Category:Economy of Taiwan]]\n", "name_user": "Danielt998", "label": "safe", "comment": "clean up, replaced: \uff0c \u2192 , (4), \uff1a \u2192 :, \u3001 \u2192 , (2)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/New_Ten_Major_Construction_Projects"}
{"title_page": "Iraq spring fighting of 2008", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox military conflict\n|conflict=Iraq Spring Fighting of 2008\n|partof=the [[Iraq War]]\n|image=Iraq 2008 fighting.png\n|image_size=300px\n|caption=Major flashpoints of the fighting\n|date=25 March \u2013 15 May 2008<br>({{Age in months, weeks and days|month1=03|day1=25|year1=2008|month2=05|day2=15|year2=2008|}})\n|place= [[Iraq]]\n|result=Ceasefire,<ref>{{cite news| url=http://edition.cnn.com/2008/WORLD/meast/05/10/iraq.main/index.html | work=CNN | title=Cease-fire reached in Baghdad's Sadr City - CNN.com | date=11 May 2008 | accessdate=5 May 2010}}</ref> Strategic ISF victory\n*Iraqi forces gain control of [[Sadr City]]\n*Iraqi forces launch further operations in [[Maysan Governorate]]\n*Eventual disarmament of Mahdi Army\n|combatant1={{flagicon|Iraq}} [[Iraqi Army]]<br />\n{{flag|United States}}<br />\n{{flagicon|Iraq}} [[Awakening movements in Iraq|Awakening Councils]]<br />\n{{Flagicon image|Badr Organisation Military flag.svg}} [[Badr Brigades]]\n|combatant2={{Flagicon image|Flag of Promised Day Brigades.svg}} [[Mahdi Army]]<br />\n{{flagicon image|Shiism_arabic_blue.PNG}} [[Special Groups (Iraq)|Special Groups]]<br />\n{{flagicon image|<!-- [[WP:NFCC]] violation: Islamic Virtue Party.svg -->}} [[Fadhila|Fadhila Militia]]<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/03/26/world/middleeast/26iraq.html?pagewanted=1&_r=1 | work=The New York Times | title=Iraqi Crackdown on Shiite Forces Sets Off Fighting | first1=Michael | last1=Kamber | first2=James | last2=Glanz | date=26 March 2008}}</ref><br />\n|commander1={{flagicon|Iraq}} [[Nouri al-Maliki]]<br />\n{{flagicon|Iraq}} [[Mohan al-Furayji]]<br />\n{{flagicon|United States}} [[David Petraeus]]<br />\n{{Flagicon image|Badr Organisation Military flag.svg}} [[Hadi al-Amiri]]\n|commander2={{Flagicon image|Flag of Promised Day Brigades.svg}} [[Muqtada al-Sadr]]<br />\n{{flagicon image|Shiism_arabic_blue.PNG}} [[Akran Hasnawi]]{{KIA}}<br />\n{{flagicon image|Shiism_arabic_blue.PNG}} [[Akram al-Kabi]]{{citation needed|date=July 2018}}<br />\n|strength1=400,000\n|strength2=60,000\n|casualties1=191 killed;<br />2,100 deserted, defected or captured<ref>{{cite news| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/middle_east/7336386.stm | work=BBC News | title='Turncoat' Basra police pursued | date=8 April 2008 | accessdate=5 May 2010}}</ref><br />(Iraqi security forces)<br />35 killed (U.S. forces)<ref>[http://www.icasualties.org/oif/prdDetails.aspx?hndRef=3-2008 Period Details<!-- Bot generated title -->] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080323131834/http://www.icasualties.org/oif/prdDetails.aspx?hndRef=3-2008 |date=23 March 2008 }}</ref><ref>[http://www.icasualties.org/oif/prdDetails.aspx?hndRef=4-2008 Period Details<!-- Bot generated title -->] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080501033612/http://www.icasualties.org/oif/prdDetails.aspx?hndRef=4-2008 |date=1 May 2008 }}</ref><ref>[http://www.icasualties.org/oif/prdDetails.aspx?hndRef=5-2008 Period Details<!-- Bot generated title -->] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080505045349/http://www.icasualties.org/oif/prdDetails.aspx?hndRef=5-2008 |date=5 May 2008 }}</ref><br />1 killed (Iraqi militia)<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.usatoday.com/news/world/iraq/2008-04-10-iraqnews_N.htm | work=USA Today | title=Sunnis form militias to counter those of Shiites | first=Charles | last=Levinson | date=11 April 2008 | accessdate=5 May 2010}}</ref><br />4 killed (Islamic Dawa Party)\n|casualties2=700 killed (US Claim)<ref>[[New York Times]] [https://www.nytimes.com/2008/05/21/world/middleeast/21sadr.html?_r=2&hp=&oref=login&pagewanted=print Operation in Sadr City Is an Iraqi Success, So Far]</ref><br />2,000+ killed (Iraqi claim)<ref>[http://www.iraqupdates.com/p_articles.php/article/32980 Mahdi Army 'going underground'] \u2013 Iraq Updates</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.longwarjournal.org/archives/2008/06/mahdi_army_decimated.php|title=Mahdi Army decimated during recent fighting|publisher=Long War Journal|date=26 June 2008|accessdate=8 December 2008|first=Bill|last=Roggio|quote=More than 1,000 Mahdi Army fighters were killed in Sadr City alone, according to a Mahdi Army commander in Baghdad. Another 415 were killed in Basrah. More than 400 were killed during fighting in the southern cities of Najaf, Karbala, Hillah, Diwaniyah, Amarah, Samawah, and Nasiriyah in late March and early April, according to numbers compiled by The Long War Journal.}}</ref>\n|casualties3=1,112 Iraqi civilians killed,<br/>2 U.S. and 2 Indian civilians killed\n}}\n{{Campaignbox Iraq War}}\nThe '''Iraq Spring Fighting of 2008''' (March \u2013 May 2008) was a series of clashes between the [[Mahdi Army]] and the [[Iraqi Army]] supported by coalition forces, in southern [[Iraq]] and [[Baghdad]], that began with an Iraqi [[Battle of Basra (2008)|offensive in Basra]]. The fighting followed a lull in the [[Civil war in Iraq (2006-07)|Civil war in Iraq]] and was the most serious crisis since October 2007.\n\n==Background==\nIn 2007, the Iraqi Army moved 4 [[brigade]]s, including a [[tank]] brigade, and a [[special forces]] battalion to [[Basra]], replacing the existing brigade stationed there which was reported to have been corrupt.<ref>[http://www.longwarjournal.org/archives/2007/12/basrah_the_untold_st.php Basrah: Missing the Iraqi Security Force Deployment \u2013 Long War Journal]</ref> The Iraqi National Police also moved two battalions to Basra. In August 2007, the Iraqi Army established the [[Iraqi Army#Structure|Basra Operational Command]] under the command of [[Mohan al-Furayji|General Mohan]]. The Vice Chief of Staff of the Iraqi Joint Staff said \"We do not have enough forces there. That is why we are having a new division, the 14th Division, to be built in Basrah, especially with the possibility that the British might be leaving us in time.\"<ref>[http://www.longwarjournal.org/archives/2007/09/iraqi_security_force_2.php Iraqi Security Forces Order of Battle: September 2007 Update \u2013 Long War Journal]</ref>\n\nSince August 2007, a unilateral ceasefire was in place, imposed by [[Muqtada al-Sadr]] on his militia, the [[Mahdi Army]]. However raids were continuing on so-called \"rogue\" elements of the militia and tensions were building. In February, Sadr extended the ceasefire even though many of his commanders were against it. Despite the extension raids continued and members of the militia accused the members of the security forces of being infiltrated by their rival militia, the [[Badr Organization|Badr Brigade]].\n\n==The Campaign==\nOn 23 March, Easter Sunday [[Iran]]ian trained militants of the Mahdi Army fired 107mm rockets on the heavily fortified [[Green Zone]] in [[Baghdad]] killing Paul Converse, a U.S. government employee, and wounding several other employees and contractors.<ref>[https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2008/04/07/AR2008040702533.html]</ref> At least 12 Iraqi civilians were also killed by rockets from Sadr City that missed the Green Zone and hit the civilian sectors around the Zone.<ref>[http://antiwar.com/updates/?articleid=12569 Sunday: 4 US Soldiers, 91 Iraqis Killed; 152 Wounded \u2013 Antiwar.com]</ref>\n\n===Basra operation===\n{{Main|Battle of Basra (2008)}}\nOn 25 March, the Iraqi Army and police attacked the second largest Iraqi city, Basra, which had for the most part been under Mahdi Army control for the past seven months since the [[Siege of U.K. bases in Basra|British troop withdrawal]] from the city in the beginning of September the previous year. Since then the city was in the middle of a turf war between three different militias, including the Mahdi Army, for the control of the [[oil]] exports which had been dominated by the Black Market.\n\nStreet fighting spread through six neighbourhoods after the government operation started at 2:00am. Plumes of smoke were seen over the northern neighbourhoods, and by the end of the first day of fighting government forces took the center of the city but the Mahdi Army was still holding on to the northern part of the city.{{Citation needed|date=March 2008}}\n\nOn 26 March, the [[Iraqi Prime Minister]] issued an ultimatum to the Mahdi Army to surrender within 72 hours.{{Citation needed|date=March 2008}}\n\nOn 28 March, U.S. aircraft bombed two targets in the city while being supported by British planes, a day after militiamen paraded in the city with some 20 captured soldiers and a captured Iraqi Army [[Humvee]]. At least two Iraqi Army armoured vehicles and a [[BMP-1|BMP infantry fighting vehicle]] were seen destroyed on the streets.\n<!-- Deleted image removed: [[File:Mahdi Army fighters take up positions during the street fighting in Basra.jpg|225px|left|thumb|Mahdi Army fighters take up positions during the street fighting in Basra 26 March 2008.]] -->\nBy 29 March, the Iraqi military offensive against the city was faltering in the face of stiff resistance as the 72-hour ultimatum by the government passed and the militants refused to surrender.\n\nOn 31 March, the fighting in the city ended after al-Sadr's declaration of a new cease-fire. By that point the Mahdi Army was still in control of about 75% of the city.\n\nUp to 236 people were killed and 1,200 wounded in the fighting in districts of central and northern Basra. 921 members of the security forces, including 421 policemen and a full Iraqi Army battalion of 500 men, deserted, defected or were captured.\n\nClashes between militiamen and al-Maliki's tribe in [[Qurna, Iraq|Qurna]], north of Basra, left 7 dead, including a policeman and a civilian, and 2 wounded on both sides.<ref>[http://www.mcclatchydc.com/212/story/31877.html Round-up of Daily Violence in Iraq, Friday March 28, 2008 McClatchy Washington Bureau] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080402181527/http://www.mcclatchydc.com/212/story/31877.html |date=2 April 2008 }}</ref>\n<ref>[http://www.aswataliraq.info/look/english/article.tpl?IdLanguage=1&IdPublication=4&NrArticle=74543&NrIssue=2&NrSection=1 5 killed, 2 wounded in clashes in Basra \u2013 Aswat Aliraq] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080402095205/http://www.aswataliraq.info/look/english/article.tpl?IdLanguage=1&IdPublication=4&NrArticle=74543&NrIssue=2&NrSection=1 |date=2 April 2008 }}</ref>\n<ref>[http://www.aswataliraq.info/look/english/article.tpl?IdLanguage=1&IdPublication=4&NrArticle=73950&NrIssue=2&NrSection=1 Civilian killed, policeman wounded in clashes in Basra \u2013 Aswat Aliraq] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080402095201/http://www.aswataliraq.info/look/english/article.tpl?IdLanguage=1&IdPublication=4&NrArticle=73950&NrIssue=2&NrSection=1 |date=2 April 2008 }}</ref>\n\nMortars also killed two policemen and wounded 23 people, including 13 policemen, in [[Karma, Iraq|Karma]], a town {{convert|50|mi|km}} north of Basra.<ref>[http://wiredispatch.com/news/?id=105058 FACTBOX-Security developments in Iraq, March 28 \u2013 Reuters] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080402100251/http://wiredispatch.com/news/?id=105058 |date=2 April 2008 }}</ref>\n\nFollowing the cease-fire in Basra there were still sporadic clashes in the city for some time leaving at least 32 civilians, 34 militants, five policemen and one U.S. Marine dead. Among the dead was also police Major Ali Haider, a commander in the police department's serious crimes directorate.<ref name=autogenerated4>{{cite news| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/middle_east/7327926.stm | work=BBC News | title=Air strike levels house in Basra | date=3 April 2008 | accessdate=5 May 2010}}</ref><ref>[http://www.mnf-iraq.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=18253&Itemid=128 Multi-National Force \u2013 Iraq \u2013 ISF recover weapons cache, kill 10 in separate operations in Basra<!-- Bot generated title -->] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080408200956/http://www.mnf-iraq.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=18253&Itemid=128 |date=8 April 2008 }}</ref><ref>[http://www.kuna.net.kw/NewsAgenciesPublicSite/ArticleDetails.aspx?id=1897387&Language=en \u0643\u0648\u0646\u0627 : Eight persons killed in fiery blast in Basra \u2013 \u0627\u0644\u062f\u0641\u0627\u0639 \u0648\u0627\u0644\u0623\u0645\u0646 \u2013 07/04/2008<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref><ref>[http://www.mnf-iraq.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=18354&Itemid=21 Multi-National Force \u2013 Iraq \u2013 UAV destroys mortar position, kills 6 (Hyanniyah)<!-- Bot generated title -->] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080514125049/http://www.mnf-iraq.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=18354&Itemid=21 |date=14 May 2008 }}</ref>\n\n===Post-operation Basra fighting ===\n1 April: Gunmen are reportedly off the streets and Iraqis cautiously emerge back on the streets of Basra with opening markets and men cleaning up trash from the roadsides. Maliki claims military \"security, stability and success\" and vows to continue operations with a seven-point plan, including recruiting 10,000 new [[Iraqi security forces]] members and moving to enhance public services in Basra.<ref name=\"cbsnews040108\">[https://www.cbsnews.com/stories/2008/04/01/iraq/main3985302.shtml Iraqi PM: Basra Strikes A \"Success\", CBS News April 1, 2008]</ref> 2500 citizens of Basra have already volunteered to work with the Iraqi army since the start of the operation, according to a US military spokesman in Baghdad.<ref>[http://www.mnf-iraq.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=18058&Itemid=131 Operational Update: Maj. Gen. Bergner, April 2] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080513235320/http://www.mnf-iraq.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=18058&Itemid=131 |date=13 May 2008 }} \u2013 MNF-I</ref>\n\n[[File:Hillah SWAT Team.jpg|thumb|200px|right|The Hillah [[SWAT]] Team in training in 2006. The unit was redeployed to Basra following operations in al-Kut and Hillah. On 1 April, they detained 20 vehicle smugglers in Basra.]]\nMaj. Gen. Abdul Aziz Mohammad, director of military operations at Iraq's Defense Ministry, said the Iraqi military planned to seal and search every neighbourhood to capture suspected criminals and confiscate weapons.<ref name=\"wp-usap040108\">[https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2008/04/01/AR2008040100833.html U.S. Appears to Take Lead in Fighting in Baghdad, Washington Post, April 1, 2008]</ref> Sadr vows to continue fight against occupation forces \"in a peaceful manner\" and plans mass demonstrations against the Coalition on 9 April.\n\nThe Hillah [[Special Weapons and Tactics]] team detained 20 vehicle smugglers in Basra as part of \"continuing deliberate operations against criminals to restore a rule of law\", according to a US military spokesman.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20080413010935/http://www.mnf-iraq.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=18036&Itemid=128 Hillah Special Weapons and Tactics unit detain 20 suspected smugglers in Basra] \u2013 MNF-I</ref>\n\nThe British defence minister announces a pause in troop reductions.<ref name=\"cnnuk040108\">[http://edition.cnn.com/2008/WORLD/meast/04/01/uk.iraq/index.html \"UK halts troop cuts after Iraq clashes\", CNN, April 1, 2008]</ref>\n\n2 April: Lt. Gen. Mohan al-Furayji leads a 12 vehicle Iraqi Army convoy though the Hayaniya district, a Sadr stronghold in central Basra, in an apparent show of force. A roadside bomb explodes near the convoy, but there were no casualties. A reporter for an Iraqi TV station was shot in the leg while filming the convoy. Afterwards gunmen attacked the convoy and one Iraqi Army Humvee was torched.<ref>ROBERT H. REID \u2013 [https://news.yahoo.com/s/ap/iraq;_ylt=ArGIX8e6ZMrutLo3VyIS52BX6GMA Iraq army flexes muscles in Basra] {{dead link|date=September 2016|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}} \u2013 AP via Yahoo News</ref> Overall, Basra was reportedly relatively calm for a third straight day.<ref name=\"reuters-bomb-040208\">[https://www.reuters.com/article/worldNews/idUSL2884231520080402?sp=true Bomb explodes near top Iraq generals in Basra, Reuters, April 2, 2008]</ref>\n\n[[Chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff|U.S. Chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff]] Admiral [[Michael Mullen]] said in a Pentagon press briefing that the Basra operation is still ongoing and that it is premature to comment on the results of the operation.<ref name=\"cjcsspeech040308\">[http://www.defenselink.mil/transcripts/transcript.aspx?transcriptid=4186 DoD Press Briefing \u2013 CJCS Adm Mullen, Transcript, April 3, 2008] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080521133807/http://www.defenselink.mil/transcripts/transcript.aspx?transcriptid=4186 |date=21 May 2008 }}</ref>\n\nA US [[Unmanned Aerial Vehicle]] (UAV) attacked a [[Technical (fighting vehicle)|technical]] in the Halaf area of Basra, killing 6 \"armed criminals\" after heavy machine gun fire was reported.<ref>[http://www.mnf-iraq.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=18112&Itemid=128 Coalition forces conduct airstrike in al-Halaf, six criminals killed (al-Halaf) ] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080517204613/http://www.mnf-iraq.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=18112&Itemid=128 |date=17 May 2008 }} \u2013 MNF-I</ref>\n\n3 April: A U.S. airstrike destroyed a house in Basra killing two militant snipers and at least six civilians.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/middle_east/7327926.stm Air strike levels house in Basra] \u2013 BBC News</ref> Iraqi Security Forces, advised by U.S. Special Forces, killed seven criminal members and detained 16 others during three separate operations in Basra directed by the Iraqi government.<ref name=\"MNFIpr040408\">[http://www.mnf-iraq.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=18111&Itemid=128 ISF kill 7 criminal members, detain 16 in 3 separate operations in Basra, MNF-I press release, April 4, 2008] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080518031127/http://www.mnf-iraq.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=18111&Itemid=128 |date=18 May 2008 }}</ref>\n\nMuqtada al-Sadr offers the Iraqi government to help purge militia members from Iraqi security forces.<ref name=\"cnn-irai-040408\">[http://edition.cnn.com/2008/WORLD/meast/04/04/iraq.main/index.html  Iraqi leader freezes assault on militias, CNN, April 4, 2008]</ref> Sadr also angrily criticises the Iraqi government for \"denying it sent envoys to him\"<ref name=\"cnn-al-sadr-040308\">[http://edition.cnn.com/2008/WORLD/meast/04/03/iraq.alsadr/index.html Al-Sadr offers to help Iraqi security forces]</ref>\n\n4 April: Iraqi PM Nuri al-Maliki orders his security forces to stop raids on suspected Shiite militiamen to \"give time to those who are repentant\" to lay down their weapons.<ref name=\"cnn-irai-040408\" /> The PM's order did not mention the Mahdi Army by name. Al-Maliki also ordered a resumption of reconstruction projects and services in the areas of fighting. 3,000 Iraqi soldiers and policemen, including soldiers from the Iraqi Army 1st Division moved into Hayyaniyah to distribute food and water to Iraqis who had been without supplies for several days.<ref>[http://www.mnf-iraq.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=18255&Itemid=128 Iraqi Army distributes food and water al-Hayyaniyah] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080515161620/http://www.mnf-iraq.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=18255&Itemid=128 |date=15 May 2008 }} \u2013 MNF-I</ref>\n\nCoalition forces attacked Mahdi Army members west of Basra and ordered an air strike during the ensuing clashes. Two children were killed along with another person.<ref>[http://antiwar.com/updates/?articleid=12633 \u2013 Antiwar.com]</ref>\n\nIn a Coalition raid during the night 10 militants were killed and two weapons caches, including 60&nbsp;mm mortar rounds, rocket propelled grenades and [[explosively formed penetrators]], were found.<ref>[http://www.mnf-iraq.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=18253&Itemid=128 ISF recover weapons cache, kill 10 in separate operations in Basra] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080408200956/http://www.mnf-iraq.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=18253&Itemid=128 |date=8 April 2008 }} \u2013 MNF I</ref>\n\n5 April: A U.S. airstrike in the Hayaniyah district hit a militant mortar position killing one gunman.<ref name=\"mnfi-coalition-040508\">[http://www.mnf-iraq.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=18152&Itemid=21 Coalition forces conduct airstrike in Basra, one criminal killed, MNF-I Press release, April 5, 2008] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080514123723/http://www.mnf-iraq.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=18152&Itemid=21 |date=14 May 2008 }}</ref>\n\n6 April: The Iraqi Political Council for National Security, with representatives from all major political parties holds a meeting and agrees unanimously to a resolution with a number of points and actions necessary to \"end the existence of this gang\" (the Mahdi Army). Among those points is a decision that the Sadr trend will not have the right to participate in the political process or take part in the provincial elections unless they disband the Mahdi army.<ref name=\"CNN-Maliki-040708\">[http://edition.cnn.com/2008/WORLD/meast/04/07/al.maliki.transcript/index.html Transcript: Prime Minister Nuri al-Maliki on Iraq, CNN, April 7, 2008]</ref> Iraqi Prime Minister Nuri al-Maliki continues to deny that any concessions were made or that Iran was involved in negotiating Muqtada al-Sadr's cease-fire order on 30 March 2008.<ref name=\"CNN-Maliki-040708\"/>\n\nAn explosion of unknown source occurred in Basra destroying a house and killing eight people. MNF-I confirms that an explosion occurred but denies involvement.<ref>[http://www.kuna.net.kw/NewsAgenciesPublicSite/ArticleDetails.aspx?id=1897387&Language=en Eight persons killed in fiery blast in Basra ] \u2013 Kuna News</ref>\n\n7 April: Moqtada al-Sadr offers to disband the Mahdi army if the highest Shi'ite religious authorities, including [[Grand Ayatollah Ali al-Sistani]] and senior Shi'ite clergy based in Iran, demand it. \"If they order the Mahdi army to disband, Muqtada al-Sadr and the Sadr movement will obey the orders of the religious leaders\", senior Sadr aide Hassan Zargani told Reuters from Iran.<ref name=\"reuters-Iraq's-080407\">[https://www.reuters.com/article/worldNews/idUSL0434078820080407?sp=true Iraq's Sadr to disband Mehdi Army if clerics order, Reuters, April 7, 2008]</ref>\n\n8 April: A roadside bomb targeted the convoy of interior ministry spokesman Major-General Abdul-Karim Khalaf, wounding two of his guards in northern Basra.<ref>[http://wiredispatch.com/news/?id=118077 FACTBOX-Security developments in Iraq, April 7<!-- Bot generated title -->] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080409103740/http://wiredispatch.com/news/?id=118077 |date=9 April 2008 }}</ref>\n\n9 April: The US military reported that [[Iraqi Special Operations Forces]] (ISOF) had captured 12 \"suspected terrorists and Special Group members\" and killed 14 others in operations in Basra in the past week.<ref>[http://www.mnf-iraq.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=18292&Itemid=128 ISOF snare terrorist and criminal suspects (Basrah)] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080515161318/http://www.mnf-iraq.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=18292&Itemid=128 |date=15 May 2008 }} \u2013 MNF-I</ref>\n\n11 April: The German Press reports that Riyad al-Nuri was the victim of an assassination as he left a mosque in Najaf on a Friday. He was gunned down by non-uniformed militants in the style of the assassinations that marked the Quds campaign in Basra. No group took credit for the killing. Riyad al-Nuri was Moqtada al-Sadr's brother-in-law, and a close aide. Moqtada al-Sadr lives in the Holy City of Qom, Iran and has become dependent on his aides in Iraq.<ref>http://news.monstersandcritics.com/middleeast/news/article_1399504.php/Al-Sadrs_brother-in-law_killed_in_Iraqs_Najaf__Roundup{{dead link|date=November 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> _\n\n12 April: Soldiers from the 1st Brigade of the 1st IA (QRF) Division from Al-Anbar, as well as elements from the 14th Division, cleared the suburb of al-Qibla in Basra \"without incident\", the US military reported. It also reported an al-Qaida in Iraq leader was captured by Iraqi forces in Abu al-Khasib, a small town 20&nbsp;km southeast of Basra.<ref>[http://www.mnf-iraq.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=18441&Itemid=128 Operation Charge of Knights continues progress in Basrah] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080515172528/http://www.mnf-iraq.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=18441&Itemid=128 |date=15 May 2008 }} \u2013 MNF-I</ref>\n\n13 April: A policeman is killed in a drive-by shooting and two dumped bodies are found.<ref>[http://antiwar.com/updates/?articleid=12686 Sunday: 46 Iraqis Killed, 29 Wounded \u2013 Antiwar.com<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\n14 April: [[Richard Butler (journalist)|Richard Butler]], a UK journalist held captive in Basra for two months after being kidnapped in central Basra was freed in an Iraqi Army sweep.<ref>[https://news.yahoo.com/s/nm/iraq_dc;_ylt=AtNLUsusFOzddv0ClLcKbcxX6GMA  Kidnapped UK journalist freed in Iraq's Basra]  {{webarchive|url=https://archive.is/20080527130348/http://news.yahoo.com/s/nm/iraq_dc;_ylt=AtNLUsusFOzddv0ClLcKbcxX6GMA |date= 27 May 2008 }} \u2013 Reuters via Yahoo News</ref> Police Major Ali Haider, a commander in the police department's serious crimes directorate, is shot and killed.<ref>[http://antiwar.com/updates/?articleid=12691 Monday: 2 US Soldiers, 87 Iraqis Killed; 142 Iraqis Wounded \u2013 Antiwar.com<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\n15 April: Maj-Gen Abdul Jalil Khalaf and Lt-Gen Mohan al-Furayji are reassigned to posts in Baghdad. The Iraqi government says that the two chiefs are returning to their posts in the Defence Ministry at the end of a 6-month assignment to the southern city. Brig. Gen. Qassim al-Moussawi, an Iraqi military spokesman, said: \"The two have done a great job and their efforts were highly appreciated by the commander in chief\". However, a spokesman for the Sadrist bloc in Basra, Ali al-Suaidi, says the Iraqi government \"wants to blame its failure on somebody\" and the moves are \"punishment for the botched execution of the campaign\".  According to Brig. Gen al-Moussawi, Gen. Furayji will be replaced by Maj. Gen. Mohammad Jawad, the commander of the 14th Division, in the Basra Operational Command and Maj. Gen. Adel Dahham will become the new police chief in Basra.<ref>{{cite news|publisher=BBC News|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/middle_east/7350434.stm|title=Basra security leaders removed|date=16 April 2008}}</ref><ref>Amit R. Paley \u2013 [https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2008/04/16/AR2008041600932.html Iraq Reassigns Chiefs Of Basra's Army, Police] \u2013 Washington Post</ref>\n\n16 April: An unmanned U.S. drone plane launched missiles that killed four militiamen and wounded one more, but police said six people were killed and three more were wounded.\n\n17 April: Gunmen tried to kill former police chief Brigadier-General Mohamed Kadhim al-Ali. One of his bodyguards was killed and two more were wounded. In a separate incident, gunmen shot and wounded a police commando. Also, two policemen were killed in a drive-by shooting.\n[[File:Weapons cache basra.jpg|thumb|225px|right|An Iraqi soldier from the 1st QRF division examines a mortar captured during clearing operations in Hayaniya, 19 April]]\n19 April: Iraqi security forces launched a clearing operation in the Hayaniya district, a Sadr stronghold in central Basra. After a show of force in which coalition forces bombed an empty area west of Hayaniya, Iraqi forces, with advisers from the [[British Army]] and the [[United States Marine Corps]].,<ref name=moduk20080421>[http://www.mod.uk/DefenceInternet/DefenceNews/MilitaryOperations/IraqiSoldiersContinueToTargetBasraMilitias.htm Iraqi soldiers continue to target Basra militias] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080513203724/http://www.mod.uk/DefenceInternet/DefenceNews/MilitaryOperations/IraqiSoldiersContinueToTargetBasraMilitias.htm |date=13 May 2008 }} \u2013 UK Ministry of Defence</ref> moved into the Hayaniya city center. According to General [[Mohan al-Furayji]], Iraqi forces faced only \"isolated skirmishes\".<ref>Aref Mohammed \u2013 [https://news.yahoo.com/s/nm/20080419/wl_nm/iraq_dc Show of force as Iraqi forces advance in Basra] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080421035946/http://news.yahoo.com/s/nm/20080419/wl_nm/iraq_dc |date=21 April 2008 }} \u2013 Reuters via Yahoo News</ref> A large number of weapons were captured during the operation, including 140 rockets, 50 mortars, 70 IEDs and a number of anti-aircraft missiles. Seven Iraqi Army vehicles were recaptured as well.<ref name=moduk20080421 />\n\n20 April: In a statement, Muqtada al-Sadr warned that he would declare \"open war\" if the campaign against him did not stop.<ref name=\"ap-alsadr-042008\">[http://hosted.ap.org/dynamic/stories/I/IRAQ?SITE=NHPOR&SECTION=HOME&TEMPLATE=DEFAULT Al-Sadr's followers refuse to disband militia in Iraq, Associated Press, April 20, 2008] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070519032040/http://hosted.ap.org/dynamic/stories/I/IRAQ?SITE=NHPOR&SECTION=HOME&TEMPLATE=DEFAULT |date=19 May 2007 }}</ref> Coincidentally, [[Al-Qaeda in Iraq]] released a similar message the same day, calling for a 30-day period of violence.<ref name=\"wp-new-042008\">[https://web.archive.org/web/20121104185737/http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2008/04/19/AR2008041901723.html New Al-Qaida in Iraq tape calls for monthlong offensive, Washington Post, April 20, 2008]</ref>\n\nIran's ambassador to Baghdad declared support for the Iraqi government crackdown against \"lawbreakers\" in Basra. Since major Sunni, Shiite and Kurdish parties have already supported the Maliki government in its crackdown for some time, Sadr appears increasingly politically isolated.<ref name=\"ap-alsadr-042008\"/>\n\n21 April: Two roadside-bombs hit two Coalition patrols in the city. One was an American, the second a British. There were no casualties suffered in the attack on the British patrol but in the first attack one U.S. Marine was killed and a second wounded.\n\nAlso, an al-Sistani aide who was wounded a week before in an attack in the city died of his wounds.\n\n24 April: Prime Minister Nuri al-Maliki claimed historic victory over armed militias. \"The ideology of having rival militias is over. The weapon is now in state hands\", a statement said that Maliki told British Foreign Secretary David Miliband during talks. \"We have political support from all [political] entities for the measures taken by the government\", Maliki continued.<ref name=\"afp-iraqi-042408\">[http://afp.google.com/article/ALeqM5iHul4DZp-axz3iOT91x_oRVSoL5Q AFP: Iraqi PM says private army mentality in Iraq is over, AFP, April 24, 2008] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080501060937/http://afp.google.com/article/ALeqM5iHul4DZp-axz3iOT91x_oRVSoL5Q |date=1 May 2008 }}</ref>\n\n[[Multinational Force Iraq|Multi-National Corps-Iraq]] commander [[Lloyd J. Austin|Lt. Gen Lloyd J. Austin]] said in a press briefing that Iraqi security forces are in control of Basra.\n\n25 April: Muqtada al-Sadr reaffirmed his cease-fire order. In a statement to followers read on his behalf during Friday prayers, Muqtada al-Sadr urged his followers to \"observe more patience in commitment to the freeze decision.\" Sadr also tried to clarify his call for \"open war\" on 20 April, stressing that the threat \"is meant against the occupiers only.\"<ref name=\"voi-open-042508\">[http://www.aswataliraq.info/look/english/article.tpl?IdLanguage=1&IdPublication=4&NrArticle=77383&NrIssue=2&NrSection=1 \"Open war against occupiers only,\" Sadr tells followers, Voices of Iraq, April 25, 2008]{{dead link|date=May 2016}}</ref>\n\nSecular life began to re-emerge. Young women dared to wear jeans, soldiers listened to pop music on their mobile phones and bands began performing at wedding parties again.<ref name=\"londontimes-themen-042508\">[http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/world/iraq/article3671861.ece The men in black vanish and Basra comes back to life], [[The Times]], 25 April 2008</ref>\n\nIn the town of Qurna, near Basra, journalist Jassim al-Batat was gunned down by gunmen in a speeding car as he left his house.<ref>[http://wiredispatch.com/news/?id=142737 Iraqi journalist killed near Basra, radio station says<!-- Bot generated title -->]{{dead link|date=May 2016}}</ref>\n\n28 April: A Sadrist lawmaker was killed and his wife was injured during an armed attack.\n\n8 May: A British soldier is wounded and two unidentified foreign contractors are killed when rockets hit the main British military base in Basra at the airport. Coalition aircraft responded to the attack killing six militants who fired on the base.\n\n10 May: Two civilians were killed and five others were wounded when a roadside bomb blasted a police patrol in Basra. Also, 14 suspects were arrested during raids.\n\n===Fighting in Sadr City and Baghdad===\n{{Main|Siege of Sadr City}}\nThe clashes, soon after the start of the security operation, spread from Basra to Baghdad, mainly the [[Sadr City]] district of the capital, which was under the control of the Mahdi Army.\n<!-- Deleted image removed: [[File:Smoke rises from the Green Zone after a mortar strike March 25, 2008.jpg|225px|right|thumb|Smoke rises from the Green Zone after a mortar strike 25 March 2008.]] -->\n'''25 March''': Militants attacked police and army checkpoints in the western and northern parts of Baghdad and the Green Zone was constantly coming under mortar and rocket attacks leaving dozens of people wounded and many Iraqi civilians killed by rockets that missed their targets. On the first day of fighting in Baghdad one U.S. soldier was among the dead, killed by a mortar in the Adhamiya district of Baghdad. The mortar was fired from the vicinity of Sadr City. In Baghdad's al-Amin neighbourhood, Mahdi Army gunmen stormed two offices of the Dawa party and clashed with guards there. Five Mahdi Army gunmen and two Dawa guards were killed. Fighters also captured six policemen with their two police vehicles from their checkpoint in New Baghdad.<ref>[https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2008/03/25/AR2008032500461_pf.html Intense Fighting Erupts In Iraq | Washington Post]</ref>\n\n'''26 March''': Mortar strikes killed five people in the Karrada neighbourhood and four in Risala on 26 March. Another two people were killed in mortar attacks elsewhere. More rockets and mortars hit the Green Zone wounding four people. Among the wounded were two American civilians and one American and one Iraqi soldier.\n\nIn Sadr City militants were planting roadside bombs on a main thoroughfare and declared the ceasefire over. Mahdi Army fighters sealed off their neighbourhoods, blocking roads with refrigerators, burning tires and garbage. Heavy clashes erupted between militiamen and U.S. and Iraqi forces. A roadside bomb set a U.S. Stryker on fire in Sadr City but all soldiers inside survived. Also in fighting in northern and eastern parts of Baghdad two US soldiers and three Iraqi civilians were killed.<ref>[http://www.csmonitor.com/2008/0326/p01s13-woiq.html Across Iraq, battles erupt with Mahdi Army \u2013 Christian Science Monitor]</ref><ref>[http://wiredispatch.com/news/?id=101578 FACTBOX-Security developments in Iraq, March 26 Reuters] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080402100230/http://wiredispatch.com/news/?id=101578 |date=2 April 2008 }}</ref>\n[[File:Sadr City April 2008.jpg|thumb|left|225px|Map showing location of fighting in eastern Baghdad, March\u2013May 2008]]\n'''27 March''': On 27 March, a mortar bomb at a Baghdad bus station killed three people and wounded 15 and 2 mortar rounds hit the Ministry of Interior, al-Tasfeerat compound in central Baghdad killing one employee and injuring four. The Green Zone was still being bombarded with one Iraqi civilian killed and another 14 wounded by misfired mortars. Several mortar rounds hit a building in the U.S. embassy complex in the Zone leaving one U.S. government employee dead and another three wounded. Also, a U.S. soldier died in the fighting during the day.\n\nStreet battles in Sadr City and other parts of the capital in the previous 24 hours left 88 people dead, including 68 militants, three U.S. and one Iraqi soldier, one Iraqi policeman and at least 15 civilians who were killed when an artillery barrage hit a market in Sadr City. At least 12 U.S. soldiers were wounded and three policemen captured.<ref name=\"mcclatchydc-212\">[http://www.mcclatchydc.com/212/story/31750.html Round-up of Daily Violence in Iraq, Thursday March 27, 2008 McClatchy Washington Bureau] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080622184755/http://www.mcclatchydc.com/212/story/31750.html |date=22 June 2008 }}</ref><ref>[http://www.mnf-iraq.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=17878&Itemid=21 24 terrorists killed in Baghdad \u2013 MNF-Iraq] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080403021027/http://www.mnf-iraq.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=17878&Itemid=21 |date=3 April 2008 }}</ref><ref>[http://www.mnf-iraq.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=17880&Itemid=21 Terrorists launch eleven indirect fire attacks, other unrest (Baghdad) \u2013 MNF-Iraq] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080403021033/http://www.mnf-iraq.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=17880&Itemid=21 |date=3 April 2008 }}</ref><ref>[http://www.mnf-iraq.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=17888&Itemid=21 ISF, CF take fight to terrorists \u2013 MNF-Iraq] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080403072414/http://www.mnf-iraq.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=17888&Itemid=21 |date=3 April 2008 }}</ref><ref>[http://www.mnf-iraq.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=17887&Itemid=21 Iraqi Security Forces, Coalition forces target terrorists, kill 26 \u2013 MNF-Iraq] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080403072408/http://www.mnf-iraq.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=17887&Itemid=21 |date=3 April 2008 }}</ref><ref>[http://www.mnf-iraq.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=17885&Itemid=21 ISF, CF defend checkpoint, kill 8 militants (Baghdad) \u2013 MNF-Iraq] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080403072404/http://www.mnf-iraq.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=17885&Itemid=21 |date=3 April 2008 }}</ref>\n\nTahseen Sheikhly, a Sunni civilian spokesman for operation Imposing Law, was kidnapped by gunmen who stormed his house in a Mahdi Army stronghold in southeastern Baghdad and torched it. Three of his bodyguards were killed.\n\nThe Times reported areas of Baghdad were slowly falling into the hands of the Mahdi Army. The Mahdi Army took over neighbourhood after neighbourhood, some amid heavy fighting, others without firing a shot. In New Baghdad, militiamen simply ordered the police to leave their checkpoints, the officers complied en masse and the guerrillas took over their checkpoints.<ref>[http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/world/iraq/article3631718.ece Areas of Baghdad fall to militias as Iraqi Army falters in Basra | Times Online]</ref> The US Army denied this. Lieutenant Colonel Steve Stover, the [[Public affairs (military)|Public Affairs Officer]] for the 4th Infantry Division and Multinational Division Baghdad said \"All checkpoints and ISF [Iraqi security forces] buildings are in ISF and/or Coalition control. No checkpoint is in enemy control.\"<ref>Bill Roggio [http://www.longwarjournal.org/archives/2008/03/fighting_in_baghdad.php Fighting in Baghdad, South against Mahdi Army completes fourth day] \u2013 Long War Journal</ref>\n\nIn other fighting during the day a father and son were killed in the Talbiyah neighbourhood where at least eight Iraqi soldiers were wounded in street battles.<ref>[http://www.mcclatchydc.com/212/story/31750.html Round-up of Daily Violence in Iraq, Thursday March 27, 2008 | McClatchy Washington Bureau] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080622184755/http://www.mcclatchydc.com/212/story/31750.html |date=22 June 2008 }}</ref>\n\n'''28 March''': Early on 28 March, a U.S. helicopter fired a Hellfire missile during fighting in Sadr City in support of ground troops who were clearing a main supply route. Four militants and nine civilians were killed. Meanwhile, an insurgent mortar hit Iraqi Vice-President Tareq Hashemi's offices in the Green Zone, killing two guards, and a U.S. air strike killed three people and wounded six in Kadhimiya. In other fighting throughout the capital 13 militants and two civilians were killed and four U.S. Stryker armoured vehicles entered Sadr City and engaged militiamen. A U.S. soldier was killed by a roadside bomb just south of Baghdad.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/middle_east/7317935.stm Iraq extends Shia arms deadline \u2013 BBC News]</ref><ref name=\"wiredispatch_Mar28\">[http://wiredispatch.com/news/?id=104998 FACTBOX-Security developments in Iraq, March 28 \u2013 Reuters] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080402100236/http://wiredispatch.com/news/?id=104998 |date=2 April 2008 }}</ref><ref>[http://www.mnf-iraq.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=17897&Itemid=21 MND-B Soldiers kill 13 terrorists \u2013 MNF-I] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080403072418/http://www.mnf-iraq.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=17897&Itemid=21 |date=3 April 2008 }}</ref>\n\nTen of the militants were killed by US forces when a joint security station in eastern Baghdad was attacked with small arms fire. In a separate incident, a US air strike destroyed a rocket site in eastern Baghdad.<ref>[http://www.mnf-iraq.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=17906&Itemid=128 MND-B Soldiers destroy rocket site, kill 12 terrorists] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080403072422/http://www.mnf-iraq.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=17906&Itemid=128 |date=3 April 2008 }} \u2013 MNF-I</ref> One U.S. soldier was killed the fighting.\n\nLate in the evening reports came in that a unit of 500 policemen decided to stop working with the government and join the Mahdi Army.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2008/03/28/AR2008032803810_pf.html | work=The Washington Post | title=19 Tense Hours in Sadr City Alongside the Mahdi Army | first=Sudarsan | last=Raghavan | accessdate=5 May 2010}}</ref>\n\n'''29 March''': In another day of mortar bombardment mortars landed in Shiite areas of eastern Baghdad, killing at least one person and injuring 12. The [[New York Times]] reported that in a well-publicized event in Sadr City, 40 men who said they were Iraqi police officers surrendered their weapons to Sadr officials saying \"We can't fight our brothers in the Mahdi Army, so we came here to submit our weapons.\" In return, the Sadr officials gave the officers olive branches and Korans. The weapons were returned after the officers pledged not to use them against Mahdi Army members.  \"These weapons are for defending the country but not for fighting your brothers,\" said Sheik Salman al-Fraji, head of the Sadr office there.<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/2008/03/30/world/middleeast/30iraq.html?_r=1&oref=slogin&ref=todayspaper&pagewanted=print Shiite Militias Cling to Swaths of Basra and Stage Raids By JAMES GLANZ and MICHAEL KAMBER]</ref> {{YouTube|OcWG-hJbSNo|Video coverage of event}} Another 15 soldiers also surrendered elsewhere in the city.\n\nBy this point the Iraqi Health Ministry reported at least 75 civilians killed and 500 injured in fighting in Sadr City and other eastern Baghdad neighbourhoods. The U.S. military sharply disputes the claims, having said that most of those killed were militia members. Two U.S. soldiers were killed by a roadside bomb in eastern Baghdad and one Iraqi policeman was killed in the Amil district by another bomb. A militia member was killed when his RPG misfired.\n\nU.S. forces stated that they killed a total of 48 militants in Baghdad in the previous 24 hours, while three US Soldiers were killed in the fighting that day.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://icasualties.org/oif/prdDetails.aspx?hndRef%3D3-2008 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=30 March 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080403055622/http://icasualties.org/oif/prdDetails.aspx?hndRef=3-2008 |archivedate=3 April 2008 }}</ref>\n\n'''30 March''': U.S. forces killed at least 62 fighters in fighting across Baghdad. Another mortar strike, aimed at the Green Zone, killed at least seven Iraqis and wounded 21 when two rounds apparently fell short, striking houses in the commercial district of Karradah. Gunmen also attacked an Iraqi checkpoint in eastern Baghdad, killing six troops. An American soldier was killed by a roadside bomb just north of the city.<ref>[http://www.mnf-iraq.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=17936&Itemid=128 Multi-National Force \u2013 Iraq \u2013 Air weapons team engages, kills 12 criminals<!-- Bot generated title -->] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080403072437/http://www.mnf-iraq.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=17936&Itemid=128 |date=3 April 2008 }}</ref><ref>[http://www.mnf-iraq.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=17957&Itemid=128 Multi-National Force \u2013 Iraq \u2013 ISF, CF kill 8 criminals, detain 2 others in pursuit to secure streets of Baghdad<!-- Bot generated title -->] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080403072533/http://www.mnf-iraq.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=17957&Itemid=128 |date=3 April 2008 }}</ref><ref>[http://www.mnf-iraq.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=17950&Itemid=128 Multi-National Force \u2013 Iraq \u2013 MND-B Soldiers kill 8 criminals in separate operations<!-- Bot generated title -->] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080403031843/http://www.mnf-iraq.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=17950&Itemid=128 |date=3 April 2008 }}</ref><ref>[http://www.mnf-iraq.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=17937&Itemid=128 Multi-National Force \u2013 Iraq \u2013 MND-B Soldiers kill 2 during routine operation<!-- Bot generated title -->] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080403072520/http://www.mnf-iraq.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=17937&Itemid=128 |date=3 April 2008 }}</ref>\n\n'''31 March''': Mortars fell again on the Green Zone, however there were only sporadic sounds of gunfire in the city, a day after al-Sadr declared a new ceasefire. One U.S. soldier was killed on the outskirts of Sadr City by a roadside bomb. Just before the fighting stopped eight civilians were killed in Sadr City due to American shelling.<ref>[http://antiwar.com/updates/?articleid=12609 Monday: 2 US Soldiers, 50 Iraqis Killed; 45 Iraqis Wounded \u2013 Antiwar.com<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\n''' 1\u20135 April''': During this time a cease-fire was in effect in Baghdad which eased the violence in the capital. However this will not last.\n\n'''6 April \u2013 11 May''': A U.S. military raid in Sadr City provokes heavy street fighting in the district and most of eastern Baghdad which leads to the collapse of the cease-fire in the district. Two Iraqi Army armoured vehicles and two trucks are destroyed and one U.S. Stryker armoured personnel carrier is damaged on the first day of the street battles. U.S. Apache helicopter gunships swooped overhead during the battle. Militants shelled the Green Zone and other U.S. military bases around the capital. Unmanned Predator aircraft fired Hellfire missiles into Sadr City every day targeting the mortar and rocket teams. At least 941 people were killed. Among the dead were 22 U.S. and 17 Iraqi soldiers as well as 331 militants and 591 civilians. 100 U.S. soldiers and more than 1,700 civilians were wounded. 549 of the civilians were killed in Sadr City<ref>[http://antiwar.com/updates/?articleid=12733 Wednesday: 2 US Soldiers, 1 US Contractor, 59 Iraqis Killed; 114 Iraqis Wounded \u2013 Antiwar.com<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> while another 42 were killed in different parts of Baghdad by mortars, fired from Sadr City, which missed the Green Zone. The fighting mostly stopped early on 11 April, as U.S. and Iraqi forces managed to advance down the main road through Sadr City and set up a forward defence line inside the district. However, that night fighting continued as U.S. and Iraqi units were attacked with small-arms, machine guns and RPGs. Snipers and roadside bombs were also used against Coalition forces.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.cnn.com/2008/WORLD/meast/04/11/iraq.main/index.html | work=CNN | title=Iraqi, U.S. troops accused of Sadr City attack - CNN.com | date=11 April 2008 | accessdate=5 May 2010}}</ref><ref name=autogenerated2>[http://www.antiwar.com/ Antiwar.com<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\nOn 17 April, a heavy dust storm engulfed Baghdad and the militiamen used this to their advantage. Gunmen attacked the coalition frontlines under the cover of the storm and heavy fighting ensued. At one point an Iraqi company deserted their position at a police station and the militiamen moved in but U.S. forces moved in soon to fill in the gap in the line. Fighting continued throughout the night and new attacks were staged the next day as the storm continued and U.S. forces were not able to send in helicopters, planes or drones to assist. This day another company of Iraqi soldiers deserted their post after almost being overrun by militants. The fighting finally died down in the evening as the sand storm lifted. In the fighting on 17 and 18 April 17 Iraqi soldiers and 22 militiamen were killed along with a number of civilians.\n\nOn 28 April, another dust storm swept through Baghdad and the Mahdi Army once again attacked the blockades around Sadr City. In an effort to resupply troops conducting extended combat operations, soldiers from [[10th Mountain Division]] staged a 40-vehicle resupply convoy; however, Mahdi Army launched a devastating indirect fire attack against FOB Loyalty, killing four U.S. soldiers and injuring twenty others.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.longwarjournal.org/archives/2008/06/mahdi_army_uses_flyi.php}}</ref> In the ensuing fighting four more U.S. soldiers, 45 militants and eight civilians were killed.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/middle_east/7370659.stm | work=BBC News | title=US troops killed in Iraq clashes | date=28 April 2008 | accessdate=5 May 2010}}</ref>\n\nOn 29 April, U.S. forces in Stryker vehicles tried to push deeper into Sadr City but were met with stiff resistance from fighters using machine-guns and RPGs. After heavy fighting the troops withdrew to their start positions. 28 militants were killed, 6 U.S. soldiers were wounded, several U.S. military vehicles were damaged and three buildings used by militants were destroyed by American bombing during the battle.\n\nOn 3\u20134 May, an infantry company from the [[10th Mountain Division]] attempted to isolate the Mahdi Army along the eastern boundary of Sadr City by placing barriers along major intersections. This was an effort to facilitate the Iraqi Army's movement into Sadr City. The U.S. forces met with strong opposition as militants attacked the soldiers with heavy machine guns, RPGs, and IEDs. The unit suffered heavy damages to men, weapons, and equipment, but maintained pressure on the militia and controlled the grounds. Using [[close air support]], tanks, and armoured vehicles the soldiers defeated militia strongholds along the eastern sections of Sadr City.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.longwarjournal.org/archives/2008/07/battle_over_sadr_cit.php}}</ref>\n\nOn 8 May, the Iraqi government called on the residents of Sadr City to flee after more than 40 days of fighting, which left between 500\u20131,000 people dead. Due to the nearly constant violence, there are ongoing shortages of food, water, and other supplies.<ref>{{cite news|last=Fadel |first=Leila |title=Iraqi military orders Sadr City residents to evacuate |publisher=McClatchy Newspapers |date=8 May 2008 |url=http://www.mcclatchydc.com/iraq/story/36436.html |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081015010410/http://www.mcclatchydc.com/iraq/story/36436.html |archivedate=15 October 2008 }}</ref>\n\nOn 10 May, Iranian backed \"special groups\" fired a surface-to-air missile at a US helicopter gunship over Sadr City, the missile was reportedly fired from an unknown location in eastern Baghdad but missed the target, it was reported to be a type 7 SAM.<ref name=autogenerated1>[http://www.zeenews.com/articles.asp?aid=442786&sid=WOR Zee News \u2013 Clashes in Iraq's Sadr City<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\nOn 11 May, a cease-fire agreement was reached, but despite this some sporadic fighting still continued in Sadr city.\n\nDuring the latest round of fighting six Iraqi and three U.S. soldiers, six policemen, one U.S.-allied militiaman, 93 militiamen and 30 civilians were killed in clashes between the Mahdi Army and security forces in other parts of the capital.<ref>[http://www.mcclatchydc.com/212/story/33381.html McClatchy Washington Bureau | 04/11/2008 | Round-up of Daily Violence in Iraq, Friday April 11, 2008<!-- Bot generated title -->] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080529035636/http://www.mcclatchydc.com/212/story/33381.html |date=29 May 2008 }}</ref>\n\n'''Post-11 May:'''\n\n12 May: Overnight clashes in Sadr city continued despite the cease-fire, the clashes killed 3 militiamen and 2 civilians and wounded 24 people. US military Spokesman Rear Adm Patrick Driscoll warned that a truce had not yet been brokered and that the Iraqi government and Shiite representatives were still talking, Sadrist lawmaker Nasar al-Rubaie said: said talks on final touches to the agreement were continuing. In fighting elsewhere in the capital 12 gunmen were killed.<ref name=autogenerated3>[http://www.zeenews.com/articles.asp?aid=442567&sid=WOR Zee News \u2013 Sadr city<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\n13 May: Clashes between security forces and Shi'ite gunmen killed 2 Iraqi soldiers, 11 militiamen and 12 civilians and wounded 28 people in Baghdad overnight. One of those killed was a seven-year-old who died after an Iraqi army vehicle ran over him. Fighting also erupted in Baghdad's Shula district, another Mahdi Army stronghold{{Vague|date=December 2008}}. Also, one U.S. soldier was killed in a roadside bombing in a northwestern part of Baghdad.<ref name=autogenerated1 />\n\n14 May: In overnight clashes five people were killed in Sadr City. Also, two militiamen were killed while planting a bomb during house-to-house searches in the area.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/middle_east/7401634.stm | work=BBC News | title=Bombing at Iraq funeral kills 20 | date=14 May 2008 | accessdate=5 May 2010}}</ref>\n\n15 May: In overnight clashes in Baghdad's Sadr City slum 7 people were killed and 19 were wounded. Two militiamen were also killed.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.reuters.com/article/worldNews/idUSL0439231320080515 | work=Reuters | title=Seven die in clashes in Baghdad's Sadr City | first=Aseel | last=Kami | date=15 May 2008}}</ref>\n\n187 dumped bodies were found during the fighting throughout Baghdad since 23 March, all apparent victims of sectarian violence.<ref name=autogenerated2 />\n\n===Al Kut fighting===\nIn the city of [[Kut|Al Kut]], the capital of [[Wasit Governorate]], militants went out in the streets in force on 25 March, and took control of 5 out of 18 districts of the city.\n\nHeavy street fighting took place on 26 March, and mortar impacts resounded leaving buildings and cars aflame. Another three districts fell into the hands of the militants for a total of eight. 35 people were reported killed, including a baby. 15 of those were killed when a mortar barrage struck homes amid the clashes.<ref>[http://www.cnn.com/2008/WORLD/meast/03/26/iraq.main/index.html More than 100 dead in two days of Iraq fighting | CNN]</ref> The security forces stated that six Iraqi soldiers and policemen died while 11 militants were killed in a combined US Special Forces-Iraqi SWAT patrol.<ref name=\"mcclatchydc-227\">[http://www.mcclatchydc.com/227/story/31662.html McClatchy Washington Bureau | 03/26/2008 | Clashes spread as U.S., Iraqi forces attack Shiite militia<!-- Bot generated title -->] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080528191600/http://www.mcclatchydc.com/227/story/31662.html |date=28 May 2008 }}</ref><ref>[http://www.mnf-iraq.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=17886&Itemid=21 Iraqi Security Forces, U.S. Special Forces engage criminal elements in Hillah, al-Kut] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120214002615/http://www.mnf-iraq.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=17886&Itemid=21 |date=14 February 2012 }} MNF-I</ref>\n\nAlso at least two policemen and one civilian were killed and another eight or ten policemen were wounded in fighting in the town of Aziziya just north of Al Kut.<ref>[http://www.alertnet.org/thenews/newsdesk/L2558442.htm FACTBOX-Security developments in Iraq, March 25 \u2013 Reuters Alertnet]</ref>\n\n49 people were killed and 75 wounded in Al Kut by 27 March.\n\nAnother four policemen and two civilians were killed in the next two days.<ref name = \"wiredispatch_Mar28\"/><ref>[http://wiredispatch.com/news/?id=106674 FACTBOX-Security developments in Iraq, March 29<!-- Bot generated title -->] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080402100256/http://wiredispatch.com/news/?id=106674 |date=2 April 2008 }}</ref>\n\n400 policemen deserted or defected during the fighting in Al Kut.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.yahoo.com/s/ap/20080413/ap_on_re_mi_ea/iraq |title=Archived copy |accessdate=13 April 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080414211801/http://news.yahoo.com/s/ap/20080413/ap_on_re_mi_ea/iraq |archivedate=14 April 2008 }}</ref>\n\nOn 26 April, a raid was conducted in the city in which one Iraqi soldier was killed.\n\n===Hilla clashes===\nFighting was also happening in [[Hilla]], the capital of [[Babil province]], where two people were killed on 25 March.\n\nOn 26 March, U.S. forces conducted air strikes in support of Hillah's Iraqi [[SWAT]] unit during fighting with Shi'ite militia in the Thawra neighbourhood. Iraqi police sources estimate the casualties at between 11 and 29 people dead and 18 and 39 wounded. At least 19 of the dead were confirmed to be militiamen.<ref>[https://abcnews.go.com/US/wireStory?id=4529879 Many killed by U.S. strike in Iraq's Hilla: sources | ABC News]</ref> 9 Iraqi SWAT members were killed and two wounded during the battle.<ref>[http://www.mnf-iraq.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=17886&Itemid=21 Iraqi Security Forces, U.S. Special Forces engage criminal elements in Hillah, al-Kut] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120214002615/http://www.mnf-iraq.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=17886&Itemid=21 |date=14 February 2012 }} \u2013 MNF-I</ref>\n\nThe next day heavy street battles continued in Hilla, most of them in the city center, with at least one soldier and five policemen killed and another 26 members of the security forces being wounded. The offices of the al-Da'wa Party and the Supreme Council were destroyed by militants.<ref>Juan Cole \u2013 [http://www.indybay.org/newsitems/2008/03/28/18489102.php \u2013  Mahdi Army Stands Firm in its Basra Neighborhoods.Demonstrations in Baghdad against al-Maliki] \u2013 Indybay.org</ref>\n\nThe toll in two days of fighting in Hilla was at least 60 dead.<ref name = \"mcclatchydc-212\"/>\n\nOn 29 March, a police source in Babil province reported that since the fighting began on 25 March 85 militiamen have been captured in the province. He also said a large number of gunmen had been killed.<ref>[http://www.aswataliraq.info/look/english/article.tpl?IdLanguage=1&IdPublication=4&NrArticle=74643&NrIssue=2&NrSection=1  12 killed, 42 wounded in Hilla clashes \u2013 source] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080402095219/http://www.aswataliraq.info/look/english/article.tpl?IdLanguage=1&IdPublication=4&NrArticle=74643&NrIssue=2&NrSection=1 |date=2 April 2008 }} \u2013 Aswat Aliraq</ref>\n\nOn 3 April, U.S. soldiers, in civilian clothes, clashed with Mahdi Army fighters during an attempted raid to arrest rogue elements in the Mehdi Army. Later Iraqi police joined the fight and five people, including four policemen were killed.<ref name=autogenerated4 />\n\nOn 4 April, a roadside bomb killed four policemen and injured one other.\n\nOn 5 April, the body of a police commando was found in the city, he was shot dead. Police killed one gunman and arrested two others when they tried to assassinate a local police chief in the town of Hamza al-Gharbi, south of Hilla.\n\nOn 25 April, a man was shot dead in the city. Six people were arrested in connection to the killing.\n\n===Other clashes===\nIn response to the fighting the political movement of powerful [[Shia Islam|Shiite]] cleric [[Muqtada al-Sadr]] launched a nationwide civil disobedience campaign across [[Iraq]] to protest the raids and detentions against the [[Mahdi Army]].<ref>[http://edition.cnn.com/2008/WORLD/meast/03/25/iraq.main/index.html Iraqi raids anger Shiite militia | CNN]</ref>\n\n'''[[Diwaniyah]]''': On 26 March, seven Iraqi soldiers, a policeman and two militants were killed and another seven militants were captured and seven policemen wounded. On 27 March, one gunman was killed and a policeman was wounded in a security operation that netted eight suspects. The next day militia fighters killed the top administrator in a village near Diwaniyah.<ref name=autogenerated6>[http://www.mcclatchydc.com/227/story/31662.html Clashes spread as U.S., Iraqi forces attack Shiite militia \u2013 McClatchy Washington Bureau] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080528191600/http://www.mcclatchydc.com/227/story/31662.html |date=28 May 2008 }}</ref><ref>[http://www.alertnet.org/thenews/newsdesk/L26327762.htm FACTBOX-Security developments in Iraq, March 26 \u2013 Reuters Alertnet]</ref>\n\nOn 29 March 200 local residents held a demonstration in support of the Iraqi operations in Basrah.<ref>[https://archive.is/20120714024110/http://news.yahoo.com/nphotos/Iraq/ss/events/ts/082701iraqplane/im:/080329/photos_wl/2008_03_29t121213_450x355_us_iraq/ Demonstrators chant slogans during a protest in Diwaniya] \u2013 Reuters via Yahoo News</ref>\n\nOn 27 April, gunmen killed a police officer outside his home.\n\n'''[[Najaf]]''': Four mortars landed in different parts of Najaf on 26 March, and sporadic fighting throughout the city left two policemen wounded. A few days later a roadside bomb killed one army officer and wounded two soldiers when it struck their vehicle in northern Najaf.<ref>[http://www.mcclatchydc.com/212/story/31661.html Round-up of Daily Violence in Iraq \u2013 Wednesday March 26, 2008 | McClatchy Washington Bureau] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080331230422/http://www.mcclatchydc.com/212/story/31661.html |date=31 March 2008 }}</ref>\n\nOn 11 April, gunmen killed a senior aide to Muqtada al-Sadr, Riyadh al-Nouri. He was the director of al-Sadr's office in Najaf.\n\nOn 21 April, an al-Sistani aide was killed in the city.\n\n'''[[Amarah]]''': In Amara, capital of [[Maysan Governorate]], two soldiers were killed by unknown gunmen. Two civilians died in clashes on the Yugoslav Bridge in northern Amara. Gunmen attacked the Badr Organization Bureau located in Hitteen Square, in the centre of Amara, using RPGs.<ref name = \"mcclatchydc-212\"/><ref>[http://www.antiwar.com/updates/?articleid=12586 Wednesday: 2 GIs, 1 British Soldier, 76 Iraqis Killed; 367 Iraqis Wounded \u2013 Antiwar.com]</ref>\n\n'''[[Nasiriyah]]''': Two Iraqi soldiers were killed near Nasiriyah as they were heading to reinforce the attack on Basra. On 28 March 2008, Sadrist forces had taken control of the center of [[Nasiriyah]]. In heavy street fighting 5 policemen, 10 militants and 20 civilians were killed. Another 52 people were wounded, including 19 policemen, 26 civilians and 7 gunmen. Another 13 militants were captured. The Mahdi Army had also taken control of the town of Shatra, 40 kilometres north of Nasiriyah.<ref>[https://www.reuters.com/article/homepageCrisis/idUSL2799267._CH_.2400 Shi'ite fighters seize centre of Nassiriya \u2013 Reuters]</ref>\n<ref>[http://www.aswataliraq.info/look/english/article.tpl?IdLanguage=1&IdPublication=4&NrArticle=74588&NrIssue=2&NrSection=1 30 killed, 52 wounded in Nassiriya until Friday night \u2013 Aswat Aliraq] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080402083026/http://www.aswataliraq.info/look/english/article.tpl?IdLanguage=1&IdPublication=4&NrArticle=74588&NrIssue=2&NrSection=1 |date=2 April 2008 }}</ref>\n\nOn 29 March, the city was back under the control of Iraqi security forces, according to a provincial police spokesman.<ref>[http://www.aswataliraq.info/look/english/article.tpl?IdLanguage=1&IdPublication=4&NrArticle=74588&NrIssue=2&NrSection=1  30 killed, 52 wounded in Nassiriya until Friday night] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080402083026/http://www.aswataliraq.info/look/english/article.tpl?IdLanguage=1&IdPublication=4&NrArticle=74588&NrIssue=2&NrSection=1 |date=2 April 2008 }} \u2013 Aswat Aliraq</ref>\n\nOn 19 April, a large firefight broke out in the village of Suq al-Shiyoukh, near Nasiriyah, which left 40 militiamen, 4 policemen and one civilian dead, another 37 militiamen were captured and 19 policemen were wounded.\n\nOn 13 May, one woman was killed in a mortar attack in the city.<ref>[http://antiwar.com/updates/?articleid=12832 Tuesday: 1 US Soldier, 36 Iraqis Killed; 73 Iraqis Wounded \u2013 Antiwar.com<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\n'''[[Mahmoudiyah, Iraq|Mahmoudiya]]''': At least 12 militia fighters were killed and seven others wounded in fighting in Mahmoudiya, {{convert|20|mi|km}} south of the capital. Some 15 Iraqi soldiers were reported to be captured. Four civilians were killed in the crossfire.\n\n'''[[Karbala]]''': In fighting in the holy city of Kerbala on 28 March 21 militants and 2 policemen were killed.<ref name = \"wiredispatch_Mar28\"/><ref>[http://today.reuters.com/news/articlenews.aspx?type=topNews&storyID=2008-03-29T121357Z_01_L24231863_RTRUKOC_0_US-IRAQ.xml&pageNumber=2&imageid=&cap=&sz=13&WTModLoc=NewsArt-C1-ArticlePage2-Death toll rises in Baghdad fighting, March 29 \u2013 Reuters] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080403084603/http://today.reuters.com/news/articlenews.aspx?type=topNews&storyID=2008-03-29T121357Z_01_L24231863_RTRUKOC_0_US-IRAQ.xml&pageNumber=2&imageid=&cap=&sz=13&WTModLoc=NewsArt-C1-ArticlePage2-Death |date=3 April 2008 }}</ref><ref>[http://www.aswataliraq.info/look/english/article.tpl?IdLanguage=1&IdPublication=4&NrArticle=74672&NrIssue=2&NrSection=1 Aswat Aliraq<!-- Bot generated title -->] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080402095232/http://www.aswataliraq.info/look/english/article.tpl?IdLanguage=1&IdPublication=4&NrArticle=74672&NrIssue=2&NrSection=1 |date=2 April 2008 }}</ref>\nOn Friday night, Iraqi forces launched a major operation targeting Mahdi Army networks in Karbala. 12 militiamen were killed and 50 wounded. 30 gunmen surrendered to police on Thursday to benefit from the Iraqi prime minister's pardon. On Saturday  an Egyptian in command of fighters in Karbala surrendered to police, along with 6 members of his group.<ref>[http://www.aswataliraq.info/look/english/article.tpl?IdLanguage=1&IdPublication=4&NrArticle=74628&NrIssue=2&NrSection=1  Egyptian leader of armed group surrenders in Karbala] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080402095214/http://www.aswataliraq.info/look/english/article.tpl?IdLanguage=1&IdPublication=4&NrArticle=74628&NrIssue=2&NrSection=1 |date=2 April 2008 }} \u2013 Aswat Aliraq</ref>\n\n'''[[Hamza, Iraq|Hamza]]''': Clashes with the Mahdi Army on 27 March, left three policemen dead in Hamza. Another officer was wounded along with two Iraqi soldiers.<ref name = \"antiwar_12591\">[http://www.antiwar.com/updates/?articleid=12591 Thursday: 225 Iraqis, 1 US Soldier, 3 US Contractors Killed; 538 Iraqis Wounded \u2013 Antiwar.com]</ref> The next day another six policemen were killed. On 30 March, police forces supported by aircraft launched a large-scale attack killing four gunmen and arresting 30.<ref>[http://www.antiwar.com/updates/?articleid=12599 Friday: 1 US Soldier, 163 Iraqis Killed; 214 Iraqis Wounded \u2013 Antiwar.com<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref><ref>[http://www.aswataliraq.info/look/english/article.tpl?IdLanguage=1&IdPublication=4&NrArticle=74725&NrIssue=2&NrSection=1 Aswat Aliraq<!-- Bot generated title -->] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080402095242/http://www.aswataliraq.info/look/english/article.tpl?IdLanguage=1&IdPublication=4&NrArticle=74725&NrIssue=2&NrSection=1 |date=2 April 2008 }}</ref>\n\n'''[[Suwayrah]]''': In clashes Iraqi Army scouts and U.S. Special Forces soldiers killed 13 militants and destroyed two cargo trucks. Another three were killed the next day.<ref>[http://www.mnf-iraq.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=17918&Itemid=21 Multi-National Force \u2013 Iraq \u2013 Iraqi Army, U.S. Special Forces patrol attacked; 13 criminal fighters killed (Suwayrah)<!-- Bot generated title -->] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080403072428/http://www.mnf-iraq.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=17918&Itemid=21 |date=3 April 2008 }}</ref><ref>[http://www.iht.com/articles/ap/2008/03/30/africa/ME-GEN-Iraq.php Shiite cleric Sadr pulls fighters off streets \u2013 International Herald Tribune<!-- Bot generated title -->] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080907024620/http://www.iht.com/articles/ap/2008/03/30/africa/ME-GEN-Iraq.php |date=7 September 2008 }}</ref>\n\n'''Nationwide''': A roadside bomb in al-Kafl, which is just south of Hilla, left three policemen dead and another four wounded.<ref name = \"antiwar_12591\"/> A roadside bomb killed four policemen and wounded four more in Mahaweel, south of Baghdad.<ref>[http://wiredispatch.com/news/?id=103111 FACTBOX-Security developments in Iraq, March 27 \u2013 Reuters] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080401063741/http://wiredispatch.com/news/?id=103111 |date=1 April 2008 }}</ref>  An Army Colonel was killed in clashes with Mehdi Army fighters in Numaniya, {{convert|72|mi|km}} south of Baghdad.<ref>[http://www.alertnet.org/thenews/newsdesk/ANW848978.htm Reuters AlertNet \u2013 FACTBOX-Security developments in Iraq, March 28<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> Militiamen attacked the village of Al Daoum, south-east of Karbala, killing five people, kidnapping six others and destroying four houses in retaliation against the families of Iraqi soldiers.<ref>[http://www.mcclatchydc.com/212/story/33729.html McClatchy Washington Bureau | 04/15/2008 | Round-up of Daily Violence in Iraq \u2013 Tuesday April 15, 2008<!-- Bot generated title -->] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081204182530/http://www.mcclatchydc.com/212/story/33729.html |date=4 December 2008 }}</ref> In another attack on a village near Karbala five people were killed and two were wounded, around 150 people were forced to flee and fourteen homes were destroyed.<ref>[http://antiwar.com/updates/?articleid=12714 Saturday: 2 US Soldiers, 95 Iraqis Killed; 185 Iraqis Wounded \u2013 Antiwar.com<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> On 21 April, the Iraqi Army reported to have killed 30 militants over the course of the previous 24 hours, in one of those clashes south of Baghdad six police officers were killed also.<ref>[http://wiredispatch.com/news/?id=136593 FACTBOX-Security developments in Iraq, April 21<!-- Bot generated title -->]{{dead link|date=May 2016}}</ref> In the town of Hussaniyah, north of Baghdad, on 22 April, an Iraqi Army patrol, accompanied by U.S. Special Forces members, was attacked by militiamen, and in the ensuing firefight nine militiamen were killed. An Iraqi army officer was killed during an armed attack near his home in Numaniya on 7 May.<ref>[http://www.mnf-iraq.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=18730&Itemid=128 Multi-National Force \u2013 Iraq \u2013 Iraqi Army Forces kill nine criminals, destroy two vehicles in Hussaniyah<!-- Bot generated title -->] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080515171421/http://www.mnf-iraq.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=18730&Itemid=128 |date=15 May 2008 }}</ref>\n\n===11 May 2008: cease-fire===\nShiite militants reached an agreement with the Iraqi government to end fighting in Baghdad's Sadr City district, a spokesman for Muqtada al-Sadr reported.<ref>[http://www2.irna.ir/en/news/view/menu-234/0805111112010754.htm Iraqi government, al-Mahdi Army agree to a cease-fire (Updates) \u2013 Irna<!-- Bot generated title -->] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120210103217/http://www2.irna.ir/en/news/view/menu-234/0805111112010754.htm |date=10 February 2012 }}</ref><ref>[http://www.presstv.com/detail.aspx?id=55052&sectionid=351020201 Press TV \u2013 Iraqi gov't, Sadrists reach agreement<!-- Bot generated title -->] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110725182652/http://www.presstv.com/detail.aspx?id=55052&sectionid=351020201 |date=25 July 2011 }}</ref> The Iraqi government confirmed that.<ref>[http://www.alertnet.org/thenews/newsdesk/L10494319.htm Reuters AlertNet \u2013 Iraqi govt confirms ceasefire with Sadr movement<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\nHowever, despite the cease-fire, sporadic fighting still continued until 15 May.<ref name=autogenerated1 /><ref name=autogenerated3 /><ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.reuters.com/article/worldNews/idUSL0434078820080512 | work=Reuters | title=Iraqi PM says crackdown shows he's not sectarian | date=12 May 2008}}</ref>\n\n==Aftermath==\nFollowing the first cease-fire at the end of March, the campaign had reached a stalemate between the two sides. However, by all accounts the Iraqi Army had a mixed performance during the clashes. Somewhere between 1,500 and 2,000 members of the Iraqi security forces out of 30,000 troops used in Basra deserted, defected or surrendered during the fighting.<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/2008/04/04/world/middleeast/04iraq.html?_r=1&ex=1364961600&en=3412ef4c4ed63d7c&ei=5090&partner=rssuserland&emc=rss&pagewanted=all&oref=slogin More Than 1,000 in Iraq's Forces Quit Basra Fight, April 4 | The New York Times]</ref> Basra was mostly under Iraqi Government control (70%). In Sadr City the Mahdi Army came to an agreement with Iraqi security forces to keep weapons off the streets and allow patrols of Iraqi Army convoys, and to give them the right to allow the arrest of members of their forces.\n\nFollowing the fighting the Maliki government allegedly agreed to [[concession (politics)|political concessions]] for a cease-fire, including legal and military immunity for the Mahdi Army and a release of its captured members, although Maliki denies any concessions were made.<ref name=\"CNN-Maliki-040708\"/> Many analysts said the Mahdi Army had scored a major political victory, which also presented the fighting capabilities of the militia that were, despite a lack of heavier weapons, far greater than those of the Iraqi security forces.{{Citation needed|date=April 2008}} However, this has apparently been objected to by the Maliki Government, since it continued its operations against Mahdi Army strongholds in Sadr City and Basrah.\n\nThe Mahdi Army stated that it will only disarm if the Shiite Clergy agree with Maliki's aims.\n\nIn light of the battle with the Mahdi army, there has been consensus from Kurdish, Sunni and the Shia political parties not aligned with Sadrists to support Prime Minister Maliki's efforts to impose Government authority in the south, even showing support to revoking the right of any political party to be represented in the October provincial elections if they continue to operate militias outside of Iraqi law.<ref>[https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=89231774&ft=1&f=1001 Fighting Calms in Iraq amid Mahdi Army Cease-Fire : NPR<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.reuters.com/article/homepageCrisis/idUSCOL144127._CH_.2400 | work=Reuters | title=ANALYSIS-Iraqi crackdown backfires, strengthens Sadrists | first=Randy | last=Fabi | date=31 March 2008}}</ref><ref>[http://www.mcclatchydc.com/iraq/story/32187.html McClatchy Washington Bureau | 03/31/2008 | With calm restored in Basra, Iraqis ask 'Who won?'<!-- Bot generated title -->] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080405212953/http://www.mcclatchydc.com/iraq/story/32187.html |date=5 April 2008 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/world/iraq/article3701511.ece | work=The Times | location=London | title=Iraq AlMahdi army offers to lay down its arms | first=James | last=Hider | date=8 April 2008 | accessdate=5 May 2010}}</ref>\n\nBy early May the fighting was centered mostly on Sadr City in Baghdad and Basra was reportedly under government control.{{Citation needed|date=May 2008}}\n\nSome 5,000 fighters belonging to the [[Special Groups (Iraq)|Special Groups]] fled across the border into Iran during the offensive and after the cease-fire.<ref>[https://www.rand.org/pubs/monographs/2010/RAND_MG911.pdf page 45]</ref>\n\n==See also==\n\n*[[Battle of Basra (2008)]]\n*[[Civil war in Iraq (2006-07)|Civil war in Iraq]]\n*[[Iraq Spring Fighting of 2004]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/middle-east/the-man-left-to-pick-up-the-p.htmls-in-basra-401617.html Article about General Mohan from the UK newspaper ''Independent'']\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Spring Fighting Of 2008}}\n[[Category:Military operations of the Iraq War]]\n[[Category:Military operations of the Iraq War involving the United States]]\n[[Category:Military operations of the Iraq War involving Iraq]]\n[[Category:2008 in Iraq]]\n[[Category:March 2008 events in Asia]]\n[[Category:April 2008 events in Asia]]\n[[Category:May 2008 events in Asia]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2016}}\n{{Infobox military conflict\n|conflict=Iraq Spring Fighting of 2008\n|partof=the [[Iraq War]]\n|image=Iraq 2008 fighting.png\n|image_size=300px\n|caption=Major flashpoints of the fighting\n|date=25 March \u2013 15 May 2008<br>({{Age in months, weeks and days|month1=03|day1=25|year1=2008|month2=05|day2=15|year2=2008|}})\n|place= [[Iraq]]\n|result=Ceasefire,<ref>{{cite news| url=http://edition.cnn.com/2008/WORLD/meast/05/10/iraq.main/index.html | work=CNN | title=Cease-fire reached in Baghdad's Sadr City - CNN.com | date=11 May 2008 | accessdate=5 May 2010}}</ref> Strategic ISF victory\n*Iraqi forces gain control of [[Sadr City]]\n*Iraqi forces launch further operations in [[Maysan Governorate]]\n*Eventual disarmament of Mahdi Army\n|combatant1={{flagicon|Iraq}} [[Iraqi Army]]<br />\n{{flag|United States}}<br />\n{{flagicon|Iraq}} [[Awakening movements in Iraq|Awakening Councils]]<br />\n{{Flagicon image|Badr Organisation Military flag.svg}} [[Badr Brigades]]\n|combatant2={{Flagicon image|Flag of Promised Day Brigades.svg}} [[Mahdi Army]]<br />\n{{flagicon image|Shiism_arabic_blue.PNG}} [[Special Groups (Iraq)|Special Groups]]<br />\n{{flagicon image|<!-- [[WP:NFCC]] violation: Islamic Virtue Party.svg -->}} [[Fadhila|Fadhila Militia]]<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/03/26/world/middleeast/26iraq.html?pagewanted=1&_r=1 | work=The New York Times | title=Iraqi Crackdown on Shiite Forces Sets Off Fighting | first1=Michael | last1=Kamber | first2=James | last2=Glanz | date=26 March 2008}}</ref><br />\n|commander1={{flagicon|Iraq}} [[Nouri al-Maliki]]<br />\n{{flagicon|Iraq}} [[Mohan al-Furayji]]<br />\n{{flagicon|United States}} [[David Petraeus]]<br />\n{{Flagicon image|Badr Organisation Military flag.svg}} [[Hadi al-Amiri]]\n|commander2={{Flagicon image|Flag of Promised Day Brigades.svg}} [[Muqtada al-Sadr]]<br />\n{{flagicon image|Shiism_arabic_blue.PNG}} [[Akran Hasnawi]]{{KIA}}<br />\n{{flagicon image|Shiism_arabic_blue.PNG}} [[Akram al-Kabi]]{{citation needed|date=July 2018}}<br />\n|strength1=400,000\n|strength2=60,000\n|casualties1=191 killed;<br />2,100 deserted, defected or captured<ref>{{cite news| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/middle_east/7336386.stm | work=BBC News | title='Turncoat' Basra police pursued | date=8 April 2008 | accessdate=5 May 2010}}</ref><br />(Iraqi security forces)<br />35 killed (U.S. forces)<ref>[http://www.icasualties.org/oif/prdDetails.aspx?hndRef=3-2008 Period Details<!-- Bot generated title -->] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080323131834/http://www.icasualties.org/oif/prdDetails.aspx?hndRef=3-2008 |date=23 March 2008 }}</ref><ref>[http://www.icasualties.org/oif/prdDetails.aspx?hndRef=4-2008 Period Details<!-- Bot generated title -->] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080501033612/http://www.icasualties.org/oif/prdDetails.aspx?hndRef=4-2008 |date=1 May 2008 }}</ref><ref>[http://www.icasualties.org/oif/prdDetails.aspx?hndRef=5-2008 Period Details<!-- Bot generated title -->] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080505045349/http://www.icasualties.org/oif/prdDetails.aspx?hndRef=5-2008 |date=5 May 2008 }}</ref><br />1 killed (Iraqi militia)<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.usatoday.com/news/world/iraq/2008-04-10-iraqnews_N.htm | work=USA Today | title=Sunnis form militias to counter those of Shiites | first=Charles | last=Levinson | date=11 April 2008 | accessdate=5 May 2010}}</ref><br />4 killed (Islamic Dawa Party)\n|casualties2=700 killed (US Claim)<ref>[[New York Times]] [https://www.nytimes.com/2008/05/21/world/middleeast/21sadr.html?_r=2&hp=&oref=login&pagewanted=print Operation in Sadr City Is an Iraqi Success, So Far]</ref><br />2,000+ killed (Iraqi claim)<ref>[http://www.iraqupdates.com/p_articles.php/article/32980 Mahdi Army 'going underground'] \u2013 Iraq Updates</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.longwarjournal.org/archives/2008/06/mahdi_army_decimated.php|title=Mahdi Army decimated during recent fighting|publisher=Long War Journal|date=26 June 2008|accessdate=8 December 2008|first=Bill|last=Roggio|quote=More than 1,000 Mahdi Army fighters were killed in Sadr City alone, according to a Mahdi Army commander in Baghdad. Another 415 were killed in Basrah. More than 400 were killed during fighting in the southern cities of Najaf, Karbala, Hillah, Diwaniyah, Amarah, Samawah, and Nasiriyah in late March and early April, according to numbers compiled by The Long War Journal.}}</ref>\n|casualties3=1,112 Iraqi civilians killed,<br/>2 U.S. and 2 Indian civilians killed\n}}\n{{Campaignbox Iraq War}}\nThe '''Iraq Spring Fighting of 2008''' (March \u2013 May 2008) was a series of clashes between the [[Mahdi Army]] and the [[Iraqi Army]] supported by coalition forces, in southern [[Iraq]] and [[Baghdad]], that began with an Iraqi [[Battle of Basra (2008)|offensive in Basra]]. The fighting followed a lull in the [[Civil war in Iraq (2006-07)|Civil war in Iraq]] and was the most serious crisis since October 2007.\n\n==Background==\nIn 2007, the Iraqi Army moved 4 [[brigade]]s, including a [[tank]] brigade, and a [[special forces]] battalion to [[Basra]], replacing the existing brigade stationed there which was reported to have been corrupt.<ref>[http://www.longwarjournal.org/archives/2007/12/basrah_the_untold_st.php Basrah: Missing the Iraqi Security Force Deployment \u2013 Long War Journal]</ref> The Iraqi National Police also moved two battalions to Basra. In August 2007, the Iraqi Army established the [[Iraqi Army#Structure|Basra Operational Command]] under the command of [[Mohan al-Furayji|General Mohan]]. The Vice Chief of Staff of the Iraqi Joint Staff said \"We do not have enough forces there. That is why we are having a new division, the 14th Division, to be built in Basrah, especially with the possibility that the British might be leaving us in time.\"<ref>[http://www.longwarjournal.org/archives/2007/09/iraqi_security_force_2.php Iraqi Security Forces Order of Battle: September 2007 Update \u2013 Long War Journal]</ref>\n\nSince August 2007, a unilateral ceasefire was in place, imposed by [[Muqtada al-Sadr]] on his militia, the [[Mahdi Army]]. However raids were continuing on so-called \"rogue\" elements of the militia and tensions were building. In February, Sadr extended the ceasefire even though many of his commanders were against it. Despite the extension raids continued and members of the militia accused the members of the security forces of being infiltrated by their rival militia, the [[Badr Organization|Badr Brigade]].\n\n==The Campaign==\nOn 23 March, Easter Sunday [[Iran]]ian trained militants of the Mahdi Army fired 107mm rockets on the heavily fortified [[Green Zone]] in [[Baghdad]] killing Paul Converse, a U.S. government employee, and wounding several other employees and contractors.<ref>[https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2008/04/07/AR2008040702533.html]</ref> At least 12 Iraqi civilians were also killed by rockets from Sadr City that missed the Green Zone and hit the civilian sectors around the Zone.<ref>[http://antiwar.com/updates/?articleid=12569 Sunday: 4 US Soldiers, 91 Iraqis Killed; 152 Wounded \u2013 Antiwar.com]</ref>\n\n===Basra operation===\n{{Main|Battle of Basra (2008)}}\nOn 25 March, the Iraqi Army and police attacked the second largest Iraqi city, Basra, which had for the most part been under Mahdi Army control for the past seven months since the [[Siege of U.K. bases in Basra|British troop withdrawal]] from the city in the beginning of September the previous year. Since then the city was in the middle of a turf war between three different militias, including the Mahdi Army, for the control of the [[oil]] exports which had been dominated by the Black Market.\n\nStreet fighting spread through six neighbourhoods after the government operation started at 2:00am. Plumes of smoke were seen over the northern neighbourhoods, and by the end of the first day of fighting government forces took the center of the city but the Mahdi Army was still holding on to the northern part of the city.{{Citation needed|date=March 2008}}\n\nOn 26 March, the [[Iraqi Prime Minister]] issued an ultimatum to the Mahdi Army to surrender within 72 hours.{{Citation needed|date=March 2008}}\n\nOn 28 March, U.S. aircraft bombed two targets in the city while being supported by British planes, a day after militiamen paraded in the city with some 20 captured soldiers and a captured Iraqi Army [[Humvee]]. At least two Iraqi Army armoured vehicles and a [[BMP-1|BMP infantry fighting vehicle]] were seen destroyed on the streets.\n<!-- Deleted image removed: [[File:Mahdi Army fighters take up positions during the street fighting in Basra.jpg|225px|left|thumb|Mahdi Army fighters take up positions during the street fighting in Basra 26 March 2008.]] -->\nBy 29 March, the Iraqi military offensive against the city was faltering in the face of stiff resistance as the 72-hour ultimatum by the government passed and the militants refused to surrender.\n\nOn 31 March, the fighting in the city ended after al-Sadr's declaration of a new cease-fire. By that point the Mahdi Army was still in control of about 75% of the city.\n\nUp to 236 people were killed and 1,200 wounded in the fighting in districts of central and northern Basra. 921 members of the security forces, including 421 policemen and a full Iraqi Army battalion of 500 men, deserted, defected or were captured.\n\nClashes between militiamen and al-Maliki's tribe in [[Qurna, Iraq|Qurna]], north of Basra, left 7 dead, including a policeman and a civilian, and 2 wounded on both sides.<ref>[http://www.mcclatchydc.com/212/story/31877.html Round-up of Daily Violence in Iraq, Friday March 28, 2008 McClatchy Washington Bureau] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080402181527/http://www.mcclatchydc.com/212/story/31877.html |date=2 April 2008 }}</ref>\n<ref>[http://www.aswataliraq.info/look/english/article.tpl?IdLanguage=1&IdPublication=4&NrArticle=74543&NrIssue=2&NrSection=1 5 killed, 2 wounded in clashes in Basra \u2013 Aswat Aliraq] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080402095205/http://www.aswataliraq.info/look/english/article.tpl?IdLanguage=1&IdPublication=4&NrArticle=74543&NrIssue=2&NrSection=1 |date=2 April 2008 }}</ref>\n<ref>[http://www.aswataliraq.info/look/english/article.tpl?IdLanguage=1&IdPublication=4&NrArticle=73950&NrIssue=2&NrSection=1 Civilian killed, policeman wounded in clashes in Basra \u2013 Aswat Aliraq] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080402095201/http://www.aswataliraq.info/look/english/article.tpl?IdLanguage=1&IdPublication=4&NrArticle=73950&NrIssue=2&NrSection=1 |date=2 April 2008 }}</ref>\n\nMortars also killed two policemen and wounded 23 people, including 13 policemen, in [[Karma, Iraq|Karma]], a town {{convert|50|mi|km}} north of Basra.<ref>[http://wiredispatch.com/news/?id=105058 FACTBOX-Security developments in Iraq, March 28 \u2013 Reuters] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080402100251/http://wiredispatch.com/news/?id=105058 |date=2 April 2008 }}</ref>\n\nFollowing the cease-fire in Basra there were still sporadic clashes in the city for some time leaving at least 32 civilians, 34 militants, five policemen and one U.S. Marine dead. Among the dead was also police Major Ali Haider, a commander in the police department's serious crimes directorate.<ref name=autogenerated4>{{cite news| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/middle_east/7327926.stm | work=BBC News | title=Air strike levels house in Basra | date=3 April 2008 | accessdate=5 May 2010}}</ref><ref>[http://www.mnf-iraq.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=18253&Itemid=128 Multi-National Force \u2013 Iraq \u2013 ISF recover weapons cache, kill 10 in separate operations in Basra<!-- Bot generated title -->] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080408200956/http://www.mnf-iraq.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=18253&Itemid=128 |date=8 April 2008 }}</ref><ref>[http://www.kuna.net.kw/NewsAgenciesPublicSite/ArticleDetails.aspx?id=1897387&Language=en \u0643\u0648\u0646\u0627 : Eight persons killed in fiery blast in Basra \u2013 \u0627\u0644\u062f\u0641\u0627\u0639 \u0648\u0627\u0644\u0623\u0645\u0646 \u2013 07/04/2008<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref><ref>[http://www.mnf-iraq.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=18354&Itemid=21 Multi-National Force \u2013 Iraq \u2013 UAV destroys mortar position, kills 6 (Hyanniyah)<!-- Bot generated title -->] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080514125049/http://www.mnf-iraq.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=18354&Itemid=21 |date=14 May 2008 }}</ref>\n\n===Post-operation Basra fighting ===\n1 April: Gunmen are reportedly off the streets and Iraqis cautiously emerge back on the streets of Basra with opening markets and men cleaning up trash from the roadsides. Maliki claims military \"security, stability and success\" and vows to continue operations with a seven-point plan, including recruiting 10,000 new [[Iraqi security forces]] members and moving to enhance public services in Basra.<ref name=\"cbsnews040108\">[https://www.cbsnews.com/stories/2008/04/01/iraq/main3985302.shtml Iraqi PM: Basra Strikes A \"Success\", CBS News April 1, 2008]</ref> 2500 citizens of Basra have already volunteered to work with the Iraqi army since the start of the operation, according to a US military spokesman in Baghdad.<ref>[http://www.mnf-iraq.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=18058&Itemid=131 Operational Update: Maj. Gen. Bergner, April 2] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080513235320/http://www.mnf-iraq.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=18058&Itemid=131 |date=13 May 2008 }} \u2013 MNF-I</ref>\n\n[[File:Hillah SWAT Team.jpg|thumb|200px|right|The Hillah [[SWAT]] Team in training in 2006. The unit was redeployed to Basra following operations in al-Kut and Hillah. On 1 April, they detained 20 vehicle smugglers in Basra.]]\nMaj. Gen. Abdul Aziz Mohammad, director of military operations at Iraq's Defense Ministry, said the Iraqi military planned to seal and search every neighborhood to capture suspected criminals and confiscate weapons.<ref name=\"wp-usap040108\">[https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2008/04/01/AR2008040100833.html U.S. Appears to Take Lead in Fighting in Baghdad, Washington Post, April 1, 2008]</ref> Sadr vows to continue fight against occupation forces \"in a peaceful manner\" and plans mass demonstrations against the Coalition on 9 April.\n\nThe Hillah [[Special Weapons and Tactics]] team detained 20 vehicle smugglers in Basra as part of \"continuing deliberate operations against criminals to restore a rule of law\", according to a US military spokesman.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20080413010935/http://www.mnf-iraq.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=18036&Itemid=128 Hillah Special Weapons and Tactics unit detain 20 suspected smugglers in Basra] \u2013 MNF-I</ref>\n\nThe British defense minister announces a pause in troop reductions.<ref name=\"cnnuk040108\">[http://edition.cnn.com/2008/WORLD/meast/04/01/uk.iraq/index.html \"UK halts troop cuts after Iraq clashes\", CNN, April 1, 2008]</ref>\n\n2 April: Lt. Gen. Mohan al-Furayji leads a 12 vehicle Iraqi Army convoy though the Hayaniya district, a Sadr stronghold in central Basra, in an apparent show of force. A roadside bomb explodes near the convoy, but there were no casualties. A reporter for an Iraqi TV station was shot in the leg while filming the convoy. Afterwards gunmen attacked the convoy and one Iraqi Army Humvee was torched.<ref>ROBERT H. REID \u2013 [https://news.yahoo.com/s/ap/iraq;_ylt=ArGIX8e6ZMrutLo3VyIS52BX6GMA Iraq army flexes muscles in Basra] {{dead link|date=September 2016|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}} \u2013 AP via Yahoo News</ref> Overall, Basra was reportedly relatively calm for a third straight day.<ref name=\"reuters-bomb-040208\">[https://www.reuters.com/article/worldNews/idUSL2884231520080402?sp=true Bomb explodes near top Iraq generals in Basra, Reuters, April 2, 2008]</ref>\n\n[[Chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff|U.S. Chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff]] Admiral [[Michael Mullen]] said in a Pentagon press briefing that the Basra operation is still ongoing and that it is premature to comment on the results of the operation.<ref name=\"cjcsspeech040308\">[http://www.defenselink.mil/transcripts/transcript.aspx?transcriptid=4186 DoD Press Briefing \u2013 CJCS Adm Mullen, Transcript, April 3, 2008] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080521133807/http://www.defenselink.mil/transcripts/transcript.aspx?transcriptid=4186 |date=21 May 2008 }}</ref>\n\nA US [[Unmanned Aerial Vehicle]] (UAV) attacked a [[Technical (fighting vehicle)|technical]] in the Halaf area of Basra, killing 6 \"armed criminals\" after heavy machine gun fire was reported.<ref>[http://www.mnf-iraq.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=18112&Itemid=128 Coalition forces conduct airstrike in al-Halaf, six criminals killed (al-Halaf) ] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080517204613/http://www.mnf-iraq.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=18112&Itemid=128 |date=17 May 2008 }} \u2013 MNF-I</ref>\n\n3 April: A U.S. airstrike destroyed a house in Basra killing two militant snipers and at least six civilians.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/middle_east/7327926.stm Air strike levels house in Basra] \u2013 BBC News</ref> Iraqi Security Forces, advised by U.S. Special Forces, killed seven criminal members and detained 16 others during three separate operations in Basra directed by the Iraqi government.<ref name=\"MNFIpr040408\">[http://www.mnf-iraq.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=18111&Itemid=128 ISF kill 7 criminal members, detain 16 in 3 separate operations in Basra, MNF-I press release, April 4, 2008] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080518031127/http://www.mnf-iraq.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=18111&Itemid=128 |date=18 May 2008 }}</ref>\n\nMuqtada al-Sadr offers the Iraqi government to help purge militia members from Iraqi security forces.<ref name=\"cnn-irai-040408\">[http://edition.cnn.com/2008/WORLD/meast/04/04/iraq.main/index.html  Iraqi leader freezes assault on militias, CNN, April 4, 2008]</ref> Sadr also angrily criticizes the Iraqi government for \"denying it sent envoys to him\"<ref name=\"cnn-al-sadr-040308\">[http://edition.cnn.com/2008/WORLD/meast/04/03/iraq.alsadr/index.html Al-Sadr offers to help Iraqi security forces]</ref>\n\n4 April: Iraqi PM Nuri al-Maliki orders his security forces to stop raids on suspected Shiite militiamen to \"give time to those who are repentant\" to lay down their weapons.<ref name=\"cnn-irai-040408\" /> The PM's order did not mention the Mahdi Army by name. Al-Maliki also ordered a resumption of reconstruction projects and services in the areas of fighting. 3,000 Iraqi soldiers and policemen, including soldiers from the Iraqi Army 1st Division moved into Hayyaniyah to distribute food and water to Iraqis who had been without supplies for several days.<ref>[http://www.mnf-iraq.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=18255&Itemid=128 Iraqi Army distributes food and water al-Hayyaniyah] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080515161620/http://www.mnf-iraq.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=18255&Itemid=128 |date=15 May 2008 }} \u2013 MNF-I</ref>\n\nCoalition forces attacked Mahdi Army members west of Basra and ordered an air strike during the ensuing clashes. Two children were killed along with another person.<ref>[http://antiwar.com/updates/?articleid=12633 \u2013 Antiwar.com]</ref>\n\nIn a Coalition raid during the night 10 militants were killed and two weapons caches, including 60&nbsp;mm mortar rounds, rocket propelled grenades and [[explosively formed penetrators]], were found.<ref>[http://www.mnf-iraq.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=18253&Itemid=128 ISF recover weapons cache, kill 10 in separate operations in Basra] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080408200956/http://www.mnf-iraq.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=18253&Itemid=128 |date=8 April 2008 }} \u2013 MNF I</ref>\n\n5 April: A U.S. airstrike in the Hayaniyah district hit a militant mortar position killing one gunman.<ref name=\"mnfi-coalition-040508\">[http://www.mnf-iraq.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=18152&Itemid=21 Coalition forces conduct airstrike in Basra, one criminal killed, MNF-I Press release, April 5, 2008] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080514123723/http://www.mnf-iraq.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=18152&Itemid=21 |date=14 May 2008 }}</ref>\n\n6 April: The Iraqi Political Council for National Security, with representatives from all major political parties holds a meeting and agrees unanimously to a resolution with a number of points and actions necessary to \"end the existence of this gang\" (the Mahdi Army). Among those points is a decision that the Sadr trend will not have the right to participate in the political process or take part in the provincial elections unless they disband the Mahdi army.<ref name=\"CNN-Maliki-040708\">[http://edition.cnn.com/2008/WORLD/meast/04/07/al.maliki.transcript/index.html Transcript: Prime Minister Nuri al-Maliki on Iraq, CNN, April 7, 2008]</ref> Iraqi Prime Minister Nuri al-Maliki continues to deny that any concessions were made or that Iran was involved in negotiating Muqtada al-Sadr's cease-fire order on 30 March 2008.<ref name=\"CNN-Maliki-040708\"/>\n\nAn explosion of unknown source occurred in Basra destroying a house and killing eight people. MNF-I confirms that an explosion occurred but denies involvement.<ref>[http://www.kuna.net.kw/NewsAgenciesPublicSite/ArticleDetails.aspx?id=1897387&Language=en Eight persons killed in fiery blast in Basra ] \u2013 Kuna News</ref>\n\n7 April: Moqtada al-Sadr offers to disband the Mahdi army if the highest Shi'ite religious authorities, including [[Grand Ayatollah Ali al-Sistani]] and senior Shi'ite clergy based in Iran, demand it. \"If they order the Mahdi army to disband, Muqtada al-Sadr and the Sadr movement will obey the orders of the religious leaders\", senior Sadr aide Hassan Zargani told Reuters from Iran.<ref name=\"reuters-Iraq's-080407\">[https://www.reuters.com/article/worldNews/idUSL0434078820080407?sp=true Iraq's Sadr to disband Mehdi Army if clerics order, Reuters, April 7, 2008]</ref>\n\n8 April: A roadside bomb targeted the convoy of interior ministry spokesman Major-General Abdul-Karim Khalaf, wounding two of his guards in northern Basra.<ref>[http://wiredispatch.com/news/?id=118077 FACTBOX-Security developments in Iraq, April 7<!-- Bot generated title -->] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080409103740/http://wiredispatch.com/news/?id=118077 |date=9 April 2008 }}</ref>\n\n9 April: The US military reported that [[Iraqi Special Operations Forces]] (ISOF) had captured 12 \"suspected terrorists and Special Group members\" and killed 14 others in operations in Basra in the past week.<ref>[http://www.mnf-iraq.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=18292&Itemid=128 ISOF snare terrorist and criminal suspects (Basrah)] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080515161318/http://www.mnf-iraq.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=18292&Itemid=128 |date=15 May 2008 }} \u2013 MNF-I</ref>\n\n11 April: The German Press reports that Riyad al-Nuri was the victim of an assassination as he left a mosque in Najaf on a Friday. He was gunned down by non-uniformed militants in the style of the assassinations that marked the Quds campaign in Basra. No group took credit for the killing. Riyad al-Nuri was Moqtada al-Sadr's brother-in-law, and a close aide. Moqtada al-Sadr lives in the Holy City of Qom, Iran and has become dependent on his aides in Iraq.<ref>http://news.monstersandcritics.com/middleeast/news/article_1399504.php/Al-Sadrs_brother-in-law_killed_in_Iraqs_Najaf__Roundup{{dead link|date=November 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> _\n\n12 April: Soldiers from the 1st Brigade of the 1st IA (QRF) Division from Al-Anbar, as well as elements from the 14th Division, cleared the suburb of al-Qibla in Basra \"without incident\", the US military reported. It also reported an al-Qaida in Iraq leader was captured by Iraqi forces in Abu al-Khasib, a small town 20&nbsp;km southeast of Basra.<ref>[http://www.mnf-iraq.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=18441&Itemid=128 Operation Charge of Knights continues progress in Basrah] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080515172528/http://www.mnf-iraq.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=18441&Itemid=128 |date=15 May 2008 }} \u2013 MNF-I</ref>\n\n13 April: A policeman is killed in a drive-by shooting and two dumped bodies are found.<ref>[http://antiwar.com/updates/?articleid=12686 Sunday: 46 Iraqis Killed, 29 Wounded \u2013 Antiwar.com<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\n14 April: [[Richard Butler (journalist)|Richard Butler]], a UK journalist held captive in Basra for two months after being kidnapped in central Basra was freed in an Iraqi Army sweep.<ref>[https://news.yahoo.com/s/nm/iraq_dc;_ylt=AtNLUsusFOzddv0ClLcKbcxX6GMA  Kidnapped UK journalist freed in Iraq's Basra]  {{webarchive|url=https://archive.is/20080527130348/http://news.yahoo.com/s/nm/iraq_dc;_ylt=AtNLUsusFOzddv0ClLcKbcxX6GMA |date= 27 May 2008 }} \u2013 Reuters via Yahoo News</ref> Police Major Ali Haider, a commander in the police department's serious crimes directorate, is shot and killed.<ref>[http://antiwar.com/updates/?articleid=12691 Monday: 2 US Soldiers, 87 Iraqis Killed; 142 Iraqis Wounded \u2013 Antiwar.com<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\n15 April: Maj-Gen Abdul Jalil Khalaf and Lt-Gen Mohan al-Furayji are reassigned to posts in Baghdad. The Iraqi government says that the two chiefs are returning to their posts in the Defence Ministry at the end of a 6-month assignment to the southern city. Brig. Gen. Qassim al-Moussawi, an Iraqi military spokesman, said: \"The two have done a great job and their efforts were highly appreciated by the commander in chief\". However, a spokesman for the Sadrist bloc in Basra, Ali al-Suaidi, says the Iraqi government \"wants to blame its failure on somebody\" and the moves are \"punishment for the botched execution of the campaign\".  According to Brig. Gen al-Moussawi, Gen. Furayji will be replaced by Maj. Gen. Mohammad Jawad, the commander of the 14th Division, in the Basra Operational Command and Maj. Gen. Adel Dahham will become the new police chief in Basra.<ref>{{cite news|publisher=BBC News|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/middle_east/7350434.stm|title=Basra security leaders removed|date=16 April 2008}}</ref><ref>Amit R. Paley \u2013 [https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2008/04/16/AR2008041600932.html Iraq Reassigns Chiefs Of Basra's Army, Police] \u2013 Washington Post</ref>\n\n16 April: An unmanned U.S. drone plane launched missiles that killed four militiamen and wounded one more, but police said six people were killed and three more were wounded.\n\n17 April: Gunmen tried to kill former police chief Brigadier-General Mohamed Kadhim al-Ali. One of his bodyguards was killed and two more were wounded. In a separate incident, gunmen shot and wounded a police commando. Also, two policemen were killed in a drive-by shooting.\n[[File:Weapons cache basra.jpg|thumb|225px|right|An Iraqi soldier from the 1st QRF division examines a mortar captured during clearing operations in Hayaniya, 19 April]]\n19 April: Iraqi security forces launched a clearing operation in the Hayaniya district, a Sadr stronghold in central Basra. After a show of force in which coalition forces bombed an empty area west of Hayaniya, Iraqi forces, with advisers from the [[British Army]] and the [[United States Marine Corps]].,<ref name=moduk20080421>[http://www.mod.uk/DefenceInternet/DefenceNews/MilitaryOperations/IraqiSoldiersContinueToTargetBasraMilitias.htm Iraqi soldiers continue to target Basra militias] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080513203724/http://www.mod.uk/DefenceInternet/DefenceNews/MilitaryOperations/IraqiSoldiersContinueToTargetBasraMilitias.htm |date=13 May 2008 }} \u2013 UK Ministry of Defence</ref> moved into the Hayaniya city center. According to General [[Mohan al-Furayji]], Iraqi forces faced only \"isolated skirmishes\".<ref>Aref Mohammed \u2013 [https://news.yahoo.com/s/nm/20080419/wl_nm/iraq_dc Show of force as Iraqi forces advance in Basra] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080421035946/http://news.yahoo.com/s/nm/20080419/wl_nm/iraq_dc |date=21 April 2008 }} \u2013 Reuters via Yahoo News</ref> A large number of weapons were captured during the operation, including 140 rockets, 50 mortars, 70 IEDs and a number of anti-aircraft missiles. Seven Iraqi Army vehicles were recaptured as well.<ref name=moduk20080421 />\n\n20 April: In a statement, Muqtada al-Sadr warned that he would declare \"open war\" if the campaign against him did not stop.<ref name=\"ap-alsadr-042008\">[http://hosted.ap.org/dynamic/stories/I/IRAQ?SITE=NHPOR&SECTION=HOME&TEMPLATE=DEFAULT Al-Sadr's followers refuse to disband militia in Iraq, Associated Press, April 20, 2008] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070519032040/http://hosted.ap.org/dynamic/stories/I/IRAQ?SITE=NHPOR&SECTION=HOME&TEMPLATE=DEFAULT |date=19 May 2007 }}</ref> Coincidentally, [[Al-Qaeda in Iraq]] released a similar message the same day, calling for a 30-day period of violence.<ref name=\"wp-new-042008\">[https://web.archive.org/web/20121104185737/http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2008/04/19/AR2008041901723.html New Al-Qaida in Iraq tape calls for monthlong offensive, Washington Post, April 20, 2008]</ref>\n\nIran's ambassador to Baghdad declared support for the Iraqi government crackdown against \"lawbreakers\" in Basra. Since major Sunni, Shiite and Kurdish parties have already supported the Maliki government in its crackdown for some time, Sadr appears increasingly politically isolated.<ref name=\"ap-alsadr-042008\"/>\n\n21 April: Two roadside-bombs hit two Coalition patrols in the city. One was an American, the second a British. There were no casualties suffered in the attack on the British patrol but in the first attack one U.S. Marine was killed and a second wounded.\n\nAlso, an al-Sistani aide who was wounded a week before in an attack in the city died of his wounds.\n\n24 April: Prime Minister Nuri al-Maliki claimed historic victory over armed militias. \"The ideology of having rival militias is over. The weapon is now in state hands\", a statement said that Maliki told British Foreign Secretary David Miliband during talks. \"We have political support from all [political] entities for the measures taken by the government\", Maliki continued.<ref name=\"afp-iraqi-042408\">[http://afp.google.com/article/ALeqM5iHul4DZp-axz3iOT91x_oRVSoL5Q AFP: Iraqi PM says private army mentality in Iraq is over, AFP, April 24, 2008] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080501060937/http://afp.google.com/article/ALeqM5iHul4DZp-axz3iOT91x_oRVSoL5Q |date=1 May 2008 }}</ref>\n\n[[Multinational Force Iraq|Multi-National Corps-Iraq]] commander [[Lloyd J. Austin|Lt. Gen Lloyd J. Austin]] said in a press briefing that Iraqi security forces are in control of Basra.\n\n25 April: Muqtada al-Sadr reaffirmed his cease-fire order. In a statement to followers read on his behalf during Friday prayers, Muqtada al-Sadr urged his followers to \"observe more patience in commitment to the freeze decision.\" Sadr also tried to clarify his call for \"open war\" on 20 April, stressing that the threat \"is meant against the occupiers only.\"<ref name=\"voi-open-042508\">[http://www.aswataliraq.info/look/english/article.tpl?IdLanguage=1&IdPublication=4&NrArticle=77383&NrIssue=2&NrSection=1 \"Open war against occupiers only,\" Sadr tells followers, Voices of Iraq, April 25, 2008]{{dead link|date=May 2016}}</ref>\n\nSecular life began to re-emerge. Young women dared to wear jeans, soldiers listened to pop music on their mobile phones and bands began performing at wedding parties again.<ref name=\"londontimes-themen-042508\">[http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/world/iraq/article3671861.ece The men in black vanish and Basra comes back to life], [[The Times]], 25 April 2008</ref>\n\nIn the town of Qurna, near Basra, journalist Jassim al-Batat was gunned down by gunmen in a speeding car as he left his house.<ref>[http://wiredispatch.com/news/?id=142737 Iraqi journalist killed near Basra, radio station says<!-- Bot generated title -->]{{dead link|date=May 2016}}</ref>\n\n28 April: A Sadrist lawmaker was killed and his wife was injured during an armed attack.\n\n8 May: A British soldier is wounded and two unidentified foreign contractors are killed when rockets hit the main British military base in Basra at the airport. Coalition aircraft responded to the attack killing six militants who fired on the base.\n\n10 May: Two civilians were killed and five others were wounded when a roadside bomb blasted a police patrol in Basra. Also, 14 suspects were arrested during raids.\n\n===Fighting in Sadr City and Baghdad===\n{{Main|Siege of Sadr City}}\nThe clashes, soon after the start of the security operation, spread from Basra to Baghdad, mainly the [[Sadr City]] district of the capital, which was under the control of the Mahdi Army.\n<!-- Deleted image removed: [[File:Smoke rises from the Green Zone after a mortar strike March 25, 2008.jpg|225px|right|thumb|Smoke rises from the Green Zone after a mortar strike 25 March 2008.]] -->\n'''25 March''': Militants attacked police and army checkpoints in the western and northern parts of Baghdad and the Green Zone was constantly coming under mortar and rocket attacks leaving dozens of people wounded and many Iraqi civilians killed by rockets that missed their targets. On the first day of fighting in Baghdad one U.S. soldier was among the dead, killed by a mortar in the Adhamiya district of Baghdad. The mortar was fired from the vicinity of Sadr City. In Baghdad's al-Amin neighborhood, Mahdi Army gunmen stormed two offices of the Dawa party and clashed with guards there. Five Mahdi Army gunmen and two Dawa guards were killed. Fighters also captured six policemen with their two police vehicles from their checkpoint in New Baghdad.<ref>[https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2008/03/25/AR2008032500461_pf.html Intense Fighting Erupts In Iraq | Washington Post]</ref>\n\n'''26 March''': Mortar strikes killed five people in the Karrada neighborhood and four in Risala on 26 March. Another two people were killed in mortar attacks elsewhere. More rockets and mortars hit the Green Zone wounding four people. Among the wounded were two American civilians and one American and one Iraqi soldier.\n\nIn Sadr City militants were planting roadside bombs on a main thoroughfare and declared the ceasefire over. Mahdi Army fighters sealed off their neighborhoods, blocking roads with refrigerators, burning tires and garbage. Heavy clashes erupted between militiamen and U.S. and Iraqi forces. A roadside bomb set a U.S. Stryker on fire in Sadr City but all soldiers inside survived. Also in fighting in northern and eastern parts of Baghdad two US soldiers and three Iraqi civilians were killed.<ref>[http://www.csmonitor.com/2008/0326/p01s13-woiq.html Across Iraq, battles erupt with Mahdi Army \u2013 Christian Science Monitor]</ref><ref>[http://wiredispatch.com/news/?id=101578 FACTBOX-Security developments in Iraq, March 26 Reuters] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080402100230/http://wiredispatch.com/news/?id=101578 |date=2 April 2008 }}</ref>\n[[File:Sadr City April 2008.jpg|thumb|left|225px|Map showing location of fighting in eastern Baghdad, March\u2013May 2008]]\n'''27 March''': On 27 March, a mortar bomb at a Baghdad bus station killed three people and wounded 15 and 2 mortar rounds hit the Ministry of Interior, al-Tasfeerat compound in central Baghdad killing one employee and injuring four. The Green Zone was still being bombarded with one Iraqi civilian killed and another 14 wounded by misfired mortars. Several mortar rounds hit a building in the U.S. embassy complex in the Zone leaving one U.S. government employee dead and another three wounded. Also, a U.S. soldier died in the fighting during the day.\n\nStreet battles in Sadr City and other parts of the capital in the previous 24 hours left 88 people dead, including 68 militants, three U.S. and one Iraqi soldier, one Iraqi policeman and at least 15 civilians who were killed when an artillery barrage hit a market in Sadr City. At least 12 U.S. soldiers were wounded and three policemen captured.<ref name=\"mcclatchydc-212\">[http://www.mcclatchydc.com/212/story/31750.html Round-up of Daily Violence in Iraq, Thursday March 27, 2008 McClatchy Washington Bureau] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080622184755/http://www.mcclatchydc.com/212/story/31750.html |date=22 June 2008 }}</ref><ref>[http://www.mnf-iraq.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=17878&Itemid=21 24 terrorists killed in Baghdad \u2013 MNF-Iraq] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080403021027/http://www.mnf-iraq.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=17878&Itemid=21 |date=3 April 2008 }}</ref><ref>[http://www.mnf-iraq.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=17880&Itemid=21 Terrorists launch eleven indirect fire attacks, other unrest (Baghdad) \u2013 MNF-Iraq] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080403021033/http://www.mnf-iraq.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=17880&Itemid=21 |date=3 April 2008 }}</ref><ref>[http://www.mnf-iraq.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=17888&Itemid=21 ISF, CF take fight to terrorists \u2013 MNF-Iraq] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080403072414/http://www.mnf-iraq.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=17888&Itemid=21 |date=3 April 2008 }}</ref><ref>[http://www.mnf-iraq.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=17887&Itemid=21 Iraqi Security Forces, Coalition forces target terrorists, kill 26 \u2013 MNF-Iraq] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080403072408/http://www.mnf-iraq.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=17887&Itemid=21 |date=3 April 2008 }}</ref><ref>[http://www.mnf-iraq.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=17885&Itemid=21 ISF, CF defend checkpoint, kill 8 militants (Baghdad) \u2013 MNF-Iraq] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080403072404/http://www.mnf-iraq.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=17885&Itemid=21 |date=3 April 2008 }}</ref>\n\nTahseen Sheikhly, a Sunni civilian spokesman for operation Imposing Law, was kidnapped by gunmen who stormed his house in a Mahdi Army stronghold in southeastern Baghdad and torched it. Three of his bodyguards were killed.\n\nThe Times reported areas of Baghdad were slowly falling into the hands of the Mahdi Army. The Mahdi Army took over neighbourhood after neighbourhood, some amid heavy fighting, others without firing a shot. In New Baghdad, militiamen simply ordered the police to leave their checkpoints, the officers complied en masse and the guerrillas took over their checkpoints.<ref>[http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/world/iraq/article3631718.ece Areas of Baghdad fall to militias as Iraqi Army falters in Basra | Times Online]</ref> The US Army denied this. Lieutenant Colonel Steve Stover, the [[Public affairs (military)|Public Affairs Officer]] for the 4th Infantry Division and Multinational Division Baghdad said \"All checkpoints and ISF [Iraqi security forces] buildings are in ISF and/or Coalition control. No checkpoint is in enemy control.\"<ref>Bill Roggio [http://www.longwarjournal.org/archives/2008/03/fighting_in_baghdad.php Fighting in Baghdad, South against Mahdi Army completes fourth day] \u2013 Long War Journal</ref>\n\nIn other fighting during the day a father and son were killed in the Talbiyah neighbourhood where at least eight Iraqi soldiers were wounded in street battles.<ref>[http://www.mcclatchydc.com/212/story/31750.html Round-up of Daily Violence in Iraq, Thursday March 27, 2008 | McClatchy Washington Bureau] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080622184755/http://www.mcclatchydc.com/212/story/31750.html |date=22 June 2008 }}</ref>\n\n'''28 March''': Early on 28 March, a U.S. helicopter fired a Hellfire missile during fighting in Sadr City in support of ground troops who were clearing a main supply route. Four militants and nine civilians were killed. Meanwhile, an insurgent mortar hit Iraqi Vice-President Tareq Hashemi's offices in the Green Zone, killing two guards, and a U.S. air strike killed three people and wounded six in Kadhimiya. In other fighting throughout the capital 13 militants and two civilians were killed and four U.S. Stryker armored vehicles entered Sadr City and engaged militiamen. A U.S. soldier was killed by a roadside bomb just south of Baghdad.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/middle_east/7317935.stm Iraq extends Shia arms deadline \u2013 BBC News]</ref><ref name=\"wiredispatch_Mar28\">[http://wiredispatch.com/news/?id=104998 FACTBOX-Security developments in Iraq, March 28 \u2013 Reuters] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080402100236/http://wiredispatch.com/news/?id=104998 |date=2 April 2008 }}</ref><ref>[http://www.mnf-iraq.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=17897&Itemid=21 MND-B Soldiers kill 13 terrorists \u2013 MNF-I] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080403072418/http://www.mnf-iraq.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=17897&Itemid=21 |date=3 April 2008 }}</ref>\n\nTen of the militants were killed by US forces when a joint security station in eastern Baghdad was attacked with small arms fire. In a separate incident, a US air strike destroyed a rocket site in eastern Baghdad.<ref>[http://www.mnf-iraq.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=17906&Itemid=128 MND-B Soldiers destroy rocket site, kill 12 terrorists] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080403072422/http://www.mnf-iraq.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=17906&Itemid=128 |date=3 April 2008 }} \u2013 MNF-I</ref> One U.S. soldier was killed the fighting.\n\nLate in the evening reports came in that a unit of 500 policemen decided to stop working with the government and join the Mahdi Army.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2008/03/28/AR2008032803810_pf.html | work=The Washington Post | title=19 Tense Hours in Sadr City Alongside the Mahdi Army | first=Sudarsan | last=Raghavan | accessdate=5 May 2010}}</ref>\n\n'''29 March''': In another day of mortar bombardment mortars landed in Shiite areas of eastern Baghdad, killing at least one person and injuring 12. The [[New York Times]] reported that in a well-publicized event in Sadr City, 40 men who said they were Iraqi police officers surrendered their weapons to Sadr officials saying \"We can't fight our brothers in the Mahdi Army, so we came here to submit our weapons.\" In return, the Sadr officials gave the officers olive branches and Korans. The weapons were returned after the officers pledged not to use them against Mahdi Army members.  \"These weapons are for defending the country but not for fighting your brothers,\" said Sheik Salman al-Fraji, head of the Sadr office there.<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/2008/03/30/world/middleeast/30iraq.html?_r=1&oref=slogin&ref=todayspaper&pagewanted=print Shiite Militias Cling to Swaths of Basra and Stage Raids By JAMES GLANZ and MICHAEL KAMBER]</ref> {{YouTube|OcWG-hJbSNo|Video coverage of event}} Another 15 soldiers also surrendered elsewhere in the city.\n\nBy this point the Iraqi Health Ministry reported at least 75 civilians killed and 500 injured in fighting in Sadr City and other eastern Baghdad neighborhoods. The U.S. military sharply disputes the claims, having said that most of those killed were militia members. Two U.S. soldiers were killed by a roadside bomb in eastern Baghdad and one Iraqi policeman was killed in the Amil district by another bomb. A militia member was killed when his RPG misfired.\n\nU.S. forces stated that they killed a total of 48 militants in Baghdad in the previous 24 hours, while three US Soldiers were killed in the fighting that day.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://icasualties.org/oif/prdDetails.aspx?hndRef%3D3-2008 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=30 March 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080403055622/http://icasualties.org/oif/prdDetails.aspx?hndRef=3-2008 |archivedate=3 April 2008 }}</ref>\n\n'''30 March''': U.S. forces killed at least 62 fighters in fighting across Baghdad. Another mortar strike, aimed at the Green Zone, killed at least seven Iraqis and wounded 21 when two rounds apparently fell short, striking houses in the commercial district of Karradah. Gunmen also attacked an Iraqi checkpoint in eastern Baghdad, killing six troops. An American soldier was killed by a roadside bomb just north of the city.<ref>[http://www.mnf-iraq.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=17936&Itemid=128 Multi-National Force \u2013 Iraq \u2013 Air weapons team engages, kills 12 criminals<!-- Bot generated title -->] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080403072437/http://www.mnf-iraq.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=17936&Itemid=128 |date=3 April 2008 }}</ref><ref>[http://www.mnf-iraq.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=17957&Itemid=128 Multi-National Force \u2013 Iraq \u2013 ISF, CF kill 8 criminals, detain 2 others in pursuit to secure streets of Baghdad<!-- Bot generated title -->] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080403072533/http://www.mnf-iraq.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=17957&Itemid=128 |date=3 April 2008 }}</ref><ref>[http://www.mnf-iraq.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=17950&Itemid=128 Multi-National Force \u2013 Iraq \u2013 MND-B Soldiers kill 8 criminals in separate operations<!-- Bot generated title -->] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080403031843/http://www.mnf-iraq.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=17950&Itemid=128 |date=3 April 2008 }}</ref><ref>[http://www.mnf-iraq.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=17937&Itemid=128 Multi-National Force \u2013 Iraq \u2013 MND-B Soldiers kill 2 during routine operation<!-- Bot generated title -->] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080403072520/http://www.mnf-iraq.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=17937&Itemid=128 |date=3 April 2008 }}</ref>\n\n'''31 March''': Mortars fell again on the Green Zone, however there were only sporadic sounds of gunfire in the city, a day after al-Sadr declared a new ceasefire. One U.S. soldier was killed on the outskirts of Sadr City by a roadside bomb. Just before the fighting stopped eight civilians were killed in Sadr City due to American shelling.<ref>[http://antiwar.com/updates/?articleid=12609 Monday: 2 US Soldiers, 50 Iraqis Killed; 45 Iraqis Wounded \u2013 Antiwar.com<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\n''' 1\u20135 April''': During this time a cease-fire was in effect in Baghdad which eased the violence in the capital. However this will not last.\n\n'''6 April \u2013 11 May''': A U.S. military raid in Sadr City provokes heavy street fighting in the district and most of eastern Baghdad which leads to the collapse of the cease-fire in the district. Two Iraqi Army armored vehicles and two trucks are destroyed and one U.S. Stryker armored personnel carrier is damaged on the first day of the street battles. U.S. Apache helicopter gunships swooped overhead during the battle. Militants shelled the Green Zone and other U.S. military bases around the capital. Unmanned Predator aircraft fired Hellfire missiles into Sadr City every day targeting the mortar and rocket teams. At least 941 people were killed. Among the dead were 22 U.S. and 17 Iraqi soldiers as well as 331 militants and 591 civilians. 100 U.S. soldiers and more than 1,700 civilians were wounded. 549 of the civilians were killed in Sadr City<ref>[http://antiwar.com/updates/?articleid=12733 Wednesday: 2 US Soldiers, 1 US Contractor, 59 Iraqis Killed; 114 Iraqis Wounded \u2013 Antiwar.com<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> while another 42 were killed in different parts of Baghdad by mortars, fired from Sadr City, which missed the Green Zone. The fighting mostly stopped early on 11 April, as U.S. and Iraqi forces managed to advance down the main road through Sadr City and set up a forward defence line inside the district. However, that night fighting continued as U.S. and Iraqi units were attacked with small-arms, machine guns and RPGs. Snipers and roadside bombs were also used against Coalition forces.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.cnn.com/2008/WORLD/meast/04/11/iraq.main/index.html | work=CNN | title=Iraqi, U.S. troops accused of Sadr City attack - CNN.com | date=11 April 2008 | accessdate=5 May 2010}}</ref><ref name=autogenerated2>[http://www.antiwar.com/ Antiwar.com<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\nOn 17 April, a heavy dust storm engulfed Baghdad and the militiamen used this to their advantage. Gunmen attacked the coalition frontlines under the cover of the storm and heavy fighting ensued. At one point an Iraqi company deserted their position at a police station and the militiamen moved in but U.S. forces moved in soon to fill in the gap in the line. Fighting continued throughout the night and new attacks were staged the next day as the storm continued and U.S. forces were not able to send in helicopters, planes or drones to assist. This day another company of Iraqi soldiers deserted their post after almost being overrun by militants. The fighting finally died down in the evening as the sand storm lifted. In the fighting on 17 and 18 April 17 Iraqi soldiers and 22 militiamen were killed along with a number of civilians.\n\nOn 28 April, another dust storm swept through Baghdad and the Mahdi Army once again attacked the blockades around Sadr City. In an effort to resupply troops conducting extended combat operations, soldiers from [[10th Mountain Division]] staged a 40-vehicle resupply convoy; however, Mahdi Army launched a devastating indirect fire attack against FOB Loyalty, killing four U.S. soldiers and injuring twenty others.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.longwarjournal.org/archives/2008/06/mahdi_army_uses_flyi.php}}</ref> In the ensuing fighting four more U.S. soldiers, 45 militants and eight civilians were killed.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/middle_east/7370659.stm | work=BBC News | title=US troops killed in Iraq clashes | date=28 April 2008 | accessdate=5 May 2010}}</ref>\n\nOn 29 April, U.S. forces in Stryker vehicles tried to push deeper into Sadr City but were met with stiff resistance from fighters using machine-guns and RPGs. After heavy fighting the troops withdrew to their start positions. 28 militants were killed, 6 U.S. soldiers were wounded, several U.S. military vehicles were damaged and three buildings used by militants were destroyed by American bombing during the battle.\n\nOn 3\u20134 May, an infantry company from the [[10th Mountain Division]] attempted to isolate the Mahdi Army along the eastern boundary of Sadr City by placing barriers along major intersections. This was an effort to facilitate the Iraqi Army's movement into Sadr City. The U.S. forces met with strong opposition as militants attacked the soldiers with heavy machine guns, RPGs, and IEDs. The unit suffered heavy damages to men, weapons, and equipment, but maintained pressure on the militia and controlled the grounds. Using [[close air support]], tanks, and armored vehicles the soldiers defeated militia strongholds along the eastern sections of Sadr City.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.longwarjournal.org/archives/2008/07/battle_over_sadr_cit.php}}</ref>\n\nOn 8 May, the Iraqi government called on the residents of Sadr City to flee after more than 40 days of fighting, which left between 500\u20131,000 people dead. Due to the nearly constant violence, there are ongoing shortages of food, water, and other supplies.<ref>{{cite news|last=Fadel |first=Leila |title=Iraqi military orders Sadr City residents to evacuate |publisher=McClatchy Newspapers |date=8 May 2008 |url=http://www.mcclatchydc.com/iraq/story/36436.html |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081015010410/http://www.mcclatchydc.com/iraq/story/36436.html |archivedate=15 October 2008 }}</ref>\n\nOn 10 May, Iranian backed \"special groups\" fired a surface-to-air missile at a US helicopter gunship over Sadr City, the missile was reportedly fired from an unknown location in eastern Baghdad but missed the target, it was reported to be a type 7 SAM.<ref name=autogenerated1>[http://www.zeenews.com/articles.asp?aid=442786&sid=WOR Zee News \u2013 Clashes in Iraq's Sadr City<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\nOn 11 May, a cease-fire agreement was reached, but despite this some sporadic fighting still continued in Sadr city.\n\nDuring the latest round of fighting six Iraqi and three U.S. soldiers, six policemen, one U.S.-allied militiaman, 93 militiamen and 30 civilians were killed in clashes between the Mahdi Army and security forces in other parts of the capital.<ref>[http://www.mcclatchydc.com/212/story/33381.html McClatchy Washington Bureau | 04/11/2008 | Round-up of Daily Violence in Iraq, Friday April 11, 2008<!-- Bot generated title -->] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080529035636/http://www.mcclatchydc.com/212/story/33381.html |date=29 May 2008 }}</ref>\n\n'''Post-11 May:'''\n\n12 May: Overnight clashes in Sadr city continued despite the cease-fire, the clashes killed 3 militiamen and 2 civilians and wounded 24 people. US military Spokesman Rear Adm Patrick Driscoll warned that a truce had not yet been brokered and that the Iraqi government and Shiite representatives were still talking, Sadrist lawmaker Nasar al-Rubaie said: said talks on final touches to the agreement were continuing. In fighting elsewhere in the capital 12 gunmen were killed.<ref name=autogenerated3>[http://www.zeenews.com/articles.asp?aid=442567&sid=WOR Zee News \u2013 Sadr city<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\n13 May: Clashes between security forces and Shi'ite gunmen killed 2 Iraqi soldiers, 11 militiamen and 12 civilians and wounded 28 people in Baghdad overnight. One of those killed was a seven-year-old who died after an Iraqi army vehicle ran over him. Fighting also erupted in Baghdad's Shula district, another Mahdi Army stronghold{{Vague|date=December 2008}}. Also, one U.S. soldier was killed in a roadside bombing in a northwestern part of Baghdad.<ref name=autogenerated1 />\n\n14 May: In overnight clashes five people were killed in Sadr City. Also, two militiamen were killed while planting a bomb during house-to-house searches in the area.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/middle_east/7401634.stm | work=BBC News | title=Bombing at Iraq funeral kills 20 | date=14 May 2008 | accessdate=5 May 2010}}</ref>\n\n15 May: In overnight clashes in Baghdad's Sadr City slum 7 people were killed and 19 were wounded. Two militiamen were also killed.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.reuters.com/article/worldNews/idUSL0439231320080515 | work=Reuters | title=Seven die in clashes in Baghdad's Sadr City | first=Aseel | last=Kami | date=15 May 2008}}</ref>\n\n187 dumped bodies were found during the fighting throughout Baghdad since 23 March, all apparent victims of sectarian violence.<ref name=autogenerated2 />\n\n===Al Kut fighting===\nIn the city of [[Kut|Al Kut]], the capital of [[Wasit Governorate]], militants went out in the streets in force on 25 March, and took control of 5 out of 18 districts of the city.\n\nHeavy street fighting took place on 26 March, and mortar impacts resounded leaving buildings and cars aflame. Another three districts fell into the hands of the militants for a total of eight. 35 people were reported killed, including a baby. 15 of those were killed when a mortar barrage struck homes amid the clashes.<ref>[http://www.cnn.com/2008/WORLD/meast/03/26/iraq.main/index.html More than 100 dead in two days of Iraq fighting | CNN]</ref> The security forces stated that six Iraqi soldiers and policemen died while 11 militants were killed in a combined US Special Forces-Iraqi SWAT patrol.<ref name=\"mcclatchydc-227\">[http://www.mcclatchydc.com/227/story/31662.html McClatchy Washington Bureau | 03/26/2008 | Clashes spread as U.S., Iraqi forces attack Shiite militia<!-- Bot generated title -->] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080528191600/http://www.mcclatchydc.com/227/story/31662.html |date=28 May 2008 }}</ref><ref>[http://www.mnf-iraq.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=17886&Itemid=21 Iraqi Security Forces, U.S. Special Forces engage criminal elements in Hillah, al-Kut] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120214002615/http://www.mnf-iraq.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=17886&Itemid=21 |date=14 February 2012 }} MNF-I</ref>\n\nAlso at least two policemen and one civilian were killed and another eight or ten policemen were wounded in fighting in the town of Aziziya just north of Al Kut.<ref>[http://www.alertnet.org/thenews/newsdesk/L2558442.htm FACTBOX-Security developments in Iraq, March 25 \u2013 Reuters Alertnet]</ref>\n\n49 people were killed and 75 wounded in Al Kut by 27 March.\n\nAnother four policemen and two civilians were killed in the next two days.<ref name = \"wiredispatch_Mar28\"/><ref>[http://wiredispatch.com/news/?id=106674 FACTBOX-Security developments in Iraq, March 29<!-- Bot generated title -->] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080402100256/http://wiredispatch.com/news/?id=106674 |date=2 April 2008 }}</ref>\n\n400 policemen deserted or defected during the fighting in Al Kut.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.yahoo.com/s/ap/20080413/ap_on_re_mi_ea/iraq |title=Archived copy |accessdate=13 April 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080414211801/http://news.yahoo.com/s/ap/20080413/ap_on_re_mi_ea/iraq |archivedate=14 April 2008 }}</ref>\n\nOn 26 April, a raid was conducted in the city in which one Iraqi soldier was killed.\n\n===Hilla clashes===\nFighting was also happening in [[Hilla]], the capital of [[Babil province]], where two people were killed on 25 March.\n\nOn 26 March, U.S. forces conducted air strikes in support of Hillah's Iraqi [[SWAT]] unit during fighting with Shi'ite militia in the Thawra neighbourhood. Iraqi police sources estimate the casualties at between 11 and 29 people dead and 18 and 39 wounded. At least 19 of the dead were confirmed to be militiamen.<ref>[https://abcnews.go.com/US/wireStory?id=4529879 Many killed by U.S. strike in Iraq's Hilla: sources | ABC News]</ref> 9 Iraqi SWAT members were killed and two wounded during the battle.<ref>[http://www.mnf-iraq.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=17886&Itemid=21 Iraqi Security Forces, U.S. Special Forces engage criminal elements in Hillah, al-Kut] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120214002615/http://www.mnf-iraq.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=17886&Itemid=21 |date=14 February 2012 }} \u2013 MNF-I</ref>\n\nThe next day heavy street battles continued in Hilla, most of them in the city center, with at least one soldier and five policemen killed and another 26 members of the security forces being wounded. The offices of the al-Da'wa Party and the Supreme Council were destroyed by militants.<ref>Juan Cole \u2013 [http://www.indybay.org/newsitems/2008/03/28/18489102.php \u2013  Mahdi Army Stands Firm in its Basra Neighborhoods.Demonstrations in Baghdad against al-Maliki] \u2013 Indybay.org</ref>\n\nThe toll in two days of fighting in Hilla was at least 60 dead.<ref name = \"mcclatchydc-212\"/>\n\nOn 29 March, a police source in Babil province reported that since the fighting began on 25 March 85 militiamen have been captured in the province. He also said a large number of gunmen had been killed.<ref>[http://www.aswataliraq.info/look/english/article.tpl?IdLanguage=1&IdPublication=4&NrArticle=74643&NrIssue=2&NrSection=1  12 killed, 42 wounded in Hilla clashes \u2013 source] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080402095219/http://www.aswataliraq.info/look/english/article.tpl?IdLanguage=1&IdPublication=4&NrArticle=74643&NrIssue=2&NrSection=1 |date=2 April 2008 }} \u2013 Aswat Aliraq</ref>\n\nOn 3 April, U.S. soldiers, in civilian clothes, clashed with Mahdi Army fighters during an attempted raid to arrest rogue elements in the Mehdi Army. Later Iraqi police joined the fight and five people, including four policemen were killed.<ref name=autogenerated4 />\n\nOn 4 April, a roadside bomb killed four policemen and injured one other.\n\nOn 5 April, the body of a police commando was found in the city, he was shot dead. Police killed one gunman and arrested two others when they tried to assassinate a local police chief in the town of Hamza al-Gharbi, south of Hilla.\n\nOn 25 April, a man was shot dead in the city. Six people were arrested in connection to the killing.\n\n===Other clashes===\nIn response to the fighting the political movement of powerful [[Shia Islam|Shiite]] cleric [[Muqtada al-Sadr]] launched a nationwide civil disobedience campaign across [[Iraq]] to protest the raids and detentions against the [[Mahdi Army]].<ref>[http://edition.cnn.com/2008/WORLD/meast/03/25/iraq.main/index.html Iraqi raids anger Shiite militia | CNN]</ref>\n\n'''[[Diwaniyah]]''': On 26 March, seven Iraqi soldiers, a policeman and two militants were killed and another seven militants were captured and seven policemen wounded. On 27 March, one gunman was killed and a policeman was wounded in a security operation that netted eight suspects. The next day militia fighters killed the top administrator in a village near Diwaniyah.<ref name=autogenerated6>[http://www.mcclatchydc.com/227/story/31662.html Clashes spread as U.S., Iraqi forces attack Shiite militia \u2013 McClatchy Washington Bureau] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080528191600/http://www.mcclatchydc.com/227/story/31662.html |date=28 May 2008 }}</ref><ref>[http://www.alertnet.org/thenews/newsdesk/L26327762.htm FACTBOX-Security developments in Iraq, March 26 \u2013 Reuters Alertnet]</ref>\n\nOn 29 March 200 local residents held a demonstration in support of the Iraqi operations in Basrah.<ref>[https://archive.is/20120714024110/http://news.yahoo.com/nphotos/Iraq/ss/events/ts/082701iraqplane/im:/080329/photos_wl/2008_03_29t121213_450x355_us_iraq/ Demonstrators chant slogans during a protest in Diwaniya] \u2013 Reuters via Yahoo News</ref>\n\nOn 27 April, gunmen killed a police officer outside his home.\n\n'''[[Najaf]]''': Four mortars landed in different parts of Najaf on 26 March, and sporadic fighting throughout the city left two policemen wounded. A few days later a roadside bomb killed one army officer and wounded two soldiers when it struck their vehicle in northern Najaf.<ref>[http://www.mcclatchydc.com/212/story/31661.html Round-up of Daily Violence in Iraq \u2013 Wednesday March 26, 2008 | McClatchy Washington Bureau] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080331230422/http://www.mcclatchydc.com/212/story/31661.html |date=31 March 2008 }}</ref>\n\nOn 11 April, gunmen killed a senior aide to Muqtada al-Sadr, Riyadh al-Nouri. He was the director of al-Sadr's office in Najaf.\n\nOn 21 April, an al-Sistani aide was killed in the city.\n\n'''[[Amarah]]''': In Amara, capital of [[Maysan Governorate]], two soldiers were killed by unknown gunmen. Two civilians died in clashes on the Yugoslav Bridge in northern Amara. Gunmen attacked the Badr Organization Bureau located in Hitteen Square, in the centre of Amara, using RPGs.<ref name = \"mcclatchydc-212\"/><ref>[http://www.antiwar.com/updates/?articleid=12586 Wednesday: 2 GIs, 1 British Soldier, 76 Iraqis Killed; 367 Iraqis Wounded \u2013 Antiwar.com]</ref>\n\n'''[[Nasiriyah]]''': Two Iraqi soldiers were killed near Nasiriyah as they were heading to reinforce the attack on Basra. On 28 March 2008, Sadrist forces had taken control of the center of [[Nasiriyah]]. In heavy street fighting 5 policemen, 10 militants and 20 civilians were killed. Another 52 people were wounded, including 19 policemen, 26 civilians and 7 gunmen. Another 13 militants were captured. The Mahdi Army had also taken control of the town of Shatra, 40 kilometers north of Nasiriyah.<ref>[https://www.reuters.com/article/homepageCrisis/idUSL2799267._CH_.2400 Shi'ite fighters seize centre of Nassiriya \u2013 Reuters]</ref>\n<ref>[http://www.aswataliraq.info/look/english/article.tpl?IdLanguage=1&IdPublication=4&NrArticle=74588&NrIssue=2&NrSection=1 30 killed, 52 wounded in Nassiriya until Friday night \u2013 Aswat Aliraq] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080402083026/http://www.aswataliraq.info/look/english/article.tpl?IdLanguage=1&IdPublication=4&NrArticle=74588&NrIssue=2&NrSection=1 |date=2 April 2008 }}</ref>\n\nOn 29 March, the city was back under the control of Iraqi security forces, according to a provincial police spokesman.<ref>[http://www.aswataliraq.info/look/english/article.tpl?IdLanguage=1&IdPublication=4&NrArticle=74588&NrIssue=2&NrSection=1  30 killed, 52 wounded in Nassiriya until Friday night] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080402083026/http://www.aswataliraq.info/look/english/article.tpl?IdLanguage=1&IdPublication=4&NrArticle=74588&NrIssue=2&NrSection=1 |date=2 April 2008 }} \u2013 Aswat Aliraq</ref>\n\nOn 19 April, a large firefight broke out in the village of Suq al-Shiyoukh, near Nasiriyah, which left 40 militiamen, 4 policemen and one civilian dead, another 37 militiamen were captured and 19 policemen were wounded.\n\nOn 13 May, one woman was killed in a mortar attack in the city.<ref>[http://antiwar.com/updates/?articleid=12832 Tuesday: 1 US Soldier, 36 Iraqis Killed; 73 Iraqis Wounded \u2013 Antiwar.com<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\n'''[[Mahmoudiyah, Iraq|Mahmoudiya]]''': At least 12 militia fighters were killed and seven others wounded in fighting in Mahmoudiya, {{convert|20|mi|km}} south of the capital. Some 15 Iraqi soldiers were reported to be captured. Four civilians were killed in the crossfire.\n\n'''[[Karbala]]''': In fighting in the holy city of Kerbala on 28 March 21 militants and 2 policemen were killed.<ref name = \"wiredispatch_Mar28\"/><ref>[http://today.reuters.com/news/articlenews.aspx?type=topNews&storyID=2008-03-29T121357Z_01_L24231863_RTRUKOC_0_US-IRAQ.xml&pageNumber=2&imageid=&cap=&sz=13&WTModLoc=NewsArt-C1-ArticlePage2-Death toll rises in Baghdad fighting, March 29 \u2013 Reuters] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080403084603/http://today.reuters.com/news/articlenews.aspx?type=topNews&storyID=2008-03-29T121357Z_01_L24231863_RTRUKOC_0_US-IRAQ.xml&pageNumber=2&imageid=&cap=&sz=13&WTModLoc=NewsArt-C1-ArticlePage2-Death |date=3 April 2008 }}</ref><ref>[http://www.aswataliraq.info/look/english/article.tpl?IdLanguage=1&IdPublication=4&NrArticle=74672&NrIssue=2&NrSection=1 Aswat Aliraq<!-- Bot generated title -->] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080402095232/http://www.aswataliraq.info/look/english/article.tpl?IdLanguage=1&IdPublication=4&NrArticle=74672&NrIssue=2&NrSection=1 |date=2 April 2008 }}</ref>\nOn Friday night, Iraqi forces launched a major operation targeting Mahdi Army networks in Karbala. 12 militiamen were killed and 50 wounded. 30 gunmen surrendered to police on Thursday to benefit from the Iraqi prime minister's pardon. On Saturday  an Egyptian in command of fighters in Karbala surrendered to police, along with 6 members of his group.<ref>[http://www.aswataliraq.info/look/english/article.tpl?IdLanguage=1&IdPublication=4&NrArticle=74628&NrIssue=2&NrSection=1  Egyptian leader of armed group surrenders in Karbala] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080402095214/http://www.aswataliraq.info/look/english/article.tpl?IdLanguage=1&IdPublication=4&NrArticle=74628&NrIssue=2&NrSection=1 |date=2 April 2008 }} \u2013 Aswat Aliraq</ref>\n\n'''[[Hamza, Iraq|Hamza]]''': Clashes with the Mahdi Army on 27 March, left three policemen dead in Hamza. Another officer was wounded along with two Iraqi soldiers.<ref name = \"antiwar_12591\">[http://www.antiwar.com/updates/?articleid=12591 Thursday: 225 Iraqis, 1 US Soldier, 3 US Contractors Killed; 538 Iraqis Wounded \u2013 Antiwar.com]</ref> The next day another six policemen were killed. On 30 March, police forces supported by aircraft launched a large-scale attack killing four gunmen and arresting 30.<ref>[http://www.antiwar.com/updates/?articleid=12599 Friday: 1 US Soldier, 163 Iraqis Killed; 214 Iraqis Wounded \u2013 Antiwar.com<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref><ref>[http://www.aswataliraq.info/look/english/article.tpl?IdLanguage=1&IdPublication=4&NrArticle=74725&NrIssue=2&NrSection=1 Aswat Aliraq<!-- Bot generated title -->] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080402095242/http://www.aswataliraq.info/look/english/article.tpl?IdLanguage=1&IdPublication=4&NrArticle=74725&NrIssue=2&NrSection=1 |date=2 April 2008 }}</ref>\n\n'''[[Suwayrah]]''': In clashes Iraqi Army scouts and U.S. Special Forces soldiers killed 13 militants and destroyed two cargo trucks. Another three were killed the next day.<ref>[http://www.mnf-iraq.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=17918&Itemid=21 Multi-National Force \u2013 Iraq \u2013 Iraqi Army, U.S. Special Forces patrol attacked; 13 criminal fighters killed (Suwayrah)<!-- Bot generated title -->] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080403072428/http://www.mnf-iraq.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=17918&Itemid=21 |date=3 April 2008 }}</ref><ref>[http://www.iht.com/articles/ap/2008/03/30/africa/ME-GEN-Iraq.php Shiite cleric Sadr pulls fighters off streets \u2013 International Herald Tribune<!-- Bot generated title -->] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080907024620/http://www.iht.com/articles/ap/2008/03/30/africa/ME-GEN-Iraq.php |date=7 September 2008 }}</ref>\n\n'''Nationwide''': A roadside bomb in al-Kafl, which is just south of Hilla, left three policemen dead and another four wounded.<ref name = \"antiwar_12591\"/> A roadside bomb killed four policemen and wounded four more in Mahaweel, south of Baghdad.<ref>[http://wiredispatch.com/news/?id=103111 FACTBOX-Security developments in Iraq, March 27 \u2013 Reuters] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080401063741/http://wiredispatch.com/news/?id=103111 |date=1 April 2008 }}</ref>  An Army Colonel was killed in clashes with Mehdi Army fighters in Numaniya, {{convert|72|mi|km}} south of Baghdad.<ref>[http://www.alertnet.org/thenews/newsdesk/ANW848978.htm Reuters AlertNet \u2013 FACTBOX-Security developments in Iraq, March 28<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> Militiamen attacked the village of Al Daoum, south-east of Karbala, killing five people, kidnapping six others and destroying four houses in retaliation against the families of Iraqi soldiers.<ref>[http://www.mcclatchydc.com/212/story/33729.html McClatchy Washington Bureau | 04/15/2008 | Round-up of Daily Violence in Iraq \u2013 Tuesday April 15, 2008<!-- Bot generated title -->] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081204182530/http://www.mcclatchydc.com/212/story/33729.html |date=4 December 2008 }}</ref> In another attack on a village near Karbala five people were killed and two were wounded, around 150 people were forced to flee and fourteen homes were destroyed.<ref>[http://antiwar.com/updates/?articleid=12714 Saturday: 2 US Soldiers, 95 Iraqis Killed; 185 Iraqis Wounded \u2013 Antiwar.com<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> On 21 April, the Iraqi Army reported to have killed 30 militants over the course of the previous 24 hours, in one of those clashes south of Baghdad six police officers were killed also.<ref>[http://wiredispatch.com/news/?id=136593 FACTBOX-Security developments in Iraq, April 21<!-- Bot generated title -->]{{dead link|date=May 2016}}</ref> In the town of Hussaniyah, north of Baghdad, on 22 April, an Iraqi Army patrol, accompanied by U.S. Special Forces members, was attacked by militiamen, and in the ensuing firefight nine militiamen were killed. An Iraqi army officer was killed during an armed attack near his home in Numaniya on 7 May.<ref>[http://www.mnf-iraq.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=18730&Itemid=128 Multi-National Force \u2013 Iraq \u2013 Iraqi Army Forces kill nine criminals, destroy two vehicles in Hussaniyah<!-- Bot generated title -->] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080515171421/http://www.mnf-iraq.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=18730&Itemid=128 |date=15 May 2008 }}</ref>\n\n===11 May 2008: cease-fire===\nShiite militants reached an agreement with the Iraqi government to end fighting in Baghdad's Sadr City district, a spokesman for Muqtada al-Sadr reported.<ref>[http://www2.irna.ir/en/news/view/menu-234/0805111112010754.htm Iraqi government, al-Mahdi Army agree to a cease-fire (Updates) \u2013 Irna<!-- Bot generated title -->] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120210103217/http://www2.irna.ir/en/news/view/menu-234/0805111112010754.htm |date=10 February 2012 }}</ref><ref>[http://www.presstv.com/detail.aspx?id=55052&sectionid=351020201 Press TV \u2013 Iraqi gov't, Sadrists reach agreement<!-- Bot generated title -->] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110725182652/http://www.presstv.com/detail.aspx?id=55052&sectionid=351020201 |date=25 July 2011 }}</ref> The Iraqi government confirmed that.<ref>[http://www.alertnet.org/thenews/newsdesk/L10494319.htm Reuters AlertNet \u2013 Iraqi govt confirms ceasefire with Sadr movement<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\nHowever, despite the cease-fire, sporadic fighting still continued until 15 May.<ref name=autogenerated1 /><ref name=autogenerated3 /><ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.reuters.com/article/worldNews/idUSL0434078820080512 | work=Reuters | title=Iraqi PM says crackdown shows he's not sectarian | date=12 May 2008}}</ref>\n\n==Aftermath==\nFollowing the first cease-fire at the end of March, the campaign had reached a stalemate between the two sides. However, by all accounts the Iraqi Army had a mixed performance during the clashes. Somewhere between 1,500 and 2,000 members of the Iraqi security forces out of 30,000 troops used in Basra deserted, defected or surrendered during the fighting.<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/2008/04/04/world/middleeast/04iraq.html?_r=1&ex=1364961600&en=3412ef4c4ed63d7c&ei=5090&partner=rssuserland&emc=rss&pagewanted=all&oref=slogin More Than 1,000 in Iraq\u2019s Forces Quit Basra Fight, April 4 | The New York Times]</ref> Basra was mostly under Iraqi Government control (70%). In Sadr City the Mahdi Army came to an agreement with Iraqi security forces to keep weapons off the streets and allow patrols of Iraqi Army convoys, and to give them the right to allow the arrest of members of their forces.\n\nFollowing the fighting the Maliki government allegedly agreed to [[concession (politics)|political concessions]] for a cease-fire, including legal and military immunity for the Mahdi Army and a release of its captured members, although Maliki denies any concessions were made.<ref name=\"CNN-Maliki-040708\"/> Many analysts said the Mahdi Army had scored a major political victory, which also presented the fighting capabilities of the militia that were, despite a lack of heavier weapons, far greater than those of the Iraqi security forces.{{Citation needed|date=April 2008}} However, this has apparently been objected to by the Maliki Government, since it continued its operations against Mahdi Army strongholds in Sadr City and Basrah.\n\nThe Mahdi Army stated that it will only disarm if the Shiite Clergy agree with Maliki's aims.\n\nIn light of the battle with the Mahdi army, there has been consensus from Kurdish, Sunni and the Shia political parties not aligned with Sadrists to support Prime Minister Maliki's efforts to impose Government authority in the south, even showing support to revoking the right of any political party to be represented in the October provincial elections if they continue to operate militias outside of Iraqi law.<ref>[https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=89231774&ft=1&f=1001 Fighting Calms in Iraq amid Mahdi Army Cease-Fire : NPR<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.reuters.com/article/homepageCrisis/idUSCOL144127._CH_.2400 | work=Reuters | title=ANALYSIS-Iraqi crackdown backfires, strengthens Sadrists | first=Randy | last=Fabi | date=31 March 2008}}</ref><ref>[http://www.mcclatchydc.com/iraq/story/32187.html McClatchy Washington Bureau | 03/31/2008 | With calm restored in Basra, Iraqis ask 'Who won?'<!-- Bot generated title -->] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080405212953/http://www.mcclatchydc.com/iraq/story/32187.html |date=5 April 2008 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/world/iraq/article3701511.ece | work=The Times | location=London | title=Iraq AlMahdi army offers to lay down its arms | first=James | last=Hider | date=8 April 2008 | accessdate=5 May 2010}}</ref>\n\nBy early May the fighting was centered mostly on Sadr City in Baghdad and Basra was reportedly under government control.{{Citation needed|date=May 2008}}\n\nSome 5,000 fighters belonging to the [[Special Groups (Iraq)|Special Groups]] fled across the border into Iran during the offensive and after the cease-fire.<ref>[https://www.rand.org/pubs/monographs/2010/RAND_MG911.pdf page 45]</ref>\n\n==See also==\n\n*[[Battle of Basra (2008)]]\n*[[Civil war in Iraq (2006-07)|Civil war in Iraq]]\n*[[Iraq Spring Fighting of 2004]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/middle-east/the-man-left-to-pick-up-the-p.htmls-in-basra-401617.html Article about General Mohan from the UK newspaper ''Independent'']\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Spring Fighting Of 2008}}\n[[Category:Military operations of the Iraq War]]\n[[Category:Military operations of the Iraq War involving the United States]]\n[[Category:Military operations of the Iraq War involving Iraq]]\n[[Category:2008 in Iraq]]\n[[Category:March 2008 events in Asia]]\n[[Category:April 2008 events in Asia]]\n[[Category:May 2008 events in Asia]]\n", "name_user": "DemonDays64", "label": "safe", "comment": "EngvarB, date formats perMOS:DATEFORMATbyscript| Replaced smart quotes with dumb withscript. Problem?Tell the author", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Iraq_spring_fighting_of_2008"}
{"title_page": "Eiji Band\u014d", "text_new": "{{short description|Japanese television entertainer, former baseball player, and Youtuber}}\n{{Infobox baseball biography\n| name           = Eiji Band\u014d\n| image          = \n| image_size     = \n| caption        = \n| position       = Pitcher\n| birth_date     = {{Birth date and age|1940|4|5}}\n| birth_place    = [[Manchukuo]]\n| bats           = Right\n| throws         = Right\n| debutleague    = [[Nippon Professional Baseball|NPB]]\n| debutdate      = \n| debutyear      = 1959\n| debutteam      = [[Chunichi Dragons]]\n| finaldate      = \n| finalyear      = 1969\n| finalteam      = [[Chunichi Dragons]]\n| statleague     = NPB\n| stat1label     = Win-Loss\n| stat1value     = 77-65\n| stat2label     = ERA\n| stat2value     = 2.89\n| stat3label     = Strikeouts\n| stat3value     = 748\n| teams          = \n* [[Chunichi Dragons]] ({{Baseball year|1959}} \u2013 {{Baseball year|1969}})\n| highlights     = \n}}\n{{nihongo|'''Eiji Band\u014d'''|\u677f\u6771 \u82f1\u4e8c|''Band\u014d Eiji''|extra=born April 5, 1940}} is a Japanese television entertainer, former baseball player and Youtuber{{citation needed|date=July 2017}}. He pitched many innings in his high school career. The [[Japan High School Baseball Federation]] was afraid that he would injure his arm, so they set a new rematch rule in 1958. However, he pitched 18 innings in a 1958 quarterfinal game, which resulted in the first rematch in the [[National High School Baseball Championship]]. He reached the final, but didn't win. His record of 83 strikeouts in the tournament remains unbroken.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www2.asahi.com/koshien/special/kiroku/TKY200506210178.html |script-title=ja:\u9244\u8155\u677f\u6771\u3001\u9a5a\u7570\u306e\u596a\u4e09\u632f\u8a18\u9332 |language=Japanese |publisher=[[Asahi Shimbun]] |year=2005 |accessdate=2010-09-03 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080906142901/http://www2.asahi.com/koshien/special/kiroku/TKY200506210178.html |archive-date=2008-09-06 |url-status=dead }}</ref> He joined [[Chunichi Dragons]] but it is said that he didn't regain his pitching strength.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://search.japantimes.co.jp/cgi-bin/sp20000820mk.html |title=Koshien horror stories -- stop this madness now! |accessdate=2007-12-17 |date=2000-08-20 |publisher=The Japan Times |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090719093115/http://search.japantimes.co.jp/cgi-bin/sp20000820mk.html |archivedate=2009-07-19 }}</ref> He can't extend his elbow even now.{{citation needed|date=July 2017}}\n\n== Works ==\n\n=== Singles ===\n* \"Moeyo Dragons!\" \u2013 1974\n\n=== Information ===\n* ''Doy\u014d Daisuki! 830'' ([[Kansai Telecasting Corporation|Kansai TV]]) \u2013 1987\u20131997\n\n=== Variety show ===\n* ''Sunday Dragons'' ([[Chubu-Nippon Broadcasting|CBC]]) \u2013 1983\u2013\u2013present\n* [[Unbelievable (TV series)|''Unbelievable'']] ([[Fuji TV]]) \u2013 1997\u20131998\n\n=== Game show ===\n* ''Sekai Fushigi Hakken!'' ([[Tokyo Broadcasting System Television|TBS]]) \u2013 1986\u2013\u2013present\n* ''Magical Brain Power !! '' ([[Nippon TV]]) \u2013 1990\u20131999, 2001\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Chunichi Dragons Opening Day starting pitchers}}\n{{Japan Academy Prize for Best Supporting Actor}}\n{{Nikkan Sports Film Award for Best Supporting Actor}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bando, Eiji}}\n[[Category:1940 births]]\n[[Category:Japanese male actors]]\n[[category:Baseball people from Tokushima Prefecture]]\n[[Category:Japanese baseball players]]\n[[Category:Nippon Professional Baseball pitchers]]\n[[Category:Chunichi Dragons players]]\n[[Category:Japanese people from Manchukuo]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Former Stardust Promotion artists]]\n\n\n{{Japan-baseball-pitcher-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Japanese television entertainer, former baseball player, and Youtuber}}\n{{Infobox baseball biography\n| name           = Eiji Band\u014d\n