{"title_page": "Phil Healey", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2017}}\n{{Infobox rugby biography\n| name = Phil Healey\n| honorific_suffix = \n| image = \n| caption = \n| nickname = \n| birth_name = Phil Healey\n| birth_date = \n| birth_place = [[Hamilton, New Zealand|Hamilton]], [[New Zealand]]\n| death_place = \n| death_date =\n| rl_coachclubs = \n| rl_coachyears = \n| ru_position = \n| height = \n| weight = \n| ru_coachclubs = {{plainlist|[[Counties Manukau Rugby Football Union|Counties Manukau]] ''(Head Strength & Conditioning)''\n*[[Chiefs (rugby union)|Chiefs]] ''(Head Strength & Conditioning)''\n*[[Glasgow Warriors]] ''(Head Strength & Conditioning)''\n*[[Blues (Super Rugby)|Blues]]}}\n| ru_coachyears = 2003\u201308<br/>2008\u201317<br/>2017\u201318<br/>2018-\n| ru_amateuryears = \n| ru_amateurclubs = \n| ru_clubyears = \n| ru_proclubs = \n| ru_clubcaps = \n| ru_clubupdate = \n| ru_nationalteam =\n| ru_nationalyears = \n| ru_nationalcaps = \n| ru_nationalpoints =\n| ru_province = \n| ru_provinceyears = \n| ru_provincecaps = \n| ru_provincepoints = \n| occupation = \n| family = \n| spouse = \n| children = \n| relatives = \n| school = [[Pukekohe High School]]\n| university =\n}}\n\n'''Phil Healey''' is a [[rugby union]] strength and conditioning coach with the [[Blues (Super Rugby)|Blues]] in Auckland, having previously been with [[Glasgow Warriors]]. He joined the Glasgow side for the [[2017\u201318 Glasgow Warriors season|2017\u201318 season]]. Before he was with Glasgow he was previously a strength and conditioning coach for the [[Chiefs (rugby union)|Chiefs]] in [[New Zealand]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.glasgowwarriors.org/club-staff-0|title=Club Staff - Glasgow Warriors|website=Glasgowwarriors.org|accessdate=31 August 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Rugby union coaching career==\nHealey was the head strength and conditioning coach for [[Counties Manukau Rugby Football Union]] from 2003 until 2008.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.steelers.co.nz/news/article/41/|title=News \u2013 Counties Manukau Rugby Football Union|first=72DPI Limited -|last=www.72dpi.co.nz|website=Steelers.co.nz}}</ref>\n\nHe then joined the [[Chiefs (rugby union)|Chiefs]] in 2008 and stayed there until 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://statsports.com/behind-the-science-with-phil-healey-head-sc-coach-chiefs-rugby/|title=STATSports \u2013   Behind The Science With Phil Healey \u2013 Head S&C Coach, Chiefs Rugby|website=Statsports.com}}</ref> In 2016 the Chief's Head Coach, [[Dave Rennie]], credited part of the team's success to the strength and conditioning work by Healey and his team.<ref>[http://www.nzherald.co.nz/sport/news/article.cfm?c_id=4&objectid=11616163 Rugby: Rennie receiving plenty of help from his friends], NZ Herald on line, 3 April 2016, retrieved 31 August 2017</ref> During Healey's time at the Chief's [[Waikato University]]'s Sport and Leisure Studies students worked as interns with him.<ref>[http://fitnessjournal.co.nz/a-winning-partnership/ A winning partnership], NZ Fitness Journal, 3 May 2016, retrieved 31 August 2017</ref>\n\nHe joined [[Glasgow Warriors]] for the [[2017\u201318 Glasgow Warriors season|2017\u201318 season]] along with Dave Rennie.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.glasgowwarriors.org/news/17/06/22/warriors-confirm-rugby-support-staff-new-season|title=Warriors confirm rugby support staff for new season \u2013 Glasgow Warriors|website=Glasgowwarriors.org}}</ref>\n\nOn 23 October 2018 it was announced that Healey would leave Glasgow Warriors for personal reasons to return home to New Zealand. He will take up a position with [[Blues (Super Rugby)|The Blues]] in Auckland.<ref>http://www.glasgowwarriors.org/news/18/10/23/alainuuese-finalises-toulon-move</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=komtZHXgthw Phil Healey of The Chiefs discusses STATSports Viper]\n*[http://www.planetrugby.com/news/conditioning-key-to-chiefs-success/ Conditioning key to Chiefs success]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Healey, Phil}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Glasgow Warriors coaches]]\n[[Category:People from Hamilton, New Zealand]]\n[[Category:Rugby union strength and conditioning coaches]]\n[[Category:People educated at Pukekohe High School]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2017}}\n{{Infobox rugby biography\n| name = Phil Healey\n| honorific_suffix = \n| image = \n| caption = \n| nickname = \n| birth_name = Phil Healey\n| birth_date = \n| birth_place = [[Hamilton, New Zealand|Hamilton]], [[New Zealand]]\n| death_place = \n| death_date =\n| rl_coachclubs = \n| rl_coachyears = \n| ru_position = \n| height = \n| weight = \n| ru_coachclubs = {{plainlist|[[Counties Manukau Rugby Football Union|Counties Manukau]] ''(Head Strength & Conditioning)''\n*[[Chiefs (rugby union)|Chiefs]] ''(Head Strength & Conditioning)''\n*[[Glasgow Warriors]] ''(Head Strength & Conditioning)''\n*[[Blues (Super Rugby)|Blues]]}}\n| ru_coachyears = 2003\u201308<br/>2008\u201317<br/>2017\u201318<br/>2018-\n| ru_amateuryears = \n| ru_amateurclubs = \n| ru_clubyears = \n| ru_proclubs = \n| ru_clubcaps = \n| ru_clubupdate = \n| ru_nationalteam =\n| ru_nationalyears = \n| ru_nationalcaps = \n| ru_nationalpoints =\n| ru_province = \n| ru_provinceyears = \n| ru_provincecaps = \n| ru_provincepoints = \n| occupation = \n| family = \n| spouse = \n| children = \n| relatives = \n| school = [[Pukekohe High School]]\n| university =\n}}\n\n'''Phil Healey''' is a [[rugby union]] strength and conditioning coach with the [[Blues (Super Rugby)|Blues]] in Auckland, having previously been with [[Glasgow Warriors]]. He joined the Glasgow side for the [[2017\u201318 Glasgow Warriors season|2017\u201318 season]]. Before he was with Glasgow he was previously a strength and conditioning coach for the [[Chiefs (rugby union)|Chiefs]] in [[New Zealand]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.glasgowwarriors.org/club-staff-0|title=Club Staff - Glasgow Warriors|we